var P_HTM = [];
P_HTM[1]="*Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa* **";
P_HTM[2]="*Dīghanikāyo* **";
P_HTM[3]="*Mahāvaggapāḷi* **";
P_HTM[4]="*14. Mahāpadānasutta  ** The Great Discourse on the Harvest of Deeds *";
P_HTM[5]="*1. Pubbenivāsapaṭisaṃyuttakathā**1. On Past Lives*";
P_HTM[6]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[7]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme karerikuṭikāyaṃ.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery, in the hut by the kareri tree.*";
P_HTM[8]="*Atha kho sambahulānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkantānaṃ karerimaṇḍalamāḷe sannisinnānaṃ sannipatitānaṃ pubbenivāsapaṭisaṃyuttā dhammī kathā udapādi:**Then after the meal, on return from alms-round, several senior mendicants sat together in the pavilion by the kareri tree and this Dhamma talk on the subject of past lives came up among them,*";
P_HTM[9]="*“itipi pubbenivāso, itipi pubbenivāso”ti.**“So it was in a past life; such it was in a past life.”*";
P_HTM[10]="*Assosi kho bhagavā dibbāya sotadhātuyā visuddhāya atikkantamānusikāya tesaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ imaṃ kathāsallāpaṃ.**With clairaudience that is purified and superhuman, the Buddha heard that discussion among the mendicants.*";
P_HTM[11]="*Atha kho bhagavā uṭṭhāyāsanā yena karerimaṇḍalamāḷo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi, nisajja kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**So he got up from his seat and went to the pavilion, where he sat on the seat spread out and addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[12]="*“kāya nuttha, bhikkhave, etarahi kathāya sannisinnā;**“Mendicants, what were you sitting talking about just now?*";
P_HTM[13]="*kā ca pana vo antarākathā vippakatā”ti?**What conversation was unfinished?”*";
P_HTM[14]="*Evaṃ vutte, te bhikkhū bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**The mendicants told him what had happened, adding,*";
P_HTM[15]="*“idha, bhante, amhākaṃ pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkantānaṃ karerimaṇḍalamāḷe sannisinnānaṃ sannipatitānaṃ pubbenivāsapaṭisaṃyuttā dhammī kathā udapādi:* **";
P_HTM[16]="*‘itipi pubbenivāso itipi pubbenivāso’ti.* **";
P_HTM[17]="*Ayaṃ kho no, bhante, antarākathā vippakatā. Atha bhagavā anuppatto”ti.**“This is the conversation that was unfinished when the Buddha arrived.”*";
P_HTM[18]="*“Iccheyyātha no tumhe, bhikkhave, pubbenivāsapaṭisaṃyuttaṃ dhammiṃ kathaṃ sotun”ti?**“Would you like to hear a Dhamma talk on the subject of past lives?”*";
P_HTM[19]="*“Etassa, bhagavā, kālo; etassa, sugata, kālo;**“Now is the time, Blessed One! Now is the time, Holy One!*";
P_HTM[20]="*yaṃ bhagavā pubbenivāsapaṭisaṃyuttaṃ dhammiṃ kathaṃ kareyya, bhagavato sutvā bhikkhū dhāressantī”ti.**Let the Buddha give a Dhamma talk on the subject of past lives. The mendicants will listen and remember it.”*";
P_HTM[21]="*“Tena hi, bhikkhave, suṇātha sādhukaṃ manasi karotha bhāsissāmī”ti.**“Well then, mendicants, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[22]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[23]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[24]="*“Ito so, bhikkhave, ekanavutikappe yaṃ vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho loke udapādi.**“Ninety-one eons ago, the Buddha Vipassī arose in the world, perfected and fully awakened.*";
P_HTM[25]="*Ito so, bhikkhave, ekatiṃse kappe yaṃ sikhī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho loke udapādi.**Thirty-one eons ago, the Buddha Sikhī arose in the world, perfected and fully awakened.*";
P_HTM[26]="*Tasmiññeva kho, bhikkhave, ekatiṃse kappe vessabhū bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho loke udapādi.**In the same thirty-first eon, the Buddha Vessabhū arose in the world, perfected and fully awakened.*";
P_HTM[27]="*Imasmiññeva kho, bhikkhave, bhaddakappe kakusandho bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho loke udapādi.**In the present fortunate eon, the Buddhas Kakusandha,*";
P_HTM[28]="*Imasmiññeva kho, bhikkhave, bhaddakappe koṇāgamano bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho loke udapādi.**Koṇāgamana,*";
P_HTM[29]="*Imasmiññeva kho, bhikkhave, bhaddakappe kassapo bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho loke udapādi.**and Kassapa arose in the world, perfected and fully awakened.*";
P_HTM[30]="*Imasmiññeva kho, bhikkhave, bhaddakappe ahaṃ etarahi arahaṃ sammāsambuddho loke uppanno.**And in the present fortunate eon, I have arisen in the world, perfected and fully awakened.*";
P_HTM[31]="*Vipassī, bhikkhave, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho khattiyo jātiyā ahosi, khattiyakule udapādi.**The Buddhas Vipassī,*";
P_HTM[32]="*Sikhī, bhikkhave, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho khattiyo jātiyā ahosi, khattiyakule udapādi.**Sikhī,*";
P_HTM[33]="*Vessabhū, bhikkhave, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho khattiyo jātiyā ahosi, khattiyakule udapādi.**and Vessabhū were born as aristocrats into aristocrat families.*";
P_HTM[34]="*Kakusandho, bhikkhave, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho brāhmaṇo jātiyā ahosi, brāhmaṇakule udapādi.**The Buddhas Kakusandha,*";
P_HTM[35]="*Koṇāgamano, bhikkhave, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho brāhmaṇo jātiyā ahosi, brāhmaṇakule udapādi.**Koṇāgamana,*";
P_HTM[36]="*Kassapo, bhikkhave, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho brāhmaṇo jātiyā ahosi, brāhmaṇakule udapādi.**and Kassapa were born as brahmins into brahmin families.*";
P_HTM[37]="*Ahaṃ, bhikkhave, etarahi arahaṃ sammāsambuddho khattiyo jātiyā ahosiṃ, khattiyakule uppanno.**I was born as an aristocrat into an aristocrat family.*";
P_HTM[38]="*Vipassī, bhikkhave, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho koṇḍañño gottena ahosi.**Koṇḍañña was the clan of Vipassī,*";
P_HTM[39]="*Sikhī, bhikkhave, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho koṇḍañño gottena ahosi.**Sikhī,*";
P_HTM[40]="*Vessabhū, bhikkhave, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho koṇḍañño gottena ahosi.**and Vessabhū.*";
P_HTM[41]="*Kakusandho, bhikkhave, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho kassapo gottena ahosi.**Kassapa was the clan of Kakusandha,*";
P_HTM[42]="*Koṇāgamano, bhikkhave, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho kassapo gottena ahosi.**Koṇāgamana,*";
P_HTM[43]="*Kassapo, bhikkhave, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho kassapo gottena ahosi.**and Kassapa.*";
P_HTM[44]="*Ahaṃ, bhikkhave, etarahi arahaṃ sammāsambuddho gotamo gottena ahosiṃ.**Gotama is my clan.*";
P_HTM[45]="*Vipassissa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa asītivassasahassāni āyuppamāṇaṃ ahosi.**Vipassī lived for 80,000 years.*";
P_HTM[46]="*Sikhissa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa sattativassasahassāni āyuppamāṇaṃ ahosi.**Sikhī lived for 70,000 years.*";
P_HTM[47]="*Vessabhussa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa saṭṭhivassasahassāni āyuppamāṇaṃ ahosi.**Vessabhū lived for 60,000 years.*";
P_HTM[48]="*Kakusandhassa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa cattālīsavassasahassāni āyuppamāṇaṃ ahosi.**Kakusandha lived for 40,000 years.*";
P_HTM[49]="*Koṇāgamanassa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa tiṃsavassasahassāni āyuppamāṇaṃ ahosi.**Koṇāgamana lived for 30,000 years.*";
P_HTM[50]="*Kassapassa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa vīsativassasahassāni āyuppamāṇaṃ ahosi.**Kassapa lived for 20,000 years.*";
P_HTM[51]="*Mayhaṃ, bhikkhave, etarahi appakaṃ āyuppamāṇaṃ parittaṃ lahukaṃ; yo ciraṃ jīvati, so vassasataṃ appaṃ vā bhiyyo.**For me these days the life-span is short, brief, and fleeting. A long-lived person lives for a century or a little more.*";
P_HTM[52]="*Vipassī, bhikkhave, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho pāṭaliyā mūle abhisambuddho.**Vipassī was awakened at the root of a trumpet flower tree.*";
P_HTM[53]="*Sikhī, bhikkhave, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho puṇḍarīkassa mūle abhisambuddho.**Sikhī was awakened at the root of a white-mango tree.*";
P_HTM[54]="*Vessabhū, bhikkhave, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho sālassa mūle abhisambuddho.**Vessabhū was awakened at the root of a sal tree.*";
P_HTM[55]="*Kakusandho, bhikkhave, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho sirīsassa mūle abhisambuddho.**Kakusandha was awakened at the root of an acacia tree.*";
P_HTM[56]="*Koṇāgamano, bhikkhave, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho udumbarassa mūle abhisambuddho.**Koṇāgamana was awakened at the root of a cluster fig tree.*";
P_HTM[57]="*Kassapo, bhikkhave, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho nigrodhassa mūle abhisambuddho.**Kassapa was awakened at the root of a banyan tree.*";
P_HTM[58]="*Ahaṃ, bhikkhave, etarahi arahaṃ sammāsambuddho assatthassa mūle abhisambuddho.**I was awakened at the root of a peepul tree.*";
P_HTM[59]="*Vipassissa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa khaṇḍatissaṃ nāma sāvakayugaṃ ahosi aggaṃ bhaddayugaṃ.**Vipassī had a fine pair of chief disciples named Khaṇḍa and Tissa.*";
P_HTM[60]="*Sikhissa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa abhibhūsambhavaṃ nāma sāvakayugaṃ ahosi aggaṃ bhaddayugaṃ.**Sikhī had a fine pair of chief disciples named Abhibhū and Sambhava.*";
P_HTM[61]="*Vessabhussa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa soṇuttaraṃ nāma sāvakayugaṃ ahosi aggaṃ bhaddayugaṃ.**Vessabhū had a fine pair of chief disciples named Soṇa and Uttara.*";
P_HTM[62]="*Kakusandhassa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa vidhurasañjīvaṃ nāma sāvakayugaṃ ahosi aggaṃ bhaddayugaṃ.**Kakusandha had a fine pair of chief disciples named Vidhura and Sañjīva.*";
P_HTM[63]="*Koṇāgamanassa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa bhiyyosuttaraṃ nāma sāvakayugaṃ ahosi aggaṃ bhaddayugaṃ.**Koṇāgamana had a fine pair of chief disciples named Bhiyyosa and Uttara.*";
P_HTM[64]="*Kassapassa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa tissabhāradvājaṃ nāma sāvakayugaṃ ahosi aggaṃ bhaddayugaṃ.**Kassapa had a fine pair of chief disciples named Tissa and Bhāradvāja.*";
P_HTM[65]="*Mayhaṃ, bhikkhave, etarahi sāriputtamoggallānaṃ nāma sāvakayugaṃ ahosi aggaṃ bhaddayugaṃ.**I have a fine pair of chief disciples named Sāriputta and Moggallāna.*";
P_HTM[66]="*Vipassissa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa tayo sāvakānaṃ sannipātā ahesuṃ. Eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi aṭṭhasaṭṭhibhikkhusatasahassaṃ, eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi bhikkhusatasahassaṃ, eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi asītibhikkhusahassāni. Vipassissa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa ime tayo sāvakānaṃ sannipātā ahesuṃ sabbesaṃyeva khīṇāsavānaṃ.**Vipassī had three gatherings of disciples—one of 6,800,000, one of 100,000, and one of 80,000—all of them mendicants who had ended their defilements.*";
P_HTM[67]="*Sikhissa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa tayo sāvakānaṃ sannipātā ahesuṃ. Eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi bhikkhusatasahassaṃ, eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi asītibhikkhusahassāni, eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi sattatibhikkhusahassāni. Sikhissa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa ime tayo sāvakānaṃ sannipātā ahesuṃ sabbesaṃyeva khīṇāsavānaṃ.**Sikhī had three gatherings of disciples—one of 100,000, one of 80,000, and one of 70,000—all of them mendicants who had ended their defilements.*";
P_HTM[68]="*Vessabhussa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa tayo sāvakānaṃ sannipātā ahesuṃ. Eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi asītibhikkhusahassāni, eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi sattatibhikkhusahassāni, eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi saṭṭhibhikkhusahassāni. Vessabhussa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa ime tayo sāvakānaṃ sannipātā ahesuṃ sabbesaṃyeva khīṇāsavānaṃ.**Vessabhū had three gatherings of disciples—one of 80,000, one of 70,000, and one of 60,000—all of them mendicants who had ended their defilements.*";
P_HTM[69]="*Kakusandhassa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi cattālīsabhikkhusahassāni. Kakusandhassa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa ayaṃ eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi sabbesaṃyeva khīṇāsavānaṃ.**Kakusandha had one gathering of disciples—40,000 mendicants who had ended their defilements.*";
P_HTM[70]="*Koṇāgamanassa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi tiṃsabhikkhusahassāni. Koṇāgamanassa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa ayaṃ eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi sabbesaṃyeva khīṇāsavānaṃ.**Koṇāgamana had one gathering of disciples—30,000 mendicants who had ended their defilements.*";
P_HTM[71]="*Kassapassa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi vīsatibhikkhusahassāni. Kassapassa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa ayaṃ eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi sabbesaṃyeva khīṇāsavānaṃ.**Kassapa had one gathering of disciples—20,000 mendicants who had ended their defilements.*";
P_HTM[72]="*Mayhaṃ, bhikkhave, etarahi eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi aḍḍhateḷasāni bhikkhusatāni. Mayhaṃ, bhikkhave, ayaṃ eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi sabbesaṃyeva khīṇāsavānaṃ.**I have had one gathering of disciples—1,250 mendicants who had ended their defilements.*";
P_HTM[73]="*Vipassissa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa asoko nāma bhikkhu upaṭṭhāko ahosi aggupaṭṭhāko.**Vipassī had as chief attendant a mendicant named Asoka.*";
P_HTM[74]="*Sikhissa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa khemaṅkaro nāma bhikkhu upaṭṭhāko ahosi aggupaṭṭhāko.**Sikhī had as chief attendant a mendicant named Khemaṅkara.*";
P_HTM[75]="*Vessabhussa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa upasanto nāma bhikkhu upaṭṭhāko ahosi aggupaṭṭhāko.**Vessabhū had as chief attendant a mendicant named Upasanta.*";
P_HTM[76]="*Kakusandhassa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa buddhijo nāma bhikkhu upaṭṭhāko ahosi aggupaṭṭhāko.**Kakusandha had as chief attendant a mendicant named Buddhija.*";
P_HTM[77]="*Koṇāgamanassa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa sotthijo nāma bhikkhu upaṭṭhāko ahosi aggupaṭṭhāko.**Koṇāgamana had as chief attendant a mendicant named Sotthija.*";
P_HTM[78]="*Kassapassa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa sabbamitto nāma bhikkhu upaṭṭhāko ahosi aggupaṭṭhāko.**Kassapa had as chief attendant a mendicant named Sabbamitta.*";
P_HTM[79]="*Mayhaṃ, bhikkhave, etarahi ānando nāma bhikkhu upaṭṭhāko ahosi aggupaṭṭhāko.**I have as chief attendant a mendicant named Ānanda.*";
P_HTM[80]="*Vipassissa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa bandhumā nāma rājā pitā ahosi.**Vipassī’s father was King Bandhuma,*";
P_HTM[81]="*Bandhumatī nāma devī mātā ahosi janetti.**his birth mother was Queen Bandhumatī,*";
P_HTM[82]="*Bandhumassa rañño bandhumatī nāma nagaraṃ rājadhānī ahosi.**and their capital city was named Bandhumatī.*";
P_HTM[83]="*Sikhissa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa aruṇo nāma rājā pitā ahosi.**Sikhī’s father was King Aruṇa,*";
P_HTM[84]="*Pabhāvatī nāma devī mātā ahosi janetti.**his birth mother was Queen Pabhāvatī,*";
P_HTM[85]="*Aruṇassa rañño aruṇavatī nāma nagaraṃ rājadhānī ahosi.**and their capital city was named Aruṇavatī.*";
P_HTM[86]="*Vessabhussa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa suppatito nāma rājā pitā ahosi.**Vessabhū’s father was King Suppatīta,*";
P_HTM[87]="*Vassavatī nāma devī mātā ahosi janetti.**his birth mother was Queen Vassavatī,*";
P_HTM[88]="*Suppatitassa rañño anomaṃ nāma nagaraṃ rājadhānī ahosi.**and their capital city was named Suppatīta.*";
P_HTM[89]="*Kakusandhassa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa aggidatto nāma brāhmaṇo pitā ahosi.**Kakusandha’s father was the brahmin Aggidatta,*";
P_HTM[90]="*Visākhā nāma brāhmaṇī mātā ahosi janetti.**and his birth mother was the brahmin lady Visākhā.*";
P_HTM[91]="*Tena kho pana, bhikkhave, samayena khemo nāma rājā ahosi.**At that time the king was Khema,*";
P_HTM[92]="*Khemassa rañño khemavatī nāma nagaraṃ rājadhānī ahosi.**whose capital city was named Khemavatī.*";
P_HTM[93]="*Koṇāgamanassa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa yaññadatto nāma brāhmaṇo pitā ahosi.**Koṇāgamana’s father was the brahmin Yaññadatta,*";
P_HTM[94]="*Uttarā nāma brāhmaṇī mātā ahosi janetti.**and his birth mother was the brahmin lady Uttarā.*";
P_HTM[95]="*Tena kho pana, bhikkhave, samayena sobho nāma rājā ahosi.**At that time the king was Sobha,*";
P_HTM[96]="*Sobhassa rañño sobhavatī nāma nagaraṃ rājadhānī ahosi.**whose capital city was named Sobhavatī.*";
P_HTM[97]="*Kassapassa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa brahmadatto nāma brāhmaṇo pitā ahosi.**Kassapa’s father was the brahmin Brahmadatta,*";
P_HTM[98]="*Dhanavatī nāma brāhmaṇī mātā ahosi janetti.**and his birth mother was the brahmin lady Dhanavatī.*";
P_HTM[99]="*Tena kho pana, bhikkhave, samayena kikī nāma rājā ahosi.**At that time the king was Kikī,*";
P_HTM[100]="*Kikissa rañño bārāṇasī nāma nagaraṃ rājadhānī ahosi.**whose capital city was named Benares.*";
P_HTM[101]="*Mayhaṃ, bhikkhave, etarahi suddhodano nāma rājā pitā ahosi.**My father was King Suddhodana,*";
P_HTM[102]="*Māyā nāma devī mātā ahosi janetti.**my birth mother was Queen Māyā,*";
P_HTM[103]="*Kapilavatthu nāma nagaraṃ rājadhānī ahosī”ti.**and our capital city was Kapilavatthu.”*";
P_HTM[104]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[105]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato uṭṭhāyāsanā vihāraṃ pāvisi.**When he had spoken, the Holy One got up from his seat and entered his dwelling.*";
P_HTM[106]="*Atha kho tesaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ acirapakkantassa bhagavato ayamantarākathā udapādi:**Soon after the Buddha left, those mendicants discussed among themselves:*";
P_HTM[107]="*“acchariyaṃ, āvuso, abbhutaṃ, āvuso, tathāgatassa mahiddhikatā mahānubhāvatā.**“It’s incredible, reverends, it’s amazing, the power and might of a Realized One!*";
P_HTM[108]="*Yatra hi nāma tathāgato atīte buddhe parinibbute chinnapapañce chinnavaṭume pariyādinnavaṭṭe sabbadukkhavītivatte jātitopi anussarissati, nāmatopi anussarissati, gottatopi anussarissati, āyuppamāṇatopi anussarissati, sāvakayugatopi anussarissati, sāvakasannipātatopi anussarissati:**For he is able to recollect the caste, names, clans, life-span, chief disciples, and gatherings of disciples of the Buddhas of the past who have become completely extinguished, cut off proliferation, cut off the track, finished off the cycle, and transcended suffering.*";
P_HTM[109]="*‘evaṃjaccā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipi, evaṃnāmā evaṅgottā evaṃsīlā evaṃdhammā evaṃpaññā evaṃvihārī evaṃvimuttā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipī’”ti.**He knows the caste they were born in, and also their names, clans, conduct, qualities, wisdom, meditation, and freedom.*";
P_HTM[110]="*“Kiṃ nu kho, āvuso, tathāgatasseva nu kho esā dhammadhātu suppaṭividdhā, yassā dhammadhātuyā suppaṭividdhattā tathāgato atīte buddhe parinibbute chinnapapañce chinnavaṭume pariyādinnavaṭṭe sabbadukkhavītivatte jātitopi anussarati, nāmatopi anussarati, gottatopi anussarati, āyuppamāṇatopi anussarati, sāvakayugatopi anussarati, sāvakasannipātatopi anussarati: ‘evaṃjaccā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipi, evaṃnāmā evaṅgottā evaṃsīlā evaṃdhammā evaṃpaññā evaṃvihārī evaṃvimuttā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipī’ti,**Is it because the Realized One has clearly comprehended the principle of the teachings that he can recollect all these things?*";
P_HTM[111]="*udāhu devatā tathāgatassa etamatthaṃ ārocesuṃ, yena tathāgato atīte buddhe parinibbute chinnapapañce chinnavaṭume pariyādinnavaṭṭe sabbadukkhavītivatte jātitopi anussarati, nāmatopi anussarati, gottatopi anussarati, āyuppamāṇatopi anussarati, sāvakayugatopi anussarati, sāvakasannipātatopi anussarati: ‘evaṃjaccā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipi, evaṃnāmā evaṅgottā evaṃsīlā evaṃdhammā evaṃpaññā evaṃvihārī evaṃvimuttā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipī’”ti.**Or did deities tell him?”*";
P_HTM[112]="*Ayañca hidaṃ tesaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ antarākathā vippakatā hoti.**But this conversation among those mendicants was left unfinished.*";
P_HTM[113]="*Atha kho bhagavā sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito yena karerimaṇḍalamāḷo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then in the late afternoon, the Buddha came out of retreat and went to the pavilion by the kareri tree, where he sat on the seat spread out*";
P_HTM[114]="*Nisajja kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**and addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[115]="*“kāya nuttha, bhikkhave, etarahi kathāya sannisinnā;**“Mendicants, what were you sitting talking about just now?*";
P_HTM[116]="*kā ca pana vo antarākathā vippakatā”ti?**What conversation was unfinished?”*";
P_HTM[117]="*Evaṃ vutte, te bhikkhū bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**The mendicants told him what had happened, adding,*";
P_HTM[118]="*“idha, bhante, amhākaṃ acirapakkantassa bhagavato ayaṃ antarākathā udapādi:* **";
P_HTM[119]="*‘acchariyaṃ, āvuso, abbhutaṃ, āvuso, tathāgatassa mahiddhikatā mahānubhāvatā.* **";
P_HTM[120]="*Yatra hi nāma tathāgato atīte buddhe parinibbute chinnapapañce chinnavaṭume pariyādinnavaṭṭe sabbadukkhavītivatte jātitopi anussarissati, nāmatopi anussarissati, gottatopi anussarissati, āyuppamāṇatopi anussarissati, sāvakayugatopi anussarissati, sāvakasannipātatopi anussarissati:* **";
P_HTM[121]="*“evaṃjaccā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipi, evaṃnāmā evaṅgottā evaṃsīlā evaṃdhammā evaṃpaññā evaṃvihārī evaṃvimuttā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[122]="*Kiṃ nu kho, āvuso, tathāgatasseva nu kho esā dhammadhātu suppaṭividdhā, yassā dhammadhātuyā suppaṭividdhattā tathāgato atīte buddhe parinibbute chinnapapañce chinnavaṭume pariyādinnavaṭṭe sabbadukkhavītivatte jātitopi anussarati, nāmatopi anussarati, gottatopi anussarati, āyuppamāṇatopi anussarati, sāvakayugatopi anussarati, sāvakasannipātatopi anussarati:* **";
P_HTM[123]="*“evaṃjaccā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipi, evaṃnāmā evaṅgottā evaṃsīlā evaṃdhammā evaṃpaññā evaṃvihārī evaṃvimuttā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[124]="*Udāhu devatā tathāgatassa etamatthaṃ ārocesuṃ, yena tathāgato atīte buddhe parinibbute chinnapapañce chinnavaṭume pariyādinnavaṭṭe sabbadukkhavītivatte jātitopi anussarati, nāmatopi anussarati, gottatopi anussarati, āyuppamāṇatopi anussarati, sāvakayugatopi anussarati, sāvakasannipātatopi anussarati:* **";
P_HTM[125]="*“evaṃjaccā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipi, evaṃnāmā evaṅgottā evaṃsīlā evaṃdhammā evaṃpaññā evaṃvihārī evaṃvimuttā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipī”’ti?* **";
P_HTM[126]="*Ayaṃ kho no, bhante, antarākathā vippakatā, atha bhagavā anuppatto”ti.**“This was our conversation that was unfinished when the Buddha arrived.”*";
P_HTM[127]="*“Tathāgatassevesā, bhikkhave, dhammadhātu suppaṭividdhā, yassā dhammadhātuyā suppaṭividdhattā tathāgato atīte buddhe parinibbute chinnapapañce chinnavaṭume pariyādinnavaṭṭe sabbadukkhavītivatte jātitopi anussarati, nāmatopi anussarati, gottatopi anussarati, āyuppamāṇatopi anussarati, sāvakayugatopi anussarati, sāvakasannipātatopi anussarati:**“It is because the Realized One has clearly comprehended the principle of the teachings that he can recollect all these things.*";
P_HTM[128]="*‘evaṃjaccā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipi, evaṃnāmā evaṅgottā evaṃsīlā evaṃdhammā evaṃpaññā evaṃvihārī evaṃvimuttā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[129]="*Devatāpi tathāgatassa etamatthaṃ ārocesuṃ, yena tathāgato atīte buddhe parinibbute chinnapapañce chinnavaṭume pariyādinnavaṭṭe sabbadukkhavītivatte jātitopi anussarati, nāmatopi anussarati, gottatopi anussarati, āyuppamāṇatopi anussarati, sāvakayugatopi anussarati, sāvakasannipātatopi anussarati:**And the deities also told me.*";
P_HTM[130]="*‘evaṃjaccā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipi, evaṃnāmā evaṅgottā evaṃsīlā evaṃdhammā evaṃpaññā evaṃvihārī evaṃvimuttā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[131]="*Iccheyyātha no tumhe, bhikkhave, bhiyyoso mattāya pubbenivāsapaṭisaṃyuttaṃ dhammiṃ kathaṃ sotun”ti?**Would you like to hear a further Dhamma talk on the subject of past lives?”*";
P_HTM[132]="*“Etassa, bhagavā, kālo; etassa, sugata, kālo;**“Now is the time, Blessed One! Now is the time, Holy One!*";
P_HTM[133]="*yaṃ bhagavā bhiyyoso mattāya pubbenivāsapaṭisaṃyuttaṃ dhammiṃ kathaṃ kareyya, bhagavato sutvā bhikkhū dhāressantī”ti.**Let the Buddha give a further Dhamma talk on the subject of past lives. The mendicants will listen and remember it.”*";
P_HTM[134]="*“Tena hi, bhikkhave, suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**“Well then, mendicants, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[135]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[136]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[137]="*“Ito so, bhikkhave, ekanavutikappe yaṃ vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho loke udapādi.**“Ninety-one eons ago, the Buddha Vipassī arose in the world, perfected and fully awakened.*";
P_HTM[138]="*Vipassī, bhikkhave, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho khattiyo jātiyā ahosi, khattiyakule udapādi.**He was born as an aristocrat into an aristocrat family.*";
P_HTM[139]="*Vipassī, bhikkhave, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho koṇḍañño gottena ahosi.**His clan was Koṇḍañña.*";
P_HTM[140]="*Vipassissa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa asītivassasahassāni āyuppamāṇaṃ ahosi.**He lived for 80,000 years.*";
P_HTM[141]="*Vipassī, bhikkhave, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho pāṭaliyā mūle abhisambuddho.**He was awakened at the root of a trumpet flower tree.*";
P_HTM[142]="*Vipassissa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa khaṇḍatissaṃ nāma sāvakayugaṃ ahosi aggaṃ bhaddayugaṃ.**He had a fine pair of chief disciples named Khaṇḍa and Tissa.*";
P_HTM[143]="*Vipassissa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa tayo sāvakānaṃ sannipātā ahesuṃ.**He had three gatherings of disciples—*";
P_HTM[144]="*Eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi aṭṭhasaṭṭhibhikkhusatasahassaṃ, eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi bhikkhusatasahassaṃ, eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi asītibhikkhusahassāni.**one of 6,800,000, one of 100,000, and one of 80,000—*";
P_HTM[145]="*Vipassissa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa ime tayo sāvakānaṃ sannipātā ahesuṃ sabbesaṃyeva khīṇāsavānaṃ.**all of them mendicants who had ended their defilements.*";
P_HTM[146]="*Vipassissa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa asoko nāma bhikkhu upaṭṭhāko ahosi aggupaṭṭhāko.**He had as chief attendant a mendicant named Asoka.*";
P_HTM[147]="*Vipassissa, bhikkhave, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa bandhumā nāma rājā pitā ahosi.**His father was King Bandhuma,*";
P_HTM[148]="*Bandhumatī nāma devī mātā ahosi janetti.**his birth mother was Queen Bandhumatī,*";
P_HTM[149]="*Bandhumassa rañño bandhumatī nāma nagaraṃ rājadhānī ahosi.**and their capital city was named Bandhumatī.*";
P_HTM[150]="*2. Bodhisattadhammatā**2. What’s Normal For One Intent on Awakening*";
P_HTM[151]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassī bodhisatto tusitā kāyā cavitvā sato sampajāno mātukucchiṃ okkami.**When Vipassī, the being intent on awakening, passed away from the host of Joyful Gods, he was conceived in his mother’s womb, mindful and aware.*";
P_HTM[152]="*Ayamettha dhammatā. (1)**This is normal in such a case.*";
P_HTM[153]="*Dhammatā esā, bhikkhave, yadā bodhisatto tusitā kāyā cavitvā mātukucchiṃ okkamati.**It’s normal that, when the being intent on awakening passes away from the host of Joyful Gods, he is conceived in his mother’s womb.*";
P_HTM[154]="*Atha sadevake loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya appamāṇo uḷāro obhāso pātubhavati atikkammeva devānaṃ devānubhāvaṃ.**And then—in this world with its gods, Māras and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, gods and humans—an immeasurable, magnificent light appears, surpassing the glory of the gods.*";
P_HTM[155]="*Yāpi tā lokantarikā aghā asaṃvutā andhakārā andhakāratimisā, yatthapime candimasūriyā evaṃmahiddhikā evaṃmahānubhāvā ābhāya nānubhonti, tatthapi appamāṇo uḷāro obhāso pātubhavati atikkammeva devānaṃ devānubhāvaṃ.**Even in the boundless desolation of interstellar space—so utterly dark that even the light of the moon and the sun, so mighty and powerful, makes no impression—an immeasurable, magnificent light appears, surpassing the glory of the gods.*";
P_HTM[156]="*Yepi tattha sattā upapannā, tepi tenobhāsena aññamaññaṃ sañjānanti: ‘aññepi kira, bho, santi sattā idhūpapannā’ti.**And the sentient beings reborn there recognize each other by that light: ‘So, it seems other sentient beings have been reborn here!’*";
P_HTM[157]="*Ayañca dasasahassī lokadhātu saṅkampati sampakampati sampavedhati. Appamāṇo ca uḷāro obhāso loke pātubhavati atikkammeva devānaṃ devānubhāvaṃ.**And this galaxy shakes and rocks and trembles. And an immeasurable, magnificent light appears in the world, surpassing the glory of the gods.*";
P_HTM[158]="*Ayamettha dhammatā. (2)**This is normal in such a case.*";
P_HTM[159]="*Dhammatā esā, bhikkhave, yadā bodhisatto mātukucchiṃ okkanto hoti, cattāro naṃ devaputtā catuddisaṃ rakkhāya upagacchanti: ‘mā naṃ bodhisattaṃ vā bodhisattamātaraṃ vā manusso vā amanusso vā koci vā viheṭhesī’ti.**It’s normal that, when the being intent on awakening is conceived in his mother’s belly, four gods approach to guard the four directions, so that no human or non-human or anyone at all shall harm the being intent on awakening or his mother.*";
P_HTM[160]="*Ayamettha dhammatā. (3)**This is normal in such a case.*";
P_HTM[161]="*Dhammatā esā, bhikkhave, yadā bodhisatto mātukucchiṃ okkanto hoti, pakatiyā sīlavatī bodhisattamātā hoti, viratā pāṇātipātā, viratā adinnādānā, viratā kāmesumicchācārā, viratā musāvādā, viratā surāmerayamajjappamādaṭṭhānā.**It’s normal that, when the being intent on awakening is conceived in his mother’s belly, she becomes naturally ethical. She refrains from killing living creatures, stealing, sexual misconduct, lying, and alcoholic drinks that cause negligence.*";
P_HTM[162]="*Ayamettha dhammatā. (4)**This is normal in such a case.*";
P_HTM[163]="*Dhammatā esā, bhikkhave, yadā bodhisatto mātukucchiṃ okkanto hoti, na bodhisattamātu purisesu mānasaṃ uppajjati kāmaguṇūpasaṃhitaṃ, anatikkamanīyā ca bodhisattamātā hoti kenaci purisena rattacittena.**It’s normal that, when the being intent on awakening is conceived in his mother’s belly, she no longer feels sexual desire for men, and she cannot be violated by a man of lustful intent.*";
P_HTM[164]="*Ayamettha dhammatā. (5)**This is normal in such a case.*";
P_HTM[165]="*Dhammatā esā, bhikkhave, yadā bodhisatto mātukucchiṃ okkanto hoti, lābhinī bodhisattamātā hoti pañcannaṃ kāmaguṇānaṃ. Sā pañcahi kāmaguṇehi samappitā samaṅgībhūtā paricāreti.**It’s normal that, when the being intent on awakening is conceived in his mother’s belly, she obtains the five kinds of sensual stimulation and amuses herself, supplied and provided with them.*";
P_HTM[166]="*Ayamettha dhammatā. (6)**This is normal in such a case.*";
P_HTM[167]="*Dhammatā esā, bhikkhave, yadā bodhisatto mātukucchiṃ okkanto hoti, na bodhisattamātu kocideva ābādho uppajjati. Sukhinī bodhisattamātā hoti akilantakāyā, bodhisattañca bodhisattamātā tirokucchigataṃ passati sabbaṅgapaccaṅgiṃ ahīnindriyaṃ.**It’s normal that, when the being intent on awakening is conceived in his mother’s belly, no afflictions beset her. She’s happy and free of bodily fatigue. And she sees the being intent on awakening in her womb, complete with all his various parts, not deficient in any faculty.*";
P_HTM[168]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, maṇi veḷuriyo subho jātimā aṭṭhaṃso suparikammakato accho vippasanno anāvilo sabbākārasampanno. Tatrāssa suttaṃ āvutaṃ nīlaṃ vā pītaṃ vā lohitaṃ vā odātaṃ vā paṇḍusuttaṃ vā.**Suppose there was a beryl gem that was naturally beautiful, eight-faceted, well-worked, transparent, clear, and unclouded, endowed with all good qualities. And it was strung with a thread of blue, yellow, red, white, or golden brown.*";
P_HTM[169]="*Tamenaṃ cakkhumā puriso hatthe karitvā paccavekkheyya: ‘ayaṃ kho maṇi veḷuriyo subho jātimā aṭṭhaṃso suparikammakato accho vippasanno anāvilo sabbākārasampanno. Tatridaṃ suttaṃ āvutaṃ nīlaṃ vā pītaṃ vā lohitaṃ vā odātaṃ vā paṇḍusuttaṃ vā’ti.**And someone with good eyesight were to take it in their hand and examine it: ‘This beryl gem is naturally beautiful, eight-faceted, well-worked, transparent, clear, and unclouded, endowed with all good qualities. And it’s strung with a thread of blue, yellow, red, white, or golden brown.’*";
P_HTM[170]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, yadā bodhisatto mātukucchiṃ okkanto hoti, na bodhisattamātu kocideva ābādho uppajjati, sukhinī bodhisattamātā hoti akilantakāyā, bodhisattañca bodhisattamātā tirokucchigataṃ passati sabbaṅgapaccaṅgiṃ ahīnindriyaṃ.**In the same way, when the being intent on awakening is conceived in his mother’s belly, no afflictions beset her. She’s happy and free of bodily fatigue. And she sees the being intent on awakening in her womb, complete with all his various parts, not deficient in any faculty.*";
P_HTM[171]="*Ayamettha dhammatā. (7)**This is normal in such a case.*";
P_HTM[172]="*Dhammatā esā, bhikkhave, sattāhajāte bodhisatte bodhisattamātā kālaṃ karoti tusitaṃ kāyaṃ upapajjati.**It’s normal that, seven days after the being intent on awakening is born, his mother passes away and is reborn in the host of Joyful Gods.*";
P_HTM[173]="*Ayamettha dhammatā. (8)**This is normal in such a case.*";
P_HTM[174]="*Dhammatā esā, bhikkhave, yathā aññā itthikā nava vā dasa vā māse gabbhaṃ kucchinā pariharitvā vijāyanti, na hevaṃ bodhisattaṃ bodhisattamātā vijāyati. Daseva māsāni bodhisattaṃ bodhisattamātā kucchinā pariharitvā vijāyati.**It’s normal that, while other women carry the infant in the womb for nine or ten months before giving birth, not so the mother of the being intent on awakening. She gives birth after exactly ten months.*";
P_HTM[175]="*Ayamettha dhammatā. (9)**This is normal in such a case.*";
P_HTM[176]="*Dhammatā esā, bhikkhave, yathā aññā itthikā nisinnā vā nipannā vā vijāyanti, na hevaṃ bodhisattaṃ bodhisattamātā vijāyati. Ṭhitāva bodhisattaṃ bodhisattamātā vijāyati.**It’s normal that, while other women give birth while sitting or lying down, not so the mother of the being intent on awakening. She only gives birth standing up.*";
P_HTM[177]="*Ayamettha dhammatā. (10)**This is normal in such a case.*";
P_HTM[178]="*Dhammatā esā, bhikkhave, yadā bodhisatto mātukucchimhā nikkhamati, devā paṭhamaṃ paṭiggaṇhanti, pacchā manussā.**It’s normal that, when the being intent on awakening emerges from his mother’s womb, gods receive him first, then humans.*";
P_HTM[179]="*Ayamettha dhammatā. (11)**This is normal in such a case.*";
P_HTM[180]="*Dhammatā esā, bhikkhave, yadā bodhisatto mātukucchimhā nikkhamati, appattova bodhisatto pathaviṃ hoti, cattāro naṃ devaputtā paṭiggahetvā mātu purato ṭhapenti: ‘attamanā, devi, hohi; mahesakkho te putto uppanno’ti.**It’s normal that, when the being intent on awakening emerges from his mother’s womb, before he reaches the ground, four gods receive him and place him before his mother, saying: ‘Rejoice, O Queen! An illustrious child is born to you.’*";
P_HTM[181]="*Ayamettha dhammatā. (12)**This is normal in such a case.*";
P_HTM[182]="*Dhammatā esā, bhikkhave, yadā bodhisatto mātukucchimhā nikkhamati, visadova nikkhamati amakkhito udena amakkhito semhena amakkhito ruhirena amakkhito kenaci asucinā suddho visado.**It’s normal that, when the being intent on awakening emerges from his mother’s womb, he emerges already clean, unsoiled by waters, mucus, blood, or any other kind of impurity, pure and clean.*";
P_HTM[183]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, maṇiratanaṃ kāsike vatthe nikkhittaṃ neva maṇiratanaṃ kāsikaṃ vatthaṃ makkheti, nāpi kāsikaṃ vatthaṃ maṇiratanaṃ makkheti.**Suppose a jewel-treasure was placed on a cloth from Kāsī. The jewel would not soil the cloth, nor would the cloth soil the jewel.*";
P_HTM[184]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[185]="*Ubhinnaṃ suddhattā.**Because of the cleanliness of them both.*";
P_HTM[186]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, yadā bodhisatto mātukucchimhā nikkhamati, visadova nikkhamati amakkhito, udena amakkhito semhena amakkhito ruhirena amakkhito kenaci asucinā suddho visado.**In the same way, when the being intent on awakening emerges from his mother’s womb, he emerges already clean, unsoiled by waters, mucus, blood, or any other kind of impurity, pure and clean.*";
P_HTM[187]="*Ayamettha dhammatā. (13)**This is normal in such a case.*";
P_HTM[188]="*Dhammatā esā, bhikkhave, yadā bodhisatto mātukucchimhā nikkhamati, dve udakassa dhārā antalikkhā pātubhavanti—ekā sītassa ekā uṇhassa yena bodhisattassa udakakiccaṃ karonti mātu ca.**It’s normal that, when the being intent on awakening emerges from his mother’s womb, two streams of water appear in the sky, one cool, one warm, for bathing the being intent on awakening and his mother.*";
P_HTM[189]="*Ayamettha dhammatā. (14)**This is normal in such a case.*";
P_HTM[190]="*Dhammatā esā, bhikkhave, sampatijāto bodhisatto samehi pādehi patiṭṭhahitvā uttarābhimukho sattapadavītihārena gacchati setamhi chatte anudhāriyamāne, sabbā ca disā anuviloketi, āsabhiṃ vācaṃ bhāsati ‘aggohamasmi lokassa, jeṭṭhohamasmi lokassa, seṭṭhohamasmi lokassa, ayamantimā jāti, natthi dāni punabbhavo’ti.**It’s normal that, as soon as he’s born, the being intent on awakening stands firm with his own feet on the ground. Facing north, he takes seven strides with a white parasol held above him, surveys all quarters, and makes this dramatic statement: ‘I am the foremost in the world! I am the eldest in the world! I am the best in the world! This is my last rebirth. Now there are no more future lives.’*";
P_HTM[191]="*Ayamettha dhammatā. (15)**This is normal in such a case.*";
P_HTM[192]="*Dhammatā esā, bhikkhave, yadā bodhisatto mātukucchimhā nikkhamati, atha sadevake loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya appamāṇo uḷāro obhāso pātubhavati, atikkammeva devānaṃ devānubhāvaṃ.**It’s normal that, when the being intent on awakening emerges from his mother’s womb, then—in this world with its gods, Māras and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, gods and humans—an immeasurable, magnificent light appears, surpassing the glory of the gods.*";
P_HTM[193]="*Yāpi tā lokantarikā aghā asaṃvutā andhakārā andhakāratimisā, yatthapime candimasūriyā evaṃmahiddhikā evaṃmahānubhāvā ābhāya nānubhonti, tatthapi appamāṇo uḷāro obhāso pātubhavati atikkammeva devānaṃ devānubhāvaṃ.**Even in the boundless desolation of interstellar space—so utterly dark that even the light of the moon and the sun, so mighty and powerful, makes no impression—an immeasurable, magnificent light appears, surpassing the glory of the gods.*";
P_HTM[194]="*Yepi tattha sattā upapannā, tepi tenobhāsena aññamaññaṃ sañjānanti: ‘aññepi kira, bho, santi sattā idhūpapannā’ti.**And the sentient beings reborn there recognize each other by that light: ‘So, it seems other sentient beings have been reborn here!’*";
P_HTM[195]="*Ayañca dasasahassī lokadhātu saṅkampati sampakampati sampavedhati appamāṇo ca uḷāro obhāso loke pātubhavati atikkammeva devānaṃ devānubhāvaṃ.**And this galaxy shakes and rocks and trembles. And an immeasurable, magnificent light appears in the world, surpassing the glory of the gods.*";
P_HTM[196]="*Ayamettha dhammatā. (16)**This is normal in such a case.*";
P_HTM[197]="*3. Dvattiṃsamahāpurisalakkhaṇā**3. The Thirty-Two Marks of a Great Man*";
P_HTM[198]="*Jāte kho pana, bhikkhave, vipassimhi kumāre bandhumato rañño paṭivedesuṃ:**When Prince Vipassī was born, they announced it to King Bandhumata,*";
P_HTM[199]="*‘putto te, deva, jāto, taṃ devo passatū’ti.**‘Sire, your son is born! Let your majesty examine him!’*";
P_HTM[200]="*Addasā kho, bhikkhave, bandhumā rājā vipassiṃ kumāraṃ, disvā nemitte brāhmaṇe āmantāpetvā etadavoca:**When the king had examined the prince, he had the brahmin soothsayers summoned and said to them,*";
P_HTM[201]="*‘passantu bhonto nemittā brāhmaṇā kumāran’ti.**‘Gentlemen, please examine the prince.’*";
P_HTM[202]="*Addasaṃsu kho, bhikkhave, nemittā brāhmaṇā vipassiṃ kumāraṃ, disvā bandhumantaṃ rājānaṃ etadavocuṃ:**When they had examined him they said to the king,*";
P_HTM[203]="*‘attamano, deva, hohi, mahesakkho te putto uppanno, lābhā te, mahārāja, suladdhaṃ te, mahārāja, yassa te kule evarūpo putto uppanno.**‘Rejoice, O King! An illustrious son is born to you. You are fortunate, so very fortunate, to have a son such as this born in this family!’*";
P_HTM[204]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro dvattiṃsamahāpurisalakkhaṇehi samannāgato, yehi samannāgatassa mahāpurisassa dveva gatiyo bhavanti anaññā.**For the prince has the thirty-two marks of a great man. A great man who possesses these has only two possible destinies, no other.*";
P_HTM[205]="*Sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī dhammiko dhammarājā cāturanto vijitāvī janapadatthāvariyappatto sattaratanasamannāgato.**If he stays at home he becomes a king, a wheel-turning monarch, a just and principled king. His dominion extends to all four sides, he achieves stability in the country, and he possesses the seven treasures.*";
P_HTM[206]="*Tassimāni sattaratanāni bhavanti.**He has the following seven treasures:*";
P_HTM[207]="*Seyyathidaṃ—cakkaratanaṃ hatthiratanaṃ assaratanaṃ maṇiratanaṃ itthiratanaṃ gahapatiratanaṃ pariṇāyakaratanameva sattamaṃ.**the wheel, the elephant, the horse, the jewel, the woman, the treasurer, and the counselor as the seventh treasure.*";
P_HTM[208]="*Parosahassaṃ kho panassa puttā bhavanti sūrā vīraṅgarūpā parasenappamaddanā.**He has over a thousand sons who are valiant and heroic, crushing the armies of his enemies.*";
P_HTM[209]="*So imaṃ pathaviṃ sāgarapariyantaṃ adaṇḍena asatthena dhammena abhivijiya ajjhāvasati.**After conquering this land girt by sea, he reigns by principle, without rod or sword.*";
P_HTM[210]="*Sace kho pana agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati, arahaṃ hoti sammāsambuddho loke vivaṭacchado.**But if he goes forth from the lay life to homelessness, he becomes a perfected one, a fully awakened Buddha, who draws back the veil from the world.*";
P_HTM[211]="*Katamehi cāyaṃ, deva, kumāro dvattiṃsamahāpurisalakkhaṇehi samannāgato, yehi samannāgatassa mahāpurisassa dveva gatiyo bhavanti anaññā.**And what are the marks which he possesses?*";
P_HTM[212]="*Sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī dhammiko dhammarājā cāturanto vijitāvī janapadatthāvariyappatto sattaratanasamannāgato.* **";
P_HTM[213]="*Tassimāni sattaratanāni bhavanti.* **";
P_HTM[214]="*Seyyathidaṃ—cakkaratanaṃ hatthiratanaṃ assaratanaṃ maṇiratanaṃ itthiratanaṃ gahapatiratanaṃ pariṇāyakaratanameva sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[215]="*Parosahassaṃ kho panassa puttā bhavanti sūrā vīraṅgarūpā parasenappamaddanā.* **";
P_HTM[216]="*So imaṃ pathaviṃ sāgarapariyantaṃ adaṇḍena asatthena dhammena abhivijiya ajjhāvasati.**After conquering this land girt by sea, he reigns by principle, without rod or sword.*";
P_HTM[217]="*Sace kho pana agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati, arahaṃ hoti sammāsambuddho loke vivaṭacchado. Ayañhi, deva, kumāro suppatiṭṭhitapādo. Yaṃ pāyaṃ, deva, kumāro suppatiṭṭhitapādo. Idampissa mahāpurisassa mahāpurisalakkhaṇaṃ bhavati. (1)**He has well-planted feet.*";
P_HTM[218]="*Imassa, deva, kumārassa heṭṭhā pādatalesu cakkāni jātāni sahassārāni sanemikāni sanābhikāni sabbākāraparipūrāni. Yampi imassa, deva, kumārassa heṭṭhā pādatalesu cakkāni jātāni sahassārāni sanemikāni sanābhikāni sabbākāraparipūrāni, idampissa mahāpurisassa mahāpurisalakkhaṇaṃ bhavati. (2)**On the soles of his feet there are thousand-spoked wheels, with rims and hubs, complete in every detail.*";
P_HTM[219]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro āyatapaṇhī … pe … (3)**He has projecting heels.*";
P_HTM[220]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro dīghaṅgulī … pe … (4)**He has long fingers.*";
P_HTM[221]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro mudutalunahatthapādo … pe … (5)**His hands and feet are tender.*";
P_HTM[222]="*Ayañhi, deva kumāro jālahatthapādo … pe … (6)**His hands and feet cling gracefully.*";
P_HTM[223]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro ussaṅkhapādo … pe … (7)**His feet are arched.*";
P_HTM[224]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro eṇijaṅgho … pe … (8)**His calves are like those of an antelope.*";
P_HTM[225]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro ṭhitakova anonamanto ubhohi pāṇitalehi jaṇṇukāni parimasati parimajjati … pe … (9)**When standing upright and not bending over, the palms of both hands touch the knees.*";
P_HTM[226]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro kosohitavatthaguyho … pe … (10)**His private parts are retracted.*";
P_HTM[227]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro suvaṇṇavaṇṇo kañcanasannibhattaco … pe … (11)**He is gold colored; his skin has a golden sheen.*";
P_HTM[228]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro sukhumacchavī; sukhumattā chaviyā rajojallaṃ kāye na upalimpati … pe … (12)**He has delicate skin, so delicate that dust and dirt don’t stick to his body.*";
P_HTM[229]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro ekekalomo; ekekāni lomāni lomakūpesu jātāni … pe … (13)**His hairs grow one per pore.*";
P_HTM[230]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro uddhaggalomo; uddhaggāni lomāni jātāni nīlāni añjanavaṇṇāni kuṇḍalāvaṭṭāni dakkhiṇāvaṭṭakajātāni … pe … (14)**His hairs stand up; they’re blue-black and curl clockwise.*";
P_HTM[231]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro brahmujugatto … pe … (15)**His body is as straight as Brahmā’s.*";
P_HTM[232]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro sattussado … pe … (16)**He has bulging muscles in seven places.*";
P_HTM[233]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro sīhapubbaddhakāyo … pe … (17)**His chest is like that of a lion.*";
P_HTM[234]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro citantaraṃso … pe … (18)**The gap between the shoulder-blades is filled in.*";
P_HTM[235]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro nigrodhaparimaṇḍalo yāvatakvassa kāyo tāvatakvassa byāmo, yāvatakvassa byāmo, tāvatakvassa kāyo … pe … (19)**He has the proportional circumference of a banyan tree: the span of his arms equals the height of his body.*";
P_HTM[236]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro samavaṭṭakkhandho … pe … (20)**His torso is cylindrical.*";
P_HTM[237]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro rasaggasaggī … pe … (21)**He has an excellent sense of taste.*";
P_HTM[238]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro sīhahanu … pe … (22)**His jaw is like that of a lion.*";
P_HTM[239]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro cattālīsadanto … pe … (23)**He has forty teeth.*";
P_HTM[240]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro samadanto … pe … (24)**His teeth are even.*";
P_HTM[241]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro aviraḷadanto … pe … (25)**His teeth have no gaps.*";
P_HTM[242]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro susukkadāṭho … pe … (26)**His teeth are perfectly white.*";
P_HTM[243]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro pahūtajivho … pe … (27)**He has a large tongue.*";
P_HTM[244]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro brahmassaro karavīkabhāṇī … pe … (28)**He has the voice of Brahmā, like a cuckoo’s call.*";
P_HTM[245]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro abhinīlanetto … pe … (29)**His eyes are deep blue.*";
P_HTM[246]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro gopakhumo … pe … (30)**He has eyelashes like a cow’s.*";
P_HTM[247]="*Imassa, deva, kumārassa uṇṇā bhamukantare jātā odātā mudutūlasannibhā. Yampi imassa, deva, kumārassa uṇṇā bhamukantare jātā odātā mudutūlasannibhā, idampimassa mahāpurisassa mahāpurisalakkhaṇaṃ bhavati. (31)**Between his eyebrows there grows a tuft, soft and white like cotton-wool.*";
P_HTM[248]="*Ayañhi, deva, kumāro uṇhīsasīso. Yaṃ pāyaṃ, deva, kumāro uṇhīsasīso, idampissa mahāpurisassa mahāpurisalakkhaṇaṃ bhavati. (32)**His head is shaped like a turban.*";
P_HTM[249]="*Imehi kho ayaṃ, deva, kumāro dvattiṃsamahāpurisalakkhaṇehi samannāgato, yehi samannāgatassa mahāpurisassa dveva gatiyo bhavanti anaññā.**These are the thirty-two marks of a great man that the prince has. A great man who possesses these has only two possible destinies, no other.*";
P_HTM[250]="*Sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī dhammiko dhammarājā cāturanto vijitāvī janapadatthāvariyappatto sattaratanasamannāgato.**If he stays at home he becomes a king, a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[251]="*Tassimāni sattaratanāni bhavanti.* **";
P_HTM[252]="*Seyyathidaṃ—cakkaratanaṃ hatthiratanaṃ assaratanaṃ maṇiratanaṃ itthiratanaṃ gahapatiratanaṃ pariṇāyakaratanameva sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[253]="*Parosahassaṃ kho panassa puttā bhavanti sūrā vīraṅgarūpā parasenappamaddanā.* **";
P_HTM[254]="*So imaṃ pathaviṃ sāgarapariyantaṃ adaṇḍena asatthena dhammena abhivijiya ajjhāvasati.* **";
P_HTM[255]="*Sace kho pana agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati, arahaṃ hoti sammāsambuddho loke vivaṭacchado’ti.**But if he goes forth from the lay life to homelessness, he becomes a perfected one, a fully awakened Buddha, who draws back the veil from the world.’*";
P_HTM[256]="*4. Vipassīsamaññā**4. How He Came to be Known as Vipassī*";
P_HTM[257]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, bandhumā rājā nemitte brāhmaṇe ahatehi vatthehi acchādāpetvā sabbakāmehi santappesi.**Then King Bandhuma had the brahmin soothsayers dressed in fresh clothes and satisfied all their needs.*";
P_HTM[258]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, bandhumā rājā vipassissa kumārassa dhātiyo upaṭṭhāpesi.**Then the king appointed nurses for Prince Vipassī.*";
P_HTM[259]="*Aññā khīraṃ pāyenti, aññā nhāpenti, aññā dhārenti, aññā aṅkena pariharanti.**Some suckled him, some bathed him, some held him, and some carried him on their hip.*";
P_HTM[260]="*Jātassa kho pana, bhikkhave, vipassissa kumārassa setacchattaṃ dhārayittha divā ceva rattiñca:**From when he was born, a white parasol was held over him night and day, with the thought,*";
P_HTM[261]="*‘mā naṃ sītaṃ vā uṇhaṃ vā tiṇaṃ vā rajo vā ussāvo vā bādhayitthā’ti.**‘Don’t let cold, heat, grass, dust, or damp bother him.’*";
P_HTM[262]="*Jāto kho pana, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro bahuno janassa piyo ahosi manāpo.**He was dear and beloved by many people,*";
P_HTM[263]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, uppalaṃ vā padumaṃ vā puṇḍarīkaṃ vā bahuno janassa piyaṃ manāpaṃ;**like a blue water lily, or a pink or white lotus.*";
P_HTM[264]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro bahuno janassa piyo ahosi manāpo.* **";
P_HTM[265]="*Svāssudaṃ aṅkeneva aṅkaṃ parihariyati.**He was always passed from hip to hip.*";
P_HTM[266]="*Jāto kho pana, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro mañjussaro ca ahosi vaggussaro ca madhurassaro ca pemaniyassaro ca.**From when he was born, his voice was charming, graceful, sweet, and lovely.*";
P_HTM[267]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, himavante pabbate karavīkā nāma sakuṇajāti mañjussarā ca vaggussarā ca madhurassarā ca pemaniyassarā ca;**It was as sweet as the song of a cuckoo-bird found in the Himalayas.*";
P_HTM[268]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro mañjussaro ca ahosi vaggussaro ca madhurassaro ca pemaniyassaro ca.* **";
P_HTM[269]="*Jātassa kho pana, bhikkhave, vipassissa kumārassa kammavipākajaṃ dibbacakkhu pāturahosi yena sudaṃ samantā yojanaṃ passati divā ceva rattiñca.**From when he was born, Prince Vipassī had the power of clairvoyance which manifested as a result of past deeds. He could see for a league all around both by day and by night.*";
P_HTM[270]="*Jāto kho pana, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro animisanto pekkhati seyyathāpi devā tāvatiṃsā.**And he was unblinkingly watchful, like the gods of the Thirty-Three.*";
P_HTM[271]="*‘Animisanto kumāro pekkhatī’ti kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa kumārassa ‘vipassī vipassī’ tveva samaññā udapādi.**And because it was said that he was unblinkingly watchful, he came to be known as ‘Vipassī’.*";
P_HTM[272]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, bandhumā rājā atthakaraṇe nisinno vipassiṃ kumāraṃ aṅke nisīdāpetvā atthe anusāsati.**Then while King Bandhuma was sitting in judgment, he’d sit Prince Vipassī in his lap and explain the case to him.*";
P_HTM[273]="*Tatra sudaṃ, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro pituaṅke nisinno viceyya viceyya atthe panāyati ñāyena.**And sitting there in his father’s lap, Vipassī would thoroughly consider the case and draw a conclusion using a logical procedure.*";
P_HTM[274]="*Viceyya viceyya kumāro atthe panāyati ñāyenāti kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa kumārassa bhiyyoso mattāya ‘vipassī vipassī’ tveva samaññā udapādi.**So this was all the more reason for him to be known as ‘Vipassī’.*";
P_HTM[275]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, bandhumā rājā vipassissa kumārassa tayo pāsāde kārāpesi, ekaṃ vassikaṃ ekaṃ hemantikaṃ ekaṃ gimhikaṃ;**Then King Bandhuma had three stilt longhouses built for him—one for the winter, one for the summer, and one for the rainy season,*";
P_HTM[276]="*pañca kāmaguṇāni upaṭṭhāpesi.**and provided him with the five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[277]="*Tatra sudaṃ, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro vassike pāsāde cattāro māse nippurisehi tūriyehi paricārayamāno na heṭṭhāpāsādaṃ orohatīti.**Prince Vipassī stayed in a stilt longhouse without coming downstairs for the four months of the rainy season, where he was entertained by musicians—none of them men.*";
P_HTM[278]="*Paṭhamabhāṇavāro.* **";
P_HTM[279]="*5. Jiṇṇapurisa**5. The Old Man*";
P_HTM[280]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro bahūnaṃ vassānaṃ bahūnaṃ vassasatānaṃ bahūnaṃ vassasahassānaṃ accayena sārathiṃ āmantesi:**Then, after many thousand years had passed, Prince Vipassī addressed his charioteer,*";
P_HTM[281]="*‘yojehi, samma sārathi, bhaddāni bhaddāni yānāni uyyānabhūmiṃ gacchāma subhūmidassanāyā’ti.**‘My dear charioteer, harness the finest chariots. We will go to a park and see the scenery.’*";
P_HTM[282]="*‘Evaṃ, devā’ti kho, bhikkhave, sārathi vipassissa kumārassa paṭissutvā bhaddāni bhaddāni yānāni yojetvā vipassissa kumārassa paṭivedesi:**‘Yes, sir,’ replied the charioteer. He harnessed the chariots and informed the prince,*";
P_HTM[283]="*‘yuttāni kho te, deva, bhaddāni bhaddāni yānāni,**‘Sire, the finest chariots are harnessed.*";
P_HTM[284]="*yassadāni kālaṃ maññasī’ti.**Please go at your convenience.’*";
P_HTM[285]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro bhaddaṃ bhaddaṃ yānaṃ abhiruhitvā bhaddehi bhaddehi yānehi uyyānabhūmiṃ niyyāsi.**Then Prince Vipassī mounted a fine carriage and, along with other fine carriages, set out for the park.*";
P_HTM[286]="*Addasā kho, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro uyyānabhūmiṃ niyyanto purisaṃ jiṇṇaṃ gopānasivaṅkaṃ bhoggaṃ daṇḍaparāyanaṃ pavedhamānaṃ gacchantaṃ āturaṃ gatayobbanaṃ.**Along the way he saw an elderly man, bent double, crooked, leaning on a staff, trembling as he walked, ailing, past his prime.*";
P_HTM[287]="*Disvā sārathiṃ āmantesi:**He addressed his charioteer,*";
P_HTM[288]="*‘ayaṃ pana, samma sārathi, puriso kiṃkato?**‘My dear charioteer, what has that man done?*";
P_HTM[289]="*Kesāpissa na yathā aññesaṃ, kāyopissa na yathā aññesan’ti.**For his hair and his body are unlike those of other men.’*";
P_HTM[290]="*‘Eso kho, deva, jiṇṇo nāmā’ti.**‘That, Your Majesty, is called an old man.’*";
P_HTM[291]="*‘Kiṃ paneso, samma sārathi, jiṇṇo nāmā’ti?**‘But why is he called an old man?’*";
P_HTM[292]="*‘Eso kho, deva, jiṇṇo nāma. Na dāni tena ciraṃ jīvitabbaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**‘He’s called an old man because now he has not long to live.’*";
P_HTM[293]="*‘Kiṃ pana, samma sārathi, ahampi jarādhammo, jaraṃ anatīto’ti?**‘But my dear charioteer, am I liable to grow old? Am I not exempt from old age?’*";
P_HTM[294]="*‘Tvañca, deva, mayañcamha sabbe jarādhammā, jaraṃ anatītā’ti.**‘Everyone is liable to grow old, Your Majesty, including you. No-one is exempt from old age.’*";
P_HTM[295]="*‘Tena hi, samma sārathi, alaṃ dānajja uyyānabhūmiyā. Itova antepuraṃ paccaniyyāhī’ti.**‘Well then, my dear charioteer, that’s enough of the park for today. Let’s return to the royal compound.’*";
P_HTM[296]="*‘Evaṃ, devā’ti kho, bhikkhave, sārathi vipassissa kumārassa paṭissutvā tatova antepuraṃ paccaniyyāsi.**‘Yes, Your Majesty,’ replied the charioteer and did so.*";
P_HTM[297]="*Tatra sudaṃ, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro antepuraṃ gato dukkhī dummano pajjhāyati:**Back at the royal compound, the prince brooded, miserable and sad:*";
P_HTM[298]="*‘dhiratthu kira, bho, jāti nāma, yatra hi nāma jātassa jarā paññāyissatī’ti.**‘Damn this thing called rebirth, since old age will come to anyone who’s born.’*";
P_HTM[299]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, bandhumā rājā sārathiṃ āmantāpetvā etadavoca:**Then King Bandhuma summoned the charioteer and said,*";
P_HTM[300]="*‘kacci, samma sārathi, kumāro uyyānabhūmiyā abhiramittha? Kacci, samma sārathi, kumāro uyyānabhūmiyā attamano ahosī’ti?**‘My dear charioteer, I hope the prince enjoyed himself at the park? I hope he was happy there?’*";
P_HTM[301]="*‘Na kho, deva, kumāro uyyānabhūmiyā abhiramittha, na kho, deva, kumāro uyyānabhūmiyā attamano ahosī’ti.**‘No, Your Majesty, the prince didn’t enjoy himself at the park.’*";
P_HTM[302]="*‘Kiṃ pana, samma sārathi, addasa kumāro uyyānabhūmiṃ niyyanto’ti?**‘But what did he see on the way to the park?’*";
P_HTM[303]="*‘Addasā kho, deva, kumāro uyyānabhūmiṃ niyyanto purisaṃ jiṇṇaṃ gopānasivaṅkaṃ bhoggaṃ daṇḍaparāyanaṃ pavedhamānaṃ gacchantaṃ āturaṃ gatayobbanaṃ.**And the charioteer told the king about seeing the old man and the prince’s reaction.*";
P_HTM[304]="*Disvā maṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[305]="*“ayaṃ pana, samma sārathi, puriso kiṅkato, kesāpissa na yathā aññesaṃ, kāyopissa na yathā aññesan”ti?* **";
P_HTM[306]="*“Eso kho, deva, jiṇṇo nāmā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[307]="*“Kiṃ paneso, samma sārathi, jiṇṇo nāmā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[308]="*“Eso kho, deva, jiṇṇo nāma na dāni tena ciraṃ jīvitabbaṃ bhavissatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[309]="*“Kiṃ pana, samma sārathi, ahampi jarādhammo, jaraṃ anatīto”ti?* **";
P_HTM[310]="*“Tvañca, deva, mayañcamha sabbe jarādhammā, jaraṃ anatītā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[311]="*“Tena hi, samma sārathi, alaṃ dānajja uyyānabhūmiyā, itova antepuraṃ paccaniyyāhī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[312]="*“Evaṃ, devā”ti kho ahaṃ, deva, vipassissa kumārassa paṭissutvā tatova antepuraṃ paccaniyyāsiṃ.* **";
P_HTM[313]="*So kho, deva, kumāro antepuraṃ gato dukkhī dummano pajjhāyati:* **";
P_HTM[314]="*“dhiratthu kira, bho, jāti nāma, yatra hi nāma jātassa jarā paññāyissatī”’ti.* **";
P_HTM[315]="*6. Byādhitapurisa**6. The Sick Man*";
P_HTM[316]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, bandhumassa rañño etadahosi:**Then King Bandhuma thought,*";
P_HTM[317]="*‘Mā heva kho vipassī kumāro na rajjaṃ kāresi, mā heva vipassī kumāro agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbaji, mā heva nemittānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ saccaṃ assa vacanan’ti.**‘Prince Vipassī must not renounce the throne. He must not go forth from the lay life to homelessness. And the words of the brahmin soothsayers must not come true.’*";
P_HTM[318]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, bandhumā rājā vipassissa kumārassa bhiyyoso mattāya pañca kāmaguṇāni upaṭṭhāpesi:**To this end he provided the prince with even more of the five kinds of sensual stimulation,*";
P_HTM[319]="*‘yathā vipassī kumāro rajjaṃ kareyya, yathā vipassī kumāro na agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajeyya, yathā nemittānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ micchā assa vacanan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[320]="*Tatra sudaṃ, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro pañcahi kāmaguṇehi samappito samaṅgībhūto paricāreti.**with which the prince amused himself.*";
P_HTM[321]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro bahūnaṃ vassānaṃ … pe …**Then, after many thousand years had passed, Prince Vipassī had his charioteer drive him to the park once more.*";
P_HTM[322]="*Addasā kho, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro uyyānabhūmiṃ niyyanto purisaṃ ābādhikaṃ dukkhitaṃ bāḷhagilānaṃ sake muttakarīse palipannaṃ semānaṃ aññehi vuṭṭhāpiyamānaṃ aññehi saṃvesiyamānaṃ.**Along the way he saw a man who was ill, suffering, gravely ill, collapsed in his own urine and feces, being picked up by some and put down by others.*";
P_HTM[323]="*Disvā sārathiṃ āmantesi:**He addressed his charioteer,*";
P_HTM[324]="*‘ayaṃ pana, samma sārathi, puriso kiṃkato?**‘My dear charioteer, what has that man done?*";
P_HTM[325]="*Akkhīnipissa na yathā aññesaṃ, saropissa na yathā aññesan’ti?**For his eyes and his voice are unlike those of other men.’*";
P_HTM[326]="*‘Eso kho, deva, byādhito nāmā’ti.**‘That, Your Majesty, is called a sick man.’*";
P_HTM[327]="*‘Kiṃ paneso, samma sārathi, byādhito nāmā’ti?**‘But why is he called a sick man?’*";
P_HTM[328]="*‘Eso kho, deva, byādhito nāma appeva nāma tamhā ābādhā vuṭṭhaheyyā’ti.**‘He’s called an sick man; hopefully he will recover from that illness.’*";
P_HTM[329]="*‘Kiṃ pana, samma sārathi, ahampi byādhidhammo, byādhiṃ anatīto’ti?**‘But my dear charioteer, am I liable to fall sick? Am I not exempt from sickness?’*";
P_HTM[330]="*‘Tvañca, deva, mayañcamha sabbe byādhidhammā, byādhiṃ anatītā’ti.**‘Everyone is liable to fall sick, Your Majesty, including you. No-one is exempt from sickness.’*";
P_HTM[331]="*‘Tena hi, samma sārathi, alaṃ dānajja uyyānabhūmiyā, itova antepuraṃ paccaniyyāhī’ti.**‘Well then, my dear charioteer, that’s enough of the park for today. Let’s return to the royal compound.’*";
P_HTM[332]="*‘Evaṃ, devā’ti kho, bhikkhave, sārathi vipassissa kumārassa paṭissutvā tatova antepuraṃ paccaniyyāsi.**‘Yes, Your Majesty,’ replied the charioteer and did so.*";
P_HTM[333]="*Tatra sudaṃ, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro antepuraṃ gato dukkhī dummano pajjhāyati:**Back at the royal compound, the prince brooded, miserable and sad:*";
P_HTM[334]="*‘dhiratthu kira, bho, jāti nāma, yatra hi nāma jātassa jarā paññāyissati, byādhi paññāyissatī’ti.**‘Damn this thing called rebirth, since old age and sickness will come to anyone who’s born.’*";
P_HTM[335]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, bandhumā rājā sārathiṃ āmantāpetvā etadavoca:**Then King Bandhuma summoned the charioteer and said,*";
P_HTM[336]="*‘kacci, samma sārathi, kumāro uyyānabhūmiyā abhiramittha, kacci, samma sārathi, kumāro uyyānabhūmiyā attamano ahosī’ti?**‘My dear charioteer, I hope the prince enjoyed himself at the park? I hope he was happy there?’*";
P_HTM[337]="*‘Na kho, deva, kumāro uyyānabhūmiyā abhiramittha, na kho, deva, kumāro uyyānabhūmiyā attamano ahosī’ti.**‘No, Your Majesty, the prince didn’t enjoy himself at the park.’*";
P_HTM[338]="*‘Kiṃ pana, samma sārathi, addasa kumāro uyyānabhūmiṃ niyyanto’ti?**‘But what did he see on the way to the park?’*";
P_HTM[339]="*‘Addasā kho, deva, kumāro uyyānabhūmiṃ niyyanto purisaṃ ābādhikaṃ dukkhitaṃ bāḷhagilānaṃ sake muttakarīse palipannaṃ semānaṃ aññehi vuṭṭhāpiyamānaṃ aññehi saṃvesiyamānaṃ.**And the charioteer told the king about seeing the sick man and the prince’s reaction.*";
P_HTM[340]="*Disvā maṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[341]="*“ayaṃ pana, samma sārathi, puriso kiṅkato, akkhīnipissa na yathā aññesaṃ, saropissa na yathā aññesan”ti?* **";
P_HTM[342]="*“Eso kho, deva, byādhito nāmā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[343]="*“Kiṃ paneso, samma sārathi, byādhito nāmā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[344]="*“Eso kho, deva, byādhito nāma appeva nāma tamhā ābādhā vuṭṭhaheyyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[345]="*“Kiṃ pana, samma sārathi, ahampi byādhidhammo, byādhiṃ anatīto”ti?* **";
P_HTM[346]="*“Tvañca, deva, mayañcamha sabbe byādhidhammā, byādhiṃ anatītā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[347]="*“Tena hi, samma sārathi, alaṃ dānajja uyyānabhūmiyā, itova antepuraṃ paccaniyyāhī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[348]="*“Evaṃ, devā”ti kho ahaṃ, deva, vipassissa kumārassa paṭissutvā tatova antepuraṃ paccaniyyāsiṃ.* **";
P_HTM[349]="*So kho, deva, kumāro antepuraṃ gato dukkhī dummano pajjhāyati:* **";
P_HTM[350]="*“dhiratthu kira, bho, jāti nāma, yatra hi nāma jātassa jarā paññāyissati, byādhi paññāyissatī”’ti.* **";
P_HTM[351]="*7. Kālaṅkatapurisa**7. The Dead Man*";
P_HTM[352]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, bandhumassa rañño etadahosi:**Then King Bandhuma thought,*";
P_HTM[353]="*‘mā heva kho vipassī kumāro na rajjaṃ kāresi, mā heva vipassī kumāro agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbaji, mā heva nemittānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ saccaṃ assa vacanan’ti.**‘Prince Vipassī must not renounce the throne. He must not go forth from the lay life to homelessness. And the words of the brahmin soothsayers must not come true.’*";
P_HTM[354]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, bandhumā rājā vipassissa kumārassa bhiyyoso mattāya pañca kāmaguṇāni upaṭṭhāpesi:**To this end he provided the prince with even more of the five kinds of sensual stimulation,*";
P_HTM[355]="*‘yathā vipassī kumāro rajjaṃ kareyya, yathā vipassī kumāro na agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajeyya, yathā nemittānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ micchā assa vacanan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[356]="*Tatra sudaṃ, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro pañcahi kāmaguṇehi samappito samaṅgībhūto paricāreti.**with which the prince amused himself.*";
P_HTM[357]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro bahūnaṃ vassānaṃ … pe …**Then, after many thousand years had passed, Prince Vipassī had his charioteer drive him to the park once more.*";
P_HTM[358]="*Addasā kho, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro uyyānabhūmiṃ niyyanto mahājanakāyaṃ sannipatitaṃ nānārattānañca dussānaṃ vilātaṃ kayiramānaṃ.**Along the way he saw a large crowd gathered making a bier out of garments of different colors.*";
P_HTM[359]="*Disvā sārathiṃ āmantesi:**He addressed his charioteer,*";
P_HTM[360]="*‘kiṃ nu kho so, samma sārathi, mahājanakāyo sannipatito nānārattānañca dussānaṃ vilātaṃ kayiratī’ti?**‘My dear charioteer, why is that crowd making a bier?’*";
P_HTM[361]="*‘Eso kho, deva, kālaṅkato nāmā’ti.**‘That, Your Majesty, is for someone who’s departed.’*";
P_HTM[362]="*‘Tena hi, samma sārathi, yena so kālaṅkato tena rathaṃ pesehī’ti.**‘Well then, drive the chariot up to the departed.’*";
P_HTM[363]="*‘Evaṃ, devā’ti kho, bhikkhave, sārathi vipassissa kumārassa paṭissutvā yena so kālaṅkato tena rathaṃ pesesi.**‘Yes, Your Majesty,’ replied the charioteer, and did so.*";
P_HTM[364]="*Addasā kho, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro petaṃ kālaṅkataṃ, disvā sārathiṃ āmantesi:**When the prince saw the corpse of the departed, he addressed the charioteer,*";
P_HTM[365]="*‘kiṃ panāyaṃ, samma sārathi, kālaṅkato nāmā’ti?**‘But why is he called departed?’*";
P_HTM[366]="*‘Eso kho, deva, kālaṅkato nāma. Na dāni taṃ dakkhanti mātā vā pitā vā aññe vā ñātisālohitā, sopi na dakkhissati mātaraṃ vā pitaraṃ vā aññe vā ñātisālohite’ti.**‘He’s called departed because now his mother and father, his relatives and kin shall see him no more, and he shall never again see them.’*";
P_HTM[367]="*‘Kiṃ pana, samma sārathi, ahampi maraṇadhammo maraṇaṃ anatīto;**‘But my dear charioteer, am I liable to die? Am I not exempt from death?*";
P_HTM[368]="*mampi na dakkhanti devo vā devī vā aññe vā ñātisālohitā;**Will the king and queen and my other relatives and kin see me no more?*";
P_HTM[369]="*ahampi na dakkhissāmi devaṃ vā deviṃ vā aññe vā ñātisālohite’ti?**And shall I never again see them?’*";
P_HTM[370]="*‘Tvañca, deva, mayañcamha sabbe maraṇadhammā maraṇaṃ anatītā;**‘Everyone is liable to die, Your Majesty, including you. No-one is exempt from death.*";
P_HTM[371]="*tampi na dakkhanti devo vā devī vā aññe vā ñātisālohitā;**The king and queen and your other relatives and kin shall see you no more,*";
P_HTM[372]="*tvampi na dakkhissasi devaṃ vā deviṃ vā aññe vā ñātisālohite’ti.**and you shall never again see them.’*";
P_HTM[373]="*‘Tena hi, samma sārathi, alaṃ dānajja uyyānabhūmiyā, itova antepuraṃ paccaniyyāhī’ti.**‘Well then, my dear charioteer, that’s enough of the park for today. Let’s return to the royal compound.’*";
P_HTM[374]="*‘Evaṃ, devā’ti kho, bhikkhave, sārathi vipassissa kumārassa paṭissutvā tatova antepuraṃ paccaniyyāsi.**‘Yes, Your Majesty,’ replied the charioteer and did so.*";
P_HTM[375]="*Tatra sudaṃ, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro antepuraṃ gato dukkhī dummano pajjhāyati:**Back at the royal compound, the prince brooded, miserable and sad:*";
P_HTM[376]="*‘dhiratthu kira, bho, jāti nāma, yatra hi nāma jātassa jarā paññāyissati, byādhi paññāyissati, maraṇaṃ paññāyissatī’ti.**‘Damn this thing called rebirth, since old age, sickness, and death will come to anyone who’s born.’*";
P_HTM[377]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, bandhumā rājā sārathiṃ āmantāpetvā etadavoca:**Then King Bandhuma summoned the charioteer and said,*";
P_HTM[378]="*‘kacci, samma sārathi, kumāro uyyānabhūmiyā abhiramittha, kacci, samma sārathi, kumāro uyyānabhūmiyā attamano ahosī’ti?**‘My dear charioteer, I hope the prince enjoyed himself at the park? I hope he was happy there?’*";
P_HTM[379]="*‘Na kho, deva, kumāro uyyānabhūmiyā abhiramittha, na kho, deva, kumāro uyyānabhūmiyā attamano ahosī’ti.**‘No, Your Majesty, the prince didn’t enjoy himself at the park.’*";
P_HTM[380]="*‘Kiṃ pana, samma sārathi, addasa kumāro uyyānabhūmiṃ niyyanto’ti?**‘But what did he see on the way to the park?’*";
P_HTM[381]="*‘Addasā kho, deva, kumāro uyyānabhūmiṃ niyyanto mahājanakāyaṃ sannipatitaṃ nānārattānañca dussānaṃ vilātaṃ kayiramānaṃ.**And the charioteer told the king about seeing the dead man and the prince’s reaction.*";
P_HTM[382]="*Disvā maṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[383]="*“kiṃ nu kho so, samma sārathi, mahājanakāyo sannipatito nānārattānañca dussānaṃ vilātaṃ kayiratī”ti?* **";
P_HTM[384]="*“Eso kho, deva, kālaṅkato nāmā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[385]="*“Tena hi, samma sārathi, yena so kālaṅkato tena rathaṃ pesehī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[386]="*“Evaṃ, devā”ti kho ahaṃ, deva, vipassissa kumārassa paṭissutvā yena so kālaṅkato tena rathaṃ pesesiṃ.* **";
P_HTM[387]="*Addasā kho, deva, kumāro petaṃ kālaṅkataṃ, disvā maṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[388]="*“kiṃ panāyaṃ, samma sārathi, kālaṅkato nāmā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[389]="*“Eso kho, deva, kālaṅkato nāma.* **";
P_HTM[390]="*Na dāni taṃ dakkhanti mātā vā pitā vā aññe vā ñātisālohitā, sopi na dakkhissati mātaraṃ vā pitaraṃ vā aññe vā ñātisālohite”ti.* **";
P_HTM[391]="*“Kiṃ pana, samma sārathi, ahampi maraṇadhammo maraṇaṃ anatīto;* **";
P_HTM[392]="*mampi na dakkhanti devo vā devī vā aññe vā ñātisālohitā;* **";
P_HTM[393]="*ahampi na dakkhissāmi devaṃ vā deviṃ vā aññe vā ñātisālohite”ti?* **";
P_HTM[394]="*“Tvañca, deva, mayañcamha sabbe maraṇadhammā maraṇaṃ anatītā;* **";
P_HTM[395]="*tampi na dakkhanti devo vā devī vā aññe vā ñātisālohitā, tvampi na dakkhissasi devaṃ vā deviṃ vā aññe vā ñātisālohite”ti.* **";
P_HTM[396]="*“Tena hi, samma sārathi, alaṃ dānajja uyyānabhūmiyā, itova antepuraṃ paccaniyyāhī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[397]="*“Evaṃ, devā”ti kho ahaṃ, deva, vipassissa kumārassa paṭissutvā tatova antepuraṃ paccaniyyāsiṃ.* **";
P_HTM[398]="*So kho, deva, kumāro antepuraṃ gato dukkhī dummano pajjhāyati:* **";
P_HTM[399]="*“dhiratthu kira, bho, jāti nāma, yatra hi nāma jātassa jarā paññāyissati, byādhi paññāyissati, maraṇaṃ paññāyissatī”’ti.* **";
P_HTM[400]="*8. Pabbajita**8. The Renunciate*";
P_HTM[401]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, bandhumassa rañño etadahosi:**Then King Bandhuma thought,*";
P_HTM[402]="*‘mā heva kho vipassī kumāro na rajjaṃ kāresi, mā heva vipassī kumāro agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbaji, mā heva nemittānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ saccaṃ assa vacanan’ti.**‘Prince Vipassī must not renounce the throne. He must not go forth from the lay life to homelessness. And the words of the brahmin soothsayers must not come true.’*";
P_HTM[403]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, bandhumā rājā vipassissa kumārassa bhiyyoso mattāya pañca kāmaguṇāni upaṭṭhāpesi:**To this end he provided the prince with even more of the five kinds of sensual stimulation,*";
P_HTM[404]="*‘yathā vipassī kumāro rajjaṃ kareyya, yathā vipassī kumāro na agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajeyya, yathā nemittānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ micchā assa vacanan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[405]="*Tatra sudaṃ, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro pañcahi kāmaguṇehi samappito samaṅgībhūto paricāreti.**with which the prince amused himself.*";
P_HTM[406]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro bahūnaṃ vassānaṃ bahūnaṃ vassasatānaṃ bahūnaṃ vassasahassānaṃ accayena sārathiṃ āmantesi:**Then, after many thousand years had passed, Prince Vipassī had his charioteer drive him to the park once more.*";
P_HTM[407]="*‘yojehi, samma sārathi, bhaddāni bhaddāni yānāni, uyyānabhūmiṃ gacchāma subhūmidassanāyā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[408]="*‘Evaṃ, devā’ti kho, bhikkhave, sārathi vipassissa kumārassa paṭissutvā bhaddāni bhaddāni yānāni yojetvā vipassissa kumārassa paṭivedesi:* **";
P_HTM[409]="*‘yuttāni kho te, deva, bhaddāni bhaddāni yānāni,* **";
P_HTM[410]="*yassadāni kālaṃ maññasī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[411]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro bhaddaṃ bhaddaṃ yānaṃ abhiruhitvā bhaddehi bhaddehi yānehi uyyānabhūmiṃ niyyāsi.* **";
P_HTM[412]="*Addasā kho, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro uyyānabhūmiṃ niyyanto purisaṃ bhaṇḍuṃ pabbajitaṃ kāsāyavasanaṃ.**Along the way he saw a man, a renunciate with shaven head, wearing an ocher robe.*";
P_HTM[413]="*Disvā sārathiṃ āmantesi:**He addressed his charioteer,*";
P_HTM[414]="*‘ayaṃ pana, samma sārathi, puriso kiṃkato?**‘My dear charioteer, what has that man done?*";
P_HTM[415]="*Sīsampissa na yathā aññesaṃ, vatthānipissa na yathā aññesan’ti?**For his head and his clothes are unlike those of other men.’*";
P_HTM[416]="*‘Eso kho, deva, pabbajito nāmā’ti.**‘That, Your Majesty, is called a renunciate.’*";
P_HTM[417]="*‘Kiṃ paneso, samma sārathi, pabbajito nāmā’ti?**‘But why is he called a renunciate?’*";
P_HTM[418]="*‘Eso kho, deva, pabbajito nāma sādhu dhammacariyā sādhu samacariyā sādhu kusalakiriyā sādhu puññakiriyā sādhu avihiṃsā sādhu bhūtānukampā’ti.**‘He is called a renunciate because he celebrates principled and fair conduct, skillful actions, good deeds, harmlessness, and compassion for living creatures.’*";
P_HTM[419]="*‘Sādhu kho so, samma sārathi, pabbajito nāma, sādhu dhammacariyā sādhu samacariyā sādhu kusalakiriyā sādhu puññakiriyā sādhu avihiṃsā sādhu bhūtānukampā.**‘Then I celebrate the one called a renunciate, who celebrates principled and fair conduct, skillful actions, good deeds, harmlessness, and compassion for living creatures!*";
P_HTM[420]="*Tena hi, samma sārathi, yena so pabbajito tena rathaṃ pesehī’ti.**Well then, drive the chariot up to that renunciate.’*";
P_HTM[421]="*‘Evaṃ, devā’ti kho, bhikkhave, sārathi vipassissa kumārassa paṭissutvā yena so pabbajito tena rathaṃ pesesi.**‘Yes, Your Majesty,’ replied the charioteer, and did so.*";
P_HTM[422]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro taṃ pabbajitaṃ etadavoca:**Then Prince Vipassī said to that renunciate,*";
P_HTM[423]="*‘tvaṃ pana, samma, kiṃkato,**‘My good man, what have you done?*";
P_HTM[424]="*sīsampi te na yathā aññesaṃ, vatthānipi te na yathā aññesan’ti?**For your head and your clothes are unlike those of other men.’*";
P_HTM[425]="*‘Ahaṃ kho, deva, pabbajito nāmā’ti.**‘Sire, I am what is called a renunciate.’*";
P_HTM[426]="*‘Kiṃ pana tvaṃ, samma, pabbajito nāmā’ti?**‘But why are you called a renunciate?’*";
P_HTM[427]="*‘Ahaṃ kho, deva, pabbajito nāma, sādhu dhammacariyā sādhu samacariyā sādhu kusalakiriyā sādhu puññakiriyā sādhu avihiṃsā sādhu bhūtānukampā’ti.**‘I am called a renunciate because I celebrate principled and fair conduct, skillful actions, good deeds, harmlessness, and compassion for living creatures.’*";
P_HTM[428]="*‘Sādhu kho tvaṃ, samma, pabbajito nāma sādhu dhammacariyā sādhu samacariyā sādhu kusalakiriyā sādhu puññakiriyā sādhu avihiṃsā sādhu bhūtānukampā’ti.**‘Then I celebrate the one called a renunciate, who celebrates principled and fair conduct, skillful actions, good deeds, harmlessness, and compassion for living creatures!’*";
P_HTM[429]="*9. Bodhisattapabbajjā**9. The Going Forth*";
P_HTM[430]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassī kumāro sārathiṃ āmantesi:**Then the prince addressed the charioteer,*";
P_HTM[431]="*‘tena hi, samma sārathi, rathaṃ ādāya itova antepuraṃ paccaniyyāhi.**‘Well then, my dear charioteer, take the chariot and return to the royal compound.*";
P_HTM[432]="*Ahaṃ pana idheva kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajissāmī’ti.**I shall shave off my hair and beard right here, dress in ocher robes, and go forth from the lay life to homelessness.’*";
P_HTM[433]="*‘Evaṃ, devā’ti kho, bhikkhave, sārathi vipassissa kumārassa paṭissutvā rathaṃ ādāya tatova antepuraṃ paccaniyyāsi.**‘Yes, Your Majesty,’ replied the charioteer and did so.*";
P_HTM[434]="*Vipassī pana kumāro tattheva kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbaji.**Then Prince Vipassī shaved off his hair and beard, dressed in ocher robes, and went forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[435]="*10. Mahājanakāyaanupabbajjā**10. A Great Crowd Goes Forth*";
P_HTM[436]="*Assosi kho, bhikkhave, bandhumatiyā rājadhāniyā mahājanakāyo caturāsītipāṇasahassāni:**A large crowd of 84,000 people in the capital of Bandhumatī heard*";
P_HTM[437]="*‘vipassī kira kumāro kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito’ti.**that Vipassī had gone forth.*";
P_HTM[438]="*Sutvāna tesaṃ etadahosi:**It occurred to them,*";
P_HTM[439]="*‘na hi nūna so orako dhammavinayo, na sā orakā pabbajjā, yattha vipassī kumāro kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito.**‘This must be no ordinary teaching and training, no ordinary going forth in which Prince Vipassī has gone forth.*";
P_HTM[440]="*Vipassīpi nāma kumāro kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajissati, kimaṅgaṃ pana mayan’ti.**If even the prince goes forth, why don’t we do the same?’*";
P_HTM[441]="*Atha kho, so bhikkhave, mahājanakāyo caturāsītipāṇasahassāni kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā vipassiṃ bodhisattaṃ agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajitaṃ anupabbajiṃsu.**Then that great crowd of 84,000 people shaved off their hair and beard, dressed in ocher robes, and followed the one intent on awakening, Vipassī, by going forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[442]="*Tāya sudaṃ, bhikkhave, parisāya parivuto vipassī bodhisatto gāmanigamajanapadarājadhānīsu cārikaṃ carati.**Escorted by that assembly, Vipassī wandered on tour among the villages, towns, and capital cities.*";
P_HTM[443]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa rahogatassa paṭisallīnassa evaṃ cetaso parivitakko udapādi:**Then as he was in private retreat this thought came to his mind,*";
P_HTM[444]="*‘na kho metaṃ patirūpaṃ yohaṃ ākiṇṇo viharāmi, yannūnāhaṃ eko gaṇamhā vūpakaṭṭho vihareyyan’ti.**‘It’s not appropriate for me to live in a crowd. Why don’t I live alone, withdrawn from the group?’*";
P_HTM[445]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassī bodhisatto aparena samayena eko gaṇamhā vūpakaṭṭho vihāsi, aññeneva tāni caturāsītipabbajitasahassāni agamaṃsu, aññena maggena vipassī bodhisatto.**After some time he withdrew from the group to live alone. The 84,000 went one way, but Vipassī went another.*";
P_HTM[446]="*11. Bodhisattaabhinivesa**11. Vipassī’s Reflections*";
P_HTM[447]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa vāsūpagatassa rahogatassa paṭisallīnassa evaṃ cetaso parivitakko udapādi:**Then as Vipassī, the one intent on awakening, was in private retreat this thought came to his mind,*";
P_HTM[448]="*‘kicchaṃ vatāyaṃ loko āpanno, jāyati ca jīyati ca mīyati ca cavati ca upapajjati ca, atha ca panimassa dukkhassa nissaraṇaṃ nappajānāti jarāmaraṇassa,**‘Alas, this world has fallen into trouble. It’s born, grows old, dies, passes away, and is reborn, yet it doesn’t understand how to escape from this suffering, from old age and death.*";
P_HTM[449]="*kudāssu nāma imassa dukkhassa nissaraṇaṃ paññāyissati jarāmaraṇassā’ti?**Oh, when will an escape be found from this suffering, from old age and death?’*";
P_HTM[450]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa etadahosi:**Then Vipassī thought,*";
P_HTM[451]="*‘kimhi nu kho sati jarāmaraṇaṃ hoti, kiṃpaccayā jarāmaraṇan’ti?**‘When what exists is there old age and death? What is a condition for old age and death?’*";
P_HTM[452]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa yoniso manasikārā ahu paññāya abhisamayo:**Then, through proper attention, Vipassī comprehended with wisdom,*";
P_HTM[453]="*‘jātiyā kho sati jarāmaraṇaṃ hoti, jātipaccayā jarāmaraṇan’ti.**‘When rebirth exists there’s old age and death. Rebirth is a condition for old age and death.’*";
P_HTM[454]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa etadahosi:**Then Vipassī thought,*";
P_HTM[455]="*‘kimhi nu kho sati jāti hoti, kiṃpaccayā jātī’ti?**‘When what exists is there rebirth? What is a condition for rebirth?’*";
P_HTM[456]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa yoniso manasikārā ahu paññāya abhisamayo:**Then, through proper attention, Vipassī comprehended with wisdom,*";
P_HTM[457]="*‘bhave kho sati jāti hoti, bhavapaccayā jātī’ti.**‘When continued existence exists there’s rebirth. Continued existence is a condition for rebirth.’*";
P_HTM[458]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa etadahosi:**Then Vipassī thought,*";
P_HTM[459]="*‘kimhi nu kho sati bhavo hoti, kiṃpaccayā bhavo’ti?**‘When what exists is there continued existence? What is a condition for continued existence?’*";
P_HTM[460]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa yoniso manasikārā ahu paññāya abhisamayo:**Then, through proper attention, Vipassī comprehended with wisdom,*";
P_HTM[461]="*‘upādāne kho sati bhavo hoti, upādānapaccayā bhavo’ti.**‘When grasping exists there’s continued existence. Grasping is a condition for continued existence.’*";
P_HTM[462]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa etadahosi:**Then Vipassī thought,*";
P_HTM[463]="*‘kimhi nu kho sati upādānaṃ hoti, kiṃpaccayā upādānan’ti?**‘When what exists is there grasping? What is a condition for grasping?’*";
P_HTM[464]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa yoniso manasikārā ahu paññāya abhisamayo:**Then, through proper attention, Vipassī comprehended with wisdom,*";
P_HTM[465]="*‘taṇhāya kho sati upādānaṃ hoti, taṇhāpaccayā upādānan’ti.**‘When craving exists there’s grasping. Craving is a condition for grasping.’*";
P_HTM[466]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa etadahosi:**Then Vipassī thought,*";
P_HTM[467]="*‘kimhi nu kho sati taṇhā hoti, kiṃpaccayā taṇhā’ti?**‘When what exists is there craving? What is a condition for craving?’*";
P_HTM[468]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa yoniso manasikārā ahu paññāya abhisamayo:**Then, through proper attention, Vipassī comprehended with wisdom,*";
P_HTM[469]="*‘vedanāya kho sati taṇhā hoti, vedanāpaccayā taṇhā’ti.**‘When feeling exists there’s craving. Feeling is a condition for craving.’*";
P_HTM[470]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa etadahosi:**Then Vipassī thought,*";
P_HTM[471]="*‘kimhi nu kho sati vedanā hoti, kiṃpaccayā vedanā’ti?**‘When what exists is there feeling? What is a condition for feeling?’*";
P_HTM[472]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa yoniso manasikārā ahu paññāya abhisamayo:**Then, through proper attention, Vipassī comprehended with wisdom,*";
P_HTM[473]="*‘phasse kho sati vedanā hoti, phassapaccayā vedanā’ti.**‘When contact exists there’s feeling. Contact is a condition for feeling.’*";
P_HTM[474]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa etadahosi:**Then Vipassī thought,*";
P_HTM[475]="*‘kimhi nu kho sati phasso hoti, kiṃpaccayā phasso’ti?**‘When what exists is there contact? What is a condition for contact?’*";
P_HTM[476]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa yoniso manasikārā ahu paññāya abhisamayo:**Then, through proper attention, Vipassī comprehended with wisdom,*";
P_HTM[477]="*‘saḷāyatane kho sati phasso hoti, saḷāyatanapaccayā phasso’ti.**‘When the six sense fields exist there’s contact. The six sense fields are a condition for contact.’*";
P_HTM[478]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa etadahosi:**Then Vipassī thought,*";
P_HTM[479]="*‘kimhi nu kho sati saḷāyatanaṃ hoti, kiṃpaccayā saḷāyatanan’ti?**‘When what exists are there the six sense fields? What is a condition for the six sense fields?’*";
P_HTM[480]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa yoniso manasikārā ahu paññāya abhisamayo:**Then, through proper attention, Vipassī comprehended with wisdom,*";
P_HTM[481]="*‘nāmarūpe kho sati saḷāyatanaṃ hoti, nāmarūpapaccayā saḷāyatanan’ti.**‘When name and form exist there are the six sense fields. Name and form are a condition for the six sense fields.’*";
P_HTM[482]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa etadahosi:**Then Vipassī thought,*";
P_HTM[483]="*‘kimhi nu kho sati nāmarūpaṃ hoti, kiṃpaccayā nāmarūpan’ti?**‘When what exists are there name and form? What is a condition for name and form?’*";
P_HTM[484]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa yoniso manasikārā ahu paññāya abhisamayo:**Then, through proper attention, Vipassī comprehended with wisdom,*";
P_HTM[485]="*‘viññāṇe kho sati nāmarūpaṃ hoti, viññāṇapaccayā nāmarūpan’ti.**‘When consciousness exists there are name and form. Consciousness is a condition for name and form.’*";
P_HTM[486]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa etadahosi:**Then Vipassī thought,*";
P_HTM[487]="*‘kimhi nu kho sati viññāṇaṃ hoti, kiṃpaccayā viññāṇan’ti?**‘When what exists is there consciousness? What is a condition for consciousness?’*";
P_HTM[488]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa yoniso manasikārā ahu paññāya abhisamayo:**Then, through proper attention, Vipassī comprehended with wisdom,*";
P_HTM[489]="*‘nāmarūpe kho sati viññāṇaṃ hoti, nāmarūpapaccayā viññāṇan’ti.**‘When name and form exist there’s consciousness. Name and form are a condition for consciousness.’*";
P_HTM[490]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa etadahosi:**Then Vipassī thought,*";
P_HTM[491]="*‘paccudāvattati kho idaṃ viññāṇaṃ nāmarūpamhā, nāparaṃ gacchati.**‘This consciousness turns back from name and form, and doesn’t go beyond that.’*";
P_HTM[492]="*Ettāvatā jāyetha vā jiyyetha vā miyyetha vā cavetha vā upapajjetha vā, yadidaṃ**It is to this extent that one may be reborn, grow old, die, pass away, or reappear. That is:*";
P_HTM[493]="*nāmarūpapaccayā viññāṇaṃ, viññāṇapaccayā nāmarūpaṃ, nāmarūpapaccayā saḷāyatanaṃ, saḷāyatanapaccayā phasso, phassapaccayā vedanā, vedanāpaccayā taṇhā, taṇhāpaccayā upādānaṃ, upādānapaccayā bhavo, bhavapaccayā jāti, jātipaccayā jarāmaraṇaṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā sambhavanti.**Name and form are conditions for consciousness. Consciousness is a condition for name and form. Name and form are conditions for the six sense fields. The six sense fields are conditions for contact. Contact is a condition for feeling. Feeling is a condition for craving. Craving is a condition for grasping. Grasping is a condition for continued existence. Continued existence is a condition for rebirth. Rebirth is a condition for old age and death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress to come to be.*";
P_HTM[494]="*Evametassa kevalassa dukkhakkhandhassa samudayo hoti’.**That is how this entire mass of suffering originates.’*";
P_HTM[495]="*‘Samudayo samudayo’ti kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**‘Origination, origination.’ Such was the vision, knowledge, wisdom, realization, and light that arose in Vipassī, the one intent on awakening, regarding teachings not learned before from another.*";
P_HTM[496]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa etadahosi:**Then Vipassī thought,*";
P_HTM[497]="*‘kimhi nu kho asati jarāmaraṇaṃ na hoti, kissa nirodhā jarāmaraṇanirodho’ti?**‘When what doesn’t exist is there no old age and death? When what ceases do old age and death cease?’*";
P_HTM[498]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa yoniso manasikārā ahu paññāya abhisamayo:**Then, through proper attention, Vipassī comprehended with wisdom,*";
P_HTM[499]="*‘jātiyā kho asati jarāmaraṇaṃ na hoti, jātinirodhā jarāmaraṇanirodho’ti.**‘When rebirth doesn’t exist there’s no old age and death. When rebirth ceases, old age and death cease.’*";
P_HTM[500]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa etadahosi:**Then Vipassī thought,*";
P_HTM[501]="*‘kimhi nu kho asati jāti na hoti, kissa nirodhā jātinirodho’ti?**‘When what doesn’t exist is there no rebirth? When what ceases does rebirth cease?’*";
P_HTM[502]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa yoniso manasikārā ahu paññāya abhisamayo:**Then, through proper attention, Vipassī comprehended with wisdom,*";
P_HTM[503]="*‘bhave kho asati jāti na hoti, bhavanirodhā jātinirodho’ti.**‘When continued existence doesn’t exist there’s no rebirth. When continued existence ceases, rebirth ceases.’*";
P_HTM[504]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa etadahosi:**Then Vipassī thought,*";
P_HTM[505]="*‘kimhi nu kho asati bhavo na hoti, kissa nirodhā bhavanirodho’ti?**‘When what doesn’t exist is there no continued existence? When what ceases does continued existence cease?’*";
P_HTM[506]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa yoniso manasikārā ahu paññāya abhisamayo:**Then, through proper attention, Vipassī comprehended with wisdom,*";
P_HTM[507]="*‘upādāne kho asati bhavo na hoti, upādānanirodhā bhavanirodho’ti.**‘When grasping doesn’t exist there’s no continued existence. When grasping ceases, continued existence ceases.’*";
P_HTM[508]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa etadahosi:**Then Vipassī thought,*";
P_HTM[509]="*‘kimhi nu kho asati upādānaṃ na hoti, kissa nirodhā upādānanirodho’ti?**‘When what doesn’t exist is there no grasping? When what ceases does grasping cease?’*";
P_HTM[510]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa yoniso manasikārā ahu paññāya abhisamayo:**Then, through proper attention, Vipassī comprehended with wisdom,*";
P_HTM[511]="*‘taṇhāya kho asati upādānaṃ na hoti, taṇhānirodhā upādānanirodho’ti.**‘When craving doesn’t exist there’s no grasping. When craving ceases, grasping ceases.’*";
P_HTM[512]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa etadahosi:**Then Vipassī thought,*";
P_HTM[513]="*‘kimhi nu kho asati taṇhā na hoti, kissa nirodhā taṇhānirodho’ti?**‘When what doesn’t exist is there no craving? When what ceases does craving cease?’*";
P_HTM[514]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa yoniso manasikārā ahu paññāya abhisamayo:**Then, through proper attention, Vipassī comprehended with wisdom,*";
P_HTM[515]="*‘vedanāya kho asati taṇhā na hoti, vedanānirodhā taṇhānirodho’ti.**‘When feeling doesn’t exist there’s no craving. When feeling ceases, craving ceases.’*";
P_HTM[516]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa etadahosi:**Then Vipassī thought,*";
P_HTM[517]="*‘kimhi nu kho asati vedanā na hoti, kissa nirodhā vedanānirodho’ti?**‘When what doesn’t exist is there no feeling? When what ceases does feeling cease?’*";
P_HTM[518]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa yoniso manasikārā ahu paññāya abhisamayo:**Then, through proper attention, Vipassī comprehended with wisdom,*";
P_HTM[519]="*‘phasse kho asati vedanā na hoti, phassanirodhā vedanānirodho’ti.**‘When contact doesn’t exist there’s no feeling. When contact ceases, feeling ceases.’*";
P_HTM[520]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa etadahosi:**Then Vipassī thought,*";
P_HTM[521]="*‘kimhi nu kho asati phasso na hoti, kissa nirodhā phassanirodho’ti?**‘When what doesn’t exist is there no contact? When what ceases does contact cease?’*";
P_HTM[522]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa yoniso manasikārā ahu paññāya abhisamayo:**Then, through proper attention, Vipassī comprehended with wisdom,*";
P_HTM[523]="*‘saḷāyatane kho asati phasso na hoti, saḷāyatananirodhā phassanirodho’ti.**‘When the six sense fields don’t exist there’s no contact. When the six sense fields cease, contact ceases.’*";
P_HTM[524]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa etadahosi:**Then Vipassī thought,*";
P_HTM[525]="*‘kimhi nu kho asati saḷāyatanaṃ na hoti, kissa nirodhā saḷāyatananirodho’ti?**‘When what doesn’t exist are there no six sense fields? When what ceases do the six sense fields cease?’*";
P_HTM[526]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa yoniso manasikārā ahu paññāya abhisamayo:**Then, through proper attention, Vipassī comprehended with wisdom,*";
P_HTM[527]="*‘nāmarūpe kho asati saḷāyatanaṃ na hoti, nāmarūpanirodhā saḷāyatananirodho’ti.**‘When name and form don’t exist there are no six sense fields. When name and form cease, the six sense fields cease.’*";
P_HTM[528]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa etadahosi:**Then Vipassī thought,*";
P_HTM[529]="*‘kimhi nu kho asati nāmarūpaṃ na hoti, kissa nirodhā nāmarūpanirodho’ti?**‘When what doesn’t exist are there no name and form? When what ceases do name and form cease?’*";
P_HTM[530]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa yoniso manasikārā ahu paññāya abhisamayo:**Then, through proper attention, Vipassī comprehended with wisdom,*";
P_HTM[531]="*‘viññāṇe kho asati nāmarūpaṃ na hoti, viññāṇanirodhā nāmarūpanirodho’ti.**‘When consciousness doesn’t exist there are no name and form. When consciousness ceases, name and form cease.’*";
P_HTM[532]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa etadahosi:**Then Vipassī thought,*";
P_HTM[533]="*‘kimhi nu kho asati viññāṇaṃ na hoti, kissa nirodhā viññāṇanirodho’ti?**‘When what doesn’t exist is there no consciousness? When what ceases does consciousness cease?’*";
P_HTM[534]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa yoniso manasikārā ahu paññāya abhisamayo:**Then, through proper attention, Vipassī comprehended with wisdom,*";
P_HTM[535]="*‘nāmarūpe kho asati viññāṇaṃ na hoti, nāmarūpanirodhā viññāṇanirodho’ti.**‘When name and form don’t exist there’s no consciousness. When name and form cease, consciousness ceases.’*";
P_HTM[536]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa etadahosi:**Then Vipassī thought,*";
P_HTM[537]="*‘adhigato kho myāyaṃ maggo sambodhāya yadidaṃ—**‘I have discovered the path to awakening. That is:*";
P_HTM[538]="*nāmarūpanirodhā viññāṇanirodho, viññāṇanirodhā nāmarūpanirodho, nāmarūpanirodhā saḷāyatananirodho, saḷāyatananirodhā phassanirodho, phassanirodhā vedanānirodho, vedanānirodhā taṇhānirodho, taṇhānirodhā upādānanirodho, upādānanirodhā bhavanirodho, bhavanirodhā jātinirodho, jātinirodhā jarāmaraṇaṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā nirujjhanti.**When name and form cease, consciousness ceases. When consciousness ceases, name and form cease. When name and form cease, the six sense fields cease. When the six sense fields cease, contact ceases. When contact ceases, feeling ceases. When feeling ceases, craving ceases. When craving ceases, grasping ceases. When grasping ceases, continued existence ceases. When continued existence ceases, rebirth ceases. When rebirth ceases, old age and death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress cease.*";
P_HTM[539]="*Evametassa kevalassa dukkhakkhandhassa nirodho hoti’.**That is how this entire mass of suffering ceases.’*";
P_HTM[540]="*‘Nirodho nirodho’ti kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bodhisattassa pubbe ananussutesu dhammesu cakkhuṃ udapādi, ñāṇaṃ udapādi, paññā udapādi, vijjā udapādi, āloko udapādi.**‘Cessation, cessation.’ Such was the vision, knowledge, wisdom, realization, and light that arose in Vipassī, the one intent on awakening, regarding teachings not learned before from another.*";
P_HTM[541]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassī bodhisatto aparena samayena pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu udayabbayānupassī vihāsi:**Some time later Vipassī meditated observing rise and fall in the five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[542]="*‘iti rūpaṃ, iti rūpassa samudayo, iti rūpassa atthaṅgamo;**‘Such is form, such is the origin of form, such is the ending of form.*";
P_HTM[543]="*iti vedanā, iti vedanāya samudayo, iti vedanāya atthaṅgamo;**Such is feeling, such is the origin of feeling, such is the ending of feeling.*";
P_HTM[544]="*iti saññā, iti saññāya samudayo, iti saññāya atthaṅgamo;**Such is perception, such is the origin of perception, such is the ending of perception.*";
P_HTM[545]="*iti saṅkhārā, iti saṅkhārānaṃ samudayo, iti saṅkhārānaṃ atthaṅgamo;**Such are choices, such is the origin of choices, such is the ending of choices.*";
P_HTM[546]="*iti viññāṇaṃ, iti viññāṇassa samudayo, iti viññāṇassa atthaṅgamo’ti,**Such is consciousness, such is the origin of consciousness, such is the ending of consciousness.’*";
P_HTM[547]="*tassa pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu udayabbayānupassino viharato na cirasseva anupādāya āsavehi cittaṃ vimuccīti.**Meditating like this his mind was soon freed from defilements by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[548]="*Dutiyabhāṇavāro.* **";
P_HTM[549]="*12. Brahmayācanakathā**12. The Appeal of Brahmā*";
P_HTM[550]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa etadahosi:**Then the Blessed One Vipassī, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha, thought,*";
P_HTM[551]="*‘yannūnāhaṃ dhammaṃ deseyyan’ti.**‘Why don’t I teach the Dhamma?’*";
P_HTM[552]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa etadahosi:**Then he thought,*";
P_HTM[553]="*‘adhigato kho myāyaṃ dhammo gambhīro duddaso duranubodho santo paṇīto atakkāvacaro nipuṇo paṇḍitavedanīyo.**‘This principle I have discovered is deep, hard to see, hard to understand, peaceful, sublime, beyond the scope of reason, subtle, comprehensible to the astute.*";
P_HTM[554]="*Ālayarāmā kho panāyaṃ pajā ālayaratā ālayasammuditā.**But people like attachment, they love it and enjoy it.*";
P_HTM[555]="*Ālayarāmāya kho pana pajāya ālayaratāya ālayasammuditāya duddasaṃ idaṃ ṭhānaṃ yadidaṃ idappaccayatāpaṭiccasamuppādo.**It’s hard for them to see this thing; that is, specific conditionality, dependent origination.*";
P_HTM[556]="*Idampi kho ṭhānaṃ duddasaṃ yadidaṃ sabbasaṅkhārasamatho sabbūpadhipaṭinissaggo taṇhākkhayo virāgo nirodho nibbānaṃ.**It’s also hard for them to see this thing; that is, the stilling of all activities, the letting go of all attachments, the ending of craving, fading away, cessation, extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[557]="*Ahañceva kho pana dhammaṃ deseyyaṃ, pare ca me na ājāneyyuṃ; so mamassa kilamatho, sā mamassa vihesā’ti.**And if I were to teach the Dhamma, others might not understand me, which would be wearying and troublesome for me.’*";
P_HTM[558]="*Apissu, bhikkhave, vipassiṃ bhagavantaṃ arahantaṃ sammāsambuddhaṃ imā anacchariyā gāthāyo paṭibhaṃsu pubbe assutapubbā:**And then these verses, which were neither supernaturally inspired, nor learned before in the past, occurred to him:*";
P_HTM[559]="*‘Kicchena me adhigataṃ,**‘I’ve struggled hard to realize this,*";
P_HTM[560]="*halaṃ dāni pakāsituṃ;**enough with trying to explain it!*";
P_HTM[561]="*Rāgadosaparetehi,**This teaching is not easily understood*";
P_HTM[562]="*nāyaṃ dhammo susambudho.**by those mired in greed and hate.*";
P_HTM[563]="*Paṭisotagāmiṃ nipuṇaṃ,**Those caught up in greed can’t see*";
P_HTM[564]="*gambhīraṃ duddasaṃ aṇuṃ;**what’s subtle, going against the stream,*";
P_HTM[565]="*Rāgarattā na dakkhanti,**deep, hard to see, and very fine,*";
P_HTM[566]="*tamokhandhena āvuṭā’ti.**for they’re shrouded in a mass of darkness.’*";
P_HTM[567]="*Itiha, bhikkhave, vipassissa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa paṭisañcikkhato appossukkatāya cittaṃ nami, no dhammadesanāya.**So, as the Buddha Vipassī reflected like this, his mind inclined to remaining passive, not to teaching the Dhamma.*";
P_HTM[568]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, aññatarassa mahābrahmuno vipassissa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa cetasā cetoparivitakkamaññāya etadahosi:**Then a certain Great Brahmā, knowing what the Buddha Vipassī was thinking, thought,*";
P_HTM[569]="*‘nassati vata bho loko, vinassati vata bho loko, yatra hi nāma vipassissa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa appossukkatāya cittaṃ namati, no dhammadesanāyā’ti.**‘Oh my goodness! The world will be lost, the world will perish! For the mind of the Realized One Vipassī, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha, inclines to remaining passive, not to teaching the Dhamma.’*";
P_HTM[570]="*Atha kho so, bhikkhave, mahābrahmā seyyathāpi nāma balavā puriso samiñjitaṃ vā bāhaṃ pasāreyya, pasāritaṃ vā bāhaṃ samiñjeyya; evameva—brahmaloke antarahito vipassissa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa purato pāturahosi.**Then, as easily as a strong person would extend or contract their arm, he vanished from the Brahmā realm and reappeared in front of the Buddha Vipassī.*";
P_HTM[571]="*Atha kho so, bhikkhave, mahābrahmā ekaṃsaṃ uttarāsaṅgaṃ karitvā dakkhiṇaṃ jāṇumaṇḍalaṃ pathaviyaṃ nihantvā yena vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho tenañjaliṃ paṇāmetvā vipassiṃ bhagavantaṃ arahantaṃ sammāsambuddhaṃ etadavoca:**He arranged his robe over one shoulder, knelt on his right knee, raised his joined palms toward the Buddha Vipassī, and said,*";
P_HTM[572]="*‘desetu, bhante, bhagavā dhammaṃ, desetu sugato dhammaṃ,**‘Sir, let the Blessed One teach the Dhamma! Let the Holy One teach the Dhamma!*";
P_HTM[573]="*santi sattā apparajakkhajātikā; assavanatā dhammassa parihāyanti,**There are beings with little dust in their eyes. They’re in decline because they haven’t heard the teaching.*";
P_HTM[574]="*bhavissanti dhammassa aññātāro’ti.**There will be those who understand the teaching!’*";
P_HTM[575]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhikkhave, vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho taṃ mahābrahmānaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, the Buddha Vipassī said to him,*";
P_HTM[576]="*‘mayhampi kho, brahme, etadahosi:**‘I too thought this, Brahmā,*";
P_HTM[577]="*“yannūnāhaṃ dhammaṃ deseyyan”ti.**“Why don’t I teach the Dhamma?”*";
P_HTM[578]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, brahme, etadahosi:**Then it occurred to me,*";
P_HTM[579]="*“adhigato kho myāyaṃ dhammo gambhīro duddaso duranubodho santo paṇīto atakkāvacaro nipuṇo paṇḍitavedanīyo.* **";
P_HTM[580]="*Ālayarāmā kho panāyaṃ pajā ālayaratā ālayasammuditā.* **";
P_HTM[581]="*Ālayarāmāya kho pana pajāya ālayaratāya ālayasammuditāya duddasaṃ idaṃ ṭhānaṃ yadidaṃ idappaccayatāpaṭiccasamuppādo.* **";
P_HTM[582]="*Idampi kho ṭhānaṃ duddasaṃ yadidaṃ sabbasaṅkhārasamatho sabbūpadhipaṭinissaggo taṇhākkhayo virāgo nirodho nibbānaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[583]="*Ahañceva kho pana dhammaṃ deseyyaṃ, pare ca me na ājāneyyuṃ; so mamassa kilamatho, sā mamassa vihesā”ti.**“If I were to teach the Dhamma, others might not understand me, which would be wearying and troublesome for me.”*";
P_HTM[584]="*Apissu maṃ, brahme, imā anacchariyā gāthāyo paṭibhaṃsu pubbe assutapubbā:* **";
P_HTM[585]="*“Kicchena me adhigataṃ,* **";
P_HTM[586]="*halaṃ dāni pakāsituṃ;* **";
P_HTM[587]="*Rāgadosaparetehi,* **";
P_HTM[588]="*nāyaṃ dhammo susambudho.* **";
P_HTM[589]="*Paṭisotagāmiṃ nipuṇaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[590]="*gambhīraṃ duddasaṃ aṇuṃ;* **";
P_HTM[591]="*Rāgarattā na dakkhanti,* **";
P_HTM[592]="*tamokhandhena āvuṭā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[593]="*Itiha me, brahme, paṭisañcikkhato appossukkatāya cittaṃ nami, no dhammadesanāyā’ti.**So, as I reflected like this, my mind inclined to remaining passive, not to teaching the Dhamma.’*";
P_HTM[594]="*Dutiyampi kho, bhikkhave, so mahābrahmā … pe …**For a second time,*";
P_HTM[595]="*tatiyampi kho, bhikkhave, so mahābrahmā vipassiṃ bhagavantaṃ arahantaṃ sammāsambuddhaṃ etadavoca:**and a third time that Great Brahmā begged the Buddha to teach.*";
P_HTM[596]="*‘desetu, bhante, bhagavā dhammaṃ, desetu sugato dhammaṃ, santi sattā apparajakkhajātikā, assavanatā dhammassa parihāyanti, bhavissanti dhammassa aññātāro’ti.* **";
P_HTM[597]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho brahmuno ca ajjhesanaṃ viditvā sattesu ca kāruññataṃ paṭicca buddhacakkhunā lokaṃ volokesi.**Then, understanding Brahmā’s invitation, the Buddha Vipassī surveyed the world with the eye of a Buddha, because of his compassion for sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[598]="*Addasā kho, bhikkhave, vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho buddhacakkhunā lokaṃ volokento satte apparajakkhe mahārajakkhe tikkhindriye mudindriye svākāre dvākāre suviññāpaye duviññāpaye appekacce paralokavajjabhayadassāvine viharante, appekacce na paralokavajjabhayadassāvine viharante.**And he saw sentient beings with little dust in their eyes, and some with much dust in their eyes; with keen faculties and with weak faculties, with good qualities and with bad qualities, easy to teach and hard to teach. And some of them lived seeing the danger in the fault to do with the next world, while others did not.*";
P_HTM[599]="*Seyyathāpi nāma uppaliniyaṃ vā paduminiyaṃ vā puṇḍarīkiniyaṃ vā appekaccāni uppalāni vā padumāni vā puṇḍarīkāni vā udake jātāni udake saṃvaḍḍhāni udakānuggatāni anto nimuggaposīni. Appekaccāni uppalāni vā padumāni vā puṇḍarīkāni vā udake jātāni udake saṃvaḍḍhāni samodakaṃ ṭhitāni. Appekaccāni uppalāni vā padumāni vā puṇḍarīkāni vā udake jātāni udake saṃvaḍḍhāni udakā accuggamma ṭhitāni anupalittāni udakena.**It’s like a pool with blue water lilies, or pink or white lotuses. Some of them sprout and grow in the water without rising above it, thriving underwater. Some of them sprout and grow in the water reaching the water’s surface. And some of them sprout and grow in the water but rise up above the water and stand with no water clinging to them.*";
P_HTM[600]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho buddhacakkhunā lokaṃ volokento addasa satte apparajakkhe mahārajakkhe tikkhindriye mudindriye svākāre dvākāre suviññāpaye duviññāpaye appekacce paralokavajjabhayadassāvine viharante, appekacce na paralokavajjabhayadassāvine viharante.**In the same way, the Buddha Vipassī saw sentient beings with little dust in their eyes, and some with much dust in their eyes.*";
P_HTM[601]="*Atha kho so, bhikkhave, mahābrahmā vipassissa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa cetasā cetoparivitakkamaññāya vipassiṃ bhagavantaṃ arahantaṃ sammāsambuddhaṃ gāthāhi ajjhabhāsi:**Then that Great Brahmā, knowing what the Buddha Vipassī was thinking, addressed him in verse:*";
P_HTM[602]="*‘Sele yathā pabbatamuddhaniṭṭhito,**‘Standing high on a rocky mountain,*";
P_HTM[603]="*Yathāpi passe janataṃ samantato;**you can see the people all around.*";
P_HTM[604]="*Tathūpamaṃ dhammamayaṃ sumedha,**In just the same way, all-seer, wise one,*";
P_HTM[605]="*Pāsādamāruyha samantacakkhu;**ascend the palace built of Dhamma!*";
P_HTM[606]="*Sokāvatiṇṇaṃ janatamapetasoko,**You’re free of sorrow; but look at these people*";
P_HTM[607]="*Avekkhassu jātijarābhibhūtaṃ.**overwhelmed with sorrow, oppressed by rebirth and old age.*";
P_HTM[608]="*Uṭṭhehi vīra vijitasaṅgāma,**Rise, hero! Victor in battle, leader of the caravan,*";
P_HTM[609]="*Satthavāha aṇaṇa vicara loke;**wander the world without obligation.*";
P_HTM[610]="*Desassu bhagavā dhammaṃ,**Let the Blessed One teach the Dhamma!*";
P_HTM[611]="*Aññātāro bhavissantī’ti.**There will be those who understand!’*";
P_HTM[612]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho taṃ mahābrahmānaṃ gāthāya ajjhabhāsi:**Then the Buddha Vipassī addressed that Great Brahmā in verse:*";
P_HTM[613]="*‘Apārutā tesaṃ amatassa dvārā,**‘Flung open are the doors to the deathless!*";
P_HTM[614]="*Ye sotavanto pamuñcantu saddhaṃ;**Let those with ears to hear decide their faith.*";
P_HTM[615]="*Vihiṃsasaññī paguṇaṃ na bhāsiṃ,**Thinking it would be troublesome, Brahmā, I did not teach*";
P_HTM[616]="*Dhammaṃ paṇītaṃ manujesu brahme’ti.**the sophisticated, sublime Dhamma among humans.’*";
P_HTM[617]="*Atha kho so, bhikkhave, mahābrahmā: ‘katāvakāso khomhi vipassinā bhagavatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena dhammadesanāyā’ti vipassiṃ bhagavantaṃ arahantaṃ sammāsambuddhaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā tattheva antaradhāyi.**Then the Great Brahmā, knowing that his request for the Buddha Vipassī to teach the Dhamma had been granted, bowed and respectfully circled him, keeping him on his right, before vanishing right there.*";
P_HTM[618]="*13. Aggasāvakayuga**13. The Chief Disciples*";
P_HTM[619]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa etadahosi:**Then the Blessed One Vipassī, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha, thought,*";
P_HTM[620]="*‘kassa nu kho ahaṃ paṭhamaṃ dhammaṃ deseyyaṃ,**‘Who should I teach first of all?*";
P_HTM[621]="*ko imaṃ dhammaṃ khippameva ājānissatī’ti?**Who will quickly understand this teaching?’*";
P_HTM[622]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa etadahosi:**Then he thought,*";
P_HTM[623]="*‘ayaṃ kho khaṇḍo ca rājaputto tisso ca purohitaputto bandhumatiyā rājadhāniyā paṭivasanti paṇḍitā viyattā medhāvino dīgharattaṃ apparajakkhajātikā.**‘That Khaṇḍa, the king’s son, and Tissa, the high priest’s son, are astute, competent, clever, and have long had little dust in their eyes.*";
P_HTM[624]="*Yannūnāhaṃ khaṇḍassa ca rājaputtassa, tissassa ca purohitaputtassa paṭhamaṃ dhammaṃ deseyyaṃ, te imaṃ dhammaṃ khippameva ājānissantī’ti.**Why don’t I teach them first of all? They will quickly understand this teaching.’*";
P_HTM[625]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho seyyathāpi nāma balavā puriso samiñjitaṃ vā bāhaṃ pasāreyya, pasāritaṃ vā bāhaṃ samiñjeyya; evameva—bodhirukkhamūle antarahito bandhumatiyā rājadhāniyā kheme migadāye pāturahosi.**Then, as easily as a strong person would extend or contract their arm, he vanished from the tree of awakening and reappeared near the capital city of Bandhumatī, in the deer park named Sanctuary.*";
P_HTM[626]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho dāyapālaṃ āmantesi:**Then the Buddha Vipassī addressed the park keeper,*";
P_HTM[627]="*‘ehi tvaṃ, samma dāyapāla, bandhumatiṃ rājadhāniṃ pavisitvā khaṇḍañca rājaputtaṃ tissañca purohitaputtaṃ evaṃ vadehi—**‘My dear park keeper, please enter the city and say this to the king’s son Khaṇḍa and the high priest’s son Tissa:*";
P_HTM[628]="*vipassī, bhante, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho bandhumatiṃ rājadhāniṃ anuppatto kheme migadāye viharati, so tumhākaṃ dassanakāmo’ti.**“Sirs, the Blessed One Vipassī, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha, has arrived at Bandhumatī and is staying in the deer park named Sanctuary. He wishes to see you.”’*";
P_HTM[629]="*‘Evaṃ, bhante’ti kho, bhikkhave, dāyapālo vipassissa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa paṭissutvā bandhumatiṃ rājadhāniṃ pavisitvā khaṇḍañca rājaputtaṃ tissañca purohitaputtaṃ etadavoca:**‘Yes, sir,’ replied the park keeper, and did as he was asked.*";
P_HTM[630]="*‘vipassī, bhante, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho bandhumatiṃ rājadhāniṃ anuppatto kheme migadāye viharati; so tumhākaṃ dassanakāmo’ti.* **";
P_HTM[631]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, khaṇḍo ca rājaputto tisso ca purohitaputto bhaddāni bhaddāni yānāni yojāpetvā bhaddaṃ bhaddaṃ yānaṃ abhiruhitvā bhaddehi bhaddehi yānehi bandhumatiyā rājadhāniyā niyyiṃsu. Yena khemo migadāyo tena pāyiṃsu.**Then the king’s son Khaṇḍa and the high priest’s son Tissa had the finest carriages harnessed. Then they mounted a fine carriage and, along with other fine carriages, set out from Bandhumatī for the Sanctuary.*";
P_HTM[632]="*Yāvatikā yānassa bhūmi, yānena gantvā yānā paccorohitvā pattikāva yena vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho tenupasaṅkamiṃsu. upasaṅkamitvā vipassiṃ bhagavantaṃ arahantaṃ sammāsambuddhaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu.**They went by carriage as far as the terrain allowed, then descended and approached the Buddha Vipassī on foot. They bowed and sat down to one side.*";
P_HTM[633]="*Tesaṃ vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho anupubbiṃ kathaṃ kathesi, seyyathidaṃ—**The Buddha Vipassī taught them step by step, with*";
P_HTM[634]="*dānakathaṃ sīlakathaṃ saggakathaṃ kāmānaṃ ādīnavaṃ okāraṃ saṃkilesaṃ nekkhamme ānisaṃsaṃ pakāsesi.**a talk on giving, ethical conduct, and heaven. He explained the drawbacks of sensual pleasures, so sordid and corrupt, and the benefit of renunciation.*";
P_HTM[635]="*Yadā te bhagavā aññāsi kallacitte muducitte vinīvaraṇacitte udaggacitte pasannacitte, atha yā buddhānaṃ sāmukkaṃsikā dhammadesanā, taṃ pakāsesi—**And when he knew that their minds were ready, pliable, rid of hindrances, joyful, and confident he explained the special teaching of the Buddhas:*";
P_HTM[636]="*dukkhaṃ samudayaṃ nirodhaṃ maggaṃ.**suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[637]="*Seyyathāpi nāma suddhaṃ vatthaṃ apagatakāḷakaṃ sammadeva rajanaṃ paṭiggaṇheyya;**Just as a clean cloth rid of stains would properly absorb dye,*";
P_HTM[638]="*evameva khaṇḍassa ca rājaputtassa tissassa ca purohitaputtassa tasmiṃyeva āsane virajaṃ vītamalaṃ dhammacakkhuṃ udapādi:**in that very seat the stainless, immaculate vision of the Dhamma arose in the king’s son Khaṇḍa and the high priest’s son Tissa:*";
P_HTM[639]="*‘yaṃ kiñci samudayadhammaṃ sabbaṃ taṃ nirodhadhamman’ti.**‘Everything that has a beginning has an end.’*";
P_HTM[640]="*Te diṭṭhadhammā pattadhammā viditadhammā pariyogāḷhadhammā tiṇṇavicikicchā vigatakathaṅkathā vesārajjappattā aparappaccayā satthusāsane vipassiṃ bhagavantaṃ arahantaṃ sammāsambuddhaṃ etadavocuṃ:**They saw, attained, understood, and fathomed the Dhamma. They went beyond doubt, got rid of indecision, and became self-assured and independent of others regarding the Teacher’s instructions. They said to the Buddha Vipassī,*";
P_HTM[641]="*‘abhikkantaṃ, bhante, abhikkantaṃ, bhante.**‘Excellent, sir! Excellent!*";
P_HTM[642]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante, nikkujjitaṃ vā ukkujjeyya, paṭicchannaṃ vā vivareyya, mūḷhassa vā maggaṃ ācikkheyya, andhakāre vā telapajjotaṃ dhāreyya: “cakkhumanto rūpāni dakkhantī”ti; evamevaṃ bhagavatā anekapariyāyena dhammo pakāsito.**As if he were righting the overturned, or revealing the hidden, or pointing out the path to the lost, or lighting a lamp in the dark so people with good eyes can see what’s there, the Buddha has made the teaching clear in many ways.*";
P_HTM[643]="*Ete mayaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāma dhammañca.**We go for refuge to the Blessed One, to the teaching, and to the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[644]="*Labheyyāma mayaṃ, bhante, bhagavato santike pabbajjaṃ, labheyyāma upasampadan’ti.**Sir, may we receive the going forth and ordination in the Buddha’s presence?’*";
P_HTM[645]="*Alatthuṃ kho, bhikkhave, khaṇḍo ca rājaputto, tisso ca purohitaputto vipassissa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa santike pabbajjaṃ alatthuṃ upasampadaṃ.**And they received the going forth, the ordination in the Buddha Vipassī’s presence.*";
P_HTM[646]="*Te vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho dhammiyā kathāya sandassesi samādapesi samuttejesi sampahaṃsesi;**Then the Buddha Vipassī educated, encouraged, fired up, and inspired them with a Dhamma talk.*";
P_HTM[647]="*saṅkhārānaṃ ādīnavaṃ okāraṃ saṃkilesaṃ nibbāne ānisaṃsaṃ pakāsesi.**He explained the drawbacks of conditioned phenomena, so sordid and corrupt, and the benefit of extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[648]="*Tesaṃ vipassinā bhagavatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena dhammiyā kathāya sandassiyamānānaṃ samādapiyamānānaṃ samuttejiyamānānaṃ sampahaṃsiyamānānaṃ nacirasseva anupādāya āsavehi cittāni vimucciṃsu.**Being taught like this their minds were soon freed from defilements by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[649]="*14. Mahājanakāyapabbajjā**14. The Going Forth of the Large Crowd*";
P_HTM[650]="*Assosi kho, bhikkhave, bandhumatiyā rājadhāniyā mahājanakāyo caturāsītipāṇasahassāni:**A large crowd of 84,000 people in the capital of Bandhumatī heard*";
P_HTM[651]="*‘vipassī kira bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho bandhumatiṃ rājadhāniṃ anuppatto kheme migadāye viharati.**that the Blessed One Vipassī, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha, had arrived at Bandhumatī and was staying in the deer park named Sanctuary.*";
P_HTM[652]="*Khaṇḍo ca kira rājaputto tisso ca purohitaputto vipassissa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa santike kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajitā’ti.**And they heard that the king’s son Khaṇḍa and the high priest’s son Tissa had shaved off their hair and beard, dressed in ocher robes, and gone forth from the lay life to homelessness in the Buddha’s presence.*";
P_HTM[653]="*Sutvāna nesaṃ etadahosi:**It occurred to them,*";
P_HTM[654]="*‘na hi nūna so orako dhammavinayo, na sā orakā pabbajjā, yattha khaṇḍo ca rājaputto tisso ca purohitaputto kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajitā.**‘This must be no ordinary teaching and training, no ordinary going forth in which the king’s son Khaṇḍa and the high priest’s son Tissa have gone forth.*";
P_HTM[655]="*Khaṇḍo ca rājaputto tisso ca purohitaputto kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajissanti, kimaṅgaṃ pana mayan’ti.**If even they go forth, why don’t we do the same?’*";
P_HTM[656]="*Atha kho so, bhikkhave, mahājanakāyo caturāsītipāṇasahassāni bandhumatiyā rājadhāniyā nikkhamitvā yena khemo migadāyo yena vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā vipassiṃ bhagavantaṃ arahantaṃ sammāsambuddhaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu.**Then those 84,000 people left Bandhumatī for the deer park named Sanctuary, where they approached the Buddha Vipassī, bowed and sat down to one side.*";
P_HTM[657]="*Tesaṃ vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho anupubbiṃ kathaṃ kathesi.**The Buddha Vipassī taught them step by step, with*";
P_HTM[658]="*Seyyathidaṃ—dānakathaṃ sīlakathaṃ saggakathaṃ kāmānaṃ ādīnavaṃ okāraṃ saṅkilesaṃ nekkhamme ānisaṃsaṃ pakāsesi.**a talk on giving, ethical conduct, and heaven. He explained the drawbacks of sensual pleasures, so sordid and corrupt, and the benefit of renunciation.*";
P_HTM[659]="*Yadā te bhagavā aññāsi kallacitte muducitte vinīvaraṇacitte udaggacitte pasannacitte, atha yā buddhānaṃ sāmukkaṃsikā dhammadesanā, taṃ pakāsesi—**And when he knew that their minds were ready, pliable, rid of hindrances, joyful, and confident he explained the special teaching of the Buddhas:*";
P_HTM[660]="*dukkhaṃ samudayaṃ nirodhaṃ maggaṃ.**suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[661]="*Seyyathāpi nāma suddhaṃ vatthaṃ apagatakāḷakaṃ sammadeva rajanaṃ paṭiggaṇheyya;**Just as a clean cloth rid of stains would properly absorb dye,*";
P_HTM[662]="*evameva tesaṃ caturāsītipāṇasahassānaṃ tasmiṃyeva āsane virajaṃ vītamalaṃ dhammacakkhuṃ udapādi:**in that very seat the stainless, immaculate vision of the Dhamma arose in those 84,000 people:*";
P_HTM[663]="*‘yaṃ kiñci samudayadhammaṃ sabbaṃ taṃ nirodhadhamman’ti.**‘Everything that has a beginning has an end.’*";
P_HTM[664]="*Te diṭṭhadhammā pattadhammā viditadhammā pariyogāḷhadhammā tiṇṇavicikicchā vigatakathaṃkathā vesārajjappattā aparappaccayā satthusāsane vipassiṃ bhagavantaṃ arahantaṃ sammāsambuddhaṃ etadavocuṃ:**They saw, attained, understood, and fathomed the Dhamma. They went beyond doubt, got rid of indecision, and became self-assured and independent of others regarding the Teacher’s instructions. They said to the Buddha Vipassī,*";
P_HTM[665]="*‘abhikkantaṃ, bhante, abhikkantaṃ, bhante.**‘Excellent, sir! Excellent!’*";
P_HTM[666]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante, nikkujjitaṃ vā ukkujjeyya, paṭicchannaṃ vā vivareyya, mūḷhassa vā maggaṃ ācikkheyya, andhakāre vā telapajjotaṃ dhāreyya: “cakkhumanto rūpāni dakkhantī”ti; evamevaṃ bhagavatā anekapariyāyena dhammo pakāsito.**And just like Khaṇḍa and Tissa they asked for and received ordination. Then the Buddha taught them further.*";
P_HTM[667]="*Ete mayaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāma dhammañca bhikkhusaṃghañca.* **";
P_HTM[668]="*Labheyyāma mayaṃ, bhante, bhagavato santike pabbajjaṃ labheyyāma upasampadan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[669]="*Alatthuṃ kho, bhikkhave, tāni caturāsītipāṇasahassāni vipassissa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa santike pabbajjaṃ, alatthuṃ upasampadaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[670]="*Te vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho dhammiyā kathāya sandassesi samādapesi samuttejesi sampahaṃsesi;* **";
P_HTM[671]="*saṅkhārānaṃ ādīnavaṃ okāraṃ saṅkilesaṃ nibbāne ānisaṃsaṃ pakāsesi.* **";
P_HTM[672]="*Tesaṃ vipassinā bhagavatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena dhammiyā kathāya sandassiyamānānaṃ samādapiyamānānaṃ samuttejiyamānānaṃ sampahaṃsiyamānānaṃ nacirasseva anupādāya āsavehi cittāni vimucciṃsu.**Being taught like this their minds were soon freed from defilements by not grasping.*";
P_HTM[673]="*15. Purimapabbajitānaṃ dhammābhisamaya**15. The 84,000 Who Had Gone Forth Previously*";
P_HTM[674]="*Assosuṃ kho, bhikkhave, tāni purimāni caturāsītipabbajitasahassāni:**The 84,000 people who had gone forth previously also heard:*";
P_HTM[675]="*‘vipassī kira bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho bandhumatiṃ rājadhāniṃ anuppatto kheme migadāye viharati, dhammañca kira desetī’ti.**‘It seems the Blessed One Vipassī, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha, has arrived at Bandhumatī and is staying in the deer park named Sanctuary. And he is teaching the Dhamma!’*";
P_HTM[676]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, tāni caturāsītipabbajitasahassāni yena bandhumatī rājadhānī yena khemo migadāyo yena vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā vipassiṃ bhagavantaṃ arahantaṃ sammāsambuddhaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu.**Then they too went to see the Buddha Vipassī, realized the Dhamma, went forth, and became freed from defilements.*";
P_HTM[677]="*Tesaṃ vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho anupubbiṃ kathaṃ kathesi.* **";
P_HTM[678]="*Seyyathidaṃ—dānakathaṃ sīlakathaṃ saggakathaṃ kāmānaṃ ādīnavaṃ okāraṃ saṅkilesaṃ nekkhamme ānisaṃsaṃ pakāsesi.* **";
P_HTM[679]="*Yadā te bhagavā aññāsi kallacitte muducitte vinīvaraṇacitte udaggacitte pasannacitte, atha yā buddhānaṃ sāmukkaṃsikā dhammadesanā, taṃ pakāsesi—* **";
P_HTM[680]="*dukkhaṃ samudayaṃ nirodhaṃ maggaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[681]="*Seyyathāpi nāma suddhaṃ vatthaṃ apagatakāḷakaṃ sammadeva rajanaṃ paṭiggaṇheyya;* **";
P_HTM[682]="*evameva tesaṃ caturāsītipabbajitasahassānaṃ tasmiṃyeva āsane virajaṃ vītamalaṃ dhammacakkhuṃ udapādi:* **";
P_HTM[683]="*‘yaṃ kiñci samudayadhammaṃ sabbaṃ taṃ nirodhadhamman’ti.* **";
P_HTM[684]="*Te diṭṭhadhammā pattadhammā viditadhammā pariyogāḷhadhammā tiṇṇavicikicchā vigatakathaṅkathā vesārajjappattā aparappaccayā satthusāsane vipassiṃ bhagavantaṃ arahantaṃ sammāsambuddhaṃ etadavocuṃ:* **";
P_HTM[685]="*‘abhikkantaṃ, bhante, abhikkantaṃ, bhante.* **";
P_HTM[686]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante, nikkujjitaṃ vā ukkujjeyya, paṭicchannaṃ vā vivareyya, mūḷhassa vā maggaṃ ācikkheyya, andhakāre vā telapajjotaṃ dhāreyya: “cakkhumanto rūpāni dakkhantī”ti; evamevaṃ bhagavatā anekapariyāyena dhammo pakāsito.* **";
P_HTM[687]="*Ete mayaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāma dhammañca bhikkhusaṅghañca.* **";
P_HTM[688]="*Labheyyāma mayaṃ, bhante, bhagavato santike pabbajjaṃ labheyyāma upasampadan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[689]="*Alatthuṃ kho, bhikkhave, tāni caturāsītipabbajitasahassāni vipassissa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa santike pabbajjaṃ alatthuṃ upasampadaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[690]="*Te vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho dhammiyā kathāya sandassesi samādapesi samuttejesi sampahaṃsesi;* **";
P_HTM[691]="*saṅkhārānaṃ ādīnavaṃ okāraṃ saṅkilesaṃ nibbāne ānisaṃsaṃ pakāsesi.* **";
P_HTM[692]="*Tesaṃ vipassinā bhagavatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena dhammiyā kathāya sandassiyamānānaṃ samādapiyamānānaṃ samuttejiyamānānaṃ sampahaṃsiyamānānaṃ nacirasseva anupādāya āsavehi cittāni vimucciṃsu.* **";
P_HTM[693]="*16. Cārikāanujānana**16. The Allowance to Wander*";
P_HTM[694]="*Tena kho pana, bhikkhave, samayena bandhumatiyā rājadhāniyā mahābhikkhusaṅgho paṭivasati aṭṭhasaṭṭhibhikkhusatasahassaṃ.**Now at that time a large Saṅgha of 6,800,000 mendicants were residing at Bandhumatī.*";
P_HTM[695]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassissa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa rahogatassa paṭisallīnassa evaṃ cetaso parivitakko udapādi:**As the Buddha Vipassī was in private retreat this thought came to his mind,*";
P_HTM[696]="*‘mahā kho etarahi bhikkhusaṅgho bandhumatiyā rājadhāniyā paṭivasati aṭṭhasaṭṭhibhikkhusatasahassaṃ, yannūnāhaṃ bhikkhū anujāneyyaṃ:**‘The Saṅgha residing at Bandhumatī now is large. What if I was to urge them:*";
P_HTM[697]="*“caratha, bhikkhave, cārikaṃ bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ;**“Wander forth, mendicants, for the welfare and happiness of the people, out of compassion for the world, for the benefit, welfare, and happiness of gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[698]="*mā ekena dve agamittha;**Let not two go by one road.*";
P_HTM[699]="*desetha, bhikkhave, dhammaṃ ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāsetha.**Teach the Dhamma that’s good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased. And reveal a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure.*";
P_HTM[700]="*Santi sattā apparajakkhajātikā, assavanatā dhammassa parihāyanti,**There are beings with little dust in their eyes. They’re in decline because they haven’t heard the teaching.*";
P_HTM[701]="*bhavissanti dhammassa aññātāro.**There will be those who understand the teaching!*";
P_HTM[702]="*Api ca channaṃ channaṃ vassānaṃ accayena bandhumatī rājadhānī upasaṅkamitabbā pātimokkhuddesāyā”’ti.**But when six years have passed, you must all come to Bandhumatī to recite the monastic code.”’*";
P_HTM[703]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, aññataro mahābrahmā vipassissa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa cetasā cetoparivitakkamaññāya seyyathāpi nāma balavā puriso samiñjitaṃ vā bāhaṃ pasāreyya, pasāritaṃ vā bāhaṃ samiñjeyya; evameva—brahmaloke antarahito vipassissa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa purato pāturahosi.**Then a certain Great Brahmā, knowing what the Buddha Vipassī was thinking, as easily as a strong person would extend or contract their arm, vanished from the Brahmā realm and reappeared in front of the Buddha Vipassī.*";
P_HTM[704]="*Atha kho so, bhikkhave, mahābrahmā ekaṃsaṃ uttarāsaṅgaṃ karitvā yena vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho tenañjaliṃ paṇāmetvā vipassiṃ bhagavantaṃ arahantaṃ sammāsambuddhaṃ etadavoca:**He arranged his robe over one shoulder, knelt on his right knee, raised his joined palms toward the Buddha Vipassī, and said,*";
P_HTM[705]="*‘evametaṃ, bhagavā, evametaṃ, sugata.**‘That’s so true, Blessed One! That’s so true, Holy One!*";
P_HTM[706]="*Mahā kho, bhante, etarahi bhikkhusaṃgho bandhumatiyā rājadhāniyā paṭivasati aṭṭhasaṭṭhibhikkhusatasahassaṃ, anujānātu, bhante, bhagavā bhikkhū:**The Saṅgha residing at Bandhumatī now is large. Please urge them to wander, as you thought.*";
P_HTM[707]="*“caratha, bhikkhave, cārikaṃ bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[708]="*mā ekena dve agamittha;* **";
P_HTM[709]="*desetha, bhikkhave, dhammaṃ ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāsetha.* **";
P_HTM[710]="*Santi sattā apparajakkhajātikā, assavanatā dhammassa parihāyanti, bhavissanti dhammassa aññātāro”ti.* **";
P_HTM[711]="*Api ca, bhante, mayaṃ tathā karissāma yathā bhikkhū channaṃ channaṃ vassānaṃ accayena bandhumatiṃ rājadhāniṃ upasaṅkamissanti pātimokkhuddesāyā’ti.**And sir, I’ll make sure that when six years have passed the mendicants will return to Bandhumatī to recite the monastic code.’*";
P_HTM[712]="*Idamavoca, bhikkhave, so mahābrahmā.**That’s what that Great Brahmā said.*";
P_HTM[713]="*Idaṃ vatvā vipassiṃ bhagavantaṃ arahantaṃ sammāsambuddhaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā tattheva antaradhāyi.**Then he bowed and respectfully circled the Buddha Vipassī, keeping him on his right side, before vanishing right there.*";
P_HTM[714]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then in the late afternoon, the Buddha Vipassī came out of retreat and addressed the mendicants, telling them all that had happened. Then he said,*";
P_HTM[715]="*‘idha mayhaṃ, bhikkhave, rahogatassa paṭisallīnassa evaṃ cetaso parivitakko udapādi:* **";
P_HTM[716]="*“mahā kho etarahi bhikkhusaṅgho bandhumatiyā rājadhāniyā paṭivasati aṭṭhasaṭṭhibhikkhusatasahassaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[717]="*Yannūnāhaṃ bhikkhū anujāneyyaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[718]="*caratha, bhikkhave, cārikaṃ bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[719]="*mā ekena dve agamittha;* **";
P_HTM[720]="*desetha, bhikkhave, dhammaṃ ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāsetha.* **";
P_HTM[721]="*Santi sattā apparajakkhajātikā, assavanatā dhammassa parihāyanti, bhavissanti dhammassa aññātāro.* **";
P_HTM[722]="*Api ca channaṃ channaṃ vassānaṃ accayena bandhumatī rājadhānī upasaṅkamitabbā pātimokkhuddesāyā”’ti.* **";
P_HTM[723]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, aññataro mahābrahmā mama cetasā cetoparivitakkamaññāya seyyathāpi nāma balavā puriso samiñjitaṃ vā bāhaṃ pasāreyya, pasāritaṃ vā bāhaṃ samiñjeyya; evameva—brahmaloke antarahito mama purato pāturahosi.* **";
P_HTM[724]="*Atha kho so, bhikkhave, mahābrahmā ekaṃsaṃ uttarāsaṅgaṃ karitvā yenāhaṃ tenañjaliṃ paṇāmetvā maṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[725]="*‘evametaṃ, bhagavā, evametaṃ, sugata.* **";
P_HTM[726]="*Mahā kho, bhante, etarahi bhikkhusaṅgho bandhumatiyā rājadhāniyā paṭivasati aṭṭhasaṭṭhibhikkhusatasahassaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[727]="*Anujānātu, bhante, bhagavā bhikkhū—* **";
P_HTM[728]="*caratha, bhikkhave, cārikaṃ bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[729]="*mā ekena dve agamittha;* **";
P_HTM[730]="*desetha, bhikkhave, dhammaṃ … pe …* **";
P_HTM[731]="*santi sattā apparajakkhajātikā, assavanatā dhammassa parihāyanti, bhavissanti dhammassa aññātāroti.* **";
P_HTM[732]="*Api ca, bhante, mayaṃ tathā karissāma, yathā bhikkhū channaṃ channaṃ vassānaṃ accayena bandhumatiṃ rājadhāniṃ upasaṅkamissanti pātimokkhuddesāyā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[733]="*Idamavoca, bhikkhave, so mahābrahmā.* **";
P_HTM[734]="*Idaṃ vatvā maṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā tattheva antaradhāyi.* **";
P_HTM[735]="*‘Anujānāmi, bhikkhave, caratha cārikaṃ bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ;**‘Wander forth, mendicants, for the welfare and happiness of the people, out of compassion for the world, for the benefit, welfare, and happiness of gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[736]="*mā ekena dve agamittha;**Let not two go by one road.*";
P_HTM[737]="*desetha, bhikkhave, dhammaṃ ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāsetha.**Teach the Dhamma that’s good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased. And reveal a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure.*";
P_HTM[738]="*Santi sattā apparajakkhajātikā, assavanatā dhammassa parihāyanti,**There are beings with little dust in their eyes. They’re in decline because they haven’t heard the teaching.*";
P_HTM[739]="*bhavissanti dhammassa aññātāro.**There will be those who understand the teaching!*";
P_HTM[740]="*Api ca, bhikkhave, channaṃ channaṃ vassānaṃ accayena bandhumatī rājadhānī upasaṅkamitabbā pātimokkhuddesāyā’ti.**But when six years have passed, you must all come to Bandhumatī to recite the monastic code.’*";
P_HTM[741]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhū yebhuyyena ekāheneva janapadacārikaṃ pakkamiṃsu.**Then most of the mendicants departed to wander the country that very day.*";
P_HTM[742]="*Tena kho pana samayena jambudīpe caturāsīti āvāsasahassāni honti.**Now at that time there were 84,000 monasteries in India.*";
P_HTM[743]="*Ekamhi hi vasse nikkhante devatā saddamanussāvesuṃ:**And when the first year came to an end the deities raised the cry:*";
P_HTM[744]="*‘nikkhantaṃ kho, mārisā, ekaṃ vassaṃ;**‘Good sirs, the first year has ended.*";
P_HTM[745]="*pañca dāni vassāni sesāni;**Now five years remain.*";
P_HTM[746]="*pañcannaṃ vassānaṃ accayena bandhumatī rājadhānī upasaṅkamitabbā pātimokkhuddesāyā’ti.**When five years have passed, you must all go to Bandhumatī to recite the monastic code.’*";
P_HTM[747]="*Dvīsu vassesu nikkhantesu …**And when the second year …*";
P_HTM[748]="*tīsu vassesu nikkhantesu …**the third year …*";
P_HTM[749]="*catūsu vassesu nikkhantesu …**the fourth year …*";
P_HTM[750]="*pañcasu vassesu nikkhantesu devatā saddamanussāvesuṃ:**the fifth year came to an end, the deities raised the cry:*";
P_HTM[751]="*‘nikkhantāni kho, mārisā, pañcavassāni;**‘Good sirs, the fifth year has ended.*";
P_HTM[752]="*ekaṃ dāni vassaṃ sesaṃ;**Now one year remains.*";
P_HTM[753]="*ekassa vassassa accayena bandhumatī rājadhānī upasaṅkamitabbā pātimokkhuddesāyā’ti.**When one year has passed, you must all go to Bandhumatī to recite the monastic code.’*";
P_HTM[754]="*Chasu vassesu nikkhantesu devatā saddamanussāvesuṃ:**And when the sixth year came to an end the deities raised the cry:*";
P_HTM[755]="*‘nikkhantāni kho, mārisā, chabbassāni,**‘Good sirs, the sixth year has ended.*";
P_HTM[756]="*samayo dāni bandhumatiṃ rājadhāniṃ upasaṅkamituṃ pātimokkhuddesāyā’ti.**Now is the time that you must go to Bandhumatī to recite the monastic code.’*";
P_HTM[757]="*Atha kho te, bhikkhave, bhikkhū appekacce sakena iddhānubhāvena appekacce devatānaṃ iddhānubhāvena ekāheneva bandhumatiṃ rājadhāniṃ upasaṅkamiṃsu pātimokkhuddesāyāti.**Then that very day the mendicants went to Bandhumatī to recite the monastic code. Some went by their own psychic power, and some by the psychic power of the deities.*";
P_HTM[758]="*Tatra sudaṃ, bhikkhave, vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho bhikkhusaṅghe evaṃ pātimokkhaṃ uddisati:**And there the Blessed One Vipassī, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha, recited the monastic code thus:*";
P_HTM[759]="*‘Khantī paramaṃ tapo titikkhā,**‘Patient acceptance is the highest austerity.*";
P_HTM[760]="*Nibbānaṃ paramaṃ vadanti buddhā;**Extinguishment is the highest, say the Buddhas.*";
P_HTM[761]="*Na hi pabbajito parūpaghātī,**No true renunciate injures another,*";
P_HTM[762]="*Na samaṇo hoti paraṃ viheṭhayanto.**nor does an ascetic hurt another.*";
P_HTM[763]="*Sabbapāpassa akaraṇaṃ,**Not to do any evil;*";
P_HTM[764]="*kusalassa upasampadā;**to embrace the good;*";
P_HTM[765]="*Sacittapariyodapanaṃ,**to purify one’s mind:*";
P_HTM[766]="*etaṃ buddhānasāsanaṃ.**this is the instruction of the Buddhas.*";
P_HTM[767]="*Anūpavādo anūpaghāto,**Not speaking ill nor doing harm;*";
P_HTM[768]="*Pātimokkhe ca saṃvaro;**restraint in the monastic code;*";
P_HTM[769]="*Mattaññutā ca bhattasmiṃ,**moderation in eating;*";
P_HTM[770]="*Pantañca sayanāsanaṃ;**staying in remote lodgings;*";
P_HTM[771]="*Adhicitte ca āyogo,**commitment to the higher mind—*";
P_HTM[772]="*Etaṃ buddhānasāsanan’ti.**this is the instruction of the Buddhas.’*";
P_HTM[773]="*17. Devatārocana**17. Being Informed by Deities*";
P_HTM[774]="*Ekamidāhaṃ, bhikkhave, samayaṃ ukkaṭṭhāyaṃ viharāmi subhagavane sālarājamūle.**At one time, mendicants, I was staying near Ukkaṭṭhā, in the Subhaga Forest at the root of a magnificent sal tree.*";
P_HTM[775]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhikkhave, rahogatassa paṭisallīnassa evaṃ cetaso parivitakko udapādi:**As I was in private retreat this thought came to mind,*";
P_HTM[776]="*‘na kho so sattāvāso sulabharūpo, yo mayā anāvutthapubbo iminā dīghena addhunā aññatra suddhāvāsehi devehi.**‘It’s not easy to find an abode of sentient beings where I haven’t previously abided in all this long time, except for the gods of the pure abodes.*";
P_HTM[777]="*Yannūnāhaṃ yena suddhāvāsā devā tenupasaṅkameyyan’ti.**Why don’t I go to see them?’*";
P_HTM[778]="*Atha khvāhaṃ, bhikkhave, seyyathāpi nāma balavā puriso samiñjitaṃ vā bāhaṃ pasāreyya, pasāritaṃ vā bāhaṃ samiñjeyya; evameva—ukkaṭṭhāyaṃ subhagavane sālarājamūle antarahito avihesu devesu pāturahosiṃ.**Then, as easily as a strong person would extend or contract their arm, I vanished from the Subhaga Forest and reappeared with the Aviha gods.*";
P_HTM[779]="*Tasmiṃ, bhikkhave, devanikāye anekāni devatāsahassāni anekāni devatāsatasahassāni yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā maṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu. Ekamantaṃ ṭhitā kho, bhikkhave, tā devatā maṃ etadavocuṃ:**In that order of gods, many thousands, many hundreds of thousands of deities approached me, bowed, stood to one side, and said to me,*";
P_HTM[780]="*‘ito so, mārisā, ekanavutikappe yaṃ vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho loke udapādi.**‘Ninety-one eons ago, good sir, the Buddha Vipassī arose in the world, perfected and fully awakened.*";
P_HTM[781]="*Vipassī, mārisā, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho khattiyo jātiyā ahosi, khattiyakule udapādi.**He was born as an aristocrat into an aristocrat family.*";
P_HTM[782]="*Vipassī, mārisā, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho koṇḍañño gottena ahosi.**Koṇḍañña was his clan.*";
P_HTM[783]="*Vipassissa, mārisā, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa asītivassasahassāni āyuppamāṇaṃ ahosi.**He lived for 80,000 years.*";
P_HTM[784]="*Vipassī, mārisā, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho pāṭaliyā mūle abhisambuddho.**He was awakened at the root of a trumpet flower tree.*";
P_HTM[785]="*Vipassissa, mārisā, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa khaṇḍatissaṃ nāma sāvakayugaṃ ahosi aggaṃ bhaddayugaṃ.**He had a fine pair of chief disciples named Khaṇḍa and Tissa.*";
P_HTM[786]="*Vipassissa, mārisā, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa tayo sāvakānaṃ sannipātā ahesuṃ. Eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi aṭṭhasaṭṭhibhikkhusatasahassaṃ. Eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi bhikkhusatasahassaṃ. Eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi asītibhikkhusahassāni. Vipassissa, mārisā, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa ime tayo sāvakānaṃ sannipātā ahesuṃ sabbesaṃyeva khīṇāsavānaṃ.**He had three gatherings of disciples—one of 6,800,000, one of 100,000, and one of 80,000—all of them mendicants who had ended their defilements.*";
P_HTM[787]="*Vipassissa, mārisā, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa asoko nāma bhikkhu upaṭṭhāko ahosi aggupaṭṭhāko.**He had as chief attendant a mendicant named Asoka.*";
P_HTM[788]="*Vipassissa, mārisā, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa bandhumā nāma rājā pitā ahosi.**His father was King Bandhuma,*";
P_HTM[789]="*Bandhumatī nāma devī mātā ahosi janetti.**his birth mother was Queen Bandhumatī,*";
P_HTM[790]="*Bandhumassa rañño bandhumatī nāma nagaraṃ rājadhānī ahosi.**and their capital city was named Bandhumatī.*";
P_HTM[791]="*Vipassissa, mārisā, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa evaṃ abhinikkhamanaṃ ahosi evaṃ pabbajjā evaṃ padhānaṃ evaṃ abhisambodhi evaṃ dhammacakkappavattanaṃ.**And such was his renunciation, such his going forth, such his striving, such his awakening, and such his rolling forth of the wheel of Dhamma.*";
P_HTM[792]="*Te mayaṃ, mārisā, vipassimhi bhagavati brahmacariyaṃ caritvā kāmesu kāmacchandaṃ virājetvā idhūpapannā’ti …**And good sir, after leading the spiritual life under that Buddha Vipassī we lost our desire for sensual pleasures and were reborn here.’*";
P_HTM[793]="*pe …**And other deities came and similarly recounted the details of the Buddhas Sikhī, Vessabhū, Kakusandha, Koṇāgamana, and Kassapa.*";
P_HTM[794]="*Tasmiṃyeva kho, bhikkhave, devanikāye anekāni devatāsahassāni anekāni devatāsatasahassāni yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā maṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu. Ekamantaṃ ṭhitā kho, bhikkhave, tā devatā maṃ etadavocuṃ:**In that order of gods, many hundreds of deities approached me, bowed, stood to one side, and said to me,*";
P_HTM[795]="*‘imasmiṃyeva kho, mārisā, bhaddakappe bhagavā etarahi arahaṃ sammāsambuddho loke uppanno.**‘In the present fortunate eon, good sir, you have arisen in the world, perfected and fully awakened.*";
P_HTM[796]="*Bhagavā, mārisā, khattiyo jātiyā khattiyakule uppanno.**You were born as an aristocrat into an aristocrat family.*";
P_HTM[797]="*Bhagavā, mārisā, gotamo gottena.**Gotama is your clan.*";
P_HTM[798]="*Bhagavato, mārisā, appakaṃ āyuppamāṇaṃ parittaṃ lahukaṃ yo ciraṃ jīvati, so vassasataṃ appaṃ vā bhiyyo.**For you the life-span is short, brief, and fleeting. A long-lived person lives for a century or a little more.*";
P_HTM[799]="*Bhagavā, mārisā, assatthassa mūle abhisambuddho.**You were awakened at the root of a peepul tree.*";
P_HTM[800]="*Bhagavato, mārisā, sāriputtamoggallānaṃ nāma sāvakayugaṃ ahosi aggaṃ bhaddayugaṃ.**You have a fine pair of chief disciples named Sāriputta and Moggallāna.*";
P_HTM[801]="*Bhagavato, mārisā, eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi aḍḍhateḷasāni bhikkhusatāni. Bhagavato, mārisā, ayaṃ eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi sabbesaṃyeva khīṇāsavānaṃ.**You have had one gathering of disciples—1,250 mendicants who had ended their defilements.*";
P_HTM[802]="*Bhagavato, mārisā, ānando nāma bhikkhu upaṭṭhāko ahosi aggupaṭṭhāko.**You have as chief attendant a mendicant named Ānanda.*";
P_HTM[803]="*Bhagavato, mārisā, suddhodano nāma rājā pitā ahosi.**Your father is King Suddhodana,*";
P_HTM[804]="*Māyā nāma devī mātā ahosi janetti.**your birth mother was Queen Māyā,*";
P_HTM[805]="*Kapilavatthu nāma nagaraṃ rājadhānī ahosi.**and your capital city was Kapilavatthu.*";
P_HTM[806]="*Bhagavato, mārisā, evaṃ abhinikkhamanaṃ ahosi evaṃ pabbajjā evaṃ padhānaṃ evaṃ abhisambodhi evaṃ dhammacakkappavattanaṃ.**And such was your renunciation, such your going forth, such your striving, such your awakening, and such your rolling forth of the wheel of Dhamma.*";
P_HTM[807]="*Te mayaṃ, mārisā, bhagavati brahmacariyaṃ caritvā kāmesu kāmacchandaṃ virājetvā idhūpapannā’ti.**And good sir, after leading the spiritual life under you we lost our desire for sensual pleasures and were reborn here.’*";
P_HTM[808]="*Atha khvāhaṃ, bhikkhave, avihehi devehi saddhiṃ yena atappā devā tenupasaṅkamiṃ … pe …**Then together with the Aviha gods I went to see the Atappa gods …*";
P_HTM[809]="*atha khvāhaṃ, bhikkhave, avihehi ca devehi atappehi ca devehi saddhiṃ yena sudassā devā tenupasaṅkamiṃ.**the Gods Fair to See …*";
P_HTM[810]="*Atha khvāhaṃ, bhikkhave, avihehi ca devehi atappehi ca devehi sudassehi ca devehi saddhiṃ yena sudassī devā tenupasaṅkamiṃ. Atha khvāhaṃ, bhikkhave, avihehi ca devehi atappehi ca devehi sudassehi ca devehi sudassīhi ca devehi saddhiṃ yena akaniṭṭhā devā tenupasaṅkamiṃ. Tasmiṃ, bhikkhave, devanikāye anekāni devatāsahassāni anekāni devatāsatasahassāni yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkamiṃsu, upasaṅkamitvā maṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu. Ekamantaṃ ṭhitā kho, bhikkhave, tā devatā maṃ etadavocuṃ:**and the Fair Seeing Gods. Then together with all these gods I went to see the Gods of Akaniṭṭha, where we had a similar conversation.*";
P_HTM[811]="*‘ito so, mārisā, ekanavutikappe yaṃ vipassī bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho loke udapādi.* **";
P_HTM[812]="*Vipassī, mārisā, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho khattiyo jātiyā ahosi.* **";
P_HTM[813]="*Khattiyakule udapādi.* **";
P_HTM[814]="*Vipassī, mārisā, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho koṇḍañño gottena ahosi.* **";
P_HTM[815]="*Vipassissa, mārisā, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa asītivassasahassāni āyuppamāṇaṃ ahosi.* **";
P_HTM[816]="*Vipassī, mārisā, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho pāṭaliyā mūle abhisambuddho.* **";
P_HTM[817]="*Vipassissa, mārisā, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa khaṇḍatissaṃ nāma sāvakayugaṃ ahosi aggaṃ bhaddayugaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[818]="*Vipassissa, mārisā, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa tayo sāvakānaṃ sannipātā ahesuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[819]="*Eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi aṭṭhasaṭṭhibhikkhusatasahassaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[820]="*Eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi bhikkhusatasahassaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[821]="*Eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi asītibhikkhusahassāni.* **";
P_HTM[822]="*Vipassissa, mārisā, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa ime tayo sāvakānaṃ sannipātā ahesuṃ sabbesaṃyeva khīṇāsavānaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[823]="*Vipassissa, mārisā, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa asoko nāma bhikkhu upaṭṭhāko ahosi aggupaṭṭhāko.* **";
P_HTM[824]="*Vipassissa, mārisā, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa bandhumā nāma rājā pitā ahosi bandhumatī nāma devī mātā ahosi janetti.* **";
P_HTM[825]="*Bandhumassa rañño bandhumatī nāma nagaraṃ rājadhānī ahosi.* **";
P_HTM[826]="*Vipassissa, mārisā, bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa evaṃ abhinikkhamanaṃ ahosi evaṃ pabbajjā evaṃ padhānaṃ evaṃ abhisambodhi, evaṃ dhammacakkappavattanaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[827]="*Te mayaṃ, mārisā, vipassimhi bhagavati brahmacariyaṃ caritvā kāmesu kāmacchandaṃ virājetvā idhūpapannā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[828]="*Tasmiṃyeva kho, bhikkhave, devanikāye anekāni devatāsahassāni anekāni devatāsatasahassāni yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā maṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu. Ekamantaṃ ṭhitā kho, bhikkhave, tā devatā maṃ etadavocuṃ:* **";
P_HTM[829]="*‘ito so, mārisā, ekatiṃse kappe yaṃ sikhī bhagavā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[830]="*te mayaṃ, mārisā, sikhimhi bhagavati tasmiññeva kho, mārisā, ekatiṃse kappe yaṃ vessabhū bhagavā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[831]="*te mayaṃ, mārisā, vessabhumhi bhagavati … pe …* **";
P_HTM[832]="*imasmiṃyeva kho, mārisā, bhaddakappe kakusandho koṇāgamano kassapo bhagavā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[833]="*te mayaṃ, mārisā, kakusandhamhi koṇāgamanamhi kassapamhi bhagavati brahmacariyaṃ caritvā kāmesu kāmacchandaṃ virājetvā idhūpapannā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[834]="*Tasmiṃyeva kho, bhikkhave, devanikāye anekāni devatāsahassāni anekāni devatāsatasahassāni yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā maṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu. Ekamantaṃ ṭhitā kho, bhikkhave, tā devatā maṃ etadavocuṃ:* **";
P_HTM[835]="*‘imasmiṃyeva kho, mārisā, bhaddakappe bhagavā etarahi arahaṃ sammāsambuddho loke uppanno.* **";
P_HTM[836]="*Bhagavā, mārisā, khattiyo jātiyā, khattiyakule uppanno.* **";
P_HTM[837]="*Bhagavā, mārisā, gotamo gottena.* **";
P_HTM[838]="*Bhagavato, mārisā, appakaṃ āyuppamāṇaṃ parittaṃ lahukaṃ yo ciraṃ jīvati, so vassasataṃ appaṃ vā bhiyyo.* **";
P_HTM[839]="*Bhagavā, mārisā, assatthassa mūle abhisambuddho.* **";
P_HTM[840]="*Bhagavato, mārisā, sāriputtamoggallānaṃ nāma sāvakayugaṃ ahosi aggaṃ bhaddayugaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[841]="*Bhagavato, mārisā, eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi aḍḍhateḷasāni bhikkhusatāni.* **";
P_HTM[842]="*Bhagavato, mārisā, ayaṃ eko sāvakānaṃ sannipāto ahosi sabbesaṃyeva khīṇāsavānaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[843]="*Bhagavato, mārisā, ānando nāma bhikkhu upaṭṭhāko aggupaṭṭhāko ahosi.* **";
P_HTM[844]="*Bhagavato, mārisā, suddhodano nāma rājā pitā ahosi.* **";
P_HTM[845]="*Māyā nāma devī mātā ahosi janetti.* **";
P_HTM[846]="*Kapilavatthu nāma nagaraṃ rājadhānī ahosi.* **";
P_HTM[847]="*Bhagavato, mārisā, evaṃ abhinikkhamanaṃ ahosi, evaṃ pabbajjā, evaṃ padhānaṃ, evaṃ abhisambodhi, evaṃ dhammacakkappavattanaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[848]="*Te mayaṃ, mārisā, bhagavati brahmacariyaṃ caritvā kāmesu kāmacchandaṃ virājetvā idhūpapannā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[849]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, tathāgatassevesā dhammadhātu suppaṭividdhā, yassā dhammadhātuyā suppaṭividdhattā tathāgato atīte buddhe parinibbute chinnapapañce chinnavaṭume pariyādinnavaṭṭe sabbadukkhavītivatte jātitopi anussarati, nāmatopi anussarati, gottatopi anussarati, āyuppamāṇatopi anussarati, sāvakayugatopi anussarati, sāvakasannipātatopi anussarati ‘evaṃjaccā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ’ itipi.**And that is how the Realized One is able to recollect the caste, names, clans, life-span, chief disciples, and gatherings of disciples of the Buddhas of the past who have become completely extinguished, cut off proliferation, cut off the track, finished off the cycle, and transcended suffering. It is both because I have clearly comprehended the principle of the teachings,*";
P_HTM[850]="*‘Evaṃnāmā evaṅgottā evaṃsīlā evaṃdhammā evaṃpaññā evaṃvihārī evaṃvimuttā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ’ itipīti.* **";
P_HTM[851]="*Devatāpi tathāgatassa etamatthaṃ ārocesuṃ, yena tathāgato atīte buddhe parinibbute chinnapapañce chinnavaṭume pariyādinnavaṭṭe sabbadukkhavītivatte jātitopi anussarati, nāmatopi anussarati, gottatopi anussarati, āyuppamāṇatopi anussarati, sāvakayugatopi anussarati, sāvakasannipātatopi anussarati ‘evaṃjaccā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ’ itipi.**and also because the deities told me.”*";
P_HTM[852]="*‘Evaṃnāmā evaṅgottā evaṃsīlā evaṃdhammā evaṃpaññā evaṃvihārī evaṃvimuttā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ’ itipī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[853]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[854]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[855]="*Mahāpadānasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[856]="*15. Mahānidānasutta  ** The Great Discourse on Causation *";
P_HTM[857]="*1. Paṭiccasamuppāda**1. Dependent Origination*";
P_HTM[858]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[859]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā kurūsu viharati kammāsadhammaṃ nāma kurūnaṃ nigamo.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Kurus, near the Kuru town named Kammāsadamma.*";
P_HTM[860]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami, upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Ānanda went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[861]="*“acchariyaṃ, bhante, abbhutaṃ, bhante.**“It’s incredible, sir, it’s amazing,*";
P_HTM[862]="*Yāva gambhīro cāyaṃ, bhante, paṭiccasamuppādo gambhīrāvabhāso ca, atha ca pana me uttānakuttānako viya khāyatī”ti.**in that this dependent origination is deep and appears deep, yet to me it seems as plain as can be.”*";
P_HTM[863]="*“Mā hevaṃ, ānanda, avaca, mā hevaṃ, ānanda, avaca.**“Don’t say that, Ānanda, don’t say that!*";
P_HTM[864]="*Gambhīro cāyaṃ, ānanda, paṭiccasamuppādo gambhīrāvabhāso ca.**This dependent origination is deep and appears deep.*";
P_HTM[865]="*Etassa, ānanda, dhammassa ananubodhā appaṭivedhā evamayaṃ pajā tantākulakajātā kulagaṇṭhikajātā muñjapabbajabhūtā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ saṃsāraṃ nātivattati.**It is because of not understanding and not penetrating this teaching that this population has become tangled like string, knotted like a ball of thread, and matted like rushes and reeds, and it doesn’t escape the places of loss, the bad places, the underworld, transmigration.*";
P_HTM[866]="*‘Atthi idappaccayā jarāmaraṇan’ti iti puṭṭhena satā, ānanda, atthītissa vacanīyaṃ.**When asked, ‘Is there a specific condition for old age and death?’ you should answer, ‘There is.’*";
P_HTM[867]="*‘Kiṃpaccayā jarāmaraṇan’ti iti ce vadeyya, ‘jātipaccayā jarāmaraṇan’ti iccassa vacanīyaṃ.**If they say, ‘What is a condition for old age and death?’ you should answer, ‘Rebirth is a condition for old age and death.’*";
P_HTM[868]="*‘Atthi idappaccayā jātī’ti iti puṭṭhena satā, ānanda, atthītissa vacanīyaṃ.**When asked, ‘Is there a specific condition for rebirth?’ you should answer, ‘There is.’*";
P_HTM[869]="*‘Kiṃpaccayā jātī’ti iti ce vadeyya, ‘bhavapaccayā jātī’ti iccassa vacanīyaṃ.**If they say, ‘What is a condition for rebirth?’ you should answer, ‘Continued existence is a condition for rebirth.’*";
P_HTM[870]="*‘Atthi idappaccayā bhavo’ti iti puṭṭhena satā, ānanda, atthītissa vacanīyaṃ.**When asked, ‘Is there a specific condition for continued existence?’ you should answer, ‘There is.’*";
P_HTM[871]="*‘Kiṃpaccayā bhavo’ti iti ce vadeyya, ‘upādānapaccayā bhavo’ti iccassa vacanīyaṃ.**If they say, ‘What is a condition for continued existence?’ you should answer, ‘Grasping is a condition for continued existence.’*";
P_HTM[872]="*‘Atthi idappaccayā upādānan’ti iti puṭṭhena satā, ānanda, atthītissa vacanīyaṃ.**When asked, ‘Is there a specific condition for grasping?’ you should answer, ‘There is.’*";
P_HTM[873]="*‘Kiṃpaccayā upādānan’ti iti ce vadeyya, ‘taṇhāpaccayā upādānan’ti iccassa vacanīyaṃ.**If they say, ‘What is a condition for grasping?’ you should answer, ‘Craving is a condition for grasping.’*";
P_HTM[874]="*‘Atthi idappaccayā taṇhā’ti iti puṭṭhena satā, ānanda, atthītissa vacanīyaṃ.**When asked, ‘Is there a specific condition for craving?’ you should answer, ‘There is.’*";
P_HTM[875]="*‘Kiṃpaccayā taṇhā’ti iti ce vadeyya, ‘vedanāpaccayā taṇhā’ti iccassa vacanīyaṃ.**If they say, ‘What is a condition for craving?’ you should answer, ‘Feeling is a condition for craving.’*";
P_HTM[876]="*‘Atthi idappaccayā vedanā’ti iti puṭṭhena satā, ānanda, atthītissa vacanīyaṃ.**When asked, ‘Is there a specific condition for feeling?’ you should answer, ‘There is.’*";
P_HTM[877]="*‘Kiṃpaccayā vedanā’ti iti ce vadeyya, ‘phassapaccayā vedanā’ti iccassa vacanīyaṃ.**If they say, ‘What is a condition for feeling?’ you should answer, ‘Contact is a condition for feeling.’*";
P_HTM[878]="*‘Atthi idappaccayā phasso’ti iti puṭṭhena satā, ānanda, atthītissa vacanīyaṃ.**When asked, ‘Is there a specific condition for contact?’ you should answer, ‘There is.’*";
P_HTM[879]="*‘Kiṃpaccayā phasso’ti iti ce vadeyya, ‘nāmarūpapaccayā phasso’ti iccassa vacanīyaṃ.**If they say, ‘What is a condition for contact?’ you should answer, ‘Name and form are conditions for contact.’*";
P_HTM[880]="*‘Atthi idappaccayā nāmarūpan’ti iti puṭṭhena satā, ānanda, atthītissa vacanīyaṃ.**When asked, ‘Is there a specific condition for name and form?’ you should answer, ‘There is.’*";
P_HTM[881]="*‘Kiṃpaccayā nāmarūpan’ti iti ce vadeyya, ‘viññāṇapaccayā nāmarūpan’ti iccassa vacanīyaṃ.**If they say, ‘What is a condition for name and form?’ you should answer, ‘Consciousness is a condition for name and form.’*";
P_HTM[882]="*‘Atthi idappaccayā viññāṇan’ti iti puṭṭhena satā, ānanda, atthītissa vacanīyaṃ.**When asked, ‘Is there a specific condition for consciousness?’ you should answer, ‘There is.’*";
P_HTM[883]="*‘Kiṃpaccayā viññāṇan’ti iti ce vadeyya, ‘nāmarūpapaccayā viññāṇan’ti iccassa vacanīyaṃ.**If they say, ‘What is a condition for consciousness?’ you should answer, ‘Name and form are conditions for consciousness.’*";
P_HTM[884]="*Iti kho, ānanda, nāmarūpapaccayā viññāṇaṃ, viññāṇapaccayā nāmarūpaṃ, nāmarūpapaccayā phasso, phassapaccayā vedanā, vedanāpaccayā taṇhā, taṇhāpaccayā upādānaṃ, upādānapaccayā bhavo, bhavapaccayā jāti, jātipaccayā jarāmaraṇaṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā sambhavanti.**So: name and form are conditions for consciousness. Consciousness is a condition for name and form. Name and form are conditions for contact. Contact is a condition for feeling. Feeling is a condition for craving. Craving is a condition for grasping. Grasping is a condition for continued existence. Continued existence is a condition for rebirth. Rebirth is a condition for old age and death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress to come to be.*";
P_HTM[885]="*Evametassa kevalassa dukkhakkhandhassa samudayo hoti.**That is how this entire mass of suffering originates.*";
P_HTM[886]="*‘Jātipaccayā jarāmaraṇan’ti iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ, tadānanda, imināpetaṃ pariyāyena veditabbaṃ, yathā jātipaccayā jarāmaraṇaṃ.**‘Rebirth is a condition for old age and death’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.*";
P_HTM[887]="*Jāti ca hi, ānanda, nābhavissa sabbena sabbaṃ sabbathā sabbaṃ kassaci kimhici, seyyathidaṃ—**Suppose there were totally and utterly no rebirth for anyone anywhere.*";
P_HTM[888]="*devānaṃ vā devattāya, gandhabbānaṃ vā gandhabbattāya, yakkhānaṃ vā yakkhattāya, bhūtānaṃ vā bhūtattāya, manussānaṃ vā manussattāya, catuppadānaṃ vā catuppadattāya, pakkhīnaṃ vā pakkhittāya, sarīsapānaṃ vā sarīsapattāya, tesaṃ tesañca hi, ānanda, sattānaṃ tadattāya jāti nābhavissa. Sabbaso jātiyā asati jātinirodhā api nu kho jarāmaraṇaṃ paññāyethā”ti?**That is, there were no rebirth of sentient beings into their various realms—of gods, fairies, spirits, creatures, humans, quadrupeds, birds, or reptiles, each into their own realm. When there’s no rebirth at all, with the cessation of rebirth, would old age and death still be found?”*";
P_HTM[889]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[890]="*“Tasmātihānanda, eseva hetu etaṃ nidānaṃ esa samudayo esa paccayo jarāmaraṇassa, yadidaṃ jāti.**“That’s why this is the cause, source, origin, and condition of old age and death, namely rebirth.*";
P_HTM[891]="*‘Bhavapaccayā jātī’ti iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ, tadānanda, imināpetaṃ pariyāyena veditabbaṃ, yathā bhavapaccayā jāti.**‘Continued existence is a condition for rebirth’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.*";
P_HTM[892]="*Bhavo ca hi, ānanda, nābhavissa sabbena sabbaṃ sabbathā sabbaṃ kassaci kimhici, seyyathidaṃ—**Suppose there were totally and utterly no continued existence for anyone anywhere.*";
P_HTM[893]="*kāmabhavo vā rūpabhavo vā arūpabhavo vā, sabbaso bhave asati bhavanirodhā api nu kho jāti paññāyethā”ti?**That is, continued existence in the sensual realm, the realm of luminous form, or the formless realm. When there’s no continued existence at all, with the cessation of continued existence, would rebirth still be found?”*";
P_HTM[894]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[895]="*“Tasmātihānanda, eseva hetu etaṃ nidānaṃ esa samudayo esa paccayo jātiyā, yadidaṃ bhavo.**“That’s why this is the cause, source, origin, and condition of rebirth, namely continued existence.*";
P_HTM[896]="*‘Upādānapaccayā bhavo’ti iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ, tadānanda, imināpetaṃ pariyāyena veditabbaṃ, yathā upādānapaccayā bhavo.**‘Grasping is a condition for continued existence’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.*";
P_HTM[897]="*Upādānañca hi, ānanda, nābhavissa sabbena sabbaṃ sabbathā sabbaṃ kassaci kimhici, seyyathidaṃ—**Suppose there were totally and utterly no grasping for anyone anywhere.*";
P_HTM[898]="*kāmupādānaṃ vā diṭṭhupādānaṃ vā sīlabbatupādānaṃ vā attavādupādānaṃ vā, sabbaso upādāne asati upādānanirodhā api nu kho bhavo paññāyethā”ti?**That is, grasping at sensual pleasures, views, precepts and observances, and theories of a self. When there’s no grasping at all, with the cessation of grasping, would continued existence still be found?”*";
P_HTM[899]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[900]="*“Tasmātihānanda, eseva hetu etaṃ nidānaṃ esa samudayo esa paccayo bhavassa, yadidaṃ upādānaṃ.**“That’s why this is the cause, source, origin, and condition of continued existence, namely grasping.*";
P_HTM[901]="*‘Taṇhāpaccayā upādānan’ti iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ tadānanda, imināpetaṃ pariyāyena veditabbaṃ, yathā taṇhāpaccayā upādānaṃ.**‘Craving is a condition for grasping’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.*";
P_HTM[902]="*Taṇhā ca hi, ānanda, nābhavissa sabbena sabbaṃ sabbathā sabbaṃ kassaci kimhici, seyyathidaṃ—**Suppose there were totally and utterly no craving for anyone anywhere.*";
P_HTM[903]="*rūpataṇhā saddataṇhā gandhataṇhā rasataṇhā phoṭṭhabbataṇhā dhammataṇhā, sabbaso taṇhāya asati taṇhānirodhā api nu kho upādānaṃ paññāyethā”ti?**That is, craving for sights, sounds, smells, tastes, touches, and thoughts. When there’s no craving at all, with the cessation of craving, would grasping still be found?”*";
P_HTM[904]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[905]="*“Tasmātihānanda, eseva hetu etaṃ nidānaṃ esa samudayo esa paccayo upādānassa, yadidaṃ taṇhā.**“That’s why this is the cause, source, origin, and condition of grasping, namely craving.*";
P_HTM[906]="*‘Vedanāpaccayā taṇhā’ti iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ, tadānanda, imināpetaṃ pariyāyena veditabbaṃ, yathā vedanāpaccayā taṇhā.**‘Feeling is a condition for craving’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.*";
P_HTM[907]="*Vedanā ca hi, ānanda, nābhavissa sabbena sabbaṃ sabbathā sabbaṃ kassaci kimhici, seyyathidaṃ—**Suppose there were totally and utterly no feeling for anyone anywhere.*";
P_HTM[908]="*cakkhusamphassajā vedanā sotasamphassajā vedanā ghānasamphassajā vedanā jivhāsamphassajā vedanā kāyasamphassajā vedanā manosamphassajā vedanā, sabbaso vedanāya asati vedanānirodhā api nu kho taṇhā paññāyethā”ti?**That is, feeling born of contact through the eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind. When there’s no feeling at all, with the cessation of feeling, would craving still be found?”*";
P_HTM[909]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[910]="*“Tasmātihānanda, eseva hetu etaṃ nidānaṃ esa samudayo esa paccayo taṇhāya, yadidaṃ vedanā.**“That’s why this is the cause, source, origin, and condition of craving, namely feeling.*";
P_HTM[911]="*Iti kho panetaṃ, ānanda, vedanaṃ paṭicca taṇhā, taṇhaṃ paṭicca pariyesanā, pariyesanaṃ paṭicca lābho, lābhaṃ paṭicca vinicchayo, vinicchayaṃ paṭicca chandarāgo, chandarāgaṃ paṭicca ajjhosānaṃ, ajjhosānaṃ paṭicca pariggaho, pariggahaṃ paṭicca macchariyaṃ, macchariyaṃ paṭicca ārakkho.**So it is, Ānanda, that feeling is a cause of craving. Craving is a cause of seeking. Seeking is a cause of gaining material possessions. Gaining material possessions is a cause of assessing. Assessing is a cause of desire and lust. Desire and lust is a cause of attachment. Attachment is a cause of possessiveness. Possessiveness is a cause of stinginess. Stinginess is a cause of safeguarding.*";
P_HTM[912]="*Ārakkhādhikaraṇaṃ daṇḍādānasatthādānakalahaviggahavivādatuvaṃtuvaṃpesuññamusāvādā aneke pāpakā akusalā dhammā sambhavanti.**Owing to safeguarding, many bad, unskillful things come to be: taking up the rod and the sword, quarrels, arguments, and fights, accusations, divisive speech, and lies.*";
P_HTM[913]="*‘Ārakkhādhikaraṇaṃ daṇḍādānasatthādānakalahaviggahavivādatuvaṃtuvaṃpesuññamusāvādā aneke pāpakā akusalā dhammā sambhavantī’ti iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ, tadānanda, imināpetaṃ pariyāyena veditabbaṃ, yathā ārakkhādhikaraṇaṃ daṇḍādānasatthādānakalahaviggahavivādatuvaṃtuvaṃpesuññamusāvādā aneke pāpakā akusalā dhammā sambhavanti.**‘Owing to safeguarding, many bad, unskillful things come to be: taking up the rod and the sword, quarrels, arguments, and fights, accusations, divisive speech, and lies’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.*";
P_HTM[914]="*Ārakkho ca hi, ānanda, nābhavissa sabbena sabbaṃ sabbathā sabbaṃ kassaci kimhici, sabbaso ārakkhe asati ārakkhanirodhā api nu kho daṇḍādānasatthādānakalahaviggahavivādatuvaṃtuvaṃpesuññamusāvādā aneke pāpakā akusalā dhammā sambhaveyyun”ti?**Suppose there were totally and utterly no safeguarding for anyone anywhere. When there’s no safeguarding at all, with the cessation of safeguarding, would those many bad, unskillful things still come to be?”*";
P_HTM[915]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[916]="*“Tasmātihānanda, eseva hetu etaṃ nidānaṃ esa samudayo esa paccayo daṇḍādānasatthādānakalahaviggahavivādatuvaṃtuvaṃpesuññamusāvādānaṃ anekesaṃ pāpakānaṃ akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ sambhavāya yadidaṃ ārakkho.**“That’s why this is the cause, source, origin, and condition for the origination of those many bad, unskillful things, namely safeguarding.*";
P_HTM[917]="*‘Macchariyaṃ paṭicca ārakkho’ti iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ, tadānanda, imināpetaṃ pariyāyena veditabbaṃ, yathā macchariyaṃ paṭicca ārakkho.**‘Stinginess is a cause of safeguarding’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.*";
P_HTM[918]="*Macchariyañca hi, ānanda, nābhavissa sabbena sabbaṃ sabbathā sabbaṃ kassaci kimhici, sabbaso macchariye asati macchariyanirodhā api nu kho ārakkho paññāyethā”ti?**Suppose there were totally and utterly no stinginess for anyone anywhere. When there’s no stinginess at all, with the cessation of stinginess, would safeguarding still be found?”*";
P_HTM[919]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[920]="*“Tasmātihānanda, eseva hetu etaṃ nidānaṃ esa samudayo esa paccayo ārakkhassa, yadidaṃ macchariyaṃ.**“That’s why this is the cause, source, origin, and condition of safeguarding, namely stinginess.*";
P_HTM[921]="*‘Pariggahaṃ paṭicca macchariyan’ti iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ, tadānanda, imināpetaṃ pariyāyena veditabbaṃ, yathā pariggahaṃ paṭicca macchariyaṃ.**‘Possessiveness is a cause of stinginess’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.*";
P_HTM[922]="*Pariggaho ca hi, ānanda, nābhavissa sabbena sabbaṃ sabbathā sabbaṃ kassaci kimhici, sabbaso pariggahe asati pariggahanirodhā api nu kho macchariyaṃ paññāyethā”ti?**Suppose there were totally and utterly no possessiveness for anyone anywhere. When there’s no possessiveness at all, with the cessation of possessiveness, would stinginess still be found?”*";
P_HTM[923]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[924]="*“Tasmātihānanda, eseva hetu etaṃ nidānaṃ esa samudayo esa paccayo macchariyassa, yadidaṃ pariggaho.**“That’s why this is the cause, source, origin, and condition of stinginess, namely possessiveness.*";
P_HTM[925]="*‘Ajjhosānaṃ paṭicca pariggaho’ti iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ, tadānanda, imināpetaṃ pariyāyena veditabbaṃ, yathā ajjhosānaṃ paṭicca pariggaho.**‘Attachment is a cause of possessiveness’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.*";
P_HTM[926]="*Ajjhosānañca hi, ānanda, nābhavissa sabbena sabbaṃ sabbathā sabbaṃ kassaci kimhici, sabbaso ajjhosāne asati ajjhosānanirodhā api nu kho pariggaho paññāyethā”ti?**Suppose there were totally and utterly no attachment for anyone anywhere. When there’s no attachment at all, with the cessation of attachment, would possessiveness still be found?”*";
P_HTM[927]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[928]="*“Tasmātihānanda, eseva hetu etaṃ nidānaṃ esa samudayo esa paccayo pariggahassa—yadidaṃ ajjhosānaṃ.**“That’s why this is the cause, source, origin, and condition of possessiveness, namely attachment.*";
P_HTM[929]="*‘Chandarāgaṃ paṭicca ajjhosānan’ti iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ, tadānanda, imināpetaṃ pariyāyena veditabbaṃ, yathā chandarāgaṃ paṭicca ajjhosānaṃ.**‘Desire and lust is a cause of attachment’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.*";
P_HTM[930]="*Chandarāgo ca hi, ānanda, nābhavissa sabbena sabbaṃ sabbathā sabbaṃ kassaci kimhici, sabbaso chandarāge asati chandarāganirodhā api nu kho ajjhosānaṃ paññāyethā”ti?**Suppose there were totally and utterly no desire and lust for anyone anywhere. When there’s no desire and lust at all, with the cessation of desire and lust, would attachment still be found?”*";
P_HTM[931]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[932]="*“Tasmātihānanda, eseva hetu etaṃ nidānaṃ esa samudayo esa paccayo ajjhosānassa, yadidaṃ chandarāgo.**“That’s why this is the cause, source, origin, and condition of attachment, namely desire and lust.*";
P_HTM[933]="*‘Vinicchayaṃ paṭicca chandarāgo’ti iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ, tadānanda, imināpetaṃ pariyāyena veditabbaṃ, yathā vinicchayaṃ paṭicca chandarāgo.**‘Assessing is a cause of desire and lust’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.*";
P_HTM[934]="*Vinicchayo ca hi, ānanda, nābhavissa sabbena sabbaṃ sabbathā sabbaṃ kassaci kimhici, sabbaso vinicchaye asati vinicchayanirodhā api nu kho chandarāgo paññāyethā”ti?**Suppose there were totally and utterly no assessing for anyone anywhere. When there’s no assessing at all, with the cessation of assessing, would desire and lust still be found?”*";
P_HTM[935]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[936]="*“Tasmātihānanda, eseva hetu etaṃ nidānaṃ esa samudayo esa paccayo chandarāgassa, yadidaṃ vinicchayo.**“That’s why this is the cause, source, origin, and condition of desire and lust, namely assessing.*";
P_HTM[937]="*‘Lābhaṃ paṭicca vinicchayo’ti iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ, tadānanda, imināpetaṃ pariyāyena veditabbaṃ, yathā lābhaṃ paṭicca vinicchayo.**‘Gaining material possessions is a cause of assessing’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.*";
P_HTM[938]="*Lābho ca hi, ānanda, nābhavissa sabbena sabbaṃ sabbathā sabbaṃ kassaci kimhici, sabbaso lābhe asati lābhanirodhā api nu kho vinicchayo paññāyethā”ti?**Suppose there were totally and utterly no gaining of material possessions for anyone anywhere. When there’s no gaining of material possessions at all, with the cessation of gaining material possessions, would assessing still be found?”*";
P_HTM[939]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[940]="*“Tasmātihānanda, eseva hetu etaṃ nidānaṃ esa samudayo esa paccayo vinicchayassa, yadidaṃ lābho.**“That’s why this is the cause, source, origin, and condition of assessing, namely the gaining of material possessions.*";
P_HTM[941]="*‘Pariyesanaṃ paṭicca lābho’ti iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ, tadānanda, imināpetaṃ pariyāyena veditabbaṃ, yathā pariyesanaṃ paṭicca lābho.**‘Seeking is a cause of gaining material possessions’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.*";
P_HTM[942]="*Pariyesanā ca hi, ānanda, nābhavissa sabbena sabbaṃ sabbathā sabbaṃ kassaci kimhici, sabbaso pariyesanāya asati pariyesanānirodhā api nu kho lābho paññāyethā”ti?**Suppose there were totally and utterly no seeking for anyone anywhere. When there’s no seeking at all, with the cessation of seeking, would the gaining of material possessions still be found?”*";
P_HTM[943]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[944]="*“Tasmātihānanda, eseva hetu etaṃ nidānaṃ esa samudayo esa paccayo lābhassa, yadidaṃ pariyesanā.**“That’s why this is the cause, source, origin, and condition of gaining material possessions, namely seeking.*";
P_HTM[945]="*‘Taṇhaṃ paṭicca pariyesanā’ti iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ, tadānanda, imināpetaṃ pariyāyena veditabbaṃ, yathā taṇhaṃ paṭicca pariyesanā.**‘Craving is a cause of seeking’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.*";
P_HTM[946]="*Taṇhā ca hi, ānanda, nābhavissa sabbena sabbaṃ sabbathā sabbaṃ kassaci kimhici, seyyathidaṃ—**Suppose there were totally and utterly no craving for anyone anywhere.*";
P_HTM[947]="*kāmataṇhā bhavataṇhā vibhavataṇhā, sabbaso taṇhāya asati taṇhānirodhā api nu kho pariyesanā paññāyethā”ti?**That is, craving for sensual pleasures, craving for continued existence, and craving to end existence. When there’s no craving at all, with the cessation of craving, would seeking still be found?”*";
P_HTM[948]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[949]="*“Tasmātihānanda, eseva hetu etaṃ nidānaṃ esa samudayo esa paccayo pariyesanāya, yadidaṃ taṇhā.**“That’s why this is the cause, source, origin, and condition of seeking, namely craving.*";
P_HTM[950]="*Iti kho, ānanda, ime dve dhammā dvayena vedanāya ekasamosaraṇā bhavanti.**And so, Ānanda, these two things are united by the two aspects of feeling.*";
P_HTM[951]="*‘Phassapaccayā vedanā’ti iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ, tadānanda, imināpetaṃ pariyāyena veditabbaṃ, yathā phassapaccayā vedanā.**‘Contact is a condition for feeling’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.*";
P_HTM[952]="*Phasso ca hi, ānanda, nābhavissa sabbena sabbaṃ sabbathā sabbaṃ kassaci kimhici, seyyathidaṃ—**Suppose there were totally and utterly no contact for anyone anywhere.*";
P_HTM[953]="*cakkhusamphasso sotasamphasso ghānasamphasso jivhāsamphasso kāyasamphasso manosamphasso, sabbaso phasse asati phassanirodhā api nu kho vedanā paññāyethā”ti?**That is, contact through the eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind. When there’s no contact at all, with the cessation of contact, would feeling still be found?”*";
P_HTM[954]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[955]="*“Tasmātihānanda, eseva hetu etaṃ nidānaṃ esa samudayo esa paccayo vedanāya, yadidaṃ phasso.**“That’s why this is the cause, source, origin, and condition of feeling, namely contact.*";
P_HTM[956]="*‘Nāmarūpapaccayā phasso’ti iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ, tadānanda, imināpetaṃ pariyāyena veditabbaṃ, yathā nāmarūpapaccayā phasso.**‘Name and form are conditions for contact’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.*";
P_HTM[957]="*Yehi, ānanda, ākārehi yehi liṅgehi yehi nimittehi yehi uddesehi nāmakāyassa paññatti hoti, tesu ākāresu tesu liṅgesu tesu nimittesu tesu uddesesu asati api nu kho rūpakāye adhivacanasamphasso paññāyethā”ti?**Suppose there were none of the features, attributes, signs, and details by which the category of mental phenomena is found. Would linguistic contact still be found in the category of physical phenomena?”*";
P_HTM[958]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[959]="*“Yehi, ānanda, ākārehi yehi liṅgehi yehi nimittehi yehi uddesehi rūpakāyassa paññatti hoti, tesu ākāresu … pe … tesu uddesesu asati api nu kho nāmakāye paṭighasamphasso paññāyethā”ti?**“Suppose there were none of the features, attributes, signs, and details by which the category of physical phenomena is found. Would impingement contact still be found in the category of mental phenomena?”*";
P_HTM[960]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[961]="*“Yehi, ānanda, ākārehi … pe … yehi uddesehi nāmakāyassa ca rūpakāyassa ca paññatti hoti, tesu ākāresu … pe … tesu uddesesu asati api nu kho adhivacanasamphasso vā paṭighasamphasso vā paññāyethā”ti?**“Suppose there were none of the features, attributes, signs, and details by which the categories of mental or physical phenomena are found. Would either linguistic contact or impingement contact still be found?”*";
P_HTM[962]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[963]="*“Yehi, ānanda, ākārehi … pe … yehi uddesehi nāmarūpassa paññatti hoti, tesu ākāresu … pe … tesu uddesesu asati api nu kho phasso paññāyethā”ti?**“Suppose there were none of the features, attributes, signs, and details by which name and form are found. Would contact still be found?”*";
P_HTM[964]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[965]="*“Tasmātihānanda, eseva hetu etaṃ nidānaṃ esa samudayo esa paccayo phassassa, yadidaṃ nāmarūpaṃ.**“That’s why this is the cause, source, origin, and condition of contact, namely name and form.*";
P_HTM[966]="*‘Viññāṇapaccayā nāmarūpan’ti iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ, tadānanda, imināpetaṃ pariyāyena veditabbaṃ, yathā viññāṇapaccayā nāmarūpaṃ.**‘Consciousness is a condition for name and form’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.*";
P_HTM[967]="*Viññāṇañca hi, ānanda, mātukucchismiṃ na okkamissatha, api nu kho nāmarūpaṃ mātukucchismiṃ samuccissathā”ti?**If consciousness were not conceived in the mother’s womb, would name and form coagulate there?”*";
P_HTM[968]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[969]="*“Viññāṇañca hi, ānanda, mātukucchismiṃ okkamitvā vokkamissatha, api nu kho nāmarūpaṃ itthattāya abhinibbattissathā”ti?**“If consciousness, after being conceived in the mother’s womb, were to be miscarried, would name and form be born into this state of existence?”*";
P_HTM[970]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[971]="*“Viññāṇañca hi, ānanda, daharasseva sato vocchijjissatha kumārakassa vā kumārikāya vā, api nu kho nāmarūpaṃ vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjissathā”ti?**“If the consciousness of a young boy or girl were to be cut off, would name and form achieve growth, increase, and maturity?”*";
P_HTM[972]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[973]="*“Tasmātihānanda, eseva hetu etaṃ nidānaṃ esa samudayo esa paccayo nāmarūpassa—yadidaṃ viññāṇaṃ.**“That’s why this is the cause, source, origin, and condition of name and form, namely consciousness.*";
P_HTM[974]="*‘Nāmarūpapaccayā viññāṇan’ti iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ, tadānanda, imināpetaṃ pariyāyena veditabbaṃ, yathā nāmarūpapaccayā viññāṇaṃ.**‘Name and form are conditions for consciousness’—that’s what I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so.*";
P_HTM[975]="*Viññāṇañca hi, ānanda, nāmarūpe patiṭṭhaṃ na labhissatha, api nu kho āyatiṃ jātijarāmaraṇaṃ dukkhasamudayasambhavo paññāyethā”ti?**If consciousness were not to become established in name and form, would the coming to be of the origin of suffering—of rebirth, old age, and death in the future—be found?”*";
P_HTM[976]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[977]="*“Tasmātihānanda, eseva hetu etaṃ nidānaṃ esa samudayo esa paccayo viññāṇassa yadidaṃ nāmarūpaṃ.**“That’s why this is the cause, source, origin, and condition of consciousness, namely name and form.*";
P_HTM[978]="*Ettāvatā kho, ānanda, jāyetha vā jīyetha vā mīyetha vā cavetha vā upapajjetha vā.**This is the extent to which one may be reborn, grow old, die, pass away, or reappear.*";
P_HTM[979]="*Ettāvatā adhivacanapatho, ettāvatā niruttipatho, ettāvatā paññattipatho, ettāvatā paññāvacaraṃ, ettāvatā vaṭṭaṃ vattati itthattaṃ paññāpanāya yadidaṃ nāmarūpaṃ saha viññāṇena aññamaññapaccayatā pavattati.**This is how far the scope of language, terminology, and description extends; how far the sphere of wisdom extends; how far the cycle of rebirths continues so that this state of existence is to be found; namely, name and form together with consciousness.*";
P_HTM[980]="*2. Attapaññatti**2. Describing the Self*";
P_HTM[981]="*Kittāvatā ca, ānanda, attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti?**How do those who describe the self describe it?*";
P_HTM[982]="*Rūpiṃ vā hi, ānanda, parittaṃ attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti:**They describe it as physical and limited:*";
P_HTM[983]="*‘rūpī me paritto attā’ti.**‘My self is physical and limited.’*";
P_HTM[984]="*Rūpiṃ vā hi, ānanda, anantaṃ attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti:**Or they describe it as physical and infinite:*";
P_HTM[985]="*‘rūpī me ananto attā’ti.**‘My self is physical and infinite.’*";
P_HTM[986]="*Arūpiṃ vā hi, ānanda, parittaṃ attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti:**Or they describe it as formless and limited:*";
P_HTM[987]="*‘arūpī me paritto attā’ti.**‘My self is formless and limited.’*";
P_HTM[988]="*Arūpiṃ vā hi, ānanda, anantaṃ attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti:**Or they describe it as formless and infinite:*";
P_HTM[989]="*‘arūpī me ananto attā’ti.**‘My self is formless and infinite.’*";
P_HTM[990]="*Tatrānanda, yo so rūpiṃ parittaṃ attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti.**Now, take those who describe the self as physical and limited.*";
P_HTM[991]="*Etarahi vā so rūpiṃ parittaṃ attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti, tattha bhāviṃ vā so rūpiṃ parittaṃ attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti, ‘atathaṃ vā pana santaṃ tathattāya upakappessāmī’ti iti vā panassa hoti.**They describe the self as physical and limited in the present; or in some future life; or else they think: ‘Though it is not like that, I will ensure it is provided with what it needs to become like that.’*";
P_HTM[992]="*Evaṃ santaṃ kho, ānanda, rūpiṃ parittattānudiṭṭhi anusetīti iccālaṃ vacanāya.**This being so, it’s appropriate to say that a view of self as physical and limited underlies them.*";
P_HTM[993]="*Tatrānanda, yo so rūpiṃ anantaṃ attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti.**Now, take those who describe the self as physical and infinite …*";
P_HTM[994]="*Etarahi vā so rūpiṃ anantaṃ attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti, tattha bhāviṃ vā so rūpiṃ anantaṃ attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti, ‘atathaṃ vā pana santaṃ tathattāya upakappessāmī’ti iti vā panassa hoti.* **";
P_HTM[995]="*Evaṃ santaṃ kho, ānanda, rūpiṃ anantattānudiṭṭhi anusetīti iccālaṃ vacanāya.* **";
P_HTM[996]="*Tatrānanda, yo so arūpiṃ parittaṃ attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti.**formless and limited …*";
P_HTM[997]="*Etarahi vā so arūpiṃ parittaṃ attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti, tattha bhāviṃ vā so arūpiṃ parittaṃ attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti, ‘atathaṃ vā pana santaṃ tathattāya upakappessāmī’ti iti vā panassa hoti.* **";
P_HTM[998]="*Evaṃ santaṃ kho, ānanda, arūpiṃ parittattānudiṭṭhi anusetīti iccālaṃ vacanāya.* **";
P_HTM[999]="*Tatrānanda, yo so arūpiṃ anantaṃ attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti.**formless and infinite.*";
P_HTM[1000]="*Etarahi vā so arūpiṃ anantaṃ attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti, tattha bhāviṃ vā so arūpiṃ anantaṃ attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti, ‘atathaṃ vā pana santaṃ tathattāya upakappessāmī’ti iti vā panassa hoti.**They describe the self as formless and infinite in the present; or in some future life; or else they think: ‘Though it is not like that, I will ensure it is provided with what it needs to become like that.’*";
P_HTM[1001]="*Evaṃ santaṃ kho, ānanda, arūpiṃ anantattānudiṭṭhi anusetīti iccālaṃ vacanāya.**This being so, it’s appropriate to say that a view of self as formless and infinite underlies them.*";
P_HTM[1002]="*Ettāvatā kho, ānanda, attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti.**That’s how those who describe the self describe it.*";
P_HTM[1003]="*3. Naattapaññatti**3. Not Describing the Self*";
P_HTM[1004]="*Kittāvatā ca, ānanda, attānaṃ na paññapento na paññapeti?**How do those who don’t describe the self not describe it?*";
P_HTM[1005]="*Rūpiṃ vā hi, ānanda, parittaṃ attānaṃ na paññapento na paññapeti:**They don’t describe it as physical and limited …*";
P_HTM[1006]="*‘rūpī me paritto attā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1007]="*Rūpiṃ vā hi, ānanda, anantaṃ attānaṃ na paññapento na paññapeti:**physical and infinite …*";
P_HTM[1008]="*‘rūpī me ananto attā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1009]="*Arūpiṃ vā hi, ānanda, parittaṃ attānaṃ na paññapento na paññapeti:**formless and limited …*";
P_HTM[1010]="*‘arūpī me paritto attā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1011]="*Arūpiṃ vā hi, ānanda, anantaṃ attānaṃ na paññapento na paññapeti:**formless and infinite:*";
P_HTM[1012]="*‘arūpī me ananto attā’ti.**‘My self is formless and infinite.’*";
P_HTM[1013]="*Tatrānanda, yo so rūpiṃ parittaṃ attānaṃ na paññapento na paññapeti.**Now, take those who don’t describe the self as physical and limited …*";
P_HTM[1014]="*Etarahi vā so rūpiṃ parittaṃ attānaṃ na paññapento na paññapeti, tattha bhāviṃ vā so rūpiṃ parittaṃ attānaṃ na paññapento na paññapeti, ‘atathaṃ vā pana santaṃ tathattāya upakappessāmī’ti iti vā panassa na hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1015]="*Evaṃ santaṃ kho, ānanda, rūpiṃ parittattānudiṭṭhi nānusetīti iccālaṃ vacanāya.* **";
P_HTM[1016]="*Tatrānanda, yo so rūpiṃ anantaṃ attānaṃ na paññapento na paññapeti.**physical and infinite …*";
P_HTM[1017]="*Etarahi vā so rūpiṃ anantaṃ attānaṃ na paññapento na paññapeti, tattha bhāviṃ vā so rūpiṃ anantaṃ attānaṃ na paññapento na paññapeti, ‘atathaṃ vā pana santaṃ tathattāya upakappessāmī’ti iti vā panassa na hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1018]="*Evaṃ santaṃ kho, ānanda, rūpiṃ anantattānudiṭṭhi nānusetīti iccālaṃ vacanāya.* **";
P_HTM[1019]="*Tatrānanda, yo so arūpiṃ parittaṃ attānaṃ na paññapento na paññapeti.**formless and limited …*";
P_HTM[1020]="*Etarahi vā so arūpiṃ parittaṃ attānaṃ na paññapento na paññapeti, tattha bhāviṃ vā so arūpiṃ parittaṃ attānaṃ na paññapento na paññapeti, ‘atathaṃ vā pana santaṃ tathattāya upakappessāmī’ti iti vā panassa na hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1021]="*Evaṃ santaṃ kho, ānanda, arūpiṃ parittattānudiṭṭhi nānusetīti iccālaṃ vacanāya.* **";
P_HTM[1022]="*Tatrānanda, yo so arūpiṃ anantaṃ attānaṃ na paññapento na paññapeti.**formless and infinite.*";
P_HTM[1023]="*Etarahi vā so arūpiṃ anantaṃ attānaṃ na paññapento na paññapeti, tattha bhāviṃ vā so arūpiṃ anantaṃ attānaṃ na paññapento na paññapeti, ‘atathaṃ vā pana santaṃ tathattāya upakappessāmī’ti iti vā panassa na hoti.**They don’t describe the self as formless and infinite in the present; or in some future life; and they don’t think: ‘Though it is not like that, I will ensure it is provided with what it needs to become like that.’*";
P_HTM[1024]="*Evaṃ santaṃ kho, ānanda, arūpiṃ anantattānudiṭṭhi nānusetīti iccālaṃ vacanāya.**This being so, it’s appropriate to say that a view of self as formless and infinite doesn’t underlie them.*";
P_HTM[1025]="*Ettāvatā kho, ānanda, attānaṃ na paññapento na paññapeti.**That’s how those who don’t describe the self don’t describe it.*";
P_HTM[1026]="*4. Attasamanupassanā**4. Regarding a Self*";
P_HTM[1027]="*Kittāvatā ca, ānanda, attānaṃ samanupassamāno samanupassati?**How do those who regard the self regard it?*";
P_HTM[1028]="*Vedanaṃ vā hi, ānanda, attānaṃ samanupassamāno samanupassati:**They regard feeling as self:*";
P_HTM[1029]="*‘vedanā me attā’ti.**‘Feeling is my self.’*";
P_HTM[1030]="*‘Na heva kho me vedanā attā, appaṭisaṃvedano me attā’ti iti vā hi, ānanda, attānaṃ samanupassamāno samanupassati.**Or they regard it like this: ‘Feeling is definitely not my self. My self does not experience feeling.’*";
P_HTM[1031]="*‘Na heva kho me vedanā attā, nopi appaṭisaṃvedano me attā, attā me vediyati, vedanādhammo hi me attā’ti iti vā hi, ānanda, attānaṃ samanupassamāno samanupassati.**Or they regard it like this: ‘Feeling is definitely not my self. But it’s not that my self does not experience feeling. My self feels, for my self is liable to feel.’*";
P_HTM[1032]="*Tatrānanda, yo so evamāha:**Now, as to those who say:*";
P_HTM[1033]="*‘vedanā me attā’ti,**‘Feeling is my self.’*";
P_HTM[1034]="*so evamassa vacanīyo:**You should say this to them:*";
P_HTM[1035]="*‘tisso kho imā, āvuso, vedanā—**‘Reverend, there are three feelings:*";
P_HTM[1036]="*sukhā vedanā dukkhā vedanā adukkhamasukhā vedanā.**pleasant, painful, and neutral.*";
P_HTM[1037]="*Imāsaṃ kho tvaṃ tissannaṃ vedanānaṃ katamaṃ attato samanupassasī’ti?**Which one of these do you regard as self?’*";
P_HTM[1038]="*Yasmiṃ, ānanda, samaye sukhaṃ vedanaṃ vedeti, neva tasmiṃ samaye dukkhaṃ vedanaṃ vedeti, na adukkhamasukhaṃ vedanaṃ vedeti;**Ānanda, at a time when you feel a pleasant feeling, you don’t feel a painful or neutral feeling;*";
P_HTM[1039]="*sukhaṃyeva tasmiṃ samaye vedanaṃ vedeti.**you only feel a pleasant feeling.*";
P_HTM[1040]="*Yasmiṃ, ānanda, samaye dukkhaṃ vedanaṃ vedeti, neva tasmiṃ samaye sukhaṃ vedanaṃ vedeti, na adukkhamasukhaṃ vedanaṃ vedeti;**At a time when you feel a painful feeling, you don’t feel a pleasant or neutral feeling;*";
P_HTM[1041]="*dukkhaṃyeva tasmiṃ samaye vedanaṃ vedeti.**you only feel a painful feeling.*";
P_HTM[1042]="*Yasmiṃ, ānanda, samaye adukkhamasukhaṃ vedanaṃ vedeti, neva tasmiṃ samaye sukhaṃ vedanaṃ vedeti, na dukkhaṃ vedanaṃ vedeti;**At a time when you feel a neutral feeling, you don’t feel a pleasant or painful feeling;*";
P_HTM[1043]="*adukkhamasukhaṃyeva tasmiṃ samaye vedanaṃ vedeti.**you only feel a neutral feeling.*";
P_HTM[1044]="*Sukhāpi kho, ānanda, vedanā aniccā saṅkhatā paṭiccasamuppannā khayadhammā vayadhammā virāgadhammā nirodhadhammā.**Pleasant feelings, painful feelings, and neutral feelings are all impermanent, conditioned, dependently originated, liable to end, vanish, fade away, and cease.*";
P_HTM[1045]="*Dukkhāpi kho, ānanda, vedanā aniccā saṅkhatā paṭiccasamuppannā khayadhammā vayadhammā virāgadhammā nirodhadhammā.* **";
P_HTM[1046]="*Adukkhamasukhāpi kho, ānanda, vedanā aniccā saṅkhatā paṭiccasamuppannā khayadhammā vayadhammā virāgadhammā nirodhadhammā.* **";
P_HTM[1047]="*Tassa sukhaṃ vedanaṃ vediyamānassa ‘eso me attā’ti hoti.**When feeling a pleasant feeling they think: ‘This is my self.’*";
P_HTM[1048]="*Tassāyeva sukhāya vedanāya nirodhā ‘byagā me attā’ti hoti.**When their pleasant feeling ceases they think: ‘My self has disappeared.’*";
P_HTM[1049]="*Dukkhaṃ vedanaṃ vediyamānassa ‘eso me attā’ti hoti.**When feeling a painful feeling they think: ‘This is my self.’*";
P_HTM[1050]="*Tassāyeva dukkhāya vedanāya nirodhā ‘byagā me attā’ti hoti.**When their painful feeling ceases they think: ‘My self has disappeared.’*";
P_HTM[1051]="*Adukkhamasukhaṃ vedanaṃ vediyamānassa ‘eso me attā’ti hoti.**When feeling a neutral feeling they think: ‘This is my self.’*";
P_HTM[1052]="*Tassāyeva adukkhamasukhāya vedanāya nirodhā ‘byagā me attā’ti hoti.**When their neutral feeling ceases they think: ‘My self has disappeared.’*";
P_HTM[1053]="*Iti so diṭṭheva dhamme aniccasukhadukkhavokiṇṇaṃ uppādavayadhammaṃ attānaṃ samanupassamāno samanupassati, yo so evamāha: ‘vedanā me attā’ti.**So those who say ‘feeling is my self’ regard as self that which is evidently impermanent, a mixture of pleasure and pain, and liable to rise and fall.*";
P_HTM[1054]="*Tasmātihānanda, etena petaṃ nakkhamati: ‘vedanā me attā’ti samanupassituṃ.**That’s why it’s not acceptable to regard feeling as self.*";
P_HTM[1055]="*Tatrānanda, yo so evamāha:**Now, as to those who say:*";
P_HTM[1056]="*‘na heva kho me vedanā attā, appaṭisaṃvedano me attā’ti, so evamassa vacanīyo:**‘Feeling is definitely not my self. My self does not experience feeling.’ You should say this to them,*";
P_HTM[1057]="*‘yattha panāvuso, sabbaso vedayitaṃ natthi api nu kho, tattha “ayamahamasmī”ti siyā’”ti?**‘But reverend, where there is nothing felt at all, would the thought “I am” occur there?’”*";
P_HTM[1058]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1059]="*“Tasmātihānanda, etena petaṃ nakkhamati: ‘na heva kho me vedanā attā, appaṭisaṃvedano me attā’ti samanupassituṃ.**“That’s why it’s not acceptable to regard self as that which does not experience feeling.*";
P_HTM[1060]="*Tatrānanda, yo so evamāha:**Now, as to those who say:*";
P_HTM[1061]="*‘na heva kho me vedanā attā, nopi appaṭisaṃvedano me attā, attā me vediyati, vedanādhammo hi me attā’ti.**‘Feeling is definitely not my self. But it’s not that my self does not experience feeling. My self feels, for my self is liable to feel.’*";
P_HTM[1062]="*So evamassa vacanīyo—**You should say this to them,*";
P_HTM[1063]="*vedanā ca hi, āvuso, sabbena sabbaṃ sabbathā sabbaṃ aparisesā nirujjheyyuṃ.**‘Suppose feelings were to totally and utterly cease without anything left over.*";
P_HTM[1064]="*Sabbaso vedanāya asati vedanānirodhā api nu kho tattha ‘ayamahamasmī’ti siyā”ti?**When there’s no feeling at all, with the cessation of feeling, would the thought “I am this” occur there?’”*";
P_HTM[1065]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1066]="*“Tasmātihānanda, etena petaṃ nakkhamati: ‘na heva kho me vedanā attā, nopi appaṭisaṃvedano me attā, attā me vediyati, vedanādhammo hi me attā’ti samanupassituṃ.**“That’s why it’s not acceptable to regard self as that which is liable to feel.*";
P_HTM[1067]="*Yato kho, ānanda, bhikkhu neva vedanaṃ attānaṃ samanupassati, nopi appaṭisaṃvedanaṃ attānaṃ samanupassati, nopi ‘attā me vediyati, vedanādhammo hi me attā’ti samanupassati.* **";
P_HTM[1068]="*So evaṃ na samanupassanto na ca kiñci loke upādiyati,**Not regarding anything in this way, they don’t grasp at anything in the world.*";
P_HTM[1069]="*anupādiyaṃ na paritassati, aparitassaṃ paccattaññeva parinibbāyati,**Not grasping, they’re not anxious. Not being anxious, they personally become extinguished.*";
P_HTM[1070]="*‘khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[1071]="*Evaṃ vimuttacittaṃ kho, ānanda, bhikkhuṃ yo evaṃ vadeyya:**It wouldn’t be appropriate to say that a mendicant whose mind is freed like this holds the following views:*";
P_HTM[1072]="*‘hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā itissa diṭṭhī’ti, tadakallaṃ.**‘A Realized One exists after death’;*";
P_HTM[1073]="*‘Na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā itissa diṭṭhī’ti, tadakallaṃ.**‘A Realized One doesn’t exist after death’;*";
P_HTM[1074]="*‘Hoti ca na ca hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā itissa diṭṭhī’ti, tadakallaṃ.**‘A Realized One both exists and doesn’t exist after death’;*";
P_HTM[1075]="*‘Neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā itissa diṭṭhī’ti, tadakallaṃ.**‘A Realized One neither exists nor doesn’t exist after death’.*";
P_HTM[1076]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[1077]="*Yāvatā, ānanda, adhivacanaṃ yāvatā adhivacanapatho, yāvatā nirutti yāvatā niruttipatho, yāvatā paññatti yāvatā paññattipatho, yāvatā paññā yāvatā paññāvacaraṃ, yāvatā vaṭṭaṃ, yāvatā vaṭṭati, tadabhiññāvimutto bhikkhu, tadabhiññāvimuttaṃ bhikkhuṃ ‘na jānāti na passati itissa diṭṭhī’ti, tadakallaṃ.**A mendicant is freed by directly knowing this: how far language and the scope of language extend; how far terminology and the scope of terminology extend; how far description and the scope of description extend; how far wisdom and the sphere of wisdom extend; how far the cycle of rebirths and its continuation extend. It wouldn’t be appropriate to say that a mendicant freed by directly knowing this holds the view: ‘There is no such thing as knowing and seeing.’*";
P_HTM[1078]="*5. Sattaviññāṇaṭṭhiti**5. Planes of Consciousness*";
P_HTM[1079]="*Satta kho, ānanda, viññāṇaṭṭhitiyo, dve āyatanāni.**Ānanda, there are seven planes of consciousness and two dimensions.*";
P_HTM[1080]="*Katamā satta?**What seven?*";
P_HTM[1081]="*Santānanda, sattā nānattakāyā nānattasaññino, seyyathāpi manussā, ekacce ca devā, ekacce ca vinipātikā.**There are sentient beings that are diverse in body and diverse in perception, such as human beings, some gods, and some beings in the underworld.*";
P_HTM[1082]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamā viññāṇaṭṭhiti.**This is the first plane of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1083]="*Santānanda, sattā nānattakāyā ekattasaññino, seyyathāpi devā brahmakāyikā paṭhamābhinibbattā.**There are sentient beings that are diverse in body and unified in perception, such as the gods reborn in Brahmā’s Host through the first absorption.*";
P_HTM[1084]="*Ayaṃ dutiyā viññāṇaṭṭhiti.**This is the second plane of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1085]="*Santānanda, sattā ekattakāyā nānattasaññino, seyyathāpi devā ābhassarā.**There are sentient beings that are unified in body and diverse in perception, such as the gods of streaming radiance.*";
P_HTM[1086]="*Ayaṃ tatiyā viññāṇaṭṭhiti.**This is the third plane of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1087]="*Santānanda, sattā ekattakāyā ekattasaññino, seyyathāpi devā subhakiṇhā.**There are sentient beings that are unified in body and unified in perception, such as the gods replete with glory.*";
P_HTM[1088]="*Ayaṃ catutthī viññāṇaṭṭhiti.**This is the fourth plane of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1089]="*Santānanda, sattā sabbaso rūpasaññānaṃ samatikkamā paṭighasaññānaṃ atthaṅgamā nānattasaññānaṃ amanasikārā ‘ananto ākāso’ti ākāsānañcāyatanūpagā.**There are sentient beings that have gone totally beyond perceptions of form. With the ending of perceptions of impingement, not focusing on perceptions of diversity, aware that ‘space is infinite’, they have been reborn in the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[1090]="*Ayaṃ pañcamī viññāṇaṭṭhiti.**This is the fifth plane of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1091]="*Santānanda, sattā sabbaso ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘anantaṃ viññāṇan’ti viññāṇañcāyatanūpagā.**There are sentient beings that have gone totally beyond the dimension of infinite space. Aware that ‘consciousness is infinite’, they have been reborn in the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1092]="*Ayaṃ chaṭṭhī viññāṇaṭṭhiti.**This is the sixth plane of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1093]="*Santānanda, sattā sabbaso viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘natthi kiñcī’ti ākiñcaññāyatanūpagā.**There are sentient beings that have gone totally beyond the dimension of infinite consciousness. Aware that ‘there is nothing at all’, they have been reborn in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[1094]="*Ayaṃ sattamī viññāṇaṭṭhiti.**This is the seventh plane of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1095]="*Asaññasattāyatanaṃ nevasaññānāsaññāyatanameva dutiyaṃ.**Then there’s the dimension of non-percipient beings, and secondly, the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[1096]="*Tatrānanda, yāyaṃ paṭhamā viññāṇaṭṭhiti nānattakāyā nānattasaññino, seyyathāpi manussā, ekacce ca devā, ekacce ca vinipātikā.**Now, regarding these seven planes of consciousness and two dimensions,*";
P_HTM[1097]="*Yo nu kho, ānanda, tañca pajānāti, tassā ca samudayaṃ pajānāti, tassā ca atthaṅgamaṃ pajānāti, tassā ca assādaṃ pajānāti, tassā ca ādīnavaṃ pajānāti, tassā ca nissaraṇaṃ pajānāti, kallaṃ nu tena tadabhinanditun”ti?**is it appropriate for someone who understands them—and their origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape—to take pleasure in them?”*";
P_HTM[1098]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante” … pe …**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1099]="*“tatrānanda, yamidaṃ asaññasattāyatanaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1100]="*Yo nu kho, ānanda, tañca pajānāti, tassa ca samudayaṃ pajānāti, tassa ca atthaṅgamaṃ pajānāti, tassa ca assādaṃ pajānāti, tassa ca ādīnavaṃ pajānāti, tassa ca nissaraṇaṃ pajānāti, kallaṃ nu tena tadabhinanditun”ti?* **";
P_HTM[1101]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[1102]="*“Tatrānanda, yamidaṃ nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1103]="*Yo nu kho, ānanda, tañca pajānāti, tassa ca samudayaṃ pajānāti, tassa ca atthaṅgamaṃ pajānāti, tassa ca assādaṃ pajānāti, tassa ca ādīnavaṃ pajānāti, tassa ca nissaraṇaṃ pajānāti, kallaṃ nu tena tadabhinanditun”ti?* **";
P_HTM[1104]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.* **";
P_HTM[1105]="*“Yato kho, ānanda, bhikkhu imāsañca sattannaṃ viññāṇaṭṭhitīnaṃ imesañca dvinnaṃ āyatanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ viditvā anupādā vimutto hoti, ayaṃ vuccatānanda, bhikkhu paññāvimutto.**“When a mendicant, having truly understood the origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape regarding these seven planes of consciousness and these two dimensions, is freed by not grasping, they’re called a mendicant who is freed by wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1106]="*6. Aṭṭhavimokkha**6. The Eight Liberations*";
P_HTM[1107]="*Aṭṭha kho ime, ānanda, vimokkhā.**Ānanda, there are these eight liberations.*";
P_HTM[1108]="*Katame aṭṭha?**What eight?*";
P_HTM[1109]="*Rūpī rūpāni passati**Having physical form, they see visions.*";
P_HTM[1110]="*ayaṃ paṭhamo vimokkho.**This is the first liberation.*";
P_HTM[1111]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī bahiddhā rūpāni passati,**Not perceiving form internally, they see visions externally.*";
P_HTM[1112]="*ayaṃ dutiyo vimokkho.**This is the second liberation.*";
P_HTM[1113]="*Subhanteva adhimutto hoti,**They’re focused only on beauty.*";
P_HTM[1114]="*ayaṃ tatiyo vimokkho.**This is the third liberation.*";
P_HTM[1115]="*Sabbaso rūpasaññānaṃ samatikkamā paṭighasaññānaṃ atthaṅgamā nānattasaññānaṃ amanasikārā ‘ananto ākāso’ti ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati,**Going totally beyond perceptions of form, with the ending of perceptions of impingement, not focusing on perceptions of diversity, aware that ‘space is infinite’, they enter and remain in the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[1116]="*ayaṃ catuttho vimokkho.**This is the fourth liberation.*";
P_HTM[1117]="*Sabbaso ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘anantaṃ viññāṇan’ti viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati,**Going totally beyond the dimension of infinite space, aware that ‘consciousness is infinite’, they enter and remain in the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1118]="*ayaṃ pañcamo vimokkho.**This is the fifth liberation.*";
P_HTM[1119]="*Sabbaso viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘natthi kiñcī’ti ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati,**Going totally beyond the dimension of infinite consciousness, aware that ‘there is nothing at all’, they enter and remain in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[1120]="*ayaṃ chaṭṭho vimokkho.**This is the sixth liberation.*";
P_HTM[1121]="*Sabbaso ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati,**Going totally beyond the dimension of nothingness, they enter and remain in the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[1122]="*ayaṃ sattamo vimokkho.**This is the seventh liberation.*";
P_HTM[1123]="*Sabbaso nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ upasampajja viharati,**Going totally beyond the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, they enter and remain in the cessation of perception and feeling.*";
P_HTM[1124]="*ayaṃ aṭṭhamo vimokkho.**This is the eighth liberation.*";
P_HTM[1125]="*Ime kho, ānanda, aṭṭha vimokkhā.**These are the eight liberations.*";
P_HTM[1126]="*Yato kho, ānanda, bhikkhu ime aṭṭha vimokkhe anulomampi samāpajjati, paṭilomampi samāpajjati, anulomapaṭilomampi samāpajjati, yatthicchakaṃ yadicchakaṃ yāvaticchakaṃ samāpajjatipi vuṭṭhātipi.**When a mendicant enters into and withdraws from these eight liberations—in forward order, in reverse order, and in forward and reverse order—wherever they wish, whenever they wish, and for as long as they wish;*";
P_HTM[1127]="*Āsavānañca khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati, ayaṃ vuccatānanda, bhikkhu ubhatobhāgavimutto.**and when they realize the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life, and live having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements, they’re called a mendicant who is freed both ways.*";
P_HTM[1128]="*Imāya ca, ānanda, ubhatobhāgavimuttiyā aññā ubhatobhāgavimutti uttaritarā vā paṇītatarā vā natthī”ti.**And, Ānanda, there is no other freedom both ways that is better or finer than this.”*";
P_HTM[1129]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1130]="*Attamano āyasmā ānando bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandīti.**Satisfied, Venerable Ānanda was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1131]="*Mahānidānasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1132]="*16. Mahāparinibbānasutta  ** The Great Discourse on the Buddha’s Extinguishment *";
P_HTM[1133]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[1134]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati gijjhakūṭe pabbate.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, on the Vulture’s Peak Mountain.*";
P_HTM[1135]="*Tena kho pana samayena rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto vajjī abhiyātukāmo hoti.**Now at that time King Ajātasattu Vedehiputta of Māgadha wanted to invade the Vajjis.*";
P_HTM[1136]="*So evamāha:**He declared:*";
P_HTM[1137]="*“ahaṃ hime vajjī evaṃmahiddhike evaṃmahānubhāve ucchecchāmi vajjī, vināsessāmi vajjī, anayabyasanaṃ āpādessāmī”ti.**“I shall wipe out these Vajjis, so mighty and powerful! I shall destroy them, and lay ruin and devastation upon them!”*";
P_HTM[1138]="*Atha kho rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto vassakāraṃ brāhmaṇaṃ magadhamahāmattaṃ āmantesi:**And then King Ajātasattu addressed Vassakāra the brahmin minister of Māgadha,*";
P_HTM[1139]="*“ehi tvaṃ, brāhmaṇa, yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkama; upasaṅkamitvā mama vacanena bhagavato pāde sirasā vandāhi, appābādhaṃ appātaṅkaṃ lahuṭṭhānaṃ balaṃ phāsuvihāraṃ puccha:**“Please, brahmin, go to the Buddha, and in my name bow with your head to his feet. Ask him if he is healthy and well, nimble, strong, and living comfortably.*";
P_HTM[1140]="*‘rājā, bhante, māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto bhagavato pāde sirasā vandati, appābādhaṃ appātaṅkaṃ lahuṭṭhānaṃ balaṃ phāsuvihāraṃ pucchatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1141]="*Evañca vadehi:**And then say:*";
P_HTM[1142]="*‘rājā, bhante, māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto vajjī abhiyātukāmo.**‘Sir, King Ajātasattu Vedehiputta of Māgadha wants to invade the Vajjis.*";
P_HTM[1143]="*So evamāha:**He says,*";
P_HTM[1144]="*“ahaṃ hime vajjī evaṃmahiddhike evaṃmahānubhāve ucchecchāmi vajjī, vināsessāmi vajjī, anayabyasanaṃ āpādessāmī”’ti.**“I shall wipe out these Vajjis, so mighty and powerful! I shall destroy them, and lay ruin and devastation upon them!”’*";
P_HTM[1145]="*Yathā te bhagavā byākaroti, taṃ sādhukaṃ uggahetvā mama āroceyyāsi.**Remember well how the Buddha answers and tell it to me.*";
P_HTM[1146]="*Na hi tathāgatā vitathaṃ bhaṇantī”ti.**For Realized Ones say nothing that is not so.”*";
P_HTM[1147]="*1. Vassakārabrāhmaṇa**1. The Brahmin Vassakāra*";
P_HTM[1148]="*“Evaṃ, bho”ti kho vassakāro brāhmaṇo magadhamahāmatto rañño māgadhassa ajātasattussa vedehiputtassa paṭissutvā bhaddāni bhaddāni yānāni yojetvā bhaddaṃ bhaddaṃ yānaṃ abhiruhitvā bhaddehi bhaddehi yānehi rājagahamhā niyyāsi, yena gijjhakūṭo pabbato tena pāyāsi.**“Yes, sir,” Vassakāra replied. He had the finest carriages harnessed. Then he mounted a fine carriage and, along with other fine carriages, set out from Rājagaha for the Vulture’s Peak Mountain.*";
P_HTM[1149]="*Yāvatikā yānassa bhūmi, yānena gantvā, yānā paccorohitvā pattikova yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodi.**He went by carriage as far as the terrain allowed, then descended and approached the Buddha on foot, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[1150]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho vassakāro brāhmaṇo magadhamahāmatto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1151]="*“rājā, bho gotama, māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto bhoto gotamassa pāde sirasā vandati, appābādhaṃ appātaṅkaṃ lahuṭṭhānaṃ balaṃ phāsuvihāraṃ pucchati.**“Master Gotama, King Ajātasattu Vedehiputta of Māgadha bows with his head to your feet. He asks if you are healthy and well, nimble, strong, and living comfortably.*";
P_HTM[1152]="*Rājā, bho gotama, māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto vajjī abhiyātukāmo.**Master Gotama, King Ajātasattu wants to invade the Vajjis.*";
P_HTM[1153]="*So evamāha:**He has declared:*";
P_HTM[1154]="*‘ahaṃ hime vajjī evaṃmahiddhike evaṃmahānubhāve ucchecchāmi vajjī, vināsessāmi vajjī, anayabyasanaṃ āpādessāmī’”ti.**‘I shall wipe out these Vajjis, so mighty and powerful! I shall destroy them, and lay ruin and devastation upon them!’”*";
P_HTM[1155]="*2. Rājaaparihāniyadhamma**2. Principles That Prevent Decline*";
P_HTM[1156]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā ānando bhagavato piṭṭhito ṭhito hoti bhagavantaṃ bījayamāno.**Now at that time Venerable Ānanda was standing behind the Buddha fanning him.*";
P_HTM[1157]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**Then the Buddha said to him,*";
P_HTM[1158]="*“kinti te, ānanda, sutaṃ, ‘vajjī abhiṇhaṃ sannipātā sannipātabahulā’”ti?**“Ānanda, have you heard that the Vajjis meet frequently and have many meetings?”*";
P_HTM[1159]="*“Sutaṃ metaṃ, bhante: ‘vajjī abhiṇhaṃ sannipātā sannipātabahulā’”ti.**“I have heard that, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1160]="*“Yāvakīvañca, ānanda, vajjī abhiṇhaṃ sannipātā sannipātabahulā bhavissanti, vuddhiyeva, ānanda, vajjīnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (1)**“As long as the Vajjis meet frequently and have many meetings, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1161]="*Kinti te, ānanda, sutaṃ, ‘vajjī samaggā sannipatanti, samaggā vuṭṭhahanti, samaggā vajjikaraṇīyāni karontī’”ti?**Ānanda, have you heard that the Vajjis meet in harmony, leave in harmony, and carry on their business in harmony?”*";
P_HTM[1162]="*“Sutaṃ metaṃ, bhante: ‘vajjī samaggā sannipatanti, samaggā vuṭṭhahanti, samaggā vajjikaraṇīyāni karontī’”ti.**“I have heard that, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1163]="*“Yāvakīvañca, ānanda, vajjī samaggā sannipatissanti, samaggā vuṭṭhahissanti, samaggā vajjikaraṇīyāni karissanti, vuddhiyeva, ānanda, vajjīnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (2)**“As long as the Vajjis meet in harmony, leave in harmony, and carry on their business in harmony, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1164]="*Kinti te, ānanda, sutaṃ, ‘vajjī apaññattaṃ na paññapenti, paññattaṃ na samucchindanti, yathāpaññatte porāṇe vajjidhamme samādāya vattantī’”ti?**Ānanda, have you heard that the Vajjis don’t make new decrees or abolish existing decrees, but proceed having undertaken the traditional Vajjian principles as they have been decreed?”*";
P_HTM[1165]="*“Sutaṃ metaṃ, bhante: ‘vajjī apaññattaṃ na paññapenti, paññattaṃ na samucchindanti, yathāpaññatte porāṇe vajjidhamme samādāya vattantī’”ti.**“I have heard that, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1166]="*“Yāvakīvañca, ānanda, vajjī apaññattaṃ na paññapessanti, paññattaṃ na samucchindissanti, yathāpaññatte porāṇe vajjidhamme samādāya vattissanti, vuddhiyeva, ānanda, vajjīnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (3)**“As long as the Vajjis don’t make new decrees or abolish existing decrees, but proceed having undertaken the traditional Vajjian principles as they have been decreed, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1167]="*Kinti te, ānanda, sutaṃ, ‘vajjī ye te vajjīnaṃ vajjimahallakā, te sakkaronti garuṃ karonti mānenti pūjenti, tesañca sotabbaṃ maññantī’”ti?**Ānanda, have you heard that the Vajjis honor, respect, esteem, and venerate Vajjian elders, and think them worth listening to?”*";
P_HTM[1168]="*“Sutaṃ metaṃ, bhante: ‘vajjī ye te vajjīnaṃ vajjimahallakā, te sakkaronti garuṃ karonti mānenti pūjenti, tesañca sotabbaṃ maññantī’”ti.**“I have heard that, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1169]="*“Yāvakīvañca, ānanda, vajjī ye te vajjīnaṃ vajjimahallakā, te sakkarissanti garuṃ karissanti mānessanti pūjessanti, tesañca sotabbaṃ maññissanti, vuddhiyeva, ānanda, vajjīnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (4)**“As long as the Vajjis honor, respect, esteem, and venerate Vajjian elders, and think them worth listening to, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1170]="*Kinti te, ānanda, sutaṃ, ‘vajjī yā tā kulitthiyo kulakumāriyo, tā na okkassa pasayha vāsentī’”ti?**Ānanda, have you heard that the Vajjis don’t rape or abduct women or girls from their families and force them to live with them?”*";
P_HTM[1171]="*“Sutaṃ metaṃ, bhante: ‘vajjī yā tā kulitthiyo kulakumāriyo tā na okkassa pasayha vāsentī’”ti.**“I have heard that, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1172]="*“Yāvakīvañca, ānanda, vajjī yā tā kulitthiyo kulakumāriyo, tā na okkassa pasayha vāsessanti, vuddhiyeva, ānanda, vajjīnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (5)**“As long as the Vajjis don’t rape or abduct women or girls from their families and force them to live with them, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1173]="*Kinti te, ānanda, sutaṃ, ‘vajjī yāni tāni vajjīnaṃ vajjicetiyāni abbhantarāni ceva bāhirāni ca, tāni sakkaronti garuṃ karonti mānenti pūjenti, tesañca dinnapubbaṃ katapubbaṃ dhammikaṃ baliṃ no parihāpentī’”ti?**Ānanda, have you heard that the Vajjis honor, respect, esteem, and venerate the Vajjian shrines, whether inner or outer, not neglecting the proper spirit-offerings that were given and made in the past?”*";
P_HTM[1174]="*“Sutaṃ metaṃ, bhante: ‘vajjī yāni tāni vajjīnaṃ vajjicetiyāni abbhantarāni ceva bāhirāni ca, tāni sakkaronti garuṃ karonti mānenti pūjenti tesañca dinnapubbaṃ katapubbaṃ dhammikaṃ baliṃ no parihāpentī’”ti.**“I have heard that, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1175]="*“Yāvakīvañca, ānanda, vajjī yāni tāni vajjīnaṃ vajjicetiyāni abbhantarāni ceva bāhirāni ca, tāni sakkarissanti garuṃ karissanti mānessanti pūjessanti, tesañca dinnapubbaṃ katapubbaṃ dhammikaṃ baliṃ no parihāpessanti, vuddhiyeva, ānanda, vajjīnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (6)**“As long as the Vajjis honor, respect, esteem, and venerate the Vajjian shrines, whether inner or outer, not neglecting the proper spirit-offerings that were given and made in the past, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1176]="*Kinti te, ānanda, sutaṃ, ‘vajjīnaṃ arahantesu dhammikā rakkhāvaraṇagutti susaṃvihitā, kinti anāgatā ca arahanto vijitaṃ āgaccheyyuṃ, āgatā ca arahanto vijite phāsu vihareyyun’”ti?**Ānanda, have you heard that the Vajjis arrange for proper protection, shelter, and security for perfected ones, so that more perfected ones might come to the realm and those already here may live in comfort?”*";
P_HTM[1177]="*“Sutaṃ metaṃ, bhante ‘vajjīnaṃ arahantesu dhammikā rakkhāvaraṇagutti susaṃvihitā kinti anāgatā ca arahanto vijitaṃ āgaccheyyuṃ, āgatā ca arahanto vijite phāsu vihareyyun’”ti.**“I have heard that, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1178]="*“Yāvakīvañca, ānanda, vajjīnaṃ arahantesu dhammikā rakkhāvaraṇagutti susaṃvihitā bhavissati, kinti anāgatā ca arahanto vijitaṃ āgaccheyyuṃ, āgatā ca arahanto vijite phāsu vihareyyunti. Vuddhiyeva, ānanda, vajjīnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihānī”ti. (7)**“As long as the Vajjis arrange for proper protection, shelter, and security for perfected ones, so that more perfected ones might come to the realm and those already here may live in comfort, they can expect growth, not decline.”*";
P_HTM[1179]="*Atha kho bhagavā vassakāraṃ brāhmaṇaṃ magadhamahāmattaṃ āmantesi:**Then the Buddha said to Vassakāra,*";
P_HTM[1180]="*“ekamidāhaṃ, brāhmaṇa, samayaṃ vesāliyaṃ viharāmi sārandade cetiye.**“Brahmin, this one time I was staying near Vesālī at the Sarandada woodland shrine.*";
P_HTM[1181]="*Tatrāhaṃ vajjīnaṃ ime satta aparihāniye dhamme desesiṃ.**There I taught the Vajjis these seven principles that prevent decline.*";
P_HTM[1182]="*Yāvakīvañca, brāhmaṇa, ime satta aparihāniyā dhammā vajjīsu ṭhassanti, imesu ca sattasu aparihāniyesu dhammesu vajjī sandississanti, vuddhiyeva, brāhmaṇa, vajjīnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihānī”ti.**As long as these seven principles that prevent decline last among the Vajjis, and as long as the Vajjis are seen following them, they can expect growth, not decline.”*";
P_HTM[1183]="*Evaṃ vutte, vassakāro brāhmaṇo magadhamahāmatto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When the Buddha had spoken, Vassakāra said to him,*";
P_HTM[1184]="*“ekamekenapi, bho gotama, aparihāniyena dhammena samannāgatānaṃ vajjīnaṃ vuddhiyeva pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni.**“Master Gotama, if the Vajjis follow even a single one of these principles they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1185]="*Ko pana vādo sattahi aparihāniyehi dhammehi.**How much more so all seven!*";
P_HTM[1186]="*Akaraṇīyāva, bho gotama, vajjī raññā māgadhena ajātasattunā vedehiputtena yadidaṃ yuddhassa, aññatra upalāpanāya aññatra mithubhedā.**King Ajātasattu cannot defeat the Vajjis in war, unless by diplomacy or by sowing dissension.*";
P_HTM[1187]="*Handa ca dāni mayaṃ, bho gotama, gacchāma, bahukiccā mayaṃ bahukaraṇīyā”ti.**Well, now, Master Gotama, I must go. I have many duties, and much to do.”*";
P_HTM[1188]="*“Yassadāni tvaṃ, brāhmaṇa, kālaṃ maññasī”ti.**“Please, brahmin, go at your convenience.”*";
P_HTM[1189]="*Atha kho vassakāro brāhmaṇo magadhamahāmatto bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkāmi.**Then Vassakāra the brahmin, having approved and agreed with what the Buddha said, got up from his seat and left.*";
P_HTM[1190]="*3. Bhikkhuaparihāniyadhamma**3. Principles That Prevent Decline Among the Mendicants*";
P_HTM[1191]="*Atha kho bhagavā acirapakkante vassakāre brāhmaṇe magadhamahāmatte āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**Soon after he had left, the Buddha said to Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[1192]="*“gaccha tvaṃ, ānanda, yāvatikā bhikkhū rājagahaṃ upanissāya viharanti, te sabbe upaṭṭhānasālāyaṃ sannipātehī”ti.**“Go, Ānanda, gather all the mendicants staying in the vicinity of Rājagaha together in the assembly hall.”*";
P_HTM[1193]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paṭissutvā yāvatikā bhikkhū rājagahaṃ upanissāya viharanti, te sabbe upaṭṭhānasālāyaṃ sannipātetvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi. Ekamantaṃ ṭhito kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**“Yes, sir,” replied Ānanda. He did what the Buddha asked. Then he went back, bowed, stood to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[1194]="*“sannipatito, bhante, bhikkhusaṅgho, yassadāni, bhante, bhagavā kālaṃ maññatī”ti.**“Sir, the mendicant Saṅgha has assembled. Please, sir, go at your convenience.”*";
P_HTM[1195]="*Atha kho bhagavā uṭṭhāyāsanā yena upaṭṭhānasālā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then the Buddha went to the assembly hall, where he sat on the seat spread out*";
P_HTM[1196]="*Nisajja kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**and addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[1197]="*“satta vo, bhikkhave, aparihāniye dhamme desessāmi,**“Mendicants, I will teach you these seven principles that prevent decline.*";
P_HTM[1198]="*taṃ suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasikarotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**Listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[1199]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[1200]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[1201]="*“Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhū abhiṇhaṃ sannipātā sannipātabahulā bhavissanti, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (1)**“As long as the mendicants meet frequently and have many meetings, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1202]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhū samaggā sannipatissanti, samaggā vuṭṭhahissanti, samaggā saṅghakaraṇīyāni karissanti, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (2)**As long as the mendicants meet in harmony, leave in harmony, and carry on their business in harmony, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1203]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhū apaññattaṃ na paññapessanti, paññattaṃ na samucchindissanti, yathāpaññattesu sikkhāpadesu samādāya vattissanti, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (3)**As long as the mendicants don’t make new decrees or abolish existing decrees, but undertake and follow the training rules as they have been decreed, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1204]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhū ye te bhikkhū therā rattaññū cirapabbajitā saṅghapitaro saṅghapariṇāyakā, te sakkarissanti garuṃ karissanti mānessanti pūjessanti, tesañca sotabbaṃ maññissanti, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (4)**As long as the mendicants honor, respect, esteem, and venerate the senior mendicants—of long standing, long gone forth, fathers and leaders of the Saṅgha—and think them worth listening to, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1205]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhū uppannāya taṇhāya ponobbhavikāya na vasaṃ gacchissanti, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (5)**As long as the mendicants don’t fall under the sway of arisen craving for future lives, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1206]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhū āraññakesu senāsanesu sāpekkhā bhavissanti, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (6)**As long as the mendicants take care to live in wilderness lodgings, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1207]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhū paccattaññeva satiṃ upaṭṭhapessanti: ‘kinti anāgatā ca pesalā sabrahmacārī āgaccheyyuṃ, āgatā ca pesalā sabrahmacārī phāsu vihareyyun’ti. Vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (7)**As long as the mendicants individually establish mindfulness, so that more good-hearted spiritual companions might come, and those that have already come may live comfortably, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1208]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, ime satta aparihāniyā dhammā bhikkhūsu ṭhassanti, imesu ca sattasu aparihāniyesu dhammesu bhikkhū sandississanti, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni.**As long as these seven principles that prevent decline last among the mendicants, and as long as the mendicants are seen following them, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1209]="*Aparepi vo, bhikkhave, satta aparihāniye dhamme desessāmi, taṃ suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasikarotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**I will teach you seven more principles that prevent decline. …*";
P_HTM[1210]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1211]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[1212]="*“Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhū na kammārāmā bhavissanti na kammaratā na kammārāmatamanuyuttā, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (1)**As long as the mendicants don’t relish work, loving it and liking to relish it, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1213]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhū na bhassārāmā bhavissanti na bhassaratā na bhassārāmatamanuyuttā, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (2)**As long as they don’t enjoy talk …*";
P_HTM[1214]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhū na niddārāmā bhavissanti na niddāratā na niddārāmatamanuyuttā, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (3)**sleep …*";
P_HTM[1215]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhū na saṅgaṇikārāmā bhavissanti na saṅgaṇikaratā na saṅgaṇikārāmatamanuyuttā, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (4)**company …*";
P_HTM[1216]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhū na pāpicchā bhavissanti na pāpikānaṃ icchānaṃ vasaṃ gatā, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (5)**they don’t have wicked desires, falling under the sway of wicked desires …*";
P_HTM[1217]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhū na pāpamittā bhavissanti na pāpasahāyā na pāpasampavaṅkā, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (6)**they don’t have bad friends, companions, and associates …*";
P_HTM[1218]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhū na oramattakena visesādhigamena antarāvosānaṃ āpajjissanti, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (7)**they don’t stop half-way after achieving some insignificant distinction, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1219]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, ime satta aparihāniyā dhammā bhikkhūsu ṭhassanti, imesu ca sattasu aparihāniyesu dhammesu bhikkhū sandississanti, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni.**As long as these seven principles that prevent decline last among the mendicants, and as long as the mendicants are seen following them, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1220]="*Aparepi vo, bhikkhave, satta aparihāniye dhamme desessāmi … pe ….**I will teach you seven more principles that prevent decline. …*";
P_HTM[1221]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhū saddhā bhavissanti … pe …**As long as the mendicants are faithful …*";
P_HTM[1222]="*hirimanā bhavissanti …**conscientious …*";
P_HTM[1223]="*ottappī bhavissanti …**prudent …*";
P_HTM[1224]="*bahussutā bhavissanti …**learned …*";
P_HTM[1225]="*āraddhavīriyā bhavissanti …**energetic …*";
P_HTM[1226]="*upaṭṭhitassatī bhavissanti …**mindful …*";
P_HTM[1227]="*paññavanto bhavissanti, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni.**wise, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1228]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, ime satta aparihāniyā dhammā bhikkhūsu ṭhassanti, imesu ca sattasu aparihāniyesu dhammesu bhikkhū sandississanti, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni.**As long as these seven principles that prevent decline last among the mendicants, and as long as the mendicants are seen following them, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1229]="*Aparepi vo, bhikkhave, satta aparihāniye dhamme desessāmi, taṃ suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasikarotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**I will teach you seven more principles that prevent decline. …*";
P_HTM[1230]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1231]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[1232]="*“Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu satisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāvessanti … pe …**As long as the mendicants develop the awakening factors of mindfulness …*";
P_HTM[1233]="*dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāvessanti …**investigation of principles …*";
P_HTM[1234]="*vīriyasambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāvessanti …**energy …*";
P_HTM[1235]="*pītisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāvessanti …**rapture …*";
P_HTM[1236]="*passaddhisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāvessanti …**tranquility …*";
P_HTM[1237]="*samādhisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāvessanti …**immersion …*";
P_HTM[1238]="*upekkhāsambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāvessanti, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni.**equanimity, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1239]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, ime satta aparihāniyā dhammā bhikkhūsu ṭhassanti, imesu ca sattasu aparihāniyesu dhammesu bhikkhū sandississanti, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā no parihāni.**As long as these seven principles that prevent decline last among the mendicants, and as long as the mendicants are seen following them, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1240]="*Aparepi vo, bhikkhave, satta aparihāniye dhamme desessāmi, taṃ suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasikarotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**I will teach you seven more principles that prevent decline. …*";
P_HTM[1241]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1242]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[1243]="*“Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhū aniccasaññaṃ bhāvessanti … pe …**As long as the mendicants develop the perceptions of impermanence …*";
P_HTM[1244]="*anattasaññaṃ bhāvessanti …**not-self …*";
P_HTM[1245]="*asubhasaññaṃ bhāvessanti …**ugliness …*";
P_HTM[1246]="*ādīnavasaññaṃ bhāvessanti …**drawbacks …*";
P_HTM[1247]="*pahānasaññaṃ bhāvessanti …**giving up …*";
P_HTM[1248]="*virāgasaññaṃ bhāvessanti …**fading away …*";
P_HTM[1249]="*nirodhasaññaṃ bhāvessanti, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni.**cessation, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1250]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, ime satta aparihāniyā dhammā bhikkhūsu ṭhassanti, imesu ca sattasu aparihāniyesu dhammesu bhikkhū sandississanti, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni.**As long as these seven principles that prevent decline last among the mendicants, and as long as the mendicants are seen following them, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1251]="*Cha vo, bhikkhave, aparihāniye dhamme desessāmi, taṃ suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasikarotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**I will teach you six principles that prevent decline. …*";
P_HTM[1252]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1253]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[1254]="*“Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhū mettaṃ kāyakammaṃ paccupaṭṭhāpessanti sabrahmacārīsu āvi ceva raho ca, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (1)**As long as the mendicants consistently treat their spiritual companions with bodily kindness …*";
P_HTM[1255]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhū mettaṃ vacīkammaṃ paccupaṭṭhāpessanti … pe … (2)**verbal kindness …*";
P_HTM[1256]="*mettaṃ manokammaṃ paccupaṭṭhāpessanti sabrahmacārīsu āvi ceva raho ca, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (3)**and mental kindness both in public and in private, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1257]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhū, ye te lābhā dhammikā dhammaladdhā antamaso pattapariyāpannamattampi tathārūpehi lābhehi appaṭivibhattabhogī bhavissanti sīlavantehi sabrahmacārīhi sādhāraṇabhogī, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (4)**As long as the mendicants share without reservation any material possessions they have gained by legitimate means, even the food placed in the alms-bowl, using them in common with their ethical spiritual companions, they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1258]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhū yāni tāni sīlāni akhaṇḍāni acchiddāni asabalāni akammāsāni bhujissāni viññūpasatthāni aparāmaṭṭhāni samādhisaṃvattanikāni tathārūpesu sīlesu sīlasāmaññagatā viharissanti sabrahmacārīhi āvi ceva raho ca, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (5)**As long as the mendicants live according to the precepts shared with their spiritual companions, both in public and in private—such precepts as are unbroken, impeccable, spotless, and unmarred, liberating, praised by sensible people, not mistaken, and leading to immersion—they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1259]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhū yāyaṃ diṭṭhi ariyā niyyānikā, niyyāti takkarassa sammā dukkhakkhayāya, tathārūpāya diṭṭhiyā diṭṭhisāmaññagatā viharissanti sabrahmacārīhi āvi ceva raho ca, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni. (6)**As long as the mendicants live according to the view shared with their spiritual companions, both in public and in private—the view that is noble and emancipating, and leads one who practices it to the complete end of suffering—they can expect growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1260]="*Yāvakīvañca, bhikkhave, ime cha aparihāniyā dhammā bhikkhūsu ṭhassanti, imesu ca chasu aparihāniyesu dhammesu bhikkhū sandississanti, vuddhiyeva, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihānī”ti.**As long as these six principles that prevent decline last among the mendicants, and as long as the mendicants are seen following them, they can expect growth, not decline.”*";
P_HTM[1261]="*()* **";
P_HTM[1262]="*Tatra sudaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharanto gijjhakūṭe pabbate etadeva bahulaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ dhammiṃ kathaṃ karoti:**And while staying there at the Vulture’s Peak the Buddha often gave this Dhamma talk to the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[1263]="*“iti sīlaṃ, iti samādhi, iti paññā.**“Such is ethics, such is immersion, such is wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1264]="*Sīlaparibhāvito samādhi mahapphalo hoti mahānisaṃso.**When immersion is imbued with ethics it’s very fruitful and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[1265]="*Samādhiparibhāvitā paññā mahapphalā hoti mahānisaṃsā.**When wisdom is imbued with immersion it’s very fruitful and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[1266]="*Paññāparibhāvitaṃ cittaṃ sammadeva āsavehi vimuccati, seyyathidaṃ—**When the mind is imbued with wisdom it is rightly freed from the defilements, namely,*";
P_HTM[1267]="*kāmāsavā, bhavāsavā, avijjāsavā”ti.**the defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.”*";
P_HTM[1268]="*Atha kho bhagavā rājagahe yathābhirantaṃ viharitvā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**When the Buddha had stayed in Rājagaha as long as he wished, he addressed Venerable Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[1269]="*“āyāmānanda, yena ambalaṭṭhikā tenupasaṅkamissāmā”ti.**“Come, Ānanda, let’s go to Ambalaṭṭhikā.”*";
P_HTM[1270]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Ānanda replied.*";
P_HTM[1271]="*Atha kho bhagavā mahatā bhikkhusaṅghena saddhiṃ yena ambalaṭṭhikā tadavasari.**Then the Buddha together with a large Saṅgha of mendicants arrived at Ambalaṭṭhikā,*";
P_HTM[1272]="*Tatra sudaṃ bhagavā ambalaṭṭhikāyaṃ viharati rājāgārake.**where he stayed in the royal rest-house.*";
P_HTM[1273]="*Tatrāpi sudaṃ bhagavā ambalaṭṭhikāyaṃ viharanto rājāgārake etadeva bahulaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ dhammiṃ kathaṃ karoti:**And while staying there, too, he often gave this Dhamma talk to the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[1274]="*“iti sīlaṃ iti samādhi iti paññā.**“Such is ethics, such is immersion, such is wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1275]="*Sīlaparibhāvito samādhi mahapphalo hoti mahānisaṃso.**When immersion is imbued with ethics it’s very fruitful and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[1276]="*Samādhiparibhāvitā paññā mahapphalā hoti mahānisaṃsā.**When wisdom is imbued with immersion it’s very fruitful and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[1277]="*Paññāparibhāvitaṃ cittaṃ sammadeva āsavehi vimuccati, seyyathidaṃ—**When the mind is imbued with wisdom it is rightly freed from the defilements, namely,*";
P_HTM[1278]="*kāmāsavā, bhavāsavā, avijjāsavā”ti.**the defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.”*";
P_HTM[1279]="*Atha kho bhagavā ambalaṭṭhikāyaṃ yathābhirantaṃ viharitvā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**When the Buddha had stayed in Ambalaṭṭhikā as long as he wished, he addressed Venerable Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[1280]="*“āyāmānanda, yena nāḷandā tenupasaṅkamissāmā”ti.**“Come, Ānanda, let’s go to Nāḷandā.”*";
P_HTM[1281]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Ānanda replied.*";
P_HTM[1282]="*Atha kho bhagavā mahatā bhikkhusaṅghena saddhiṃ yena nāḷandā tadavasari,**Then the Buddha together with a large Saṅgha of mendicants arrived at Nāḷandā,*";
P_HTM[1283]="*tatra sudaṃ bhagavā nāḷandāyaṃ viharati pāvārikambavane.**where he stayed in Pāvārika’s mango grove.*";
P_HTM[1284]="*4. Sāriputtasīhanāda**4. Sāriputta’s Lion’s Roar*";
P_HTM[1285]="*Atha kho āyasmā sāriputto yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā sāriputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Sāriputta went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[1286]="*“evaṃ pasanno ahaṃ, bhante, bhagavati;**“Sir, I have such confidence in the Buddha that*";
P_HTM[1287]="*na cāhu na ca bhavissati na cetarahi vijjati añño samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā bhagavatā bhiyyobhiññataro yadidaṃ sambodhiyan”ti.**I believe there’s no other ascetic or brahmin—whether past, future, or present—whose direct knowledge is superior to the Buddha when it comes to awakening.”*";
P_HTM[1288]="*“Uḷārā kho te ayaṃ, sāriputta, āsabhī vācā bhāsitā, ekaṃso gahito, sīhanādo nadito:**“That’s a grand and dramatic statement, Sāriputta. You’ve roared a definitive, categorical lion’s roar, saying:*";
P_HTM[1289]="*‘evaṃpasanno ahaṃ, bhante, bhagavati;**‘I have such confidence in the Buddha that*";
P_HTM[1290]="*na cāhu na ca bhavissati na cetarahi vijjati añño samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā bhagavatā bhiyyobhiññataro yadidaṃ sambodhiyan’ti.**I believe there’s no other ascetic or brahmin—whether past, future, or present—whose direct knowledge is superior to the Buddha when it comes to awakening.’*";
P_HTM[1291]="*Kiṃ te, sāriputta, ye te ahesuṃ atītamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā, sabbe te bhagavanto cetasā ceto paricca viditā:**What about all the perfected ones, the fully awakened Buddhas who lived in the past? Have you comprehended their minds to know that*";
P_HTM[1292]="*‘evaṃsīlā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipi, evaṃdhammā evaṃpaññā evaṃvihārī evaṃvimuttā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipī’”ti?**those Buddhas had such ethics, or such qualities, or such wisdom, or such meditation, or such freedom?”*";
P_HTM[1293]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1294]="*“Kiṃ pana te, sāriputta, ye te bhavissanti anāgatamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā, sabbe te bhagavanto cetasā ceto paricca viditā:**“And what about all the perfected ones, the fully awakened Buddhas who will live in the future? Have you comprehended their minds to know that*";
P_HTM[1295]="*‘evaṃsīlā te bhagavanto bhavissanti itipi, evaṃdhammā evaṃpaññā evaṃvihārī evaṃvimuttā te bhagavanto bhavissanti itipī’”ti?**those Buddhas will have such ethics, or such qualities, or such wisdom, or such meditation, or such freedom?”*";
P_HTM[1296]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1297]="*“Kiṃ pana te, sāriputta, ahaṃ etarahi arahaṃ sammāsambuddho cetasā ceto paricca vidito:**“And what about me, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha at present? Have you comprehended my mind to know that*";
P_HTM[1298]="*‘evaṃsīlo bhagavā itipi, evaṃdhammo evaṃpañño evaṃvihārī evaṃvimutto bhagavā itipī’”ti?**I have such ethics, or such teachings, or such wisdom, or such meditation, or such freedom?”*";
P_HTM[1299]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1300]="*“Ettha ca hi te, sāriputta, atītānāgatapaccuppannesu arahantesu sammāsambuddhesu cetopariyañāṇaṃ natthi.**“Well then, Sāriputta, given that you don’t comprehend the minds of Buddhas past, future, or present,*";
P_HTM[1301]="*Atha kiñcarahi te ayaṃ, sāriputta, uḷārā āsabhī vācā bhāsitā, ekaṃso gahito, sīhanādo nadito:**what exactly are you doing, making such a grand and dramatic statement, roaring such a definitive, categorical lion’s roar?”*";
P_HTM[1302]="*‘evaṃpasanno ahaṃ, bhante, bhagavati; na cāhu na ca bhavissati na cetarahi vijjati añño samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā bhagavatā bhiyyobhiññataro yadidaṃ sambodhiyan’”ti?* **";
P_HTM[1303]="*“Na kho me, bhante, atītānāgatapaccuppannesu arahantesu sammāsambuddhesu cetopariyañāṇaṃ atthi,**“Sir, though I don’t comprehend the minds of Buddhas past, future, and present,*";
P_HTM[1304]="*api ca me dhammanvayo vidito.**still I understand this by inference from the teaching.*";
P_HTM[1305]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante, rañño paccantimaṃ nagaraṃ daḷhuddhāpaṃ daḷhapākāratoraṇaṃ ekadvāraṃ,**Suppose there was a king’s frontier citadel with fortified embankments, ramparts, and arches, and a single gate.*";
P_HTM[1306]="*tatrassa dovāriko paṇḍito viyatto medhāvī aññātānaṃ nivāretā ñātānaṃ pavesetā.**And it has a gatekeeper who is astute, competent, and intelligent. He keeps strangers out and lets known people in.*";
P_HTM[1307]="*So tassa nagarassa samantā anupariyāyapathaṃ anukkamamāno na passeyya pākārasandhiṃ vā pākāravivaraṃ vā, antamaso biḷāranikkhamanamattampi.**As he walks around the patrol path, he doesn’t see a hole or cleft in the wall, not even one big enough for a cat to slip out.*";
P_HTM[1308]="*Tassa evamassa:**He thinks:*";
P_HTM[1309]="*‘ye kho keci oḷārikā pāṇā imaṃ nagaraṃ pavisanti vā nikkhamanti vā, sabbe te imināva dvārena pavisanti vā nikkhamanti vā’ti.**‘Whatever sizable creatures enter or leave the citadel, all of them do so via this gate.’*";
P_HTM[1310]="*Evameva kho me, bhante, dhammanvayo vidito:**In the same way, I understand this by inference from the teaching:*";
P_HTM[1311]="*‘ye te, bhante, ahesuṃ atītamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā, sabbe te bhagavanto pañca nīvaraṇe pahāya cetaso upakkilese paññāya dubbalīkaraṇe catūsu satipaṭṭhānesu supatiṭṭhitacittā sattabojjhaṅge yathābhūtaṃ bhāvetvā anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambujjhiṃsu.**‘All the perfected ones, fully awakened Buddhas—whether past, future, or present—give up the five hindrances, corruptions of the heart that weaken wisdom. Their mind is firmly established in the four kinds of mindfulness meditation. They correctly develop the seven awakening factors. And they wake up to the supreme perfect awakening.’”*";
P_HTM[1312]="*Yepi te, bhante, bhavissanti anāgatamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā, sabbe te bhagavanto pañca nīvaraṇe pahāya cetaso upakkilese paññāya dubbalīkaraṇe catūsu satipaṭṭhānesu supatiṭṭhitacittā satta bojjhaṅge yathābhūtaṃ bhāvetvā anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambujjhissanti.* **";
P_HTM[1313]="*Bhagavāpi, bhante, etarahi arahaṃ sammāsambuddho pañca nīvaraṇe pahāya cetaso upakkilese paññāya dubbalīkaraṇe catūsu satipaṭṭhānesu supatiṭṭhitacitto satta bojjhaṅge yathābhūtaṃ bhāvetvā anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambuddho’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1314]="*Tatrapi sudaṃ bhagavā nāḷandāyaṃ viharanto pāvārikambavane etadeva bahulaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ dhammiṃ kathaṃ karoti:**And while staying at Nāḷandā, too, the Buddha often gave this Dhamma talk to the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[1315]="*“iti sīlaṃ, iti samādhi, iti paññā.**“Such is ethics, such is immersion, such is wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1316]="*Sīlaparibhāvito samādhi mahapphalo hoti mahānisaṃso.**When immersion is imbued with ethics it’s very fruitful and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[1317]="*Samādhiparibhāvitā paññā mahapphalā hoti mahānisaṃsā.**When wisdom is imbued with immersion it’s very fruitful and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[1318]="*Paññāparibhāvitaṃ cittaṃ sammadeva āsavehi vimuccati, seyyathidaṃ—**When the mind is imbued with wisdom it is rightly freed from the defilements, namely,*";
P_HTM[1319]="*kāmāsavā, bhavāsavā, avijjāsavā”ti.**the defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.”*";
P_HTM[1320]="*5. Dussīlaādīnava**5. The Drawbacks of Unethical Conduct*";
P_HTM[1321]="*Atha kho bhagavā nāḷandāyaṃ yathābhirantaṃ viharitvā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**When the Buddha had stayed in Nāḷandā as long as he wished, he addressed Venerable Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[1322]="*“āyāmānanda, yena pāṭaligāmo tenupasaṅkamissāmā”ti.**“Come, Ānanda, let’s go to Pāṭaligāma.”*";
P_HTM[1323]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Ānanda replied.*";
P_HTM[1324]="*Atha kho bhagavā mahatā bhikkhusaṃghena saddhiṃ yena pāṭaligāmo tadavasari.**Then the Buddha together with a large Saṅgha of mendicants arrived at Pāṭaligāma.*";
P_HTM[1325]="*Assosuṃ kho pāṭaligāmikā upāsakā: “bhagavā kira pāṭaligāmaṃ anuppatto”ti.**The lay followers of Pāṭaligāma heard that he had arrived.*";
P_HTM[1326]="*Atha kho pāṭaligāmikā upāsakā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho pāṭaligāmikā upāsakā bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**So they went to see him, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[1327]="*“adhivāsetu no, bhante, bhagavā āvasathāgāran”ti.**“Sir, please consent to come to our guest house.”*";
P_HTM[1328]="*Adhivāsesi bhagavā tuṇhībhāvena.**The Buddha consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[1329]="*Atha kho pāṭaligāmikā upāsakā bhagavato adhivāsanaṃ viditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā yena āvasathāgāraṃ tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā sabbasanthariṃ āvasathāgāraṃ santharitvā āsanāni paññapetvā udakamaṇikaṃ patiṭṭhāpetvā telapadīpaṃ āropetvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu, upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu. Ekamantaṃ ṭhitā kho pāṭaligāmikā upāsakā bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**Then, knowing that the Buddha had consented, the lay followers of Pāṭaligāma got up from their seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on their right. Then they went to the guest house, where they spread carpets all over, prepared seats, set up a water jar, and placed a lamp. Then they went back to the Buddha, bowed, stood to one side, and told him of their preparations, saying:*";
P_HTM[1330]="*“sabbasantharisanthataṃ, bhante, āvasathāgāraṃ, āsanāni paññattāni, udakamaṇiko patiṭṭhāpito, telapadīpo āropito;* **";
P_HTM[1331]="*yassadāni, bhante, bhagavā kālaṃ maññatī”ti.**“Please, sir, come at your convenience.”*";
P_HTM[1332]="*Atha kho bhagavā sāyanhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya saddhiṃ bhikkhusaṃghena yena āvasathāgāraṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā pāde pakkhāletvā āvasathāgāraṃ pavisitvā majjhimaṃ thambhaṃ nissāya puratthābhimukho nisīdi.**In the morning, the Buddha robed up and, taking his bowl and robe, went to the guest house together with the Saṅgha of mendicants. Having washed his feet he entered the guest house and sat against the central column facing east.*";
P_HTM[1333]="*Bhikkhusaṃghopi kho pāde pakkhāletvā āvasathāgāraṃ pavisitvā pacchimaṃ bhittiṃ nissāya puratthābhimukho nisīdi bhagavantameva purakkhatvā.**The Saṅgha of mendicants also washed their feet, entered the guest house, and sat against the west wall facing east, with the Buddha right in front of them.*";
P_HTM[1334]="*Pāṭaligāmikāpi kho upāsakā pāde pakkhāletvā āvasathāgāraṃ pavisitvā puratthimaṃ bhittiṃ nissāya pacchimābhimukhā nisīdiṃsu bhagavantameva purakkhatvā.**The lay followers of Pāṭaligāma also washed their feet, entered the guest house, and sat against the east wall facing west, with the Buddha right in front of them.*";
P_HTM[1335]="*()* **";
P_HTM[1336]="*Atha kho bhagavā pāṭaligāmike upāsake āmantesi:**Then the Buddha addressed them:*";
P_HTM[1337]="*“pañcime, gahapatayo, ādīnavā dussīlassa sīlavipattiyā.**“Householders, there are these five drawbacks for an unethical person because of their failure in ethics.*";
P_HTM[1338]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1339]="*Idha, gahapatayo, dussīlo sīlavipanno pamādādhikaraṇaṃ mahatiṃ bhogajāniṃ nigacchati.**Firstly, an unethical person loses substantial wealth on account of negligence.*";
P_HTM[1340]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamo ādīnavo dussīlassa sīlavipattiyā.**This is the first drawback for an unethical person because of their failure in ethics.*";
P_HTM[1341]="*Puna caparaṃ, gahapatayo, dussīlassa sīlavipannassa pāpako kittisaddo abbhuggacchati.**Furthermore, an unethical person gets a bad reputation.*";
P_HTM[1342]="*Ayaṃ dutiyo ādīnavo dussīlassa sīlavipattiyā.**This is the second drawback.*";
P_HTM[1343]="*Puna caparaṃ, gahapatayo, dussīlo sīlavipanno yaññadeva parisaṃ upasaṅkamati—yadi khattiyaparisaṃ yadi brāhmaṇaparisaṃ yadi gahapatiparisaṃ yadi samaṇaparisaṃ—avisārado upasaṅkamati maṅkubhūto.**Furthermore, an unethical person enters any kind of assembly timid and embarrassed, whether it’s an assembly of aristocrats, brahmins, householders, or ascetics.*";
P_HTM[1344]="*Ayaṃ tatiyo ādīnavo dussīlassa sīlavipattiyā.**This is the third drawback.*";
P_HTM[1345]="*Puna caparaṃ, gahapatayo, dussīlo sīlavipanno sammūḷho kālaṃ karoti.**Furthermore, an unethical person dies feeling lost.*";
P_HTM[1346]="*Ayaṃ catuttho ādīnavo dussīlassa sīlavipattiyā.**This is the fourth drawback.*";
P_HTM[1347]="*Puna caparaṃ, gahapatayo, dussīlo sīlavipanno kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.**Furthermore, an unethical person, when their body breaks up, after death, is reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[1348]="*Ayaṃ pañcamo ādīnavo dussīlassa sīlavipattiyā.**This is the fifth drawback.*";
P_HTM[1349]="*Ime kho, gahapatayo, pañca ādīnavā dussīlassa sīlavipattiyā.**These are the five drawbacks for an unethical person because of their failure in ethics.*";
P_HTM[1350]="*6. Sīlavantaānisaṃsa**6. The Benefits of Ethical Conduct*";
P_HTM[1351]="*Pañcime, gahapatayo, ānisaṃsā sīlavato sīlasampadāya.**There are these five benefits for an ethical person because of their accomplishment in ethics.*";
P_HTM[1352]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1353]="*Idha, gahapatayo, sīlavā sīlasampanno appamādādhikaraṇaṃ mahantaṃ bhogakkhandhaṃ adhigacchati.**Firstly, an ethical person gains substantial wealth on account of diligence.*";
P_HTM[1354]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamo ānisaṃso sīlavato sīlasampadāya.**This is the first benefit.*";
P_HTM[1355]="*Puna caparaṃ, gahapatayo, sīlavato sīlasampannassa kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggacchati.**Furthermore, an ethical person gets a good reputation.*";
P_HTM[1356]="*Ayaṃ dutiyo ānisaṃso sīlavato sīlasampadāya.**This is the second benefit.*";
P_HTM[1357]="*Puna caparaṃ, gahapatayo, sīlavā sīlasampanno yaññadeva parisaṃ upasaṅkamati—yadi khattiyaparisaṃ yadi brāhmaṇaparisaṃ yadi gahapatiparisaṃ yadi samaṇaparisaṃ visārado upasaṅkamati amaṅkubhūto.**Furthermore, an ethical person enters any kind of assembly bold and self-assured, whether it’s an assembly of aristocrats, brahmins, householders, or ascetics.*";
P_HTM[1358]="*Ayaṃ tatiyo ānisaṃso sīlavato sīlasampadāya.**This is the third benefit.*";
P_HTM[1359]="*Puna caparaṃ, gahapatayo, sīlavā sīlasampanno asammūḷho kālaṃ karoti.**Furthermore, an ethical person dies not feeling lost.*";
P_HTM[1360]="*Ayaṃ catuttho ānisaṃso sīlavato sīlasampadāya.**This is the fourth benefit.*";
P_HTM[1361]="*Puna caparaṃ, gahapatayo, sīlavā sīlasampanno kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**Furthermore, when an ethical person’s body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[1362]="*Ayaṃ pañcamo ānisaṃso sīlavato sīlasampadāya.**This is the fifth benefit.*";
P_HTM[1363]="*Ime kho, gahapatayo, pañca ānisaṃsā sīlavato sīlasampadāyā”ti.**These are the five benefits for an ethical person because of their accomplishment in ethics.”*";
P_HTM[1364]="*Atha kho bhagavā pāṭaligāmike upāsake bahudeva rattiṃ dhammiyā kathāya sandassetvā samādapetvā samuttejetvā sampahaṃsetvā uyyojesi:**The Buddha spent most of the night educating, encouraging, firing up, and inspiring the lay followers of Pāṭaligāma with a Dhamma talk. Then he dismissed them,*";
P_HTM[1365]="*“abhikkantā kho, gahapatayo, ratti, yassadāni tumhe kālaṃ maññathā”ti.**“The night is getting late, householders. Please go at your convenience.”*";
P_HTM[1366]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho pāṭaligāmikā upāsakā bhagavato paṭissutvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkamiṃsu.**“Yes, sir,” replied the lay followers of Pāṭaligāma. They got up from their seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on their right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[1367]="*Atha kho bhagavā acirapakkantesu pāṭaligāmikesu upāsakesu suññāgāraṃ pāvisi.**Soon after they left the Buddha entered a private cubicle.*";
P_HTM[1368]="*7. Pāṭaliputtanagaramāpana**7. Building a Citadel*";
P_HTM[1369]="*Tena kho pana samayena sunidhavassakārā magadhamahāmattā pāṭaligāme nagaraṃ māpenti vajjīnaṃ paṭibāhāya.**Now at that time the Magadhan ministers Sunidha and Vassakāra were building a citadel at Pāṭaligāma to keep the Vajjis out.*";
P_HTM[1370]="*Tena samayena sambahulā devatāyo sahasseva pāṭaligāme vatthūni pariggaṇhanti.**At that time thousands of deities were taking possession of building sites in Pāṭaligāma.*";
P_HTM[1371]="*Yasmiṃ padese mahesakkhā devatā vatthūni pariggaṇhanti, mahesakkhānaṃ tattha raññaṃ rājamahāmattānaṃ cittāni namanti nivesanāni māpetuṃ.**Illustrious rulers or royal ministers inclined to build houses at sites possessed by illustrious deities.*";
P_HTM[1372]="*Yasmiṃ padese majjhimā devatā vatthūni pariggaṇhanti, majjhimānaṃ tattha raññaṃ rājamahāmattānaṃ cittāni namanti nivesanāni māpetuṃ.**Middling rulers or royal ministers inclined to build houses at sites possessed by middling deities.*";
P_HTM[1373]="*Yasmiṃ padese nīcā devatā vatthūni pariggaṇhanti, nīcānaṃ tattha raññaṃ rājamahāmattānaṃ cittāni namanti nivesanāni māpetuṃ.**Lesser rulers or royal ministers inclined to build houses at sites possessed by lesser deities.*";
P_HTM[1374]="*Addasā kho bhagavā dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena tā devatāyo sahasseva pāṭaligāme vatthūni pariggaṇhantiyo.**With clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman, the Buddha saw those deities taking possession of building sites in Pāṭaligāma.*";
P_HTM[1375]="*Atha kho bhagavā rattiyā paccūsasamayaṃ paccuṭṭhāya āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**The Buddha rose at the crack of dawn and addressed Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[1376]="*“Ke nu kho, ānanda, pāṭaligāme nagaraṃ māpentī”ti?**“Ānanda, who is building a citadel at Pāṭaligāma?”*";
P_HTM[1377]="*“Sunidhavassakārā, bhante, magadhamahāmattā pāṭaligāme nagaraṃ māpenti vajjīnaṃ paṭibāhāyā”ti.**“Sir, the Magadhan ministers Sunidha and Vassakāra are building a citadel to keep the Vajjis out.”*";
P_HTM[1378]="*“Seyyathāpi, ānanda, devehi tāvatiṃsehi saddhiṃ mantetvā;**“It’s as if they were building the citadel in consultation with the gods of the Thirty-Three.*";
P_HTM[1379]="*evameva kho, ānanda, sunidhavassakārā magadhamahāmattā pāṭaligāme nagaraṃ māpenti vajjīnaṃ paṭibāhāya.* **";
P_HTM[1380]="*Idhāhaṃ, ānanda, addasaṃ dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena sambahulā devatāyo sahasseva pāṭaligāme vatthūni pariggaṇhantiyo.**With clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman, I saw those deities taking possession of building sites.*";
P_HTM[1381]="*Yasmiṃ, ānanda, padese mahesakkhā devatā vatthūni pariggaṇhanti, mahesakkhānaṃ tattha raññaṃ rājamahāmattānaṃ cittāni namanti nivesanāni māpetuṃ.**Illustrious rulers or royal ministers inclined to build houses at sites possessed by illustrious deities.*";
P_HTM[1382]="*Yasmiṃ padese majjhimā devatā vatthūni pariggaṇhanti, majjhimānaṃ tattha raññaṃ rājamahāmattānaṃ cittāni namanti nivesanāni māpetuṃ.**Middling rulers or royal ministers inclined to build houses at sites possessed by middling deities.*";
P_HTM[1383]="*Yasmiṃ padese nīcā devatā vatthūni pariggaṇhanti, nīcānaṃ tattha raññaṃ rājamahāmattānaṃ cittāni namanti nivesanāni māpetuṃ.**Lesser rulers or royal ministers inclined to build houses at sites possessed by lesser deities.*";
P_HTM[1384]="*Yāvatā, ānanda, ariyaṃ āyatanaṃ yāvatā vaṇippatho idaṃ agganagaraṃ bhavissati pāṭaliputtaṃ puṭabhedanaṃ.**As far as the civilized region extends, as far as the trading zone extends, this will be the chief city: the Pāṭaliputta trade center.*";
P_HTM[1385]="*Pāṭaliputtassa kho, ānanda, tayo antarāyā bhavissanti—**But Pāṭaliputta will face three threats:*";
P_HTM[1386]="*aggito vā udakato vā mithubhedā vā”ti.**from fire, flood, and dissension.”*";
P_HTM[1387]="*Atha kho sunidhavassakārā magadhamahāmattā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu,**Then the Magadhan ministers Sunidha and Vassakāra approached the Buddha, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[1388]="*sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu, ekamantaṃ ṭhitā kho sunidhavassakārā magadhamahāmattā bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, they stood to one side and said,*";
P_HTM[1389]="*“adhivāsetu no bhavaṃ gotamo ajjatanāya bhattaṃ saddhiṃ bhikkhusaṅghenā”ti.**“Would Master Gotama together with the mendicant Saṅgha please accept today’s meal from me?”*";
P_HTM[1390]="*Adhivāsesi bhagavā tuṇhībhāvena.**The Buddha consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[1391]="*Atha kho sunidhavassakārā magadhamahāmattā bhagavato adhivāsanaṃ viditvā yena sako āvasatho tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā sake āvasathe paṇītaṃ khādanīyaṃ bhojanīyaṃ paṭiyādāpetvā bhagavato kālaṃ ārocāpesuṃ:**Then, knowing that the Buddha had consented, they went to their own guest house, where they had a variety of delicious foods prepared. Then they had the Buddha informed of the time, saying,*";
P_HTM[1392]="*“kālo, bho gotama, niṭṭhitaṃ bhattan”ti.**“It’s time, Master Gotama, the meal is ready.”*";
P_HTM[1393]="*Atha kho bhagavā pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya saddhiṃ bhikkhusaṅghena yena sunidhavassakārānaṃ magadhamahāmattānaṃ āvasatho tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then the Buddha robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, went to their guest house together with the mendicant Saṅgha, where he sat on the seat spread out.*";
P_HTM[1394]="*Atha kho sunidhavassakārā magadhamahāmattā buddhappamukhaṃ bhikkhusaṅghaṃ paṇītena khādanīyena bhojanīyena sahatthā santappesuṃ sampavāresuṃ.**Then Sunidha and Vassakāra served and satisfied the mendicant Saṅgha headed by the Buddha with their own hands with a variety of delicious foods.*";
P_HTM[1395]="*Atha kho sunidhavassakārā magadhamahāmattā bhagavantaṃ bhuttāviṃ onītapattapāṇiṃ aññataraṃ nīcaṃ āsanaṃ gahetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu.**When the Buddha had eaten and washed his hand and bowl, Sunidha and Vassakāra took a low seat and sat to one side.*";
P_HTM[1396]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinne kho sunidhavassakāre magadhamahāmatte bhagavā imāhi gāthāhi anumodi:**The Buddha expressed his appreciation with these verses:*";
P_HTM[1397]="*“Yasmiṃ padese kappeti,**“In the place he makes his dwelling,*";
P_HTM[1398]="*vāsaṃ paṇḍitajātiyo;**having fed the astute*";
P_HTM[1399]="*Sīlavantettha bhojetvā,**and the virtuous here,*";
P_HTM[1400]="*saññate brahmacārayo.**the restrained spiritual practitioners,*";
P_HTM[1401]="*Yā tattha devatā āsuṃ,**he should dedicate an offering*";
P_HTM[1402]="*tāsaṃ dakkhiṇamādise;**to the deities there.*";
P_HTM[1403]="*Tā pūjitā pūjayanti,**Venerated, they venerate him;*";
P_HTM[1404]="*mānitā mānayanti naṃ.**honored, they honor him.*";
P_HTM[1405]="*Tato naṃ anukampanti,**After that they have compassion for him,*";
P_HTM[1406]="*mātā puttaṃva orasaṃ;**like a mother for the child at her breast.*";
P_HTM[1407]="*Devatānukampito poso,**A man beloved of the deities*";
P_HTM[1408]="*sadā bhadrāni passatī”ti.**always sees nice things.”*";
P_HTM[1409]="*Atha kho bhagavā sunidhavassakāre magadhamahāmatte imāhi gāthāhi anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkāmi.**When the Buddha had expressed his appreciation to Sunidha and Vassakāra with these verses, he got up from his seat and left.*";
P_HTM[1410]="*Tena kho pana samayena sunidhavassakārā magadhamahāmattā bhagavantaṃ piṭṭhito piṭṭhito anubandhā honti:**Sunidha and Vassakāra followed behind the Buddha, thinking,*";
P_HTM[1411]="*“yenajja samaṇo gotamo dvārena nikkhamissati, taṃ gotamadvāraṃ nāma bhavissati.**“The gate through which the ascetic Gotama departs today shall be named the Gotama Gate.*";
P_HTM[1412]="*Yena titthena gaṅgaṃ nadiṃ tarissati, taṃ gotamatitthaṃ nāma bhavissatī”ti.**The ford at which he crosses the Ganges River shall be named the Gotama Ford.”*";
P_HTM[1413]="*Atha kho bhagavā yena dvārena nikkhami, taṃ gotamadvāraṃ nāma ahosi.**Then the gate through which the Buddha departed was named the Gotama Gate.*";
P_HTM[1414]="*Atha kho bhagavā yena gaṅgā nadī tenupasaṅkami.**Then the Buddha came to the Ganges River.*";
P_HTM[1415]="*Tena kho pana samayena gaṅgā nadī pūrā hoti samatittikā kākapeyyā.**Now at that time the Ganges was full to the brim so a crow could drink from it.*";
P_HTM[1416]="*Appekacce manussā nāvaṃ pariyesanti, appekacce uḷumpaṃ pariyesanti, appekacce kullaṃ bandhanti apārā, pāraṃ gantukāmā.**Wanting to cross from the near to the far shore, some people were seeking a boat, some a dinghy, while some were tying up a raft.*";
P_HTM[1417]="*Atha kho bhagavā—seyyathāpi nāma balavā puriso samiñjitaṃ vā bāhaṃ pasāreyya, pasāritaṃ vā bāhaṃ samiñjeyya; evameva—gaṅgāya nadiyā orimatīre antarahito pārimatīre paccuṭṭhāsi saddhiṃ bhikkhusaṃghena.**But, as easily as a strong person would extend or contract their arm, the Buddha, together with the mendicant Saṅgha, vanished from the near shore and landed on the far shore.*";
P_HTM[1418]="*Addasā kho bhagavā te manusse appekacce nāvaṃ pariyesante appekacce uḷumpaṃ pariyesante appekacce kullaṃ bandhante apārā pāraṃ gantukāme.**He saw all those people wanting to cross over.*";
P_HTM[1419]="*Atha kho bhagavā etamatthaṃ viditvā tāyaṃ velāyaṃ imaṃ udānaṃ udānesi:**Knowing the meaning of this, on that occasion the Buddha was inspired to exclaim:*";
P_HTM[1420]="*“Ye taranti aṇṇavaṃ saraṃ,**“Those who cross a river or stream*";
P_HTM[1421]="*Setuṃ katvāna visajja pallalāni;**have built a bridge and left the marshes behind.*";
P_HTM[1422]="*Kullañhi jano bandhati,**While some people are still tying a raft,*";
P_HTM[1423]="*Tiṇṇā medhāvino janā”ti.**intelligent people have crossed over.”*";
P_HTM[1424]="*Paṭhamabhāṇavāro.* **";
P_HTM[1425]="*8. Ariyasaccakathā**8. Talk on the Noble Truths*";
P_HTM[1426]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**Then the Buddha said to Venerable Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[1427]="*“āyāmānanda, yena koṭigāmo tenupasaṅkamissāmā”ti.**“Come, Ānanda, let’s go to Koṭigāma.”*";
P_HTM[1428]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Ānanda replied.*";
P_HTM[1429]="*Atha kho bhagavā mahatā bhikkhusaṃghena saddhiṃ yena koṭigāmo tadavasari.**Then the Buddha together with a large Saṅgha of mendicants arrived at Koṭigāma,*";
P_HTM[1430]="*Tatra sudaṃ bhagavā koṭigāme viharati.**and stayed there.*";
P_HTM[1431]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There he addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[1432]="*“Catunnaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyasaccānaṃ ananubodhā appaṭivedhā evamidaṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ sandhāvitaṃ saṃsaritaṃ mamañceva tumhākañca.**“Mendicants, not understanding and not penetrating four noble truths, both you and I have wandered and transmigrated for such a very long time.*";
P_HTM[1433]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1434]="*Dukkhassa, bhikkhave, ariyasaccassa ananubodhā appaṭivedhā evamidaṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ sandhāvitaṃ saṃsaritaṃ mamañceva tumhākañca.**The noble truths of suffering,*";
P_HTM[1435]="*Dukkhasamudayassa, bhikkhave, ariyasaccassa ananubodhā appaṭivedhā evamidaṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ sandhāvitaṃ saṃsaritaṃ mamañceva tumhākañca.**the origin of suffering,*";
P_HTM[1436]="*Dukkhanirodhassa, bhikkhave, ariyasaccassa ananubodhā appaṭivedhā evamidaṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ sandhāvitaṃ saṃsaritaṃ mamañceva tumhākañca.**the cessation of suffering,*";
P_HTM[1437]="*Dukkhanirodhagāminiyā paṭipadāya, bhikkhave, ariyasaccassa ananubodhā appaṭivedhā evamidaṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ sandhāvitaṃ saṃsaritaṃ mamañceva tumhākañca.**and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[1438]="*Tayidaṃ, bhikkhave, dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ anubuddhaṃ paṭividdhaṃ, dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ anubuddhaṃ paṭividdhaṃ, dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ anubuddhaṃ paṭividdhaṃ, dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ anubuddhaṃ paṭividdhaṃ, ucchinnā bhavataṇhā, khīṇā bhavanetti, natthi dāni punabbhavo”ti.**These noble truths of suffering, origin, cessation, and the path have been understood and comprehended. Craving for continued existence has been cut off; the attachment to continued existence is ended; now there are no more future lives.”*";
P_HTM[1439]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1440]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato athāparaṃ etadavoca satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[1441]="*“Catunnaṃ ariyasaccānaṃ,**“Because of not truly seeing*";
P_HTM[1442]="*yathābhūtaṃ adassanā;**the four noble truths,*";
P_HTM[1443]="*Saṃsitaṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ,**we have transmigrated for a long time*";
P_HTM[1444]="*tāsu tāsveva jātisu.**from one rebirth to the next.*";
P_HTM[1445]="*Tāni etāni diṭṭhāni,**But now that these truths have been seen,*";
P_HTM[1446]="*bhavanetti samūhatā;**the attachment to rebirth is eradicated.*";
P_HTM[1447]="*Ucchinnaṃ mūlaṃ dukkhassa,**The root of suffering is cut off,*";
P_HTM[1448]="*natthi dāni punabbhavo”ti.**now there are no more future lives.”*";
P_HTM[1449]="*Tatrapi sudaṃ bhagavā koṭigāme viharanto etadeva bahulaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ dhammiṃ kathaṃ karoti:**And while staying at Koṭigāma, too, the Buddha often gave this Dhamma talk to the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[1450]="*“iti sīlaṃ, iti samādhi, iti paññā.**“Such is ethics, such is immersion, such is wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1451]="*Sīlaparibhāvito samādhi mahapphalo hoti mahānisaṃso.**When immersion is imbued with ethics it’s very fruitful and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[1452]="*Samādhiparibhāvitā paññā mahapphalā hoti mahānisaṃsā.**When wisdom is imbued with immersion it’s very fruitful and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[1453]="*Paññāparibhāvitaṃ cittaṃ sammadeva āsavehi vimuccati, seyyathidaṃ—**When the mind is imbued with wisdom it is rightly freed from the defilements, namely,*";
P_HTM[1454]="*kāmāsavā, bhavāsavā, avijjāsavā”ti.**the defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.”*";
P_HTM[1455]="*9. Anāvattidhammasambodhiparāyaṇa**9. The Deaths in Nādika*";
P_HTM[1456]="*Atha kho bhagavā koṭigāme yathābhirantaṃ viharitvā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**When the Buddha had stayed in Koṭigāma as long as he wished, he said to Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[1457]="*“āyāmānanda, yena nātikā tenupaṅkamissāmā”ti.**“Come, Ānanda, let’s go to Nādika.”*";
P_HTM[1458]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Ānanda replied.*";
P_HTM[1459]="*Atha kho bhagavā mahatā bhikkhusaṃghena saddhiṃ yena nātikā tadavasari.**Then the Buddha together with a large Saṅgha of mendicants arrived at Nādika,*";
P_HTM[1460]="*Tatrapi sudaṃ bhagavā nātike viharati giñjakāvasathe.**where he stayed in the brick house.*";
P_HTM[1461]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Ānanda went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[1462]="*“sāḷho nāma, bhante, bhikkhu nātike kālaṅkato, tassa kā gati, ko abhisamparāyo?**“Sir, the monk named Sāḷha has passed away in Nādika. Where has he been reborn in his next life?*";
P_HTM[1463]="*Nandā nāma, bhante, bhikkhunī nātike kālaṅkatā, tassā kā gati, ko abhisamparāyo?**The nun named Nandā,*";
P_HTM[1464]="*Sudatto nāma, bhante, upāsako nātike kālaṅkato, tassa kā gati, ko abhisamparāyo?**the layman named Sudatta,*";
P_HTM[1465]="*Sujātā nāma, bhante, upāsikā nātike kālaṅkatā, tassā kā gati, ko abhisamparāyo?**and the laywoman named Sujātā have passed away in Nādika. Where have they been reborn in the next life?*";
P_HTM[1466]="*Kukkuṭo nāma, bhante, upāsako nātike kālaṅkato, tassa kā gati, ko abhisamparāyo?**The laymen named Kakkaṭa,*";
P_HTM[1467]="*Kāḷimbo nāma, bhante, upāsako … pe …**Kaḷibha,*";
P_HTM[1468]="*nikaṭo nāma, bhante, upāsako …**Nikata,*";
P_HTM[1469]="*kaṭissaho nāma, bhante, upāsako …**Kaṭissaha,*";
P_HTM[1470]="*tuṭṭho nāma, bhante, upāsako …**Tuṭṭha,*";
P_HTM[1471]="*santuṭṭho nāma, bhante, upāsako …**Santuṭṭha,*";
P_HTM[1472]="*bhaddo nāma, bhante, upāsako …**Bhadda, and*";
P_HTM[1473]="*subhaddo nāma, bhante, upāsako nātike kālaṅkato, tassa kā gati, ko abhisamparāyo”ti?**Subhadda have passed away in Nādika. Where have they been reborn in the next life?”*";
P_HTM[1474]="*“Sāḷho, ānanda, bhikkhu āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja vihāsi.**“Ānanda, the monk Sāḷha had realized the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life, having realized it with his own insight due to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[1475]="*Nandā, ānanda, bhikkhunī pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā opapātikā tattha parinibbāyinī anāvattidhammā tasmā lokā.**The nun Nandā had ended the five lower fetters. She’s been reborn spontaneously, and will be extinguished there, not liable to return from that world.*";
P_HTM[1476]="*Sudatto, ānanda, upāsako tiṇṇaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā rāgadosamohānaṃ tanuttā sakadāgāmī sakideva imaṃ lokaṃ āgantvā dukkhassantaṃ karissati.**The layman Sudatta had ended three fetters, and weakened greed, hate, and delusion. He’s a once-returner; he will come back to this world once only, then make an end of suffering.*";
P_HTM[1477]="*Sujātā, ānanda, upāsikā tiṇṇaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā sotāpannā avinipātadhammā niyatā sambodhiparāyaṇā.**The laywoman Sujātā had ended three fetters. She’s a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.*";
P_HTM[1478]="*Kukkuṭo, ānanda, upāsako pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā opapātiko tattha parinibbāyī anāvattidhammo tasmā lokā.**The laymen Kakkaṭa,*";
P_HTM[1479]="*Kāḷimbo, ānanda, upāsako … pe …**Kaḷibha,*";
P_HTM[1480]="*nikaṭo, ānanda, upāsako …**Nikata,*";
P_HTM[1481]="*kaṭissaho, ānanda, upāsako …**Kaṭissaha,*";
P_HTM[1482]="*tuṭṭho, ānanda, upāsako …**Tuṭṭha,*";
P_HTM[1483]="*santuṭṭho, ānanda, upāsako …**Santuṭṭha,*";
P_HTM[1484]="*bhaddo, ānanda, upāsako …**Bhadda, and*";
P_HTM[1485]="*subhaddo, ānanda, upāsako pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā opapātiko tattha parinibbāyī anāvattidhammo tasmā lokā.**and Subhadda had ended the five lower fetters. They’ve been reborn spontaneously, and will be extinguished there, not liable to return from that world.*";
P_HTM[1486]="*Paropaññāsaṃ, ānanda, nātike upāsakā kālaṅkatā, pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā opapātikā tattha parinibbāyino anāvattidhammā tasmā lokā.**Over fifty laymen in Nādika have passed away having ended the five lower fetters. They’ve been reborn spontaneously, and will be extinguished there, not liable to return from that world.*";
P_HTM[1487]="*Sādhikā navuti, ānanda, nātike upāsakā kālaṅkatā tiṇṇaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā rāgadosamohānaṃ tanuttā sakadāgāmino sakideva imaṃ lokaṃ āgantvā dukkhassantaṃ karissanti.**More than ninety laymen in Nādika have passed away having ended three fetters, and weakened greed, hate, and delusion. They’re once-returners, who will come back to this world once only, then make an end of suffering.*";
P_HTM[1488]="*Sātirekāni, ānanda, pañcasatāni nātike upāsakā kālaṅkatā, tiṇṇaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā sotāpannā avinipātadhammā niyatā sambodhiparāyaṇā.**In excess of five hundred laymen in Nādika have passed away having ended three fetters. They’re stream-enterers, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.*";
P_HTM[1489]="*10. Dhammādāsadhammapariyāya**10. The Mirror of the Teaching*";
P_HTM[1490]="*Anacchariyaṃ kho panetaṃ, ānanda, yaṃ manussabhūto kālaṃ kareyya.**It’s hardly surprising that a human being should pass away.*";
P_HTM[1491]="*Tasmiṃyeva kālaṅkate tathāgataṃ upasaṅkamitvā etamatthaṃ pucchissatha, vihesā hesā, ānanda, tathāgatassa.**But if you should come and ask me about it each and every time someone passes away, that would be a bother for me.*";
P_HTM[1492]="*Tasmātihānanda, dhammādāsaṃ nāma dhammapariyāyaṃ desessāmi, yena samannāgato ariyasāvako ākaṅkhamāno attanāva attānaṃ byākareyya:**So Ānanda, I will teach you the explanation of the Dhamma called ‘the mirror of the teaching’. A noble disciple who has this may declare of themselves:*";
P_HTM[1493]="*‘khīṇanirayomhi khīṇatiracchānayoni khīṇapettivisayo khīṇāpāyaduggativinipāto, sotāpannohamasmi avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo’ti.**‘I’ve finished with rebirth in hell, the animal realm, and the ghost realm. I’ve finished with all places of loss, bad places, the underworld. I am a stream-enterer! I’m not liable to be reborn in the underworld, and am bound for awakening.’*";
P_HTM[1494]="*Katamo ca so, ānanda, dhammādāso dhammapariyāyo, yena samannāgato ariyasāvako ākaṅkhamāno attanāva attānaṃ byākareyya:**And what is that mirror of the teaching?*";
P_HTM[1495]="*‘khīṇanirayomhi khīṇatiracchānayoni khīṇapettivisayo khīṇāpāyaduggativinipāto, sotāpannohamasmi avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo’ti?* **";
P_HTM[1496]="*Idhānanda, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti:**It’s when a noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[1497]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’ti.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[1498]="*Dhamme aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti:**They have experiential confidence in the teaching:*";
P_HTM[1499]="*‘svākkhāto bhagavatā dhammo sandiṭṭhiko akāliko ehipassiko opaneyyiko paccattaṃ veditabbo viññūhī’ti.**‘The teaching is well explained by the Buddha—visible in this very life, immediately effective, inviting inspection, relevant, so that sensible people can know it for themselves.’*";
P_HTM[1500]="*Saṅghe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti:**They have experiential confidence in the Saṅgha:*";
P_HTM[1501]="*‘suppaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho, ujuppaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho, ñāyappaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho, sāmīcippaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho yadidaṃ cattāri purisayugāni aṭṭha purisapuggalā, esa bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho āhuneyyo pāhuneyyo dakkhiṇeyyo añjalikaraṇīyo anuttaraṃ puññakkhettaṃ lokassā’ti.**‘The Saṅgha of the Buddha’s disciples is practicing the way that’s good, straightforward, methodical, and proper. It consists of the four pairs, the eight individuals. This is the Saṅgha of the Buddha’s disciples that is worthy of offerings dedicated to the gods, worthy of hospitality, worthy of a religious donation, worthy of greeting with joined palms, and is the supreme field of merit for the world.’*";
P_HTM[1502]="*Ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti akhaṇḍehi acchiddehi asabalehi akammāsehi bhujissehi viññūpasatthehi aparāmaṭṭhehi samādhisaṃvattanikehi.**And a noble disciple’s ethical conduct is loved by the noble ones, unbroken, impeccable, spotless, and unmarred, liberating, praised by sensible people, not mistaken, and leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[1503]="*Ayaṃ kho so, ānanda, dhammādāso dhammapariyāyo, yena samannāgato ariyasāvako ākaṅkhamāno attanāva attānaṃ byākareyya:**This is that mirror of the teaching.”*";
P_HTM[1504]="*‘khīṇanirayomhi khīṇatiracchānayoni khīṇapettivisayo khīṇāpāyaduggativinipāto, sotāpannohamasmi avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1505]="*Tatrapi sudaṃ bhagavā nātike viharanto giñjakāvasathe etadeva bahulaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ dhammiṃ kathaṃ karoti:**And while staying there in Nādika the Buddha often gave this Dhamma talk to the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[1506]="*“Iti sīlaṃ iti samādhi iti paññā.**“Such is ethics, such is immersion, such is wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1507]="*Sīlaparibhāvito samādhi mahapphalo hoti mahānisaṃso.**When immersion is imbued with ethics it’s very fruitful and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[1508]="*Samādhiparibhāvitā paññā mahapphalā hoti mahānisaṃsā.**When wisdom is imbued with immersion it’s very fruitful and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[1509]="*Paññāparibhāvitaṃ cittaṃ sammadeva āsavehi vimuccati, seyyathidaṃ—**When the mind is imbued with wisdom it is rightly freed from the defilements, namely,*";
P_HTM[1510]="*kāmāsavā, bhavāsavā, avijjāsavā”ti.**the defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.”*";
P_HTM[1511]="*()* **";
P_HTM[1512]="*Atha kho bhagavā nātike yathābhirantaṃ viharitvā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**When the Buddha had stayed in Nādika as long as he wished, he addressed Venerable Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[1513]="*“āyāmānanda, yena vesālī tenupasaṅkamissāmā”ti.**“Come, Ānanda, let’s go to Vesālī.”*";
P_HTM[1514]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Ānanda replied.*";
P_HTM[1515]="*Atha kho bhagavā mahatā bhikkhusaṅghena saddhiṃ yena vesālī tadavasari.**Then the Buddha together with a large Saṅgha of mendicants arrived at Vesālī,*";
P_HTM[1516]="*Tatra sudaṃ bhagavā vesāliyaṃ viharati ambapālivane.**where he stayed in Ambapālī’s mango grove.*";
P_HTM[1517]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[1518]="*“Sato, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vihareyya sampajāno,**“Mendicants, a mendicant should live mindful and aware.*";
P_HTM[1519]="*ayaṃ vo amhākaṃ anusāsanī.**This is my instruction to you.*";
P_HTM[1520]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sato hoti?**And how is a mendicant mindful?*";
P_HTM[1521]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[1522]="*Vedanāsu vedanānupassī … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[1523]="*citte cittānupassī … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[1524]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[1525]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sato hoti.**That’s how a mendicant is mindful.*";
P_HTM[1526]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sampajāno hoti?**And how is a mendicant aware?*";
P_HTM[1527]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu abhikkante paṭikkante sampajānakārī hoti, ālokite vilokite sampajānakārī hoti, samiñjite pasārite sampajānakārī hoti, saṅghāṭipattacīvaradhāraṇe sampajānakārī hoti, asite pīte khāyite sāyite sampajānakārī hoti, uccārapassāvakamme sampajānakārī hoti, gate ṭhite nisinne sutte jāgarite bhāsite tuṇhībhāve sampajānakārī hoti.**It’s when a mendicant acts with situational awareness when going out and coming back; when looking ahead and aside; when bending and extending the limbs; when bearing the outer robe, bowl and robes; when eating, drinking, chewing, and tasting; when urinating and defecating; when walking, standing, sitting, sleeping, waking, speaking, and keeping silent.*";
P_HTM[1528]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sampajāno hoti.**That’s how a mendicant is aware.*";
P_HTM[1529]="*Sato, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vihareyya sampajāno,**A mendicant should live mindful and aware.*";
P_HTM[1530]="*ayaṃ vo amhākaṃ anusāsanī”ti.**This is my instruction to you.”*";
P_HTM[1531]="*11. Ambapālīgaṇikā**11. Ambapālī the Courtesan*";
P_HTM[1532]="*Assosi kho ambapālī gaṇikā: “bhagavā kira vesāliṃ anuppatto vesāliyaṃ viharati mayhaṃ ambavane”ti.**Ambapālī the courtesan heard that the Buddha had arrived and was staying in her mango grove.*";
P_HTM[1533]="*Atha kho ambapālī gaṇikā bhaddāni bhaddāni yānāni yojāpetvā bhaddaṃ bhaddaṃ yānaṃ abhiruhitvā bhaddehi bhaddehi yānehi vesāliyā niyyāsi. Yena sako ārāmo tena pāyāsi.**She had the finest carriages harnessed. Then she mounted a fine carriage and, along with other fine carriages, set out from Vesālī for her own park.*";
P_HTM[1534]="*Yāvatikā yānassa bhūmi, yānena gantvā, yānā paccorohitvā pattikāva yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**She went by carriage as far as the terrain allowed, then descended and approached the Buddha on foot. She bowed and sat down to one side.*";
P_HTM[1535]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho ambapāliṃ gaṇikaṃ bhagavā dhammiyā kathāya sandassesi samādapesi samuttejesi sampahaṃsesi.**The Buddha educated, encouraged, fired up, and inspired her with a Dhamma talk.*";
P_HTM[1536]="*Atha kho ambapālī gaṇikā bhagavatā dhammiyā kathāya sandassitā samādapitā samuttejitā sampahaṃsitā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then she said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1537]="*“adhivāsetu me, bhante, bhagavā svātanāya bhattaṃ saddhiṃ bhikkhusaṃghenā”ti.**“Sir, may the Buddha together with the mendicant Saṅgha please accept tomorrow’s meal from me.”*";
P_HTM[1538]="*Adhivāsesi bhagavā tuṇhībhāvena.**The Buddha consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[1539]="*Atha kho ambapālī gaṇikā bhagavato adhivāsanaṃ viditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkāmi.**Then, knowing that the Buddha had consented, Ambapālī got up from her seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on her right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[1540]="*Assosuṃ kho vesālikā licchavī: “bhagavā kira vesāliṃ anuppatto vesāliyaṃ viharati ambapālivane”ti.**The Licchavis of Vesālī also heard that the Buddha had arrived and was staying in Ambapālī’s mango grove.*";
P_HTM[1541]="*Atha kho te licchavī bhaddāni bhaddāni yānāni yojāpetvā bhaddaṃ bhaddaṃ yānaṃ abhiruhitvā bhaddehi bhaddehi yānehi vesāliyā niyyiṃsu.**They had the finest carriages harnessed. Then they mounted a fine carriage and, along with other fine carriages, set out from Vesālī.*";
P_HTM[1542]="*Tatra ekacce licchavī nīlā honti nīlavaṇṇā nīlavatthā nīlālaṅkārā, ekacce licchavī pītā honti pītavaṇṇā pītavatthā pītālaṅkārā, ekacce licchavī lohitā honti lohitavaṇṇā lohitavatthā lohitālaṅkārā, ekacce licchavī odātā honti odātavaṇṇā odātavatthā odātālaṅkārā.**Some of the Licchavis were in blue, of blue color, clad in blue, adorned with blue. And some were similarly colored in yellow, red, or white.*";
P_HTM[1543]="*Atha kho ambapālī gaṇikā daharānaṃ daharānaṃ licchavīnaṃ akkhena akkhaṃ cakkena cakkaṃ yugena yugaṃ paṭivaṭṭesi.**Then Ambapālī the courtesan collided with those Licchavi youths, axle to axle, wheel to wheel, yoke to yoke.*";
P_HTM[1544]="*Atha kho te licchavī ambapāliṃ gaṇikaṃ etadavocuṃ:**The Licchavis said to her,*";
P_HTM[1545]="*“kiṃ, je ambapāli, daharānaṃ daharānaṃ licchavīnaṃ akkhena akkhaṃ cakkena cakkaṃ yugena yugaṃ paṭivaṭṭesī”ti?**“What the hell, Ambapālī, are you doing colliding with us axle to axle, wheel to wheel, yoke to yoke?”*";
P_HTM[1546]="*“Tathā hi pana me, ayyaputtā, bhagavā nimantito svātanāya bhattaṃ saddhiṃ bhikkhusaṃghenā”ti.**“Well, my lords, it’s because I’ve invited the Buddha for tomorrow’s meal together with the mendicant Saṅgha.”*";
P_HTM[1547]="*“Dehi, je ambapāli, etaṃ bhattaṃ satasahassenā”ti.**“Girl, give us that meal for a hundred thousand!”*";
P_HTM[1548]="*“Sacepi me, ayyaputtā, vesāliṃ sāhāraṃ dassatha, evamahaṃ taṃ bhattaṃ na dassāmī”ti.**“My lords, even if you were to give me Vesālī with her fiefdoms, I still wouldn’t give that meal to you.”*";
P_HTM[1549]="*Atha kho te licchavī aṅguliṃ phoṭesuṃ:**Then the Licchavis snapped their fingers, saying,*";
P_HTM[1550]="*“jitamha vata bho ambakāya, jitamha vata bho ambakāyā”ti.**“We’ve been beaten by the mango-matron! We’ve been beaten by the mango-matron!”*";
P_HTM[1551]="*Atha kho te licchavī yena ambapālivanaṃ tena pāyiṃsu.**Then they continued on to Ambapālī’s grove.*";
P_HTM[1552]="*Addasā kho bhagavā te licchavī dūratova āgacchante.**The Buddha saw them coming off in the distance,*";
P_HTM[1553]="*Disvāna bhikkhū āmantesi:**and addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[1554]="*“yesaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhūnaṃ devā tāvatiṃsā adiṭṭhapubbā, oloketha, bhikkhave, licchaviparisaṃ;**“Any of the mendicants who’ve never seen the gods of the Thirty-Three, just have a look at the assembly of Licchavis.*";
P_HTM[1555]="*apaloketha, bhikkhave, licchaviparisaṃ;**See the assembly of Licchavis,*";
P_HTM[1556]="*upasaṃharatha, bhikkhave, licchaviparisaṃ—**check them out:*";
P_HTM[1557]="*tāvatiṃsasadisan”ti.**they’re just like the Thirty-Three!”*";
P_HTM[1558]="*Atha kho te licchavī yāvatikā yānassa bhūmi, yānena gantvā, yānā paccorohitvā pattikāva yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu.**The Licchavis went by carriage as far as the terrain allowed, then descended and approached the Buddha on foot. They bowed to the Buddha, sat down to one side,*";
P_HTM[1559]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinne kho te licchavī bhagavā dhammiyā kathāya sandassesi samādapesi samuttejesi sampahaṃsesi.**and the Buddha educated, encouraged, fired up, and inspired them with a Dhamma talk.*";
P_HTM[1560]="*Atha kho te licchavī bhagavatā dhammiyā kathāya sandassitā samādapitā samuttejitā sampahaṃsitā bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**Then they said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1561]="*“adhivāsetu no, bhante, bhagavā svātanāya bhattaṃ saddhiṃ bhikkhusaṃghenā”ti.**“Sir, may the Buddha together with the mendicant Saṅgha please accept tomorrow’s meal from us.”*";
P_HTM[1562]="*Atha kho bhagavā te licchavī etadavoca:**Then the Buddha said to the Licchavis,*";
P_HTM[1563]="*“adhivutthaṃ kho me, licchavī, svātanāya ambapāliyā gaṇikāya bhattan”ti.**“I have already accepted tomorrow’s meal from Ambapālī the courtesan.”*";
P_HTM[1564]="*Atha kho te licchavī aṅguliṃ phoṭesuṃ:**Then the Licchavis snapped their fingers, saying,*";
P_HTM[1565]="*“jitamha vata bho ambakāya, jitamha vata bho ambakāyā”ti.**“We’ve been beaten by the mango-matron! We’ve been beaten by the mango-matron!”*";
P_HTM[1566]="*Atha kho te licchavī bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkamiṃsu.**And then those Licchavis approved and agreed with what the Buddha said. They got up from their seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on their right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[1567]="*Atha kho ambapālī gaṇikā tassā rattiyā accayena sake ārāme paṇītaṃ khādanīyaṃ bhojanīyaṃ paṭiyādāpetvā bhagavato kālaṃ ārocāpesi:**And when the night had passed Ambapālī had a variety of delicious foods prepared in her own park. Then she had the Buddha informed of the time, saying,*";
P_HTM[1568]="*“kālo, bhante, niṭṭhitaṃ bhattan”ti.**“Sir, it’s time. The meal is ready.”*";
P_HTM[1569]="*Atha kho bhagavā pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya saddhiṃ bhikkhusaṅghena yena ambapāliyā gaṇikāya nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then the Buddha robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, went to the home of Ambapālī together with the mendicant Saṅgha, where he sat on the seat spread out.*";
P_HTM[1570]="*Atha kho ambapālī gaṇikā buddhappamukhaṃ bhikkhusaṅghaṃ paṇītena khādanīyena bhojanīyena sahatthā santappesi sampavāresi.**Then Ambapālī served and satisfied the mendicant Saṅgha headed by the Buddha with her own hands with a variety of delicious foods.*";
P_HTM[1571]="*Atha kho ambapālī gaṇikā bhagavantaṃ bhuttāviṃ onītapattapāṇiṃ aññataraṃ nīcaṃ āsanaṃ gahetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**When the Buddha had eaten and washed his hands and bowl, Ambapālī took a low seat, sat to one side,*";
P_HTM[1572]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho ambapālī gaṇikā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**and said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1573]="*“imāhaṃ, bhante, ārāmaṃ buddhappamukhassa bhikkhusaṅghassa dammī”ti.**“Sir, I present this park to the mendicant Saṅgha headed by the Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[1574]="*Paṭiggahesi bhagavā ārāmaṃ.**The Buddha accepted the park.*";
P_HTM[1575]="*Atha kho bhagavā ambapāliṃ gaṇikaṃ dhammiyā kathāya sandassetvā samādapetvā samuttejetvā sampahaṃsetvā uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkāmi.**Then the Buddha educated, encouraged, fired up, and inspired her with a Dhamma talk, after which he got up from his seat and left.*";
P_HTM[1576]="*Tatrapi sudaṃ bhagavā vesāliyaṃ viharanto ambapālivane etadeva bahulaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ dhammiṃ kathaṃ karoti:**And while staying at Vesālī, too, the Buddha often gave this Dhamma talk to the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[1577]="*“iti sīlaṃ, iti samādhi, iti paññā.**“Such is ethics, such is immersion, such is wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1578]="*Sīlaparibhāvito samādhi mahapphalo hoti mahānisaṃso.**When immersion is imbued with ethics it’s very fruitful and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[1579]="*Samādhiparibhāvitā paññā mahapphalā hoti mahānisaṃsā.**When wisdom is imbued with immersion it’s very fruitful and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[1580]="*Paññāparibhāvitaṃ cittaṃ sammadeva āsavehi vimuccati, seyyathidaṃ—**When the mind is imbued with wisdom it is rightly freed from the defilements, namely,*";
P_HTM[1581]="*kāmāsavā, bhavāsavā, avijjāsavā”ti.**the defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.”*";
P_HTM[1582]="*12. Veḷuvagāmavassūpagamana**12. Commencing the Rains at Beluva*";
P_HTM[1583]="*Atha kho bhagavā ambapālivane yathābhirantaṃ viharitvā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**When the Buddha had stayed in Ambapālī’s grove as long as he wished, he addressed Venerable Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[1584]="*“āyāmānanda, yena veḷuvagāmako tenupasaṅkamissāmā”ti.**“Come, Ānanda, let’s go to the little village of Beluva.”*";
P_HTM[1585]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Ānanda replied.*";
P_HTM[1586]="*Atha kho bhagavā mahatā bhikkhusaṃghena saddhiṃ yena veḷuvagāmako tadavasari.**Then the Buddha together with a large Saṅgha of mendicants arrived at the little village of Beluva,*";
P_HTM[1587]="*Tatra sudaṃ bhagavā veḷuvagāmake viharati.**and stayed there.*";
P_HTM[1588]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[1589]="*“etha tumhe, bhikkhave, samantā vesāliṃ yathāmittaṃ yathāsandiṭṭhaṃ yathāsambhattaṃ vassaṃ upetha.**“Mendicants, please enter the rainy season residence with whatever friends or acquaintances you have around Vesālī.*";
P_HTM[1590]="*Ahaṃ pana idheva veḷuvagāmake vassaṃ upagacchāmī”ti.**I’ll commence the rainy season residence right here in the little village of Beluva.”*";
P_HTM[1591]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paṭissutvā samantā vesāliṃ yathāmittaṃ yathāsandiṭṭhaṃ yathāsambhattaṃ vassaṃ upagacchiṃsu.**“Yes, sir,” those mendicants replied. They did as the Buddha said,*";
P_HTM[1592]="*Bhagavā pana tattheva veḷuvagāmake vassaṃ upagacchi.**while the Buddha commenced the rainy season residence right there in the little village of Beluva.*";
P_HTM[1593]="*Atha kho bhagavato vassūpagatassa kharo ābādho uppajji, bāḷhā vedanā vattanti māraṇantikā.**After the Buddha had commenced the rainy season residence, he fell severely ill, struck by dreadful pains, close to death.*";
P_HTM[1594]="*Tā sudaṃ bhagavā sato sampajāno adhivāsesi avihaññamāno.**But he endured with mindfulness and situational awareness, without worrying.*";
P_HTM[1595]="*Atha kho bhagavato etadahosi:**Then it occurred to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1596]="*“na kho metaṃ patirūpaṃ, yvāhaṃ anāmantetvā upaṭṭhāke anapaloketvā bhikkhusaṃghaṃ parinibbāyeyyaṃ.**“It would not be appropriate for me to become fully extinguished before informing my attendants and taking leave of the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[1597]="*Yannūnāhaṃ imaṃ ābādhaṃ vīriyena paṭipaṇāmetvā jīvitasaṅkhāraṃ adhiṭṭhāya vihareyyan”ti.**Why don’t I forcefully suppress this illness, stabilize the life force, and live on?”*";
P_HTM[1598]="*Atha kho bhagavā taṃ ābādhaṃ vīriyena paṭipaṇāmetvā jīvitasaṅkhāraṃ adhiṭṭhāya vihāsi.**So that is what he did.*";
P_HTM[1599]="*Atha kho bhagavato so ābādho paṭippassambhi.**Then the Buddha’s illness died down.*";
P_HTM[1600]="*Atha kho bhagavā gilānā vuṭṭhito aciravuṭṭhito gelaññā vihārā nikkhamma vihārapacchāyāyaṃ paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Soon after the Buddha had recovered from that sickness, he came out from his dwelling and sat in the shade of the porch on the seat spread out.*";
P_HTM[1601]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Ānanda went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[1602]="*“diṭṭho me, bhante, bhagavato phāsu; diṭṭhaṃ me, bhante, bhagavato khamanīyaṃ, api ca me, bhante, madhurakajāto viya kāyo.**“Sir, it’s fantastic that the Buddha is comfortable and well.*";
P_HTM[1603]="*Disāpi me na pakkhāyanti;**Because when the Buddha was sick, my body felt like it was drugged. I was disorientated, and the teachings weren’t clear to me.*";
P_HTM[1604]="*dhammāpi maṃ na paṭibhanti bhagavato gelaññena, api ca me, bhante, ahosi kācideva assāsamattā:**Still, at least I was consoled by the thought that*";
P_HTM[1605]="*‘na tāva bhagavā parinibbāyissati, na yāva bhagavā bhikkhusaṃghaṃ ārabbha kiñcideva udāharatī’”ti.**the Buddha won’t become fully extinguished without making some statement regarding the Saṅgha of mendicants.”*";
P_HTM[1606]="*“Kiṃ panānanda, bhikkhusaṃgho mayi paccāsīsati?**“But what could the mendicant Saṅgha expect from me, Ānanda?*";
P_HTM[1607]="*Desito, ānanda, mayā dhammo anantaraṃ abāhiraṃ karitvā.**I’ve taught the Dhamma without making any distinction between secret and public teachings.*";
P_HTM[1608]="*Natthānanda, tathāgatassa dhammesu ācariyamuṭṭhi.**The Realized One doesn’t have the closed fist of a teacher when it comes to the teachings.*";
P_HTM[1609]="*Yassa nūna, ānanda, evamassa:**If there’s anyone who thinks:*";
P_HTM[1610]="*‘ahaṃ bhikkhusaṃghaṃ pariharissāmī’ti vā ‘mamuddesiko bhikkhusaṃgho’ti vā, so nūna, ānanda, bhikkhusaṃghaṃ ārabbha kiñcideva udāhareyya.**‘I’ll take charge of the Saṅgha of mendicants,’ or ‘the Saṅgha of mendicants is meant for me,’ let them make a statement regarding the Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[1611]="*Tathāgatassa kho, ānanda, na evaṃ hoti:**But the Realized One doesn’t think like this,*";
P_HTM[1612]="*‘ahaṃ bhikkhusaṃghaṃ pariharissāmī’ti vā ‘mamuddesiko bhikkhusaṃgho’ti vā.* **";
P_HTM[1613]="*Sakiṃ, ānanda, tathāgato bhikkhusaṃghaṃ ārabbha kiñcideva udāharissati.**so why should he make some statement regarding the Saṅgha?*";
P_HTM[1614]="*Ahaṃ kho panānanda, etarahi jiṇṇo vuddho mahallako addhagato vayo anuppatto.**I’m now old, elderly and senior. I’m advanced in years and have reached the final stage of life.*";
P_HTM[1615]="*Āsītiko me vayo vattati.**I’m currently eighty years old.*";
P_HTM[1616]="*Seyyathāpi, ānanda, jajjarasakaṭaṃ veṭhamissakena yāpeti;**Just as a decrepit cart keeps going by relying on straps,*";
P_HTM[1617]="*evameva kho, ānanda, veṭhamissakena maññe tathāgatassa kāyo yāpeti.**in the same way, the Realized One’s body keeps going by relying on straps, or so you’d think.*";
P_HTM[1618]="*Yasmiṃ, ānanda, samaye tathāgato sabbanimittānaṃ amanasikārā ekaccānaṃ vedanānaṃ nirodhā animittaṃ cetosamādhiṃ upasampajja viharati, phāsutaro, ānanda, tasmiṃ samaye tathāgatassa kāyo hoti.**Sometimes the Realized One, not focusing on any signs, and with the cessation of certain feelings, enters and remains in the signless immersion of the heart. Only then does the Realized One’s body become more comfortable.*";
P_HTM[1619]="*Tasmātihānanda, attadīpā viharatha attasaraṇā anaññasaraṇā, dhammadīpā dhammasaraṇā anaññasaraṇā.**So Ānanda, be your own island, your own refuge, with no other refuge. Let the teaching be your island and your refuge, with no other refuge.*";
P_HTM[1620]="*Kathañcānanda, bhikkhu attadīpo viharati attasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo, dhammadīpo dhammasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo?**And how does a mendicant do this?*";
P_HTM[1621]="*Idhānanda, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati atāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[1622]="*Vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[1623]="*citte … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[1624]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[1625]="*Evaṃ kho, ānanda, bhikkhu attadīpo viharati attasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo, dhammadīpo dhammasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo.**That’s how a mendicant is their own island, their own refuge, with no other refuge. That’s how the teaching is their island and their refuge, with no other refuge.*";
P_HTM[1626]="*Ye hi keci, ānanda, etarahi vā mama vā accayena attadīpā viharissanti attasaraṇā anaññasaraṇā, dhammadīpā dhammasaraṇā anaññasaraṇā, tamatagge me te, ānanda, bhikkhū bhavissanti ye keci sikkhākāmā”ti.**Whether now or after I have passed, any who shall live as their own island, their own refuge, with no other refuge; with the teaching as their island and their refuge, with no other refuge—those mendicants of mine who want to train shall be among the best of the best.”*";
P_HTM[1627]="*Dutiyabhāṇavāro.* **";
P_HTM[1628]="*13. Nimittobhāsakathā**13. An Obvious Hint*";
P_HTM[1629]="*Atha kho bhagavā pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya vesāliṃ piṇḍāya pāvisi.**Then the Buddha robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, entered Vesālī for alms.*";
P_HTM[1630]="*Vesāliyaṃ piṇḍāya caritvā pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkanto āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**Then, after the meal, on his return from alms-round, he addressed Venerable Ānanda:*";
P_HTM[1631]="*“gaṇhāhi, ānanda, nisīdanaṃ,**“Ānanda, get your sitting cloth.*";
P_HTM[1632]="*yena cāpālaṃ cetiyaṃ tenupasaṅkamissāma divā vihārāyā”ti.**Let’s go to the Cāpāla shrine for the day’s meditation.”*";
P_HTM[1633]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paṭissutvā nisīdanaṃ ādāya bhagavantaṃ piṭṭhito piṭṭhito anubandhi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Ānanda. Taking his sitting cloth he followed behind the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1634]="*Atha kho bhagavā yena cāpālaṃ cetiyaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then the Buddha went up to the Cāpāla shrine, where he sat on the seat spread out.*";
P_HTM[1635]="*Āyasmāpi kho ānando bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**Ānanda bowed to the Buddha and sat down to one side.*";
P_HTM[1636]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said to him:*";
P_HTM[1637]="*“ramaṇīyā, ānanda, vesālī, ramaṇīyaṃ udenaṃ cetiyaṃ, ramaṇīyaṃ gotamakaṃ cetiyaṃ, ramaṇīyaṃ sattambaṃ cetiyaṃ, ramaṇīyaṃ bahuputtaṃ cetiyaṃ, ramaṇīyaṃ sārandadaṃ cetiyaṃ, ramaṇīyaṃ cāpālaṃ cetiyaṃ.**“Ānanda, Vesālī is lovely. And the Udena, Gotamaka, Sattamba, Bahuputta, Sārandada, and Cāpāla shrines are all lovely.*";
P_HTM[1638]="*Yassa kassaci, ānanda, cattāro iddhipādā bhāvitā bahulīkatā yānīkatā vatthukatā anuṭṭhitā paricitā susamāraddhā, so ākaṅkhamāno kappaṃ vā tiṭṭheyya kappāvasesaṃ vā.**Whoever has developed and cultivated the four bases of psychic power—made them a vehicle and a basis, kept them up, consolidated them, and properly implemented them—may, if they wish, live on for the eon or what’s left of the eon.*";
P_HTM[1639]="*Tathāgatassa kho, ānanda, cattāro iddhipādā bhāvitā bahulīkatā yānīkatā vatthukatā anuṭṭhitā paricitā susamāraddhā, so ākaṅkhamāno, ānanda, tathāgato kappaṃ vā tiṭṭheyya kappāvasesaṃ vā”ti.**The Realized One has developed and cultivated the four bases of psychic power, made them a vehicle and a basis, kept them up, consolidated them, and properly implemented them. If he wished, the Realized One could live on for the eon or what’s left of the eon.”*";
P_HTM[1640]="*Evampi kho āyasmā ānando bhagavatā oḷārike nimitte kayiramāne oḷārike obhāse kayiramāne nāsakkhi paṭivijjhituṃ;**But Ānanda didn’t get it, even though the Buddha dropped such an obvious hint, such a clear sign.*";
P_HTM[1641]="*na bhagavantaṃ yāci:**He didn’t beg the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[1642]="*“tiṭṭhatu, bhante, bhagavā kappaṃ, tiṭṭhatu sugato kappaṃ bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānan”ti, yathā taṃ mārena pariyuṭṭhitacitto.**“Sir, may the Blessed One please remain for the eon! May the Holy One please remain for the eon! That would be for the welfare and happiness of the people, for the benefit, welfare, and happiness of gods and humans.” For his mind was as if possessed by Māra.*";
P_HTM[1643]="*Dutiyampi kho bhagavā … pe …**For a second time …*";
P_HTM[1644]="*tatiyampi kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**And for a third time, the Buddha said to Ānanda:*";
P_HTM[1645]="*“ramaṇīyā, ānanda, vesālī, ramaṇīyaṃ udenaṃ cetiyaṃ, ramaṇīyaṃ gotamakaṃ cetiyaṃ, ramaṇīyaṃ sattambaṃ cetiyaṃ, ramaṇīyaṃ bahuputtaṃ cetiyaṃ, ramaṇīyaṃ sārandadaṃ cetiyaṃ, ramaṇīyaṃ cāpālaṃ cetiyaṃ.**“Ānanda, Vesālī is lovely. And the Udena, Gotamaka, Sattamba, Bahuputta, Sārandada, and Cāpāla shrines are all lovely.*";
P_HTM[1646]="*Yassa kassaci, ānanda, cattāro iddhipādā bhāvitā bahulīkatā yānīkatā vatthukatā anuṭṭhitā paricitā susamāraddhā, so ākaṅkhamāno kappaṃ vā tiṭṭheyya kappāvasesaṃ vā.**Whoever has developed and cultivated the four bases of psychic power—made them a vehicle and a basis, kept them up, consolidated them, and properly implemented them—may, if they wish, live on for the eon, or what’s left of it.*";
P_HTM[1647]="*Tathāgatassa kho, ānanda, cattāro iddhipādā bhāvitā bahulīkatā yānīkatā vatthukatā anuṭṭhitā paricitā susamāraddhā, so ākaṅkhamāno, ānanda, tathāgato kappaṃ vā tiṭṭheyya kappāvasesaṃ vā”ti.**The Realized One has developed and cultivated the four bases of psychic power, made them a vehicle and a basis, kept them up, consolidated them, and properly implemented them. If he wished, the Realized One could live on for the eon, or what’s left of it.”*";
P_HTM[1648]="*Evampi kho āyasmā ānando bhagavatā oḷārike nimitte kayiramāne oḷārike obhāse kayiramāne nāsakkhi paṭivijjhituṃ;**But Ānanda didn’t get it, even though the Buddha dropped such an obvious hint, such a clear sign.*";
P_HTM[1649]="*na bhagavantaṃ yāci:**He didn’t beg the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[1650]="*“tiṭṭhatu, bhante, bhagavā kappaṃ, tiṭṭhatu sugato kappaṃ bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānan”ti, yathā taṃ mārena pariyuṭṭhitacitto.**“Sir, may the Blessed One please remain for the eon! May the Holy One please remain for the eon! That would be for the welfare and happiness of the people, for the benefit, welfare, and happiness of gods and humans.” For his mind was as if possessed by Māra.*";
P_HTM[1651]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**Then the Buddha got up and said to Venerable Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[1652]="*“gaccha tvaṃ, ānanda,**“Go now, Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[1653]="*yassadāni kālaṃ maññasī”ti.**at your convenience.”*";
P_HTM[1654]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paṭissutvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā avidūre aññatarasmiṃ rukkhamūle nisīdi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Ānanda. He rose from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on his right, before sitting at the root of a tree close by.*";
P_HTM[1655]="*14. Mārayācanakathā**14. The Appeal of Māra*";
P_HTM[1656]="*Atha kho māro pāpimā acirapakkante āyasmante ānande yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi. Ekamantaṃ ṭhito kho māro pāpimā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**And then, not long after Ānanda had left, Māra the Wicked went up to the Buddha, stood to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[1657]="*“parinibbātu dāni, bhante, bhagavā, parinibbātu sugato, parinibbānakālo dāni, bhante, bhagavato.**“Sir, may the Blessed One now become fully extinguished! May the Holy One now become fully extinguished! Now is the time for the Buddha to become fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[1658]="*Bhāsitā kho panesā, bhante, bhagavatā vācā:**Sir, you once made this statement:*";
P_HTM[1659]="*‘na tāvāhaṃ, pāpima, parinibbāyissāmi, yāva me bhikkhū na sāvakā bhavissanti viyattā vinītā visāradā bahussutā dhammadharā dhammānudhammappaṭipannā sāmīcippaṭipannā anudhammacārino, sakaṃ ācariyakaṃ uggahetvā ācikkhissanti desessanti paññapessanti paṭṭhapessanti vivarissanti vibhajissanti uttānīkarissanti, uppannaṃ parappavādaṃ sahadhammena suniggahitaṃ niggahetvā sappāṭihāriyaṃ dhammaṃ desessantī’ti.**‘Wicked One, I will not become fully extinguished until I have monk disciples who are competent, educated, assured, learned, have memorized the teachings, and practice in line with the teachings. Not until they practice properly, living in line with the teaching. Not until they’ve learned their tradition, and explain, teach, assert, establish, disclose, analyze, and make it clear. Not until they can legitimately and completely refute the doctrines of others that come up, and teach with a demonstrable basis.’*";
P_HTM[1660]="*Etarahi kho pana, bhante, bhikkhū bhagavato sāvakā viyattā vinītā visāradā bahussutā dhammadharā dhammānudhammappaṭipannā sāmīcippaṭipannā anudhammacārino, sakaṃ ācariyakaṃ uggahetvā ācikkhanti desenti paññapenti paṭṭhapenti vivaranti vibhajanti uttānīkaronti, uppannaṃ parappavādaṃ sahadhammena suniggahitaṃ niggahetvā sappāṭihāriyaṃ dhammaṃ desenti.**Today you do have such monk disciples.*";
P_HTM[1661]="*Parinibbātu dāni, bhante, bhagavā, parinibbātu sugato, parinibbānakālo dāni, bhante, bhagavato.**May the Blessed One now become fully extinguished! May the Holy One now become fully extinguished! Now is the time for the Buddha to become fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[1662]="*Bhāsitā kho panesā, bhante, bhagavatā vācā:**Sir, you once made this statement:*";
P_HTM[1663]="*‘na tāvāhaṃ, pāpima, parinibbāyissāmi, yāva me bhikkhuniyo na sāvikā bhavissanti viyattā vinītā visāradā bahussutā dhammadharā dhammānudhammappaṭipannā sāmīcippaṭipannā anudhammacāriniyo, sakaṃ ācariyakaṃ uggahetvā ācikkhissanti desessanti paññapessanti paṭṭhapessanti vivarissanti vibhajissanti uttānīkarissanti, uppannaṃ parappavādaṃ sahadhammena suniggahitaṃ niggahetvā sappāṭihāriyaṃ dhammaṃ desessantī’ti.**‘Wicked One, I will not become fully extinguished until I have nun disciples who are competent, educated, assured, learned …’*";
P_HTM[1664]="*Etarahi kho pana, bhante, bhikkhuniyo bhagavato sāvikā viyattā vinītā visāradā bahussutā dhammadharā dhammānudhammappaṭipannā sāmīcippaṭipannā anudhammacāriniyo, sakaṃ ācariyakaṃ uggahetvā ācikkhanti desenti paññapenti paṭṭhapenti vivaranti vibhajanti uttānīkaronti, uppannaṃ parappavādaṃ sahadhammena suniggahitaṃ niggahetvā sappāṭihāriyaṃ dhammaṃ desenti.**Today you do have such nun disciples.*";
P_HTM[1665]="*Parinibbātu dāni, bhante, bhagavā, parinibbātu sugato, parinibbānakālo dāni, bhante, bhagavato.**May the Blessed One now become fully extinguished! May the Holy One now become fully extinguished! Now is the time for the Buddha to become fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[1666]="*Bhāsitā kho panesā, bhante, bhagavatā vācā:**Sir, you once made this statement:*";
P_HTM[1667]="*‘na tāvāhaṃ, pāpima, parinibbāyissāmi, yāva me upāsakā na sāvakā bhavissanti viyattā vinītā visāradā bahussutā dhammadharā dhammānudhammappaṭipannā sāmīcippaṭipannā anudhammacārino, sakaṃ ācariyakaṃ uggahetvā ācikkhissanti desessanti paññapessanti paṭṭhapessanti vivarissanti vibhajissanti uttānīkarissanti, uppannaṃ parappavādaṃ sahadhammena suniggahitaṃ niggahetvā sappāṭihāriyaṃ dhammaṃ desessantī’ti.**‘Wicked One, I will not become fully extinguished until I have layman disciples who are competent, educated, assured, learned …’*";
P_HTM[1668]="*Etarahi kho pana, bhante, upāsakā bhagavato sāvakā viyattā vinītā visāradā bahussutā dhammadharā dhammānudhammappaṭipannā sāmīcippaṭipannā anudhammacārino, sakaṃ ācariyakaṃ uggahetvā ācikkhanti desenti paññapenti paṭṭhapenti vivaranti vibhajanti uttānīkaronti, uppannaṃ parappavādaṃ sahadhammena suniggahitaṃ niggahetvā sappāṭihāriyaṃ dhammaṃ desenti.**Today you do have such layman disciples.*";
P_HTM[1669]="*Parinibbātu dāni, bhante, bhagavā, parinibbātu sugato, parinibbānakālo dāni, bhante, bhagavato.**May the Blessed One now become fully extinguished! May the Holy One now become fully extinguished! Now is the time for the Buddha to become fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[1670]="*Bhāsitā kho panesā, bhante, bhagavatā vācā:**Sir, you once made this statement:*";
P_HTM[1671]="*‘na tāvāhaṃ, pāpima, parinibbāyissāmi, yāva me upāsikā na sāvikā bhavissanti viyattā vinītā visāradā bahussutā dhammadharā dhammānudhammappaṭipannā sāmīcippaṭipannā anudhammacāriniyo, sakaṃ ācariyakaṃ uggahetvā ācikkhissanti desessanti paññapessanti paṭṭhapessanti vivarissanti vibhajissanti uttānīkarissanti, uppannaṃ parappavādaṃ sahadhammena suniggahitaṃ niggahetvā sappāṭihāriyaṃ dhammaṃ desessantī’ti.**‘Wicked One, I will not become fully extinguished until I have laywoman disciples who are competent, educated, assured, learned …’*";
P_HTM[1672]="*Etarahi kho pana, bhante, upāsikā bhagavato sāvikā viyattā vinītā visāradā bahussutā dhammadharā dhammānudhammappaṭipannā sāmīcippaṭipannā anudhammacāriniyo, sakaṃ ācariyakaṃ uggahetvā ācikkhanti desenti paññapenti paṭṭhapenti vivaranti vibhajanti uttānīkaronti, uppannaṃ parappavādaṃ sahadhammena suniggahitaṃ niggahetvā sappāṭihāriyaṃ dhammaṃ desenti.**Today you do have such laywoman disciples.*";
P_HTM[1673]="*Parinibbātu dāni, bhante, bhagavā, parinibbātu sugato, parinibbānakālo dāni, bhante, bhagavato.**May the Blessed One now become fully extinguished! May the Holy One now become fully extinguished! Now is the time for the Buddha to become fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[1674]="*Bhāsitā kho panesā, bhante, bhagavatā vācā:**Sir, you once made this statement:*";
P_HTM[1675]="*‘na tāvāhaṃ, pāpima, parinibbāyissāmi, yāva me idaṃ brahmacariyaṃ na iddhañceva bhavissati phītañca vitthārikaṃ bāhujaññaṃ puthubhūtaṃ yāva devamanussehi suppakāsitan’ti.**‘Wicked One, I will not become fully extinguished until my spiritual life is successful and prosperous, extensive, popular, widespread, and well proclaimed wherever there are gods and humans.’*";
P_HTM[1676]="*Etarahi kho pana, bhante, bhagavato brahmacariyaṃ iddhañceva phītañca vitthārikaṃ bāhujaññaṃ puthubhūtaṃ, yāva devamanussehi suppakāsitaṃ.**Today your spiritual life is successful and prosperous, extensive, popular, widespread, and well proclaimed wherever there are gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[1677]="*Parinibbātu dāni, bhante, bhagavā, parinibbātu sugato, parinibbānakālo dāni, bhante, bhagavato”ti.**May the Blessed One now become fully extinguished! May the Holy One now become fully extinguished! Now is the time for the Buddha to become fully extinguished.”*";
P_HTM[1678]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhagavā māraṃ pāpimantaṃ etadavoca:**When this was said, the Buddha said to Māra,*";
P_HTM[1679]="*“appossukko tvaṃ, pāpima, hohi, na ciraṃ tathāgatassa parinibbānaṃ bhavissati.**“Relax, Wicked One. The final extinguishment of the Realized One will be soon.*";
P_HTM[1680]="*Ito tiṇṇaṃ māsānaṃ accayena tathāgato parinibbāyissatī”ti.**Three months from now the Realized One will finally be extinguished.”*";
P_HTM[1681]="*15. Āyusaṅkhāraossajjana**15. Surrendering the Life Force*";
P_HTM[1682]="*Atha kho bhagavā cāpāle cetiye sato sampajāno āyusaṅkhāraṃ ossaji.**So at the Cāpāla tree shrine the Buddha, mindful and aware, surrendered the life force.*";
P_HTM[1683]="*Ossaṭṭhe ca bhagavatā āyusaṅkhāre mahābhūmicālo ahosi bhiṃsanako salomahaṃso, devadundubhiyo ca phaliṃsu.**When he did so there was a great earthquake, awe-inspiring and hair-raising, and thunder cracked the sky.*";
P_HTM[1684]="*Atha kho bhagavā etamatthaṃ viditvā tāyaṃ velāyaṃ imaṃ udānaṃ udānesi:**Then, knowing the meaning of this, on that occasion the Buddha was inspired to exclaim:*";
P_HTM[1685]="*“Tulamatulañca sambhavaṃ,**“Weighing up the incomparable against an extension of life,*";
P_HTM[1686]="*Bhavasaṅkhāramavassaji muni;**the sage surrendered the life force.*";
P_HTM[1687]="*Ajjhattarato samāhito,**Happy inside, serene,*";
P_HTM[1688]="*Abhindi kavacamivattasambhavan”ti.**he burst out of this self-made chain like a suit of armor.”*";
P_HTM[1689]="*16. Mahābhūmicālahetu**16. The Causes of Earthquakes*";
P_HTM[1690]="*Atha kho āyasmato ānandassa etadahosi:**Then Venerable Ānanda thought,*";
P_HTM[1691]="*“acchariyaṃ vata bho, abbhutaṃ vata bho, mahā vatāyaṃ bhūmicālo;**“How incredible, how amazing! That was a really big earthquake!*";
P_HTM[1692]="*sumahā vatāyaṃ bhūmicālo bhiṃsanako salomahaṃso; devadundubhiyo ca phaliṃsu.**That was really a very big earthquake; awe-inspiring and hair-raising, and thunder cracked the sky!*";
P_HTM[1693]="*Ko nu kho hetu ko paccayo mahato bhūmicālassa pātubhāvāyā”ti?**What’s the cause, what’s the reason for a great earthquake?”*";
P_HTM[1694]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami,**Then Venerable Ānanda went up to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1695]="*upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi,**bowed, sat down to one side,*";
P_HTM[1696]="*ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**and said to him,*";
P_HTM[1697]="*“acchariyaṃ, bhante, abbhutaṃ, bhante.**“How incredible, sir, how amazing!*";
P_HTM[1698]="*Mahā vatāyaṃ, bhante, bhūmicālo;**That was a really big earthquake!*";
P_HTM[1699]="*sumahā vatāyaṃ, bhante, bhūmicālo bhiṃsanako salomahaṃso; devadundubhiyo ca phaliṃsu.**That was really a very big earthquake; awe-inspiring and hair-raising, and thunder cracked the sky!*";
P_HTM[1700]="*Ko nu kho, bhante, hetu ko paccayo mahato bhūmicālassa pātubhāvāyā”ti?**What’s the cause, what’s the reason for a great earthquake?”*";
P_HTM[1701]="*“Aṭṭha kho ime, ānanda, hetū, aṭṭha paccayā mahato bhūmicālassa pātubhāvāya.**“Ānanda, there are these eight causes and reasons for a great earthquake.*";
P_HTM[1702]="*Katame aṭṭha?**What eight?*";
P_HTM[1703]="*Ayaṃ, ānanda, mahāpathavī udake patiṭṭhitā, udakaṃ vāte patiṭṭhitaṃ, vāto ākāsaṭṭho. Hoti kho so, ānanda, samayo, yaṃ mahāvātā vāyanti. Mahāvātā vāyantā udakaṃ kampenti. Udakaṃ kampitaṃ pathaviṃ kampeti.**This great earth is grounded on water, the water is grounded on air, and the air stands in space. At a time when a great wind blows, it stirs the water, and the water stirs the earth.*";
P_HTM[1704]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamo hetu paṭhamo paccayo mahato bhūmicālassa pātubhāvāya.**This is the first cause and reason for a great earthquake.*";
P_HTM[1705]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, samaṇo vā hoti brāhmaṇo vā iddhimā cetovasippatto, devo vā mahiddhiko mahānubhāvo, tassa parittā pathavīsaññā bhāvitā hoti, appamāṇā āposaññā. So imaṃ pathaviṃ kampeti saṅkampeti sampakampeti sampavedheti.**Furthermore, there is an ascetic or brahmin with psychic power who has achieved mastery of the mind, or a god who is mighty and powerful. They’ve developed a limited perception of earth and a limitless perception of water. They make the earth shake and rock and tremble.*";
P_HTM[1706]="*Ayaṃ dutiyo hetu dutiyo paccayo mahato bhūmicālassa pātubhāvāya.**This is the second cause and reason for a great earthquake.*";
P_HTM[1707]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, yadā bodhisatto tusitakāyā cavitvā sato sampajāno mātukucchiṃ okkamati, tadāyaṃ pathavī kampati saṅkampati sampakampati sampavedhati.**Furthermore, when the being intent on awakening passes away from the host of Joyful Gods, he’s conceived in his mother’s belly, mindful and aware. Then the earth shakes and rocks and trembles.*";
P_HTM[1708]="*Ayaṃ tatiyo hetu tatiyo paccayo mahato bhūmicālassa pātubhāvāya.**This is the third cause and reason for a great earthquake.*";
P_HTM[1709]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, yadā bodhisatto sato sampajāno mātukucchismā nikkhamati, tadāyaṃ pathavī kampati saṅkampati sampakampati sampavedhati.**Furthermore, when the being intent on awakening comes out of his mother’s belly mindful and aware, the earth shakes and rocks and trembles.*";
P_HTM[1710]="*Ayaṃ catuttho hetu catuttho paccayo mahato bhūmicālassa pātubhāvāya.**This is the fourth cause and reason for a great earthquake.*";
P_HTM[1711]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, yadā tathāgato anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambujjhati, tadāyaṃ pathavī kampati saṅkampati sampakampati sampavedhati.**Furthermore, when the Realized One realizes the supreme perfect awakening, the earth shakes and rocks and trembles.*";
P_HTM[1712]="*Ayaṃ pañcamo hetu pañcamo paccayo mahato bhūmicālassa pātubhāvāya.**This is the fifth cause and reason for a great earthquake.*";
P_HTM[1713]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, yadā tathāgato anuttaraṃ dhammacakkaṃ pavatteti, tadāyaṃ pathavī kampati saṅkampati sampakampati sampavedhati.**Furthermore, when the Realized One rolls forth the supreme Wheel of Dhamma, the earth shakes and rocks and trembles.*";
P_HTM[1714]="*Ayaṃ chaṭṭho hetu chaṭṭho paccayo mahato bhūmicālassa pātubhāvāya.**This is the sixth cause and reason for a great earthquake.*";
P_HTM[1715]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, yadā tathāgato sato sampajāno āyusaṅkhāraṃ ossajjati, tadāyaṃ pathavī kampati saṅkampati sampakampati sampavedhati.**Furthermore, when the Realized One, mindful and aware, surrenders the life force, the earth shakes and rocks and trembles.*";
P_HTM[1716]="*Ayaṃ sattamo hetu sattamo paccayo mahato bhūmicālassa pātubhāvāya.**This is the seventh cause and reason for a great earthquake.*";
P_HTM[1717]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, yadā tathāgato anupādisesāya nibbānadhātuyā parinibbāyati, tadāyaṃ pathavī kampati saṅkampati sampakampati sampavedhati.**Furthermore, when the Realized One becomes fully extinguished through the natural principle of extinguishment, without anything left over, the earth shakes and rocks and trembles.*";
P_HTM[1718]="*Ayaṃ aṭṭhamo hetu aṭṭhamo paccayo mahato bhūmicālassa pātubhāvāya.**This is the eighth cause and reason for a great earthquake.*";
P_HTM[1719]="*Ime kho, ānanda, aṭṭha hetū, aṭṭha paccayā mahato bhūmicālassa pātubhāvāya.**These are the eight causes and reasons for a great earthquake.*";
P_HTM[1720]="*17. Aṭṭhaparisā**17. Eight Assemblies*";
P_HTM[1721]="*Aṭṭha kho imā, ānanda, parisā.**There are, Ānanda, these eight assemblies.*";
P_HTM[1722]="*Katamā aṭṭha?**What eight?*";
P_HTM[1723]="*Khattiyaparisā, brāhmaṇaparisā, gahapatiparisā, samaṇaparisā, cātumahārājikaparisā, tāvatiṃsaparisā, māraparisā, brahmaparisā.**The assemblies of aristocrats, brahmins, householders, and ascetics. An assembly of the gods of the Four Great Kings. An assembly of the gods of the Thirty-Three. An assembly of Māras. An assembly of Brahmās.*";
P_HTM[1724]="*Abhijānāmi kho panāhaṃ, ānanda, anekasataṃ khattiyaparisaṃ upasaṅkamitā.**I recall having approached an assembly of hundreds of aristocrats.*";
P_HTM[1725]="*Tatrapi mayā sannisinnapubbañceva sallapitapubbañca sākacchā ca samāpajjitapubbā.**There I used to sit with them, converse, and engage in discussion.*";
P_HTM[1726]="*Tattha yādisako tesaṃ vaṇṇo hoti, tādisako mayhaṃ vaṇṇo hoti. Yādisako tesaṃ saro hoti, tādisako mayhaṃ saro hoti.**And my appearance and voice became just like theirs.*";
P_HTM[1727]="*Dhammiyā kathāya sandassemi samādapemi samuttejemi sampahaṃsemi.**I educated, encouraged, fired up, and inspired them with a Dhamma talk.*";
P_HTM[1728]="*Bhāsamānañca maṃ na jānanti:**But when I spoke they didn’t know:*";
P_HTM[1729]="*‘ko nu kho ayaṃ bhāsati devo vā manusso vā’ti?**‘Who is this that speaks? Is it a god or a human?’*";
P_HTM[1730]="*Dhammiyā kathāya sandassetvā samādapetvā samuttejetvā sampahaṃsetvā antaradhāyāmi.**And when my Dhamma talk was finished I vanished.*";
P_HTM[1731]="*Antarahitañca maṃ na jānanti:**But when I vanished they didn’t know:*";
P_HTM[1732]="*‘ko nu kho ayaṃ antarahito devo vā manusso vā’ti?**‘Who was that who vanished? Was it a god or a human?’*";
P_HTM[1733]="*Abhijānāmi kho panāhaṃ, ānanda, anekasataṃ brāhmaṇaparisaṃ … pe …**I recall having approached an assembly of hundreds of brahmins …*";
P_HTM[1734]="*gahapatiparisaṃ …**householders …*";
P_HTM[1735]="*samaṇaparisaṃ …**ascetics …*";
P_HTM[1736]="*cātumahārājikaparisaṃ …**the gods of the Four Great Kings …*";
P_HTM[1737]="*tāvatiṃsaparisaṃ …**the gods of the Thirty-Three …*";
P_HTM[1738]="*māraparisaṃ …**Māras …*";
P_HTM[1739]="*brahmaparisaṃ upasaṅkamitā.**Brahmās.*";
P_HTM[1740]="*Tatrapi mayā sannisinnapubbañceva sallapitapubbañca sākacchā ca samāpajjitapubbā.**There too I used to sit with them, converse, and engage in discussion.*";
P_HTM[1741]="*Tattha yādisako tesaṃ vaṇṇo hoti, tādisako mayhaṃ vaṇṇo hoti.**And my appearance and voice became just like theirs.*";
P_HTM[1742]="*Yādisako tesaṃ saro hoti, tādisako mayhaṃ saro hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1743]="*Dhammiyā kathāya sandassemi samādapemi samuttejemi sampahaṃsemi.**I educated, encouraged, fired up, and inspired them with a Dhamma talk.*";
P_HTM[1744]="*Bhāsamānañca maṃ na jānanti:**But when I spoke they didn’t know:*";
P_HTM[1745]="*‘ko nu kho ayaṃ bhāsati devo vā manusso vā’ti?**‘Who is this that speaks? Is it a god or a human?’*";
P_HTM[1746]="*Dhammiyā kathāya sandassetvā samādapetvā samuttejetvā sampahaṃsetvā antaradhāyāmi.**And when my Dhamma talk was finished I vanished.*";
P_HTM[1747]="*Antarahitañca maṃ na jānanti:**But when I vanished they didn’t know:*";
P_HTM[1748]="*‘ko nu kho ayaṃ antarahito devo vā manusso vā’ti?**‘Who was that who vanished? Was it a god or a human?’*";
P_HTM[1749]="*Imā kho, ānanda, aṭṭha parisā.**These are the eight assemblies.*";
P_HTM[1750]="*18. Aṭṭhaabhibhāyatana**18. Eight Dimensions of Mastery*";
P_HTM[1751]="*Aṭṭha kho imāni, ānanda, abhibhāyatanāni.**Ānanda, there are these eight dimensions of mastery.*";
P_HTM[1752]="*Katamāni aṭṭha?**What eight?*";
P_HTM[1753]="*Ajjhattaṃ rūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati parittāni suvaṇṇadubbaṇṇāni.**Perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, limited, both pretty and ugly.*";
P_HTM[1754]="*‘Tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[1755]="*Idaṃ paṭhamaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the first dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[1756]="*Ajjhattaṃ rūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati appamāṇāni suvaṇṇadubbaṇṇāni.**Perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, limitless, both pretty and ugly.*";
P_HTM[1757]="*‘Tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[1758]="*Idaṃ dutiyaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the second dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[1759]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati parittāni suvaṇṇadubbaṇṇāni.**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, limited, both pretty and ugly.*";
P_HTM[1760]="*‘Tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[1761]="*Idaṃ tatiyaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the third dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[1762]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati appamāṇāni suvaṇṇadubbaṇṇāni.**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, limitless, both pretty and ugly.*";
P_HTM[1763]="*‘Tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[1764]="*Idaṃ catutthaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the fourth dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[1765]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati nīlāni nīlavaṇṇāni nīlanidassanāni nīlanibhāsāni.**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally that are blue, with blue color, blue hue, and blue tint.*";
P_HTM[1766]="*Seyyathāpi nāma umāpupphaṃ nīlaṃ nīlavaṇṇaṃ nīlanidassanaṃ nīlanibhāsaṃ. Seyyathā vā pana taṃ vatthaṃ bārāṇaseyyakaṃ ubhatobhāgavimaṭṭhaṃ nīlaṃ nīlavaṇṇaṃ nīlanidassanaṃ nīlanibhāsaṃ.**They’re like a flax flower that’s blue, with blue color, blue hue, and blue tint. Or a cloth from Bāraṇasī that’s smoothed on both sides, blue, with blue color, blue hue, and blue tint.*";
P_HTM[1767]="*Evameva ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati nīlāni nīlavaṇṇāni nīlanidassanāni nīlanibhāsāni.**In the same way, not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, blue, with blue color, blue hue, and blue tint.*";
P_HTM[1768]="*‘Tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[1769]="*Idaṃ pañcamaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the fifth dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[1770]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati pītāni pītavaṇṇāni pītanidassanāni pītanibhāsāni.**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally that are yellow, with yellow color, yellow hue, and yellow tint.*";
P_HTM[1771]="*Seyyathāpi nāma kaṇikārapupphaṃ pītaṃ pītavaṇṇaṃ pītanidassanaṃ pītanibhāsaṃ. Seyyathā vā pana taṃ vatthaṃ bārāṇaseyyakaṃ ubhatobhāgavimaṭṭhaṃ pītaṃ pītavaṇṇaṃ pītanidassanaṃ pītanibhāsaṃ.**They’re like a champak flower that’s yellow, with yellow color, yellow hue, and yellow tint. Or a cloth from Bāraṇasī that’s smoothed on both sides, yellow, with yellow color, yellow hue, and yellow tint.*";
P_HTM[1772]="*Evameva ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati pītāni pītavaṇṇāni pītanidassanāni pītanibhāsāni.**In the same way, not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally that are yellow, with yellow color, yellow hue, and yellow tint.*";
P_HTM[1773]="*‘Tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[1774]="*Idaṃ chaṭṭhaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the sixth dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[1775]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati lohitakāni lohitakavaṇṇāni lohitakanidassanāni lohitakanibhāsāni.**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally that are red, with red color, red hue, and red tint.*";
P_HTM[1776]="*Seyyathāpi nāma bandhujīvakapupphaṃ lohitakaṃ lohitakavaṇṇaṃ lohitakanidassanaṃ lohitakanibhāsaṃ. Seyyathā vā pana taṃ vatthaṃ bārāṇaseyyakaṃ ubhatobhāgavimaṭṭhaṃ lohitakaṃ lohitakavaṇṇaṃ lohitakanidassanaṃ lohitakanibhāsaṃ.**They’re like a scarlet mallow flower that’s red, with red color, red hue, and red tint. Or a cloth from Bāraṇasī that’s smoothed on both sides, red, with red color, red hue, and red tint.*";
P_HTM[1777]="*Evameva ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati lohitakāni lohitakavaṇṇāni lohitakanidassanāni lohitakanibhāsāni.**In the same way, not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally that are red, with red color, red hue, and red tint.*";
P_HTM[1778]="*‘Tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[1779]="*Idaṃ sattamaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the seventh dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[1780]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati odātāni odātavaṇṇāni odātanidassanāni odātanibhāsāni.**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally that are white, with white color, white hue, and white tint.*";
P_HTM[1781]="*Seyyathāpi nāma osadhitārakā odātā odātavaṇṇā odātanidassanā odātanibhāsā. Seyyathā vā pana taṃ vatthaṃ bārāṇaseyyakaṃ ubhatobhāgavimaṭṭhaṃ odātaṃ odātavaṇṇaṃ odātanidassanaṃ odātanibhāsaṃ.**They’re like the morning star that’s white, with white color, white hue, and white tint. Or a cloth from Bāraṇasī that’s smoothed on both sides, white, with white color, white hue, and white tint.*";
P_HTM[1782]="*Evameva ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati odātāni odātavaṇṇāni odātanidassanāni odātanibhāsāni.**In the same way, not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally that are white, with white color, white hue, and white tint.*";
P_HTM[1783]="*‘Tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[1784]="*Idaṃ aṭṭhamaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the eighth dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[1785]="*Imāni kho, ānanda, aṭṭha abhibhāyatanāni.**These are the eight dimensions of mastery.*";
P_HTM[1786]="*19. Aṭṭhavimokkha**19. The Eight Liberations*";
P_HTM[1787]="*Aṭṭha kho ime, ānanda, vimokkhā.**Ānanda, there are these eight liberations.*";
P_HTM[1788]="*Katame aṭṭha?**What eight?*";
P_HTM[1789]="*Rūpī rūpāni passati,**Having physical form, they see visions.*";
P_HTM[1790]="*ayaṃ paṭhamo vimokkho.**This is the first liberation.*";
P_HTM[1791]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī bahiddhā rūpāni passati,**Not perceiving form internally, they see visions externally.*";
P_HTM[1792]="*ayaṃ dutiyo vimokkho.**This is the second liberation.*";
P_HTM[1793]="*Subhanteva adhimutto hoti,**They’re focused only on beauty.*";
P_HTM[1794]="*ayaṃ tatiyo vimokkho.**This is the third liberation.*";
P_HTM[1795]="*Sabbaso rūpasaññānaṃ samatikkamā paṭighasaññānaṃ atthaṅgamā nānattasaññānaṃ amanasikārā ‘ananto ākāso’ti ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati,**Going totally beyond perceptions of form, with the ending of perceptions of impingement, not focusing on perceptions of diversity, aware that ‘space is infinite’, they enter and remain in the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[1796]="*ayaṃ catuttho vimokkho.**This is the fourth liberation.*";
P_HTM[1797]="*Sabbaso ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘anantaṃ viññāṇan’ti viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati,**Going totally beyond the dimension of infinite space, aware that ‘consciousness is infinite’, they enter and remain in the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[1798]="*ayaṃ pañcamo vimokkho.**This is the fifth liberation.*";
P_HTM[1799]="*Sabbaso viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘natthi kiñcī’ti ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati,**Going totally beyond the dimension of infinite consciousness, aware that ‘there is nothing at all’, they enter and remain in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[1800]="*ayaṃ chaṭṭho vimokkho.**This is the sixth liberation.*";
P_HTM[1801]="*Sabbaso ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati,**Going totally beyond the dimension of nothingness, they enter and remain in the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[1802]="*ayaṃ sattamo vimokkho.**This is the seventh liberation.*";
P_HTM[1803]="*Sabbaso nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ upasampajja viharati,**Going totally beyond the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, they enter and remain in the cessation of perception and feeling.*";
P_HTM[1804]="*ayaṃ aṭṭhamo vimokkho.**This is the eighth liberation.*";
P_HTM[1805]="*Ime kho, ānanda, aṭṭha vimokkhā.**These are the eight liberations.*";
P_HTM[1806]="*()* **";
P_HTM[1807]="*Ekamidāhaṃ, ānanda, samayaṃ uruvelāyaṃ viharāmi najjā nerañjarāya tīre ajapālanigrodhe paṭhamābhisambuddho.**Ānanda, this one time, when I was first awakened, I was staying near Uruvelā at the goatherd’s banyan tree on the bank of the Nerañjarā River.*";
P_HTM[1808]="*Atha kho, ānanda, māro pāpimā yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi. Ekamantaṃ ṭhito kho, ānanda, māro pāpimā maṃ etadavoca:**Then Māra the wicked approached me, stood to one side, and said:*";
P_HTM[1809]="*‘parinibbātu dāni, bhante, bhagavā; parinibbātu sugato, parinibbānakālo dāni, bhante, bhagavato’ti.**‘Sir, may the Blessed One now become fully extinguished! May the Holy One now become fully extinguished! Now is the time for the Buddha to become fully extinguished.’*";
P_HTM[1810]="*Evaṃ vutte, ahaṃ, ānanda, māraṃ pāpimantaṃ etadavocaṃ:**When he had spoken, I said to Māra:*";
P_HTM[1811]="*‘Na tāvāhaṃ, pāpima, parinibbāyissāmi, yāva me bhikkhū na sāvakā bhavissanti viyattā vinītā visāradā bahussutā dhammadharā dhammānudhammappaṭipannā sāmīcippaṭipannā anudhammacārino, sakaṃ ācariyakaṃ uggahetvā ācikkhissanti desessanti paññapessanti paṭṭhapessanti vivarissanti vibhajissanti uttānīkarissanti, uppannaṃ parappavādaṃ sahadhammena suniggahitaṃ niggahetvā sappāṭihāriyaṃ dhammaṃ desessanti.**‘Wicked One, I will not become fully extinguished until I have monk disciples …*";
P_HTM[1812]="*Na tāvāhaṃ, pāpima, parinibbāyissāmi, yāva me bhikkhuniyo na sāvikā bhavissanti viyattā vinītā visāradā bahussutā dhammadharā dhammānudhammappaṭipannā sāmīcippaṭipannā anudhammacāriniyo, sakaṃ ācariyakaṃ uggahetvā ācikkhissanti desessanti paññapessanti paṭṭhapessanti vivarissanti vibhajissanti uttānīkarissanti, uppannaṃ parappavādaṃ sahadhammena suniggahitaṃ niggahetvā sappāṭihāriyaṃ dhammaṃ desessanti.**nun disciples …*";
P_HTM[1813]="*Na tāvāhaṃ, pāpima, parinibbāyissāmi, yāva me upāsakā na sāvakā bhavissanti viyattā vinītā visāradā bahussutā dhammadharā dhammānudhammappaṭipannā sāmīcippaṭipannā anudhammacārino, sakaṃ ācariyakaṃ uggahetvā ācikkhissanti desessanti paññapessanti paṭṭhapessanti vivarissanti vibhajissanti uttānīkarissanti, uppannaṃ parappavādaṃ sahadhammena suniggahitaṃ niggahetvā sappāṭihāriyaṃ dhammaṃ desessanti.**layman disciples …*";
P_HTM[1814]="*Na tāvāhaṃ, pāpima, parinibbāyissāmi, yāva me upāsikā na sāvikā bhavissanti viyattā vinītā visāradā bahussutā dhammadharā dhammānudhammappaṭipannā sāmīcippaṭipannā anudhammacāriniyo, sakaṃ ācariyakaṃ uggahetvā ācikkhissanti desessanti paññapessanti paṭṭhapessanti vivarissanti vibhajissanti uttānīkarissanti, uppannaṃ parappavādaṃ sahadhammena suniggahitaṃ niggahetvā sappāṭihāriyaṃ dhammaṃ desessanti.**laywoman disciples who are competent, educated, assured, learned.*";
P_HTM[1815]="*Na tāvāhaṃ, pāpima, parinibbāyissāmi, yāva me idaṃ brahmacariyaṃ na iddhañceva bhavissati phītañca vitthārikaṃ bāhujaññaṃ puthubhūtaṃ yāva devamanussehi suppakāsitan’ti.**Not until my spiritual life is successful and prosperous, extensive, popular, widespread, and well proclaimed wherever there are gods and humans.’*";
P_HTM[1816]="*Idāneva kho, ānanda, ajja cāpāle cetiye māro pāpimā yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi. Ekamantaṃ ṭhito kho, ānanda, māro pāpimā maṃ etadavoca:**Today, just now at the Cāpāla shrine Māra the Wicked approached me once more with the same request, reminding me of my former statement, and saying that those conditions had been fulfilled.*";
P_HTM[1817]="*‘parinibbātu dāni, bhante, bhagavā, parinibbātu sugato, parinibbānakālo dāni, bhante, bhagavato.* **";
P_HTM[1818]="*Bhāsitā kho panesā, bhante, bhagavatā vācā:* **";
P_HTM[1819]="*“na tāvāhaṃ, pāpima, parinibbāyissāmi, yāva me bhikkhū na sāvakā bhavissanti … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1820]="*yāva me bhikkhuniyo na sāvikā bhavissanti … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1821]="*yāva me upāsakā na sāvakā bhavissanti … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1822]="*yāva me upāsikā na sāvikā bhavissanti … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1823]="*yāva me idaṃ brahmacariyaṃ na iddhañceva bhavissati phītañca vitthārikaṃ bāhujaññaṃ puthubhūtaṃ, yāva devamanussehi suppakāsitan”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1824]="*Etarahi kho pana, bhante, bhagavato brahmacariyaṃ iddhañceva phītañca vitthārikaṃ bāhujaññaṃ puthubhūtaṃ, yāva devamanussehi suppakāsitaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1825]="*Parinibbātu dāni, bhante, bhagavā, parinibbātu sugato, parinibbānakālo dāni, bhante, bhagavato’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1826]="*Evaṃ vutte, ahaṃ, ānanda, māraṃ pāpimantaṃ etadavocaṃ:**When he had spoken, I said to Māra:*";
P_HTM[1827]="*‘appossukko tvaṃ, pāpima, hohi, na ciraṃ tathāgatassa parinibbānaṃ bhavissati.**‘Relax, Wicked One. The final extinguishment of the Realized One will be soon.*";
P_HTM[1828]="*Ito tiṇṇaṃ māsānaṃ accayena tathāgato parinibbāyissatī’ti.**Three months from now the Realized One will finally be extinguished.’*";
P_HTM[1829]="*Idāneva kho, ānanda, ajja cāpāle cetiye tathāgatena satena sampajānena āyusaṅkhāro ossaṭṭho”ti.**So today, just now at the Cāpāla tree shrine, mindful and aware, I surrendered the life force.”*";
P_HTM[1830]="*20. Ānandayācanakathā**20. The Appeal of Ānanda*";
P_HTM[1831]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Venerable Ānanda said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1832]="*“tiṭṭhatu, bhante, bhagavā kappaṃ, tiṭṭhatu sugato kappaṃ bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānan”ti.**“Sir, may the Blessed One please remain for the eon! May the Holy One please remain for the eon! That would be for the welfare and happiness of the people, for the benefit, welfare, and happiness of gods and humans.”*";
P_HTM[1833]="*“Alaṃ dāni, ānanda.**“Enough now, Ānanda.*";
P_HTM[1834]="*Mā tathāgataṃ yāci, akālo dāni, ānanda, tathāgataṃ yācanāyā”ti.**Do not beg the Realized One. Now is not the time to beg the Realized One.”*";
P_HTM[1835]="*Dutiyampi kho āyasmā ānando … pe …**For a second time …*";
P_HTM[1836]="*tatiyampi kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**For a third time, Ānanda said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1837]="*“tiṭṭhatu, bhante, bhagavā kappaṃ, tiṭṭhatu sugato kappaṃ bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānan”ti.**“Sir, may the Blessed One please remain for the eon! May the Holy One please remain for the eon! That would be for the welfare and happiness of the people, for the benefit, welfare, and happiness of gods and humans.”*";
P_HTM[1838]="*“Saddahasi tvaṃ, ānanda, tathāgatassa bodhin”ti?**“Ānanda, do you have faith in the Realized One’s awakening?”*";
P_HTM[1839]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1840]="*“Atha kiñcarahi tvaṃ, ānanda, tathāgataṃ yāvatatiyakaṃ abhinippīḷesī”ti?**“Then why do you keep pressing me up to the third time?”*";
P_HTM[1841]="*“Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**“Sir, I have heard and learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[1842]="*‘yassa kassaci, ānanda, cattāro iddhipādā bhāvitā bahulīkatā yānīkatā vatthukatā anuṭṭhitā paricitā susamāraddhā, so ākaṅkhamāno kappaṃ vā tiṭṭheyya kappāvasesaṃ vā.**‘Whoever has developed and cultivated the four bases of psychic power—made them a vehicle and a basis, kept them up, consolidated them, and properly implemented them—may, if they wish, live on for the eon or what’s left of the eon.*";
P_HTM[1843]="*Tathāgatassa kho, ānanda, cattāro iddhipādā bhāvitā bahulīkatā yānīkatā vatthukatā anuṭṭhitā paricitā susamāraddhā. So ākaṅkhamāno, ānanda, tathāgato kappaṃ vā tiṭṭheyya kappāvasesaṃ vā’”ti.**The Realized One has developed and cultivated the four bases of psychic power, made them a vehicle and a basis, kept them up, consolidated them, and properly implemented them. If he wished, the Realized One could live on for the eon or what’s left of the eon.’”*";
P_HTM[1844]="*“Saddahasi tvaṃ, ānandā”ti?**“Do you have faith, Ānanda?”*";
P_HTM[1845]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1846]="*“Tasmātihānanda, tuyhevetaṃ dukkaṭaṃ, tuyhevetaṃ aparaddhaṃ, yaṃ tvaṃ tathāgatena evaṃ oḷārike nimitte kayiramāne oḷārike obhāse kayiramāne nāsakkhi paṭivijjhituṃ, na tathāgataṃ yāci:**“Therefore, Ānanda, the misdeed is yours alone, the mistake is yours alone. For even though the Realized One dropped such an obvious hint, such a clear sign, you didn’t beg me to remain for the eon, or what’s left of it.*";
P_HTM[1847]="*‘tiṭṭhatu, bhante, bhagavā kappaṃ, tiṭṭhatu sugato kappaṃ bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1848]="*Sace tvaṃ, ānanda, tathāgataṃ yāceyyāsi, dveva te vācā tathāgato paṭikkhipeyya, atha tatiyakaṃ adhivāseyya.**If you had begged me, I would have refused you twice, but consented on the third time.*";
P_HTM[1849]="*Tasmātihānanda, tuyhevetaṃ dukkaṭaṃ, tuyhevetaṃ aparaddhaṃ.**Therefore, Ānanda, the misdeed is yours alone, the mistake is yours alone.*";
P_HTM[1850]="*Ekamidāhaṃ, ānanda, samayaṃ rājagahe viharāmi gijjhakūṭe pabbate.**Ānanda, this one time I was staying near Rājagaha, on the Vulture’s Peak Mountain.*";
P_HTM[1851]="*Tatrāpi kho tāhaṃ, ānanda, āmantesiṃ:**There I said to you:*";
P_HTM[1852]="*‘ramaṇīyaṃ, ānanda, rājagahaṃ, ramaṇīyo, ānanda, gijjhakūṭo pabbato.**‘Ānanda, Rājagaha is lovely, and so is the Vulture’s Peak.*";
P_HTM[1853]="*Yassa kassaci, ānanda, cattāro iddhipādā bhāvitā bahulīkatā yānīkatā vatthukatā anuṭṭhitā paricitā susamāraddhā, so ākaṅkhamāno kappaṃ vā tiṭṭheyya kappāvasesaṃ vā.**Whoever has developed and cultivated the four bases of psychic power—made them a vehicle and a basis, kept them up, consolidated them, and properly implemented them—may, if they wish, live on for the eon or what’s left of the eon.*";
P_HTM[1854]="*Tathāgatassa kho, ānanda, cattāro iddhipādā bhāvitā bahulīkatā yānīkatā vatthukatā anuṭṭhitā paricitā susamāraddhā, so ākaṅkhamāno, ānanda, tathāgato kappaṃ vā tiṭṭheyya kappāvasesaṃ vā’ti.**The Realized One has developed and cultivated the four bases of psychic power, made them a vehicle and a basis, kept them up, consolidated them, and properly implemented them. If he wished, the Realized One could live on for the eon or what’s left of the eon.’*";
P_HTM[1855]="*Evampi kho tvaṃ, ānanda, tathāgatena oḷārike nimitte kayiramāne oḷārike obhāse kayiramāne nāsakkhi paṭivijjhituṃ, na tathāgataṃ yāci:**But you didn’t get it, even though I dropped such an obvious hint, such a clear sign. You didn’t beg me to remain for the eon, or what’s left of it.*";
P_HTM[1856]="*‘tiṭṭhatu, bhante, bhagavā kappaṃ, tiṭṭhatu sugato kappaṃ bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1857]="*Sace tvaṃ, ānanda, tathāgataṃ yāceyyāsi, dveva te vācā tathāgato paṭikkhipeyya, atha tatiyakaṃ adhivāseyya.**If you had begged me, I would have refused you twice, but consented on the third time.*";
P_HTM[1858]="*Tasmātihānanda, tuyhevetaṃ dukkaṭaṃ, tuyhevetaṃ aparaddhaṃ.**Therefore, Ānanda, the misdeed is yours alone, the mistake is yours alone.*";
P_HTM[1859]="*Ekamidāhaṃ, ānanda, samayaṃ tattheva rājagahe viharāmi gotamanigrodhe … pe …**Ānanda, this one time I was staying right there near Rājagaha, at the Gotama banyan tree …*";
P_HTM[1860]="*tattheva rājagahe viharāmi corapapāte …**at Bandit’s Cliff …*";
P_HTM[1861]="*tattheva rājagahe viharāmi vebhārapasse sattapaṇṇiguhāyaṃ …**in the Sattapaṇṇi cave on the slopes of Vebhara …*";
P_HTM[1862]="*tattheva rājagahe viharāmi isigilipasse kāḷasilāyaṃ …**at the Black rock on the slopes of Isigili …*";
P_HTM[1863]="*tattheva rājagahe viharāmi sītavane sappasoṇḍikapabbhāre …**in the Cool Wood, under the Snake’s Hood Grotto …*";
P_HTM[1864]="*tattheva rājagahe viharāmi tapodārāme …**in the Hot Springs Monastery …*";
P_HTM[1865]="*tattheva rājagahe viharāmi veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe …**in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground …*";
P_HTM[1866]="*tattheva rājagahe viharāmi jīvakambavane …**in Jīvaka’s mango grove …*";
P_HTM[1867]="*tattheva rājagahe viharāmi maddakucchismiṃ migadāye.**in the Maddakucchi deer park …*";
P_HTM[1868]="*Tatrāpi kho tāhaṃ, ānanda, āmantesiṃ:**And in each place I said to you:*";
P_HTM[1869]="*‘ramaṇīyaṃ, ānanda, rājagahaṃ, ramaṇīyo gijjhakūṭo pabbato, ramaṇīyo gotamanigrodho, ramaṇīyo corapapāto, ramaṇīyā vebhārapasse sattapaṇṇiguhā, ramaṇīyā isigilipasse kāḷasilā, ramaṇīyo sītavane sappasoṇḍikapabbhāro, ramaṇīyo tapodārāmo, ramaṇīyo veḷuvane kalandakanivāpo, ramaṇīyaṃ jīvakambavanaṃ, ramaṇīyo maddakucchismiṃ migadāyo.**‘Ānanda, Rājagaha is lovely, and so are all these places. …*";
P_HTM[1870]="*Yassa kassaci, ānanda, cattāro iddhipādā bhāvitā bahulīkatā yānīkatā vatthukatā anuṭṭhitā paricitā susamāraddhā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1871]="*ākaṅkhamāno, ānanda, tathāgato kappaṃ vā tiṭṭheyya kappāvasesaṃ vā’ti.**If he wished, the Realized One could live on for the eon or what’s left of the eon.’*";
P_HTM[1872]="*Evampi kho tvaṃ, ānanda, tathāgatena oḷārike nimitte kayiramāne oḷārike obhāse kayiramāne nāsakkhi paṭivijjhituṃ, na tathāgataṃ yāci:**But you didn’t get it, even though I dropped such an obvious hint, such a clear sign. You didn’t beg me to remain for the eon, or what’s left of it.*";
P_HTM[1873]="*‘tiṭṭhatu, bhante, bhagavā kappaṃ, tiṭṭhatu sugato kappaṃ bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1874]="*Sace tvaṃ, ānanda, tathāgataṃ yāceyyāsi, dveva te vācā tathāgato paṭikkhipeyya, atha tatiyakaṃ adhivāseyya.* **";
P_HTM[1875]="*Tasmātihānanda, tuyhevetaṃ dukkaṭaṃ, tuyhevetaṃ aparaddhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1876]="*Ekamidāhaṃ, ānanda, samayaṃ idheva vesāliyaṃ viharāmi udene cetiye.**Ānanda, this one time I was staying right here near Vesālī, at the Udena shrine …*";
P_HTM[1877]="*Tatrāpi kho tāhaṃ, ānanda, āmantesiṃ:* **";
P_HTM[1878]="*‘ramaṇīyā, ānanda, vesālī, ramaṇīyaṃ udenaṃ cetiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1879]="*Yassa kassaci, ānanda, cattāro iddhipādā bhāvitā bahulīkatā yānīkatā vatthukatā anuṭṭhitā paricitā susamāraddhā, so ākaṅkhamāno kappaṃ vā tiṭṭheyya kappāvasesaṃ vā.* **";
P_HTM[1880]="*Tathāgatassa kho, ānanda, cattāro iddhipādā bhāvitā bahulīkatā yānīkatā vatthukatā anuṭṭhitā paricitā susamāraddhā, so ākaṅkhamāno, ānanda, tathāgato kappaṃ vā tiṭṭheyya kappāvasesaṃ vā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1881]="*Evampi kho tvaṃ, ānanda, tathāgatena oḷārike nimitte kayiramāne oḷārike obhāse kayiramāne nāsakkhi paṭivijjhituṃ, na tathāgataṃ yāci:* **";
P_HTM[1882]="*‘tiṭṭhatu, bhante, bhagavā kappaṃ, tiṭṭhatu sugato kappaṃ bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1883]="*Sace tvaṃ, ānanda, tathāgataṃ yāceyyāsi, dveva te vācā tathāgato paṭikkhipeyya, atha tatiyakaṃ adhivāseyya, tasmātihānanda, tuyhevetaṃ dukkaṭaṃ, tuyhevetaṃ aparaddhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1884]="*Ekamidāhaṃ, ānanda, samayaṃ idheva vesāliyaṃ viharāmi gotamake cetiye … pe …**at the Gotamaka shrine …*";
P_HTM[1885]="*idheva vesāliyaṃ viharāmi sattambe cetiye …**at the Sattamba shrine …*";
P_HTM[1886]="*idheva vesāliyaṃ viharāmi bahuputte cetiye …**at the Many Sons shrine …*";
P_HTM[1887]="*idheva vesāliyaṃ viharāmi sārandade cetiye …**at the Sārandada shrine …*";
P_HTM[1888]="*idāneva kho tāhaṃ, ānanda, ajja cāpāle cetiye āmantesiṃ:**and just now, today at the Cāpāla shrine. There I said to you:*";
P_HTM[1889]="*‘ramaṇīyā, ānanda, vesālī, ramaṇīyaṃ udenaṃ cetiyaṃ, ramaṇīyaṃ gotamakaṃ cetiyaṃ, ramaṇīyaṃ sattambaṃ cetiyaṃ, ramaṇīyaṃ bahuputtaṃ cetiyaṃ, ramaṇīyaṃ sārandadaṃ cetiyaṃ, ramaṇīyaṃ cāpālaṃ cetiyaṃ.**‘Ānanda, Vesālī is lovely. And the Udena, Gotamaka, Sattamba, Bahuputta, Sārandada, and Cāpāla shrines are all lovely.*";
P_HTM[1890]="*Yassa kassaci, ānanda, cattāro iddhipādā bhāvitā bahulīkatā yānīkatā vatthukatā anuṭṭhitā paricitā susamāraddhā, so ākaṅkhamāno kappaṃ vā tiṭṭheyya kappāvasesaṃ vā.**Whoever has developed and cultivated the four bases of psychic power—made them a vehicle and a basis, kept them up, consolidated them, and properly implemented them—may, if they wish, live on for the eon or what’s left of the eon.*";
P_HTM[1891]="*Tathāgatassa kho, ānanda, cattāro iddhipādā bhāvitā bahulīkatā yānīkatā vatthukatā anuṭṭhitā paricitā susamāraddhā, so ākaṅkhamāno, ānanda, tathāgato kappaṃ vā tiṭṭheyya kappāvasesaṃ vā’ti.**The Realized One has developed and cultivated the four bases of psychic power, made them a vehicle and a basis, kept them up, consolidated them, and properly implemented them. If he wished, the Realized One could live on for the eon or what’s left of the eon.’*";
P_HTM[1892]="*Evampi kho tvaṃ, ānanda, tathāgatena oḷārike nimitte kayiramāne oḷārike obhāse kayiramāne nāsakkhi paṭivijjhituṃ, na tathāgataṃ yāci:**But you didn’t get it, even though I dropped such an obvious hint, such a clear sign. You didn’t beg me to remain for the eon, or what’s left of it, saying:*";
P_HTM[1893]="*‘tiṭṭhatu bhagavā kappaṃ, tiṭṭhatu sugato kappaṃ bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānan’ti.**‘Sir, may the Blessed One please remain for the eon! May the Holy One please remain for the eon! That would be for the welfare and happiness of the people, for the benefit, welfare, and happiness of gods and humans.’*";
P_HTM[1894]="*Sace tvaṃ, ānanda, tathāgataṃ yāceyyāsi, dveva te vācā tathāgato paṭikkhipeyya, atha tatiyakaṃ adhivāseyya.**If you had begged me, I would have refused you twice, but consented on the third time.*";
P_HTM[1895]="*Tasmātihānanda, tuyhevetaṃ dukkaṭaṃ, tuyhevetaṃ aparaddhaṃ.**Therefore, Ānanda, the misdeed is yours alone, the mistake is yours alone.*";
P_HTM[1896]="*Nanu etaṃ, ānanda, mayā paṭikacceva akkhātaṃ:**Did I not prepare for this when I explained that*";
P_HTM[1897]="*‘sabbeheva piyehi manāpehi nānābhāvo vinābhāvo aññathābhāvo.**we must be parted and separated from all we hold dear and beloved?*";
P_HTM[1898]="*Taṃ kutettha, ānanda, labbhā, yaṃ taṃ jātaṃ bhūtaṃ saṅkhataṃ palokadhammaṃ, taṃ vata mā palujjīti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati’.**How could it possibly be so that what is born, created, conditioned, and liable to fall apart should not fall apart?*";
P_HTM[1899]="*Yaṃ kho panetaṃ, ānanda, tathāgatena cattaṃ vantaṃ muttaṃ pahīnaṃ paṭinissaṭṭhaṃ ossaṭṭho āyusaṅkhāro, ekaṃsena vācā bhāsitā:**The Realized One has discarded, eliminated, released, given up, relinquished, and surrendered the life force. He has definitively stated:*";
P_HTM[1900]="*‘na ciraṃ tathāgatassa parinibbānaṃ bhavissati.**‘The final extinguishment of the Realized One will be soon.*";
P_HTM[1901]="*Ito tiṇṇaṃ māsānaṃ accayena tathāgato parinibbāyissatī’ti.**Three months from now the Realized One will finally be extinguished.’*";
P_HTM[1902]="*Tañca tathāgato jīvitahetu puna paccāvamissatīti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**It’s not possible for the Realized One, for the sake of life, to take back the life force once it has been given up like that.*";
P_HTM[1903]="*Āyāmānanda, yena mahāvanaṃ kūṭāgārasālā tenupasaṅkamissāmā”ti.**Come, Ānanda, let’s go to the Great Wood, the hall with the peaked roof.”*";
P_HTM[1904]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Ānanda replied.*";
P_HTM[1905]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmatā ānandena saddhiṃ yena mahāvanaṃ kūṭāgārasālā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**So the Buddha went with Ānanda to the hall with the peaked roof, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[1906]="*“gaccha tvaṃ, ānanda, yāvatikā bhikkhū vesāliṃ upanissāya viharanti, te sabbe upaṭṭhānasālāyaṃ sannipātehī”ti.**“Go, Ānanda, gather all the mendicants staying in the vicinity of Vesālī together in the assembly hall.”*";
P_HTM[1907]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paṭissutvā yāvatikā bhikkhū vesāliṃ upanissāya viharanti, te sabbe upaṭṭhānasālāyaṃ sannipātetvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi. Ekamantaṃ ṭhito kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**“Yes, sir,” replied Ānanda. He did what the Buddha asked, went up to him, bowed, stood to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[1908]="*“sannipatito, bhante, bhikkhusaṅgho, yassadāni, bhante, bhagavā kālaṃ maññatī”ti.**“Sir, the mendicant Saṅgha has assembled. Please, sir, go at your convenience.”*";
P_HTM[1909]="*()* **";
P_HTM[1910]="*Atha kho bhagavā yenupaṭṭhānasālā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then the Buddha went to the assembly hall, where he sat on the seat spread out*";
P_HTM[1911]="*Nisajja kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**and addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[1912]="*“tasmātiha, bhikkhave, ye te mayā dhammā abhiññā desitā, te vo sādhukaṃ uggahetvā āsevitabbā bhāvetabbā bahulīkātabbā, yathayidaṃ brahmacariyaṃ addhaniyaṃ assa ciraṭṭhitikaṃ, tadassa bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**“So, mendicants, having carefully memorized those things I have taught you from my direct knowledge, you should cultivate, develop, and make much of them so that this spiritual practice may last for a long time. That would be for the welfare and happiness of the people, for the benefit, welfare, and happiness of gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[1913]="*Katame ca te, bhikkhave, dhammā mayā abhiññā desitā, ye vo sādhukaṃ uggahetvā āsevitabbā bhāvetabbā bahulīkātabbā, yathayidaṃ brahmacariyaṃ addhaniyaṃ assa ciraṭṭhitikaṃ, tadassa bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**And what are those things I have taught from my direct knowledge?*";
P_HTM[1914]="*Seyyathidaṃ—cattāro satipaṭṭhānā, cattāro sammappadhānā, cattāro iddhipādā, pañcindriyāni, pañca balāni, satta bojjhaṅgā, ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo.**They are: the four kinds of mindfulness meditation, the four right efforts, the four bases of psychic power, the five faculties, the five powers, the seven awakening factors, and the noble eightfold path.*";
P_HTM[1915]="*Ime kho te, bhikkhave, dhammā mayā abhiññā desitā, ye vo sādhukaṃ uggahetvā āsevitabbā bhāvetabbā bahulīkātabbā, yathayidaṃ brahmacariyaṃ addhaniyaṃ assa ciraṭṭhitikaṃ, tadassa bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānan”ti.**These are the things I have taught from my direct knowledge. Having carefully memorized them, you should cultivate, develop, and make much of them so that this spiritual practice may last for a long time. That would be for the welfare and happiness of the people, for the benefit, welfare, and happiness of gods and humans.”*";
P_HTM[1916]="*Atha kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then the Buddha said to the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[1917]="*“handa dāni, bhikkhave, āmantayāmi vo,**“Come now, mendicants, I say to you all:*";
P_HTM[1918]="*vayadhammā saṅkhārā, appamādena sampādetha.**‘Conditions fall apart. Persist with diligence.’*";
P_HTM[1919]="*Naciraṃ tathāgatassa parinibbānaṃ bhavissati.**The final extinguishment of the Realized One will be soon.*";
P_HTM[1920]="*Ito tiṇṇaṃ māsānaṃ accayena tathāgato parinibbāyissatī”ti.**Three months from now the Realized One will finally be extinguished.”*";
P_HTM[1921]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1922]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato athāparaṃ etadavoca satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[1923]="*“Paripakko vayo mayhaṃ,**“I’ve reached a ripe old age,*";
P_HTM[1924]="*parittaṃ mama jīvitaṃ;**and little of my life is left.*";
P_HTM[1925]="*Pahāya vo gamissāmi,**Having given it up, I’ll depart;*";
P_HTM[1926]="*kataṃ me saraṇamattano.**I’ve made a refuge for myself.*";
P_HTM[1927]="*Appamattā satīmanto,**Diligent and mindful,*";
P_HTM[1928]="*susīlā hotha bhikkhavo;**be of good virtues, mendicants!*";
P_HTM[1929]="*Susamāhitasaṅkappā,**With well-settled thoughts,*";
P_HTM[1930]="*sacittamanurakkhatha.**take good care of your minds.*";
P_HTM[1931]="*Yo imasmiṃ dhammavinaye,**Whoever meditates diligently*";
P_HTM[1932]="*appamatto vihassati;**in this teaching and training,*";
P_HTM[1933]="*Pahāya jātisaṃsāraṃ,**giving up transmigration through rebirths,*";
P_HTM[1934]="*dukkhassantaṃ karissatī”ti.**will make an end to suffering.”*";
P_HTM[1935]="*Tatiyo bhāṇavāro.* **";
P_HTM[1936]="*21. Nāgāpalokita**21. The Elephant Look*";
P_HTM[1937]="*Atha kho bhagavā pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya vesāliṃ piṇḍāya pāvisi.**Then the Buddha robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, entered Vesālī for alms.*";
P_HTM[1938]="*Vesāliyaṃ piṇḍāya caritvā pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkanto nāgāpalokitaṃ vesāliṃ apaloketvā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**Then, after the meal, on his return from alms-round, he turned his whole body, the way that elephants do, to look back at Vesālī. He said to Venerable Ānanda:*";
P_HTM[1939]="*“idaṃ pacchimakaṃ, ānanda, tathāgatassa vesāliyā dassanaṃ bhavissati.**“Ānanda, this will be the last time the Realized One sees Vesālī.*";
P_HTM[1940]="*Āyāmānanda, yena bhaṇḍagāmo tenupasaṅkamissāmā”ti.**Come, Ānanda, let’s go to Bhaṇḍagāma.”*";
P_HTM[1941]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Ānanda replied.*";
P_HTM[1942]="*Atha kho bhagavā mahatā bhikkhusaṅghena saddhiṃ yena bhaṇḍagāmo tadavasari.**Then the Buddha together with a large Saṅgha of mendicants arrived at Bhaṇḍagāma,*";
P_HTM[1943]="*Tatra sudaṃ bhagavā bhaṇḍagāme viharati.**and stayed there.*";
P_HTM[1944]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[1945]="*“catunnaṃ, bhikkhave, dhammānaṃ ananubodhā appaṭivedhā evamidaṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ sandhāvitaṃ saṃsaritaṃ mamañceva tumhākañca.**“Mendicants, not understanding and not penetrating four things, both you and I have wandered and transmigrated for such a very long time.*";
P_HTM[1946]="*Katamesaṃ catunnaṃ?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1947]="*Ariyassa, bhikkhave, sīlassa ananubodhā appaṭivedhā evamidaṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ sandhāvitaṃ saṃsaritaṃ mamañceva tumhākañca.**Noble ethics,*";
P_HTM[1948]="*Ariyassa, bhikkhave, samādhissa ananubodhā appaṭivedhā evamidaṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ sandhāvitaṃ saṃsaritaṃ mamañceva tumhākañca.**immersion,*";
P_HTM[1949]="*Ariyāya, bhikkhave, paññāya ananubodhā appaṭivedhā evamidaṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ sandhāvitaṃ saṃsaritaṃ mamañceva tumhākañca.**wisdom,*";
P_HTM[1950]="*Ariyāya, bhikkhave, vimuttiyā ananubodhā appaṭivedhā evamidaṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ sandhāvitaṃ saṃsaritaṃ mamañceva tumhākañca.**and freedom.*";
P_HTM[1951]="*Tayidaṃ, bhikkhave, ariyaṃ sīlaṃ anubuddhaṃ paṭividdhaṃ, ariyo samādhi anubuddho paṭividdho, ariyā paññā anubuddhā paṭividdhā, ariyā vimutti anubuddhā paṭividdhā, ucchinnā bhavataṇhā, khīṇā bhavanetti, natthi dāni punabbhavo”ti.**These noble ethics, immersion, wisdom, and freedom have been understood and comprehended. Craving for continued existence has been cut off; the attachment to continued existence is ended; now there are no more future lives.”*";
P_HTM[1952]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1953]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato athāparaṃ etadavoca satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[1954]="*“Sīlaṃ samādhi paññā ca,**“Ethics, immersion, and wisdom,*";
P_HTM[1955]="*vimutti ca anuttarā;**and the supreme freedom:*";
P_HTM[1956]="*Anubuddhā ime dhammā,**these things have been understood*";
P_HTM[1957]="*gotamena yasassinā.**by Gotama the renowned.*";
P_HTM[1958]="*Iti buddho abhiññāya,**And so the Buddha, having insight,*";
P_HTM[1959]="*dhammamakkhāsi bhikkhunaṃ;**explained this teaching to the mendicants.*";
P_HTM[1960]="*Dukkhassantakaro satthā,**The teacher made an end of suffering,*";
P_HTM[1961]="*cakkhumā parinibbuto”ti.**seeing clearly, he is extinguished.”*";
P_HTM[1962]="*Tatrāpi sudaṃ bhagavā bhaṇḍagāme viharanto etadeva bahulaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ dhammiṃ kathaṃ karoti:**And while staying there, too, he often gave this Dhamma talk to the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[1963]="*“iti sīlaṃ, iti samādhi, iti paññā.**“Such is ethics, such is immersion, such is wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1964]="*Sīlaparibhāvito samādhi mahapphalo hoti mahānisaṃso.**When immersion is imbued with ethics it’s very fruitful and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[1965]="*Samādhiparibhāvitā paññā mahapphalā hoti mahānisaṃsā.**When wisdom is imbued with immersion it’s very fruitful and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[1966]="*Paññāparibhāvitaṃ cittaṃ sammadeva āsavehi vimuccati, seyyathidaṃ—**When the mind is imbued with wisdom it is rightly freed from the defilements, namely,*";
P_HTM[1967]="*kāmāsavā, bhavāsavā, avijjāsavā”ti.**the defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.”*";
P_HTM[1968]="*22. Catumahāpadesakathā**22. The Four Great References*";
P_HTM[1969]="*Atha kho bhagavā bhaṇḍagāme yathābhirantaṃ viharitvā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**When the Buddha had stayed in Bhaṇḍagāma as long as he wished, he addressed Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[1970]="*“āyāmānanda, yena hatthigāmo,**“Come, Ānanda, let’s go to Hatthigāma.”…*";
P_HTM[1971]="*yena ambagāmo,**“Let’s go to Ambagāma.”…*";
P_HTM[1972]="*yena jambugāmo,**“Let’s go to Jambugāma.”…*";
P_HTM[1973]="*yena bhoganagaraṃ tenupasaṅkamissāmā”ti.**“Let’s go to Bhoganagara.”*";
P_HTM[1974]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Ānanda replied.*";
P_HTM[1975]="*Atha kho bhagavā mahatā bhikkhusaṃghena saddhiṃ yena bhoganagaraṃ tadavasari.**Then the Buddha together with a large Saṅgha of mendicants arrived at Bhoganagara,*";
P_HTM[1976]="*Tatra sudaṃ bhagavā bhoganagare viharati ānande cetiye.**where he stayed at the Ānanda shrine.*";
P_HTM[1977]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[1978]="*“cattārome, bhikkhave, mahāpadese desessāmi,**“Mendicants, I will teach you the four great references.*";
P_HTM[1979]="*taṃ suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasikarotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**Listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[1980]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[1981]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[1982]="*“Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu evaṃ vadeyya:**“Take a mendicant who says:*";
P_HTM[1983]="*‘sammukhā metaṃ, āvuso, bhagavato sutaṃ sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ,**‘Reverend, I have heard and learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[1984]="*ayaṃ dhammo ayaṃ vinayo idaṃ satthusāsanan’ti.**this is the teaching, this is the training, this is the Teacher’s instruction.’*";
P_HTM[1985]="*Tassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno bhāsitaṃ neva abhinanditabbaṃ nappaṭikkositabbaṃ.**You should neither approve nor dismiss that mendicant’s statement.*";
P_HTM[1986]="*Anabhinanditvā appaṭikkositvā tāni padabyañjanāni sādhukaṃ uggahetvā sutte osāretabbāni, vinaye sandassetabbāni.**Instead, you should carefully memorize those words and phrases, then check if they’re included in the discourses or found in the texts on monastic training.*";
P_HTM[1987]="*Tāni ce sutte osāriyamānāni vinaye sandassiyamānāni na ceva sutte osaranti, na ca vinaye sandissanti, niṭṭhamettha gantabbaṃ:**If they’re not included in the discourses or found in the texts on monastic training, you should draw the conclusion:*";
P_HTM[1988]="*‘addhā idaṃ na ceva tassa bhagavato vacanaṃ;**‘Clearly this is not the word of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1989]="*imassa ca bhikkhuno duggahitan’ti.**It has been incorrectly memorized by that mendicant.’*";
P_HTM[1990]="*Iti hetaṃ, bhikkhave, chaḍḍeyyātha.**And so you should reject it.*";
P_HTM[1991]="*Tāni ce sutte osāriyamānāni vinaye sandassiyamānāni sutte ceva osaranti, vinaye ca sandissanti, niṭṭhamettha gantabbaṃ:**If they are included in the discourses or found in the texts on monastic training, you should draw the conclusion:*";
P_HTM[1992]="*‘addhā idaṃ tassa bhagavato vacanaṃ;**‘Clearly this is the word of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1993]="*imassa ca bhikkhuno suggahitan’ti.**It has been correctly memorized by that mendicant.’*";
P_HTM[1994]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamaṃ mahāpadesaṃ dhāreyyātha. (1)**You should remember it. This is the first great reference.*";
P_HTM[1995]="*Idha pana, bhikkhave, bhikkhu evaṃ vadeyya:**Take another mendicant who says:*";
P_HTM[1996]="*‘amukasmiṃ nāma āvāse saṅgho viharati sathero sapāmokkho.**‘In such-and-such monastery lives a Saṅgha with seniors and leaders.*";
P_HTM[1997]="*Tassa me saṅghassa sammukhā sutaṃ sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ,**I’ve heard and learned this in the presence of that Saṅgha:*";
P_HTM[1998]="*ayaṃ dhammo ayaṃ vinayo idaṃ satthusāsanan’ti.**this is the teaching, this is the training, this is the Teacher’s instruction.’*";
P_HTM[1999]="*Tassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno bhāsitaṃ neva abhinanditabbaṃ nappaṭikkositabbaṃ.**You should neither approve nor dismiss that mendicant’s statement.*";
P_HTM[2000]="*Anabhinanditvā appaṭikkositvā tāni padabyañjanāni sādhukaṃ uggahetvā sutte osāretabbāni, vinaye sandassetabbāni.**Instead, you should carefully memorize those words and phrases, then check if they’re included in the discourses or found in the texts on monastic training.*";
P_HTM[2001]="*Tāni ce sutte osāriyamānāni vinaye sandassiyamānāni na ceva sutte osaranti, na ca vinaye sandissanti, niṭṭhamettha gantabbaṃ:**If they’re not included in the discourses or found in the texts on monastic training, you should draw the conclusion:*";
P_HTM[2002]="*‘addhā idaṃ na ceva tassa bhagavato vacanaṃ;**‘Clearly this is not the word of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2003]="*tassa ca saṅghassa duggahitan’ti.**It has been incorrectly memorized by that Saṅgha.’*";
P_HTM[2004]="*Itihetaṃ, bhikkhave, chaḍḍeyyātha.**And so you should reject it.*";
P_HTM[2005]="*Tāni ce sutte osāriyamānāni vinaye sandassiyamānāni sutte ceva osaranti, vinaye ca sandissanti, niṭṭhamettha gantabbaṃ:**If they are included in the discourses or found in the texts on monastic training, you should draw the conclusion:*";
P_HTM[2006]="*‘addhā idaṃ tassa bhagavato vacanaṃ;**‘Clearly this is the word of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2007]="*tassa ca saṅghassa suggahitan’ti.**It has been correctly memorized by that Saṅgha.’*";
P_HTM[2008]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyaṃ mahāpadesaṃ dhāreyyātha. (2)**You should remember it. This is the second great reference.*";
P_HTM[2009]="*Idha pana, bhikkhave, bhikkhu evaṃ vadeyya:**Take another mendicant who says:*";
P_HTM[2010]="*‘amukasmiṃ nāma āvāse sambahulā therā bhikkhū viharanti bahussutā āgatāgamā dhammadharā vinayadharā mātikādharā.**‘In such-and-such monastery there are several senior mendicants who are very learned, knowledgeable in the scriptures, who have memorized the teachings, the texts on monastic training, and the outlines.*";
P_HTM[2011]="*Tesaṃ me therānaṃ sammukhā sutaṃ sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ—**I’ve heard and learned this in the presence of those senior mendicants:*";
P_HTM[2012]="*ayaṃ dhammo ayaṃ vinayo idaṃ satthusāsanan’ti.**this is the teaching, this is the training, this is the Teacher’s instruction.’*";
P_HTM[2013]="*Tassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno bhāsitaṃ neva abhinanditabbaṃ …**You should neither approve nor dismiss that mendicant’s statement.*";
P_HTM[2014]="*pe …**Instead, you should carefully memorize those words and phrases, then check if they’re included in the discourses or found in the texts on monastic training.*";
P_HTM[2015]="*na ca vinaye sandissanti, niṭṭhamettha gantabbaṃ:**If they’re not included in the discourses or found in the texts on monastic training, you should draw the conclusion:*";
P_HTM[2016]="*‘addhā idaṃ na ceva tassa bhagavato vacanaṃ;**‘Clearly this is not the word of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2017]="*tesañca therānaṃ duggahitan’ti.**It has not been correctly memorized by those senior mendicants.’*";
P_HTM[2018]="*Itihetaṃ, bhikkhave, chaḍḍeyyātha.**And so you should reject it.*";
P_HTM[2019]="*Tāni ce sutte osāriyamānāni … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2020]="*vinaye ca sandissanti, niṭṭhamettha gantabbaṃ:**If they are included in the discourses and found in the texts on monastic training, you should draw the conclusion:*";
P_HTM[2021]="*‘addhā idaṃ tassa bhagavato vacanaṃ;**‘Clearly this is the word of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2022]="*tesañca therānaṃ suggahitan’ti.**It has been correctly memorized by those senior mendicants.’*";
P_HTM[2023]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyaṃ mahāpadesaṃ dhāreyyātha. (3)**You should remember it. This is the third great reference.*";
P_HTM[2024]="*Idha pana, bhikkhave, bhikkhu evaṃ vadeyya:**Take another mendicant who says:*";
P_HTM[2025]="*‘amukasmiṃ nāma āvāse eko thero bhikkhu viharati bahussuto āgatāgamo dhammadharo vinayadharo mātikādharo.**‘In such-and-such monastery there is a single senior mendicant who is very learned and knowledgeable in the scriptures, who has memorized the teachings, the texts on monastic training, and the outlines.*";
P_HTM[2026]="*Tassa me therassa sammukhā sutaṃ sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ—**I’ve heard and learned this in the presence of that senior mendicant:*";
P_HTM[2027]="*ayaṃ dhammo ayaṃ vinayo idaṃ satthusāsanan’ti.**this is the teaching, this is the training, this is the Teacher’s instruction.’*";
P_HTM[2028]="*Tassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno bhāsitaṃ neva abhinanditabbaṃ nappaṭikkositabbaṃ.**You should neither approve nor dismiss that mendicant’s statement.*";
P_HTM[2029]="*Anabhinanditvā appaṭikkositvā tāni padabyañjanāni sādhukaṃ uggahetvā sutte osāretabbāni, vinaye sandassetabbāni.**Instead, you should carefully memorize those words and phrases, then check if they’re included in the discourses or found in the texts on monastic training.*";
P_HTM[2030]="*Tāni ce sutte osāriyamānāni vinaye sandassiyamānāni na ceva sutte osaranti, na ca vinaye sandissanti, niṭṭhamettha gantabbaṃ:**If they’re not included in the discourses or found in the texts on monastic training, you should draw the conclusion:*";
P_HTM[2031]="*‘addhā idaṃ na ceva tassa bhagavato vacanaṃ;**‘Clearly this is not the word of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2032]="*tassa ca therassa duggahitan’ti.**It has been incorrectly memorized by that senior mendicant.’*";
P_HTM[2033]="*Itihetaṃ, bhikkhave, chaḍḍeyyātha.**And so you should reject it.*";
P_HTM[2034]="*Tāni ca sutte osāriyamānāni vinaye sandassiyamānāni sutte ceva osaranti, vinaye ca sandissanti, niṭṭhamettha gantabbaṃ:**If they are included in the discourses and found in the texts on monastic training, you should draw the conclusion:*";
P_HTM[2035]="*‘addhā idaṃ tassa bhagavato vacanaṃ;**‘Clearly this is the word of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2036]="*tassa ca therassa suggahitan’ti.**It has been correctly memorized by that senior mendicant.’*";
P_HTM[2037]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, catutthaṃ mahāpadesaṃ dhāreyyātha. (4)**You should remember it. This is the fourth great reference.*";
P_HTM[2038]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro mahāpadese dhāreyyāthā”ti.**These are the four great references. You should remember them.”*";
P_HTM[2039]="*Tatrapi sudaṃ bhagavā bhoganagare viharanto ānande cetiye etadeva bahulaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ dhammiṃ kathaṃ karoti:**And while staying at the Ānanda shrine, too, the Buddha often gave this Dhamma talk to the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[2040]="*“iti sīlaṃ, iti samādhi, iti paññā.**“Such is ethics, such is immersion, such is wisdom.*";
P_HTM[2041]="*Sīlaparibhāvito samādhi mahapphalo hoti mahānisaṃso.**When immersion is imbued with ethics it’s very fruitful and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[2042]="*Samādhiparibhāvitā paññā mahapphalā hoti mahānisaṃsā.**When wisdom is imbued with immersion it’s very fruitful and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[2043]="*Paññāparibhāvitaṃ cittaṃ sammadeva āsavehi vimuccati, seyyathidaṃ—**When the mind is imbued with wisdom it is rightly freed from the defilements, namely,*";
P_HTM[2044]="*kāmāsavā, bhavāsavā, avijjāsavā”ti.**the defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.”*";
P_HTM[2045]="*23. Kammāraputtacundavatthu**23. On Cunda the Smith*";
P_HTM[2046]="*Atha kho bhagavā bhoganagare yathābhirantaṃ viharitvā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**When the Buddha had stayed in Bhoganagara as long as he wished, he addressed Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[2047]="*“āyāmānanda, yena pāvā tenupasaṅkamissāmā”ti.**“Come, Ānanda, let’s go to Pāvā.”*";
P_HTM[2048]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Ānanda replied.*";
P_HTM[2049]="*Atha kho bhagavā mahatā bhikkhusaṃghena saddhiṃ yena pāvā tadavasari.**Then the Buddha together with a large Saṅgha of mendicants arrived at Pāvā,*";
P_HTM[2050]="*Tatra sudaṃ bhagavā pāvāyaṃ viharati cundassa kammāraputtassa ambavane.**where he stayed in Cunda the smith’s mango grove.*";
P_HTM[2051]="*Assosi kho cundo kammāraputto: “bhagavā kira pāvaṃ anuppatto, pāvāyaṃ viharati mayhaṃ ambavane”ti.**Cunda heard that the Buddha had arrived and was staying in his mango grove.*";
P_HTM[2052]="*Atha kho cundo kammāraputto yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**Then he went to the Buddha, bowed, and sat down to one side.*";
P_HTM[2053]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho cundaṃ kammāraputtaṃ bhagavā dhammiyā kathāya sandassesi samādapesi samuttejesi sampahaṃsesi.**The Buddha educated, encouraged, fired up, and inspired him with a Dhamma talk.*";
P_HTM[2054]="*Atha kho cundo kammāraputto bhagavatā dhammiyā kathāya sandassito samādapito samuttejito sampahaṃsito bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Cunda said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[2055]="*“adhivāsetu me, bhante, bhagavā svātanāya bhattaṃ saddhiṃ bhikkhusaṃghenā”ti.**“Sir, may the Buddha together with the mendicant Saṅgha please accept tomorrow’s meal from me.”*";
P_HTM[2056]="*Adhivāsesi bhagavā tuṇhībhāvena.**The Buddha consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[2057]="*Atha kho cundo kammāraputto bhagavato adhivāsanaṃ viditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkāmi.**Then, knowing that the Buddha had consented, Cunda got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on his right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[2058]="*Atha kho cundo kammāraputto tassā rattiyā accayena sake nivesane paṇītaṃ khādanīyaṃ bhojanīyaṃ paṭiyādāpetvā pahūtañca sūkaramaddavaṃ bhagavato kālaṃ ārocāpesi:**And when the night had passed Cunda had a variety of delicious foods prepared in his own home, and plenty of pork on the turn. Then he had the Buddha informed of the time, saying,*";
P_HTM[2059]="*“kālo, bhante, niṭṭhitaṃ bhattan”ti.**“Sir, it’s time. The meal is ready.”*";
P_HTM[2060]="*Atha kho bhagavā pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya saddhiṃ bhikkhusaṅghena yena cundassa kammāraputtassa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then the Buddha robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, went to the home of Cunda together with the mendicant Saṅgha, where he sat on the seat spread out*";
P_HTM[2061]="*Nisajja kho bhagavā cundaṃ kammāraputtaṃ āmantesi:**and addressed Cunda,*";
P_HTM[2062]="*“yaṃ te, cunda, sūkaramaddavaṃ paṭiyattaṃ, tena maṃ parivisa.**“Cunda, please serve me with the pork on the turn that you’ve prepared.*";
P_HTM[2063]="*Yaṃ panaññaṃ khādanīyaṃ bhojanīyaṃ paṭiyattaṃ, tena bhikkhusaṅghaṃ parivisā”ti.**And serve the mendicant Saṅgha with the other foods.”*";
P_HTM[2064]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho cundo kammāraputto bhagavato paṭissutvā yaṃ ahosi sūkaramaddavaṃ paṭiyattaṃ, tena bhagavantaṃ parivisi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Cunda, and did as he was asked.*";
P_HTM[2065]="*Yaṃ panaññaṃ khādanīyaṃ bhojanīyaṃ paṭiyattaṃ, tena bhikkhusaṅghaṃ parivisi.* **";
P_HTM[2066]="*Atha kho bhagavā cundaṃ kammāraputtaṃ āmantesi:**Then the Buddha addressed Cunda,*";
P_HTM[2067]="*“yaṃ te, cunda, sūkaramaddavaṃ avasiṭṭhaṃ, taṃ sobbhe nikhaṇāhi.**“Cunda, any pork on the turn that’s left over, you should bury it in a pond.*";
P_HTM[2068]="*Nāhaṃ taṃ, cunda, passāmi sadevake loke samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya, yassa taṃ paribhuttaṃ sammā pariṇāmaṃ gaccheyya aññatra tathāgatassā”ti.**I don’t see anyone in this world—with its gods, Māras, and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its gods and humans—who could properly digest it except for the Realized One.”*";
P_HTM[2069]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho cundo kammāraputto bhagavato paṭissutvā yaṃ ahosi sūkaramaddavaṃ avasiṭṭhaṃ, taṃ sobbhe nikhaṇitvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Cunda. He did as he was asked, then came back to the Buddha, bowed, and sat down to one side.*";
P_HTM[2070]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho cundaṃ kammāraputtaṃ bhagavā dhammiyā kathāya sandassetvā samādapetvā samuttejetvā sampahaṃsetvā uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkāmi.**Then the Buddha educated, encouraged, fired up, and inspired him with a Dhamma talk, after which he got up from his seat and left.*";
P_HTM[2071]="*()* **";
P_HTM[2072]="*Atha kho bhagavato cundassa kammāraputtassa bhattaṃ bhuttāvissa kharo ābādho uppajji, lohitapakkhandikā pabāḷhā vedanā vattanti māraṇantikā.**After the Buddha had eaten Cunda’s meal, he fell severely ill with bloody dysentery, struck by dreadful pains, close to death.*";
P_HTM[2073]="*Tā sudaṃ bhagavā sato sampajāno adhivāsesi avihaññamāno.**But he endured with mindfulness and situational awareness, without worrying.*";
P_HTM[2074]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**Then he addressed Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[2075]="*“āyāmānanda, yena kusinārā tenupasaṅkamissāmā”ti.**“Come, Ānanda, let’s go to Kusinārā.”*";
P_HTM[2076]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Ānanda replied.*";
P_HTM[2077]="*Cundassa bhattaṃ bhuñjitvā,**I’ve heard that after eating*";
P_HTM[2078]="*kammārassāti me sutaṃ;**the meal of Cunda the smith,*";
P_HTM[2079]="*Ābādhaṃ samphusī dhīro,**the wise one fell severely ill,*";
P_HTM[2080]="*pabāḷhaṃ māraṇantikaṃ.**with pains, close to death.*";
P_HTM[2081]="*Bhuttassa ca sūkaramaddavena,**A severe sickness attacked the Teacher*";
P_HTM[2082]="*Byādhippabāḷho udapādi satthuno;**who had eaten the pork on the turn.*";
P_HTM[2083]="*Virecamāno bhagavā avoca,**While still purging the Buddha said:*";
P_HTM[2084]="*“Gacchāmahaṃ kusināraṃ nagaran”ti.**“I’ll go to the citadel of Kusinārā.”*";
P_HTM[2085]="*24. Pānīyāharaṇa**24. Bringing a Drink*";
P_HTM[2086]="*Atha kho bhagavā maggā okkamma yena aññataraṃ rukkhamūlaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**Then the Buddha left the road and went to the root of a tree, where he addressed Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[2087]="*“iṅgha me tvaṃ, ānanda, catugguṇaṃ saṅghāṭiṃ paññapehi, kilantosmi, ānanda, nisīdissāmī”ti.**“Please, Ānanda, fold my outer robe in four and spread it out for me. I am tired and will sit down.”*";
P_HTM[2088]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paṭissutvā catugguṇaṃ saṅghāṭiṃ paññapesi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Ānanda, and did as he was asked.*";
P_HTM[2089]="*Nisīdi bhagavā paññatte āsane.**The Buddha sat on the seat spread out.*";
P_HTM[2090]="*Nisajja kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**When he was seated he said to Venerable Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[2091]="*“iṅgha me tvaṃ, ānanda, pānīyaṃ āhara, pipāsitosmi, ānanda, pivissāmī”ti.**“Please, Ānanda, fetch me some water. I am thirsty and will drink.”*";
P_HTM[2092]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Venerable Ānanda said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[2093]="*“idāni, bhante, pañcamattāni sakaṭasatāni atikkantāni, taṃ cakkacchinnaṃ udakaṃ parittaṃ luḷitaṃ āvilaṃ sandati.**“Sir, just now around five hundred carts have passed by. The shallow water has been churned up by their wheels, and it flows cloudy and murky.*";
P_HTM[2094]="*Ayaṃ, bhante, kakudhā nadī avidūre acchodakā sātodakā sītodakā setodakā suppatitthā ramaṇīyā.**The Kakutthā river is not far away, with clear, sweet, cool water, clean, with smooth banks, delightful.*";
P_HTM[2095]="*Ettha bhagavā pānīyañca pivissati, gattāni ca sītī karissatī”ti.**There the Buddha can drink and cool his limbs.”*";
P_HTM[2096]="*Dutiyampi kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**For a second time, the Buddha asked Ānanda for a drink,*";
P_HTM[2097]="*“iṅgha me tvaṃ, ānanda, pānīyaṃ āhara, pipāsitosmi, ānanda, pivissāmī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2098]="*Dutiyampi kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**and for a second time Ānanda suggested going to the Kakutthā river.*";
P_HTM[2099]="*“idāni, bhante, pañcamattāni sakaṭasatāni atikkantāni, taṃ cakkacchinnaṃ udakaṃ parittaṃ luḷitaṃ āvilaṃ sandati.* **";
P_HTM[2100]="*Ayaṃ, bhante, kakudhā nadī avidūre acchodakā sātodakā sītodakā setodakā suppatitthā ramaṇīyā.* **";
P_HTM[2101]="*Ettha bhagavā pānīyañca pivissati, gattāni ca sītīkarissatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2102]="*Tatiyampi kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**And for a third time, the Buddha said to Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[2103]="*“iṅgha me tvaṃ, ānanda, pānīyaṃ āhara, pipāsitosmi, ānanda, pivissāmī”ti.**“Please, Ānanda, fetch me some water. I am thirsty and will drink.”*";
P_HTM[2104]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paṭissutvā pattaṃ gahetvā yena sā nadikā tenupasaṅkami.**“Yes, sir,” replied Ānanda. Taking his bowl he went to the river.*";
P_HTM[2105]="*Atha kho sā nadikā cakkacchinnā parittā luḷitā āvilā sandamānā, āyasmante ānande upasaṅkamante acchā vippasannā anāvilā sandittha.**Now, though the shallow water in that creek had been churned up by wheels, and flowed cloudy and murky, when Ānanda approached it flowed transparent, clear, and unclouded.*";
P_HTM[2106]="*Atha kho āyasmato ānandassa etadahosi:**Then Ānanda thought,*";
P_HTM[2107]="*“acchariyaṃ vata bho, abbhutaṃ vata bho, tathāgatassa mahiddhikatā mahānubhāvatā.**“It’s incredible, it’s amazing! The Realized One has such psychic power and might!*";
P_HTM[2108]="*Ayañhi sā nadikā cakkacchinnā parittā luḷitā āvilā sandamānā mayi upasaṅkamante acchā vippasannā anāvilā sandatī”ti.**For though the shallow water in that creek had been churned up by wheels, and flowed cloudy and murky, when I approached it flowed transparent, clear, and unclouded.”*";
P_HTM[2109]="*Pattena pānīyaṃ ādāya yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Gathering a bowl of drinking water he went back to the Buddha, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[2110]="*“acchariyaṃ, bhante, abbhutaṃ, bhante, tathāgatassa mahiddhikatā mahānubhāvatā.**“It’s incredible, sir, it’s amazing! The Realized One has such psychic power and might!*";
P_HTM[2111]="*Idāni sā bhante nadikā cakkacchinnā parittā luḷitā āvilā sandamānā mayi upasaṅkamante acchā vippasannā anāvilā sandittha.**Just now, though the shallow water in that creek had been churned up by wheels, and flowed cloudy and murky, when I approached it flowed transparent, clear, and unclouded.*";
P_HTM[2112]="*Pivatu bhagavā pānīyaṃ pivatu sugato pānīyan”ti.**Drink the water, Blessed One! Drink the water, Holy One!”*";
P_HTM[2113]="*Atha kho bhagavā pānīyaṃ apāyi.**So the Buddha drank the water.*";
P_HTM[2114]="*25. Pukkusamallaputtavatthu**25. On Pukkusa the Malla*";
P_HTM[2115]="*Tena kho pana samayena pukkuso mallaputto āḷārassa kālāmassa sāvako kusinārāya pāvaṃ addhānamaggappaṭipanno hoti.**Now at that time Pukkusa the Malla, a disciple of Āḷāra Kālāma, was traveling along the road from Kusinārā and Pāvā.*";
P_HTM[2116]="*Addasā kho pukkuso mallaputto bhagavantaṃ aññatarasmiṃ rukkhamūle nisinnaṃ.**He saw the Buddha sitting at the root of a certain tree.*";
P_HTM[2117]="*Disvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho pukkuso mallaputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**He went up to him, bowed, sat down to one side, and said,*";
P_HTM[2118]="*“acchariyaṃ, bhante, abbhutaṃ, bhante, santena vata, bhante, pabbajitā vihārena viharanti.**“It’s incredible, sir, it’s amazing! Those who have gone forth remain in such peaceful meditations.*";
P_HTM[2119]="*Bhūtapubbaṃ, bhante, āḷāro kālāmo addhānamaggappaṭipanno maggā okkamma avidūre aññatarasmiṃ rukkhamūle divāvihāraṃ nisīdi.**Once it so happened that Āḷāra Kālāma, while traveling along a road, left the road and sat at the root of a nearby tree for the day’s meditation.*";
P_HTM[2120]="*Atha kho, bhante, pañcamattāni sakaṭasatāni āḷāraṃ kālāmaṃ nissāya nissāya atikkamiṃsu.**Then around five hundred carts passed by right next to Āḷāra Kālāma.*";
P_HTM[2121]="*Atha kho, bhante, aññataro puriso tassa sakaṭasatthassa piṭṭhito piṭṭhito āgacchanto yena āḷāro kālāmo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āḷāraṃ kālāmaṃ etadavoca:**Then a certain person coming behind those carts went up to Āḷāra Kālāma and said to him:*";
P_HTM[2122]="*‘api, bhante, pañcamattāni sakaṭasatāni atikkantāni addasā’ti?**‘Sir, didn’t you see the five hundred carts pass by?’*";
P_HTM[2123]="*‘Na kho ahaṃ, āvuso, addasan’ti.**‘No, friend, I didn’t see them.’*";
P_HTM[2124]="*‘Kiṃ pana, bhante, saddaṃ assosī’ti?**‘But sir, didn’t you hear a sound?’*";
P_HTM[2125]="*‘Na kho ahaṃ, āvuso, saddaṃ assosin’ti.**‘No, friend, I didn’t hear a sound.’*";
P_HTM[2126]="*‘Kiṃ pana, bhante, sutto ahosī’ti?**‘But sir, were you asleep?’*";
P_HTM[2127]="*‘Na kho ahaṃ, āvuso, sutto ahosin’ti.**‘No, friend, I wasn’t asleep.’*";
P_HTM[2128]="*‘Kiṃ pana, bhante, saññī ahosī’ti?**‘But sir, were you conscious?’*";
P_HTM[2129]="*‘Evamāvuso’ti.**‘Yes, friend.’*";
P_HTM[2130]="*‘So tvaṃ, bhante, saññī samāno jāgaro pañcamattāni sakaṭasatāni nissāya nissāya atikkantāni neva addasa, na pana saddaṃ assosi;**‘So, sir, while conscious and awake you neither saw nor heard a sound as five hundred carts passed by right next to you?*";
P_HTM[2131]="*apisu te, bhante, saṅghāṭi rajena okiṇṇā’ti?**Why sir, even your outer robe is covered with dust!’*";
P_HTM[2132]="*‘Evamāvuso’ti.**‘Yes, friend.’*";
P_HTM[2133]="*Atha kho, bhante, tassa purisassa etadahosi:**Then that person thought:*";
P_HTM[2134]="*‘acchariyaṃ vata bho, abbhutaṃ vata bho, santena vata bho pabbajitā vihārena viharanti.**‘It’s incredible, it’s amazing! Those who have gone forth remain in such peaceful meditations,*";
P_HTM[2135]="*Yatra hi nāma saññī samāno jāgaro pañcamattāni sakaṭasatāni nissāya nissāya atikkantāni neva dakkhati, na pana saddaṃ sossatī’ti.**in that, while conscious and awake he neither saw nor heard a sound as five hundred carts passed by right next to him.’*";
P_HTM[2136]="*Āḷāre kālāme uḷāraṃ pasādaṃ pavedetvā pakkāmī”ti.**And after declaring his lofty confidence in Āḷāra Kālāma, he left.”*";
P_HTM[2137]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, pukkusa,**“What do you think, Pukkusa?*";
P_HTM[2138]="*katamaṃ nu kho dukkarataraṃ vā durabhisambhavataraṃ vā—**Which is harder and more challenging to do while conscious and awake:*";
P_HTM[2139]="*yo vā saññī samāno jāgaro pañcamattāni sakaṭasatāni nissāya nissāya atikkantāni neva passeyya, na pana saddaṃ suṇeyya;**to neither see nor hear a sound as five hundred carts pass by right next to you?*";
P_HTM[2140]="*yo vā saññī samāno jāgaro deve vassante deve gaḷagaḷāyante vijjullatāsu niccharantīsu asaniyā phalantiyā neva passeyya, na pana saddaṃ suṇeyyā”ti?**Or to neither see nor hear a sound as it’s raining and pouring, lightning’s flashing, and thunder’s cracking?”*";
P_HTM[2141]="*“Kiñhi, bhante, karissanti pañca vā sakaṭasatāni cha vā sakaṭasatāni satta vā sakaṭasatāni aṭṭha vā sakaṭasatāni nava vā sakaṭasatāni, sakaṭasahassaṃ vā sakaṭasatasahassaṃ vā.**“What do five hundred carts matter, or six hundred, or seven hundred, or eight hundred, or nine hundred, or a thousand, or even a hundred thousand carts?*";
P_HTM[2142]="*Atha kho etadeva dukkaratarañceva durabhisambhavatarañca yo saññī samāno jāgaro deve vassante deve gaḷagaḷāyante vijjullatāsu niccharantīsu asaniyā phalantiyā neva passeyya, na pana saddaṃ suṇeyyā”ti.**It’s far harder and more challenging to neither see nor hear a sound as it’s raining and pouring, lightning’s flashing, and thunder’s cracking!”*";
P_HTM[2143]="*“Ekamidāhaṃ, pukkusa, samayaṃ ātumāyaṃ viharāmi bhusāgāre.**“This one time, Pukkusa, I was staying near Ātumā in a threshing-hut.*";
P_HTM[2144]="*Tena kho pana samayena deve vassante deve gaḷagaḷāyante vijjullatāsu niccharantīsu asaniyā phalantiyā avidūre bhusāgārassa dve kassakā bhātaro hatā cattāro ca balibaddā.**At that time it was raining and pouring, lightning was flashing, and thunder was cracking. And not far from the threshing-hut two farmers who were brothers were killed, as well as four oxen.*";
P_HTM[2145]="*Atha kho, pukkusa, ātumāya mahājanakāyo nikkhamitvā yena te dve kassakā bhātaro hatā cattāro ca balibaddā tenupasaṅkami.**Then a large crowd came from Ātumā to the place where that happened.*";
P_HTM[2146]="*Tena kho panāhaṃ, pukkusa, samayena bhusāgārā nikkhamitvā bhusāgāradvāre abbhokāse caṅkamāmi.**Now at that time I came out of the threshing-hut and was walking meditation in the open near the door of the hut.*";
P_HTM[2147]="*Atha kho, pukkusa, aññataro puriso tamhā mahājanakāyā yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā maṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi. Ekamantaṃ ṭhitaṃ kho ahaṃ, pukkusa, taṃ purisaṃ etadavocaṃ:**Then having left that crowd, a certain person approached me, bowed, and stood to one side. I said to them,*";
P_HTM[2148]="*‘kiṃ nu kho eso, āvuso, mahājanakāyo sannipatito’ti?**‘Why, friend, has this crowd gathered?’*";
P_HTM[2149]="*‘Idāni, bhante, deve vassante deve gaḷagaḷāyante vijjullatāsu niccharantīsu asaniyā phalantiyā dve kassakā bhātaro hatā cattāro ca balibaddā.**‘Just now, sir, it was raining and pouring, lightning was flashing, and thunder was cracking. And two farmers who were brothers were killed, as well as four oxen.*";
P_HTM[2150]="*Ettheso mahājanakāyo sannipatito.**Then this crowd gathered here.*";
P_HTM[2151]="*Tvaṃ pana, bhante, kva ahosī’ti?**But sir, where were you?’*";
P_HTM[2152]="*‘Idheva kho ahaṃ, āvuso, ahosin’ti.**‘I was right here, friend.’*";
P_HTM[2153]="*‘Kiṃ pana, bhante, addasā’ti?**‘But sir, did you see?’*";
P_HTM[2154]="*‘Na kho ahaṃ, āvuso, addasan’ti.**‘No, friend, I didn’t see anything.’*";
P_HTM[2155]="*‘Kiṃ pana, bhante, saddaṃ assosī’ti?**‘But sir, didn’t you hear a sound?’*";
P_HTM[2156]="*‘Na kho ahaṃ, āvuso, saddaṃ assosin’ti.**‘No, friend, I didn’t hear a sound.’*";
P_HTM[2157]="*‘Kiṃ pana, bhante, sutto ahosī’ti?**‘But sir, were you asleep?’*";
P_HTM[2158]="*‘Na kho ahaṃ, āvuso, sutto ahosin’ti.**‘No, friend, I wasn’t asleep.’*";
P_HTM[2159]="*‘Kiṃ pana, bhante, saññī ahosī’ti?**‘But sir, were you conscious?’*";
P_HTM[2160]="*‘Evamāvuso’ti.**‘Yes, friend.’*";
P_HTM[2161]="*‘So tvaṃ, bhante, saññī samāno jāgaro deve vassante deve gaḷagaḷāyante vijjullatāsu niccharantīsu asaniyā phalantiyā neva addasa, na pana saddaṃ assosī’ti?**‘So, sir, while conscious and awake you neither saw nor heard a sound as it was raining and pouring, lightning was flashing, and thunder was cracking?’*";
P_HTM[2162]="*‘Evamāvuso’ti?**‘Yes, friend.’*";
P_HTM[2163]="*Atha kho, pukkusa, tassa purisassa etadahosi:**Then that person thought:*";
P_HTM[2164]="*‘acchariyaṃ vata bho, abbhutaṃ vata bho, santena vata bho pabbajitā vihārena viharanti.**‘It’s incredible, it’s amazing! Those who have gone forth remain in such peaceful meditations,*";
P_HTM[2165]="*Yatra hi nāma saññī samāno jāgaro deve vassante deve gaḷagaḷāyante vijjullatāsu niccharantīsu asaniyā phalantiyā neva dakkhati, na pana saddaṃ sossatī’ti.**in that, while conscious and awake he neither saw nor heard a sound as it was raining and pouring, lightning was flashing, and thunder was cracking.’*";
P_HTM[2166]="*Mayi uḷāraṃ pasādaṃ pavedetvā maṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkāmī”ti.**And after declaring their lofty confidence in me, they bowed and respectfully circled me, keeping me on their right, before leaving.”*";
P_HTM[2167]="*Evaṃ vutte, pukkuso mallaputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Pukkusa said to him,*";
P_HTM[2168]="*“esāhaṃ, bhante, yo me āḷāre kālāme pasādo taṃ mahāvāte vā ophuṇāmi sīghasotāya vā nadiyā pavāhemi.**“Any confidence I had in Āḷāra Kālāma I sweep away as in a strong wind, or float away as down a swift stream.*";
P_HTM[2169]="*Abhikkantaṃ, bhante, abhikkantaṃ, bhante.**Excellent, sir! Excellent!*";
P_HTM[2170]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante, nikkujjitaṃ vā ukkujjeyya, paṭicchannaṃ vā vivareyya, mūḷhassa vā maggaṃ ācikkheyya, andhakāre vā telapajjotaṃ dhāreyya: ‘cakkhumanto rūpāni dakkhantī’ti; evamevaṃ bhagavatā anekapariyāyena dhammo pakāsito.**As if he were righting the overturned, or revealing the hidden, or pointing out the path to the lost, or lighting a lamp in the dark so people with good eyes can see what’s there, the Buddha has made the teaching clear in many ways.*";
P_HTM[2171]="*Esāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāmi dhammañca bhikkhusaṃghañca.**I go for refuge to the Buddha, to the teaching, and to the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[2172]="*Upāsakaṃ maṃ bhagavā dhāretu ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gatan”ti.**From this day forth, may the Buddha remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[2173]="*Atha kho pukkuso mallaputto aññataraṃ purisaṃ āmantesi:**Then Pukkusa addressed a certain man,*";
P_HTM[2174]="*“iṅgha me tvaṃ, bhaṇe, siṅgīvaṇṇaṃ yugamaṭṭhaṃ dhāraṇīyaṃ āharā”ti.**“Please, my man, fetch a pair of ready to wear polished golden garments.”*";
P_HTM[2175]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho so puriso pukkusassa mallaputtassa paṭissutvā taṃ siṅgīvaṇṇaṃ yugamaṭṭhaṃ dhāraṇīyaṃ āhari.**“Yes, sir,” replied that man, and did as he was asked.*";
P_HTM[2176]="*Atha kho pukkuso mallaputto taṃ siṅgīvaṇṇaṃ yugamaṭṭhaṃ dhāraṇīyaṃ bhagavato upanāmesi:**Then Pukkusa brought the garments to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[2177]="*“idaṃ, bhante, siṅgīvaṇṇaṃ yugamaṭṭhaṃ dhāraṇīyaṃ, taṃ me bhagavā paṭiggaṇhātu anukampaṃ upādāyā”ti.**“Sir, please accept this pair of ready to wear polished golden garments from me out of compassion.”*";
P_HTM[2178]="*“Tena hi, pukkusa, ekena maṃ acchādehi, ekena ānandan”ti.**“Well then, Pukkusa, clothe me in one, and Ānanda in the other.”*";
P_HTM[2179]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho pukkuso mallaputto bhagavato paṭissutvā ekena bhagavantaṃ acchādeti, ekena āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ.**“Yes, sir,” replied Pukkusa, and did so.*";
P_HTM[2180]="*Atha kho bhagavā pukkusaṃ mallaputtaṃ dhammiyā kathāya sandassesi samādapesi samuttejesi sampahaṃsesi.**Then the Buddha educated, encouraged, fired up, and inspired Pukkusa the Malla with a Dhamma talk,*";
P_HTM[2181]="*Atha kho pukkuso mallaputto bhagavatā dhammiyā kathāya sandassito samādapito samuttejito sampahaṃsito uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkāmi.**after which he got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha before leaving.*";
P_HTM[2182]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando acirapakkante pukkuse mallaputte taṃ siṅgīvaṇṇaṃ yugamaṭṭhaṃ dhāraṇīyaṃ bhagavato kāyaṃ upanāmesi.**Then, not long after Pukkusa had left, Ānanda placed the pair of golden garments on the Buddha’s body.*";
P_HTM[2183]="*Taṃ bhagavato kāyaṃ upanāmitaṃ hataccikaṃ viya khāyati.**But when placed on the Buddha’s body they seemed to lose their shine.*";
P_HTM[2184]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Ānanda said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[2185]="*“acchariyaṃ, bhante, abbhutaṃ, bhante, yāva parisuddho, bhante, tathāgatassa chavivaṇṇo pariyodāto.**“It’s incredible, sir, it’s amazing, how pure and bright is the color of the Realized One’s skin.*";
P_HTM[2186]="*Idaṃ, bhante, siṅgīvaṇṇaṃ yugamaṭṭhaṃ dhāraṇīyaṃ bhagavato kāyaṃ upanāmitaṃ hataccikaṃ viya khāyatī”ti.**When this pair of ready to wear polished golden garments is placed on the Buddha’s body they seem to lose their shine.”*";
P_HTM[2187]="*“Evametaṃ, ānanda, evametaṃ, ānanda, dvīsu kālesu ativiya tathāgatassa kāyo parisuddho hoti chavivaṇṇo pariyodāto.**“That’s so true, Ānanda, that’s so true! There are two times when the color of the Realized One’s skin becomes extra pure and bright.*";
P_HTM[2188]="*Katamesu dvīsu?**What two?*";
P_HTM[2189]="*Yañca, ānanda, rattiṃ tathāgato anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambujjhati, yañca rattiṃ anupādisesāya nibbānadhātuyā parinibbāyati.**The night when a Realized One understands the supreme perfect awakening; and the night he becomes fully extinguished through the natural principle of extinguishment, without anything left over.*";
P_HTM[2190]="*Imesu kho, ānanda, dvīsu kālesu ativiya tathāgatassa kāyo parisuddho hoti chavivaṇṇo pariyodāto.**These are the are two times when the color of the Realized One’s skin becomes extra pure and bright.*";
P_HTM[2191]="*Ajja kho panānanda, rattiyā pacchime yāme kusinārāyaṃ upavattane mallānaṃ sālavane antarena yamakasālānaṃ tathāgatassa parinibbānaṃ bhavissati.**Today, Ānanda, in the last watch of the night, between a pair of sal trees in the sal forest of the Mallas at Upavattana near Kusinārā, shall be the Realized One’s full extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[2192]="*Āyāmānanda, yena kakudhā nadī tenupasaṅkamissāmā”ti.**Come, Ānanda, let’s go to the Kakutthā River.”*";
P_HTM[2193]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Ānanda replied.*";
P_HTM[2194]="*Siṅgīvaṇṇaṃ yugamaṭṭhaṃ,**A pair of golden polished garments*";
P_HTM[2195]="*pukkuso abhihārayi;**was presented by Pukkusa;*";
P_HTM[2196]="*Tena acchādito satthā,**when the teacher was clothed with them,*";
P_HTM[2197]="*hemavaṇṇo asobhathāti.**his golden skin glowed bright.*";
P_HTM[2198]="*()* **";
P_HTM[2199]="*Atha kho bhagavā mahatā bhikkhusaṃghena saddhiṃ yena kakudhā nadī tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā kakudhaṃ nadiṃ ajjhogāhetvā nhatvā ca pivitvā ca paccuttaritvā yena ambavanaṃ tenupasaṅkami.**Then the Buddha together with a large Saṅgha of mendicants went to the Kakutthā River. He plunged into the river and bathed and drank. And when he had emerged, he went to the mango grove,*";
P_HTM[2200]="*Upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ cundakaṃ āmantesi:**where he addressed Venerable Cundaka,*";
P_HTM[2201]="*“iṅgha me tvaṃ, cundaka, catugguṇaṃ saṅghāṭiṃ paññapehi, kilantosmi, cundaka, nipajjissāmī”ti.**“Please, Cundaka, fold my outer robe in four and spread it out for me. I am tired and will lie down.”*";
P_HTM[2202]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā cundako bhagavato paṭissutvā catugguṇaṃ saṅghāṭiṃ paññapesi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Cundaka, and did as he was asked.*";
P_HTM[2203]="*Atha kho bhagavā dakkhiṇena passena sīhaseyyaṃ kappesi pāde pādaṃ accādhāya sato sampajāno uṭṭhānasaññaṃ manasikaritvā.**And then the Buddha laid down in the lion’s posture—on the right side, placing one foot on top of the other—mindful and aware, and focused on the time of getting up.*";
P_HTM[2204]="*Āyasmā pana cundako tattheva bhagavato purato nisīdi.**But Cundaka sat down right there in front of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2205]="*Gantvāna buddho nadikaṃ kakudhaṃ,**Having gone to Kakutthā Creek,*";
P_HTM[2206]="*Acchodakaṃ sātudakaṃ vippasannaṃ;**whose water was transparent, sweet, and clear,*";
P_HTM[2207]="*Ogāhi satthā akilantarūpo,**the Teacher, being tired, plunged in,*";
P_HTM[2208]="*Tathāgato appaṭimo ca loke.**the Realized One, without compare in the world.*";
P_HTM[2209]="*Nhatvā ca pivitvā cudatāri satthā,**And after bathing and drinking the Teacher emerged.*";
P_HTM[2210]="*Purakkhato bhikkhugaṇassa majjhe;**Before the group of mendicants, in the middle, the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[2211]="*Vattā pavattā bhagavā idha dhamme,**the Teacher who rolled forth the present dispensation,*";
P_HTM[2212]="*Upāgami ambavanaṃ mahesi.**the great hermit went to the mango grove.*";
P_HTM[2213]="*Āmantayi cundakaṃ nāma bhikkhuṃ,**He addressed the mendicant named Cundaka:*";
P_HTM[2214]="*Catugguṇaṃ santhara me nipajjaṃ;**“Spread out my folded robe so I can lie down.”*";
P_HTM[2215]="*So codito bhāvitattena cundo,**The self-developed one urged Cunda,*";
P_HTM[2216]="*Catugguṇaṃ santhari khippameva;**who quickly spread the folded robe.*";
P_HTM[2217]="*Nipajji satthā akilantarūpo,**Teacher, being tired, lay down,*";
P_HTM[2218]="*Cundopi tattha pamukhe nisīdīti.**while Cunda sat there before him.*";
P_HTM[2219]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**Then the Buddha said to Venerable Ānanda:*";
P_HTM[2220]="*“siyā kho panānanda, cundassa kammāraputtassa koci vippaṭisāraṃ uppādeyya:**“Now it may happen, Ānanda, that others may give rise to some regret for Cunda the smith:*";
P_HTM[2221]="*‘tassa te, āvuso cunda, alābhā tassa te dulladdhaṃ, yassa te tathāgato pacchimaṃ piṇḍapātaṃ paribhuñjitvā parinibbuto’ti.**‘It’s your loss, friend Cunda, it’s your misfortune, in that the Realized One became fully extinguished after eating his last meal from you.’*";
P_HTM[2222]="*Cundassa, ānanda, kammāraputtassa evaṃ vippaṭisāro paṭivinetabbo:**You should get rid of remorse in Cunda the smith like this:*";
P_HTM[2223]="*‘tassa te, āvuso cunda, lābhā tassa te suladdhaṃ,**‘You’re fortunate, friend Cunda, you’re so very fortunate,*";
P_HTM[2224]="*yassa te tathāgato pacchimaṃ piṇḍapātaṃ paribhuñjitvā parinibbuto.**in that the Realized One became fully extinguished after eating his last meal from you.*";
P_HTM[2225]="*Sammukhā metaṃ, āvuso cunda, bhagavato sutaṃ sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**I have heard and learned this in the presence of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2226]="*dveme piṇḍapātā samasamaphalā samavipākā, ativiya aññehi piṇḍapātehi mahapphalatarā ca mahānisaṃsatarā ca.**There are two meal offerings that have identical fruit and result, and are more fruitful and beneficial than other meal offerings.*";
P_HTM[2227]="*Katame dve?**What two?*";
P_HTM[2228]="*Yañca piṇḍapātaṃ paribhuñjitvā tathāgato anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambujjhati, yañca piṇḍapātaṃ paribhuñjitvā tathāgato anupādisesāya nibbānadhātuyā parinibbāyati.**The meal after eating which a Realized One understands the supreme perfect awakening; and the meal after eating which he becomes fully extinguished through the natural principle of extinguishment, without anything left over.*";
P_HTM[2229]="*Ime dve piṇḍapātā samasamaphalā samavipākā, ativiya aññehi piṇḍapātehi mahapphalatarā ca mahānisaṃsatarā ca.**These two meal offerings have identical fruit and result, and are more fruitful and beneficial than other meal offerings.*";
P_HTM[2230]="*Āyusaṃvattanikaṃ āyasmatā cundena kammāraputtena kammaṃ upacitaṃ, vaṇṇasaṃvattanikaṃ āyasmatā cundena kammāraputtena kammaṃ upacitaṃ, sukhasaṃvattanikaṃ āyasmatā cundena kammāraputtena kammaṃ upacitaṃ, yasasaṃvattanikaṃ āyasmatā cundena kammāraputtena kammaṃ upacitaṃ, saggasaṃvattanikaṃ āyasmatā cundena kammāraputtena kammaṃ upacitaṃ, ādhipateyyasaṃvattanikaṃ āyasmatā cundena kammāraputtena kammaṃ upacitan’ti.**You’ve accumulated a deed that leads to long life, beauty, happiness, fame, heaven, and sovereignty.’*";
P_HTM[2231]="*Cundassa, ānanda, kammāraputtassa evaṃ vippaṭisāro paṭivinetabbo”ti.**That’s how you should get rid of remorse in Cunda the smith.”*";
P_HTM[2232]="*Atha kho bhagavā etamatthaṃ viditvā tāyaṃ velāyaṃ imaṃ udānaṃ udānesi:**Then, knowing the meaning of this, on that occasion the Buddha was inspired to exclaim:*";
P_HTM[2233]="*“Dadato puññaṃ pavaḍḍhati,**“A giver’s merit grows;*";
P_HTM[2234]="*Saṃyamato veraṃ na cīyati;**enmity doesn’t build up when you have self-control.*";
P_HTM[2235]="*Kusalo ca jahāti pāpakaṃ,**A skillful person gives up bad things—*";
P_HTM[2236]="*Rāgadosamohakkhayā sanibbuto”ti.**with the end of greed, hate, and delusion, they’re extinguished.”*";
P_HTM[2237]="*Catuttho bhāṇavāro.* **";
P_HTM[2238]="*26. Yamakasālā**26. The Pair of Sal Trees*";
P_HTM[2239]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**Then the Buddha said to Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[2240]="*“āyāmānanda, yena hiraññavatiyā nadiyā pārimaṃ tīraṃ, yena kusinārā upavattanaṃ mallānaṃ sālavanaṃ tenupasaṅkamissāmā”ti.**“Come, Ānanda, let’s go to the far shore of the Golden River, and on to the sal forest of the Mallas at Upavattana near Kusinārā.”*";
P_HTM[2241]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Ānanda replied.*";
P_HTM[2242]="*Atha kho bhagavā mahatā bhikkhusaṃghena saddhiṃ yena hiraññavatiyā nadiyā pārimaṃ tīraṃ, yena kusinārā upavattanaṃ mallānaṃ sālavanaṃ tenupasaṅkami. upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**And that’s where they went. Then the Buddha addressed Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[2243]="*“iṅgha me tvaṃ, ānanda, antarena yamakasālānaṃ uttarasīsakaṃ mañcakaṃ paññapehi, kilantosmi, ānanda, nipajjissāmī”ti.**“Please, Ānanda, set up a cot for me between the twin sal trees, with my head to the north. I am tired and will lie down.”*";
P_HTM[2244]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paṭissutvā antarena yamakasālānaṃ uttarasīsakaṃ mañcakaṃ paññapesi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Ānanda, and did as he was asked.*";
P_HTM[2245]="*Atha kho bhagavā dakkhiṇena passena sīhaseyyaṃ kappesi pāde pādaṃ accādhāya sato sampajāno.**And then the Buddha laid down in the lion’s posture—on the right side, placing one foot on top of the other—mindful and aware.*";
P_HTM[2246]="*Tena kho pana samayena yamakasālā sabbaphāliphullā honti akālapupphehi.**Now at that time the twin sal trees were in full blossom with flowers out of season.*";
P_HTM[2247]="*Te tathāgatassa sarīraṃ okiranti ajjhokiranti abhippakiranti tathāgatassa pūjāya.**They sprinkled and bestrewed the Realized One’s body in honor of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[2248]="*Dibbānipi mandāravapupphāni antalikkhā papatanti, tāni tathāgatassa sarīraṃ okiranti ajjhokiranti abhippakiranti tathāgatassa pūjāya.**And the flowers of the heavenly Flame Tree fell from the sky, and they too sprinkled and bestrewed the Realized One’s body in honor of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[2249]="*Dibbānipi candanacuṇṇāni antalikkhā papatanti, tāni tathāgatassa sarīraṃ okiranti ajjhokiranti abhippakiranti tathāgatassa pūjāya.**And heavenly sandalwood powder fell from the sky, and it too sprinkled and bestrewed the Realized One’s body in honor of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[2250]="*Dibbānipi tūriyāni antalikkhe vajjanti tathāgatassa pūjāya.**And heavenly music played in the sky in honor of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[2251]="*Dibbānipi saṅgītāni antalikkhe vattanti tathāgatassa pūjāya.**And heavenly choirs sang in the sky in honor of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[2252]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**Then the Buddha pointed out to Ānanda what was happening, adding:*";
P_HTM[2253]="*“sabbaphāliphullā kho, ānanda, yamakasālā akālapupphehi.* **";
P_HTM[2254]="*Te tathāgatassa sarīraṃ okiranti ajjhokiranti abhippakiranti tathāgatassa pūjāya.* **";
P_HTM[2255]="*Dibbānipi mandāravapupphāni antalikkhā papatanti, tāni tathāgatassa sarīraṃ okiranti ajjhokiranti abhippakiranti tathāgatassa pūjāya.* **";
P_HTM[2256]="*Dibbānipi candanacuṇṇāni antalikkhā papatanti, tāni tathāgatassa sarīraṃ okiranti ajjhokiranti abhippakiranti tathāgatassa pūjāya.* **";
P_HTM[2257]="*Dibbānipi tūriyāni antalikkhe vajjanti tathāgatassa pūjāya.* **";
P_HTM[2258]="*Dibbānipi saṅgītāni antalikkhe vattanti tathāgatassa pūjāya.* **";
P_HTM[2259]="*Na kho, ānanda, ettāvatā tathāgato sakkato vā hoti garukato vā mānito vā pūjito vā apacito vā.**“That’s not how the Realized One is honored, respected, revered, venerated, and esteemed.*";
P_HTM[2260]="*Yo kho, ānanda, bhikkhu vā bhikkhunī vā upāsako vā upāsikā vā dhammānudhammappaṭipanno viharati sāmīcippaṭipanno anudhammacārī, so tathāgataṃ sakkaroti garuṃ karoti māneti pūjeti apaciyati, paramāya pūjāya.**Any monk or nun or male or female lay follower who practices in line with the teachings, practicing properly, living in line with the teachings—they honor, respect, revere, venerate, and esteem the Realized One with the highest honor.*";
P_HTM[2261]="*Tasmātihānanda, dhammānudhammappaṭipannā viharissāma sāmīcippaṭipannā anudhammacārinoti.**So Ānanda, you should train like this: ‘We shall practice in line with the teachings, practicing properly, living in line with the teaching.’*";
P_HTM[2262]="*Evañhi vo, ānanda, sikkhitabban”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2263]="*27. Upavāṇatthera**27. The Monk Upavāṇa*";
P_HTM[2264]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā upavāṇo bhagavato purato ṭhito hoti bhagavantaṃ bījayamāno.**Now at that time Venerable Upavāṇa was standing in front of the Buddha fanning him.*";
P_HTM[2265]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ upavāṇaṃ apasāresi:**Then the Buddha made him move,*";
P_HTM[2266]="*“apehi, bhikkhu, mā me purato aṭṭhāsī”ti.**“Move over, mendicant, don’t stand in front of me.”*";
P_HTM[2267]="*Atha kho āyasmato ānandassa etadahosi:**Ānanda thought,*";
P_HTM[2268]="*“ayaṃ kho āyasmā upavāṇo dīgharattaṃ bhagavato upaṭṭhāko santikāvacaro samīpacārī.**“This Venerable Upavāṇa has been the Buddha’s attendant for a long time, close to him, living in his presence.*";
P_HTM[2269]="*Atha ca pana bhagavā pacchime kāle āyasmantaṃ upavāṇaṃ apasāreti:**Yet in his final hour the Buddha makes him move, saying:*";
P_HTM[2270]="*‘apehi, bhikkhu, mā me purato aṭṭhāsī’ti.**‘Move over, mendicant, don’t stand in front of me.’*";
P_HTM[2271]="*Ko nu kho hetu, ko paccayo, yaṃ bhagavā āyasmantaṃ upavāṇaṃ apasāreti:**What is the cause, what is the reason for this?”*";
P_HTM[2272]="*‘apehi, bhikkhu, mā me purato aṭṭhāsī’”ti?* **";
P_HTM[2273]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Ānanda said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[2274]="*“ayaṃ, bhante, āyasmā upavāṇo dīgharattaṃ bhagavato upaṭṭhāko santikāvacaro samīpacārī.**“This Venerable Upavāṇa has been the Buddha’s attendant for a long time, close to him, living in his presence.*";
P_HTM[2275]="*Atha ca pana bhagavā pacchime kāle āyasmantaṃ upavāṇaṃ apasāreti:**Yet in his final hour the Buddha makes him move, saying:*";
P_HTM[2276]="*‘apehi, bhikkhu, mā me purato aṭṭhāsī’ti.**‘Move over, mendicant, don’t stand in front of me.’*";
P_HTM[2277]="*Ko nu kho, bhante, hetu, ko paccayo, yaṃ bhagavā āyasmantaṃ upavāṇaṃ apasāreti:**What is the cause, sir, what is the reason for this?”*";
P_HTM[2278]="*‘apehi, bhikkhu, mā me purato aṭṭhāsī’”ti?* **";
P_HTM[2279]="*“Yebhuyyena, ānanda, dasasu lokadhātūsu devatā sannipatitā tathāgataṃ dassanāya.**“Most of the deities from ten solar systems have gathered to see the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[2280]="*Yāvatā, ānanda, kusinārā upavattanaṃ mallānaṃ sālavanaṃ samantato dvādasa yojanāni, natthi so padeso vālaggakoṭinittudanamattopi mahesakkhāhi devatāhi apphuṭo.**For twelve leagues all around this sal grove there’s no spot, not even a fraction of a hair’s tip, that’s not crowded full of illustrious deities.*";
P_HTM[2281]="*Devatā, ānanda, ujjhāyanti:**The deities are complaining:*";
P_HTM[2282]="*‘dūrā ca vatamha āgatā tathāgataṃ dassanāya.**‘We’ve come such a long way to see the Realized One!*";
P_HTM[2283]="*Kadāci karahaci tathāgatā loke uppajjanti arahanto sammāsambuddhā.**Only rarely do Realized Ones arise in the world, perfected ones, fully awakened Buddhas.*";
P_HTM[2284]="*Ajjeva rattiyā pacchime yāme tathāgatassa parinibbānaṃ bhavissati.**This very day, in the last watch of the night, the Realized One will become fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[2285]="*Ayañca mahesakkho bhikkhu bhagavato purato ṭhito ovārento, na mayaṃ labhāma pacchime kāle tathāgataṃ dassanāyā’”ti.**And this illustrious mendicant is standing in front of the Buddha blocking the view. We won’t get to see the Realized One in his final hour!’”*";
P_HTM[2286]="*“Kathaṃbhūtā pana, bhante, bhagavā devatā manasikarotī”ti?**“But sir, what kind of deities are you thinking of?”*";
P_HTM[2287]="*“Santānanda, devatā ākāse pathavīsaññiniyo kese pakiriya kandanti, bāhā paggayha kandanti, chinnapātaṃ papatanti, āvaṭṭanti, vivaṭṭanti:**“There are, Ānanda, deities—both in the sky and on the earth—who are percipient of the earth. With hair disheveled and arms raised, they fall down like their feet were chopped off, rolling back and forth, lamenting:*";
P_HTM[2288]="*‘atikhippaṃ bhagavā parinibbāyissati, atikhippaṃ sugato parinibbāyissati, atikhippaṃ cakkhuṃ loke antaradhāyissatī’ti.**‘Too soon the Blessed One will become fully extinguished! Too soon the Holy One will become fully extinguished! Too soon the seer will vanish from the world!’*";
P_HTM[2289]="*Santānanda, devatā pathaviyaṃ pathavīsaññiniyo kese pakiriya kandanti, bāhā paggayha kandanti, chinnapātaṃ papatanti, āvaṭṭanti, vivaṭṭanti:* **";
P_HTM[2290]="*‘atikhippaṃ bhagavā parinibbāyissati, atikhippaṃ sugato parinibbāyissati, atikhippaṃ cakkhuṃ loke antaradhāyissatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2291]="*Yā pana tā devatā vītarāgā, tā satā sampajānā adhivāsenti:**But the deities who are free of desire endure, mindful and aware, thinking:*";
P_HTM[2292]="*‘aniccā saṅkhārā, taṃ kutettha labbhā’”ti.**‘Conditions are impermanent. How could it possibly be otherwise?’”*";
P_HTM[2293]="*28. Catusaṃvejanīyaṭhāna**28. The Four Inspiring Places*";
P_HTM[2294]="*“Pubbe, bhante, disāsu vassaṃvuṭṭhā bhikkhū āgacchanti tathāgataṃ dassanāya.**“Previously, sir, when mendicants had completed the rainy season residence in various districts they came to see the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[2295]="*Te mayaṃ labhāma manobhāvanīye bhikkhū dassanāya, labhāma payirupāsanāya.**We got to see the esteemed mendicants, and to pay homage to them.*";
P_HTM[2296]="*Bhagavato pana mayaṃ, bhante, accayena na labhissāma manobhāvanīye bhikkhū dassanāya, na labhissāma payirupāsanāyā”ti.**But when the Buddha has passed, we won’t get to see the esteemed mendicants or to pay homage to them.”*";
P_HTM[2297]="*“Cattārimāni, ānanda, saddhassa kulaputtassa dassanīyāni saṃvejanīyāni ṭhānāni.**“Ānanda, a faithful gentleman should go to see these four inspiring places.*";
P_HTM[2298]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[2299]="*‘Idha tathāgato jāto’ti, ānanda, saddhassa kulaputtassa dassanīyaṃ saṃvejanīyaṃ ṭhānaṃ.**Thinking: ‘Here the Realized One was born!’—that is an inspiring place.*";
P_HTM[2300]="*‘Idha tathāgato anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambuddho’ti, ānanda, saddhassa kulaputtassa dassanīyaṃ saṃvejanīyaṃ ṭhānaṃ.**Thinking: ‘Here the Realized One became awakened as a supreme fully awakened Buddha!’—that is an inspiring place.*";
P_HTM[2301]="*‘Idha tathāgatena anuttaraṃ dhammacakkaṃ pavattitan’ti, ānanda, saddhassa kulaputtassa dassanīyaṃ saṃvejanīyaṃ ṭhānaṃ.**Thinking: ‘Here the supreme Wheel of Dhamma was rolled forth by the Realized One!’—that is an inspiring place.*";
P_HTM[2302]="*‘Idha tathāgato anupādisesāya nibbānadhātuyā parinibbuto’ti, ānanda, saddhassa kulaputtassa dassanīyaṃ saṃvejanīyaṃ ṭhānaṃ.**Thinking: ‘Here the Realized One became fully extinguished through the natural principle of extinguishment, without anything left over!’—that is an inspiring place.*";
P_HTM[2303]="*Imāni kho, ānanda, cattāri saddhassa kulaputtassa dassanīyāni saṃvejanīyāni ṭhānāni.**These are the four inspiring places that a faithful gentleman should go to see.*";
P_HTM[2304]="*Āgamissanti kho, ānanda, saddhā bhikkhū bhikkhuniyo upāsakā upāsikāyo:**Faithful monks, nuns, laymen, and laywomen will come, and think:*";
P_HTM[2305]="*‘idha tathāgato jāto’tipi, ‘idha tathāgato anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambuddho’tipi, ‘idha tathāgatena anuttaraṃ dhammacakkaṃ pavattitan’tipi, ‘idha tathāgato anupādisesāya nibbānadhātuyā parinibbuto’tipi.**‘Here the Realized One was born!’ and ‘Here the Realized One became awakened as a supreme fully awakened Buddha!’ and ‘Here the supreme Wheel of Dhamma was rolled forth by the Realized One!’ and ‘Here the Realized One became fully extinguished through the natural principle of extinguishment, without anything left over!’*";
P_HTM[2306]="*Ye hi keci, ānanda, cetiyacārikaṃ āhiṇḍantā pasannacittā kālaṃ karissanti, sabbe te kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjissantī”ti.**Anyone who passes away while on pilgrimage to these shrines will, when their body breaks up, after death, be reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.”*";
P_HTM[2307]="*29. Ānandapucchākathā**29. Ānanda’s Questions*";
P_HTM[2308]="*“Kathaṃ mayaṃ, bhante, mātugāme paṭipajjāmā”ti?**“Sir, how do we proceed when it comes to females?”*";
P_HTM[2309]="*“Adassanaṃ, ānandā”ti.**“Without seeing, Ānanda.”*";
P_HTM[2310]="*“Dassane, bhagavā, sati kathaṃ paṭipajjitabban”ti?**“But when seeing, how to proceed?”*";
P_HTM[2311]="*“Anālāpo, ānandā”ti.**“Without getting into conversation, Ānanda.”*";
P_HTM[2312]="*“Ālapantena pana, bhante, kathaṃ paṭipajjitabban”ti?**“But when in a conversation, how to proceed?”*";
P_HTM[2313]="*“Sati, ānanda, upaṭṭhāpetabbā”ti.**“Be mindful, Ānanda.”*";
P_HTM[2314]="*“Kathaṃ mayaṃ, bhante, tathāgatassa sarīre paṭipajjāmā”ti?**“Sir, how do we proceed when it comes to the Realized One’s corpse?”*";
P_HTM[2315]="*“Abyāvaṭā tumhe, ānanda, hotha tathāgatassa sarīrapūjāya.**“Don’t get involved in the rites for venerating the Realized One’s corpse, Ānanda.*";
P_HTM[2316]="*Iṅgha tumhe, ānanda, sāratthe ghaṭatha anuyuñjatha, sāratthe appamattā ātāpino pahitattā viharatha.**Please, Ānanda, you must all strive and practice for your own goal! Meditate diligent, keen, and resolute for your own goal!*";
P_HTM[2317]="*Santānanda, khattiyapaṇḍitāpi brāhmaṇapaṇḍitāpi gahapatipaṇḍitāpi tathāgate abhippasannā, te tathāgatassa sarīrapūjaṃ karissantī”ti.**There are astute aristocrats, brahmins, and householders who are devoted to the Realized One. They will perform the rites for venerating the Realized One’s corpse.”*";
P_HTM[2318]="*“Kathaṃ pana, bhante, tathāgatassa sarīre paṭipajjitabban”ti?**“But sir, how to proceed when it comes to the Realized One’s corpse?”*";
P_HTM[2319]="*“Yathā kho, ānanda, rañño cakkavattissa sarīre paṭipajjanti, evaṃ tathāgatassa sarīre paṭipajjitabban”ti.**“Proceed in the same way as they do for the corpse of a wheel-turning monarch.”*";
P_HTM[2320]="*“Kathaṃ pana, bhante, rañño cakkavattissa sarīre paṭipajjantī”ti?**“But how do they proceed with a wheel-turning monarch’s corpse?”*";
P_HTM[2321]="*“Rañño, ānanda, cakkavattissa sarīraṃ ahatena vatthena veṭhenti, ahatena vatthena veṭhetvā vihatena kappāsena veṭhenti, vihatena kappāsena veṭhetvā ahatena vatthena veṭhenti.**“They wrap a wheel-turning monarch’s corpse with unworn cloth, then with uncarded cotton, then again with unworn cloth.*";
P_HTM[2322]="*Etenupāyena pañcahi yugasatehi rañño cakkavattissa sarīraṃ veṭhetvā āyasāya teladoṇiyā pakkhipitvā aññissā āyasāya doṇiyā paṭikujjitvā sabbagandhānaṃ citakaṃ karitvā rañño cakkavattissa sarīraṃ jhāpenti.**In this way they wrap the corpse with five hundred double-layers. Then they place it in an iron case filled with oil and close it up with another case. Then, having built a funeral pyre out of all kinds of fragrant substances, they cremate the corpse.*";
P_HTM[2323]="*Cātumahāpathe rañño cakkavattissa thūpaṃ karonti.**They build a monument for the wheel-turning monarch at the crossroads.*";
P_HTM[2324]="*Evaṃ kho, ānanda, rañño cakkavattissa sarīre paṭipajjanti.**That’s how they proceed with a wheel-turning monarch’s corpse.*";
P_HTM[2325]="*Yathā kho, ānanda, rañño cakkavattissa sarīre paṭipajjanti, evaṃ tathāgatassa sarīre paṭipajjitabbaṃ.**Proceed in the same way with the Realized One’s corpse.*";
P_HTM[2326]="*Cātumahāpathe tathāgatassa thūpo kātabbo.**A monument for the Realized One is to be built at the crossroads.*";
P_HTM[2327]="*Tattha ye mālaṃ vā gandhaṃ vā cuṇṇakaṃ vā āropessanti vā abhivādessanti vā cittaṃ vā pasādessanti tesaṃ taṃ bhavissati dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāya.**When someone there lifts up garlands or fragrance or powder, or bows, or inspires confidence in their heart, that will be for their lasting welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[2328]="*30. Thūpārahapuggala**30. Persons Worthy of Monument*";
P_HTM[2329]="*Cattārome, ānanda, thūpārahā.**Ānanda, these four are worthy of a monument.*";
P_HTM[2330]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[2331]="*Tathāgato arahaṃ sammāsambuddho thūpāraho, paccekasambuddho thūpāraho, tathāgatassa sāvako thūpāraho, rājā cakkavattī thūpārahoti.**A Realized One, a perfected one, a fully awakened Buddha; a Buddha awakened for themselves; a disciple of a Realized One; and a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[2332]="*Kiñcānanda, atthavasaṃ paṭicca tathāgato arahaṃ sammāsambuddho thūpāraho?**And for what reason is a Realized One worthy of a monument?*";
P_HTM[2333]="*‘Ayaṃ tassa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa thūpo’ti, ānanda, bahujanā cittaṃ pasādenti.**So that many people will inspire confidence in their hearts, thinking: ‘This is the monument for that Blessed One, perfected and fully awakened!’*";
P_HTM[2334]="*Te tattha cittaṃ pasādetvā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjanti.**And having done so, when their body breaks up, after death, they are reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2335]="*Idaṃ kho, ānanda, atthavasaṃ paṭicca tathāgato arahaṃ sammāsambuddho thūpāraho.**It is for this reason that a Realized One is worthy of a monument.*";
P_HTM[2336]="*Kiñcānanda, atthavasaṃ paṭicca paccekasambuddho thūpāraho?**And for what reason is a Buddha awakened for themselves worthy of a monument?*";
P_HTM[2337]="*‘Ayaṃ tassa bhagavato paccekasambuddhassa thūpo’ti, ānanda, bahujanā cittaṃ pasādenti.**So that many people will inspire confidence in their hearts, thinking: ‘This is the monument for that Buddha awakened for himself!’*";
P_HTM[2338]="*Te tattha cittaṃ pasādetvā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjanti.**And having done so, when their body breaks up, after death, they are reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2339]="*Idaṃ kho, ānanda, atthavasaṃ paṭicca paccekasambuddho thūpāraho.**It is for this reason that a Buddha awakened for himself is worthy of a monument.*";
P_HTM[2340]="*Kiñcānanda, atthavasaṃ paṭicca tathāgatassa sāvako thūpāraho?**And for what reason is a Realized One’s disciple worthy of a monument?*";
P_HTM[2341]="*‘Ayaṃ tassa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa sāvakassa thūpo’ti, ānanda, bahujanā cittaṃ pasādenti.**So that many people will inspire confidence in their hearts, thinking: ‘This is the monument for that Blessed One’s disciple!’*";
P_HTM[2342]="*Te tattha cittaṃ pasādetvā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjanti.**And having done so, when their body breaks up, after death, they are reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2343]="*Idaṃ kho, ānanda, atthavasaṃ paṭicca tathāgatassa sāvako thūpāraho.**It is for this reason that a Realized One’s disciple is worthy of a monument.*";
P_HTM[2344]="*Kiñcānanda, atthavasaṃ paṭicca rājā cakkavattī thūpāraho?**And for what reason is a wheel-turning monarch worthy of a monument?*";
P_HTM[2345]="*‘Ayaṃ tassa dhammikassa dhammarañño thūpo’ti, ānanda, bahujanā cittaṃ pasādenti.**So that many people will inspire confidence in their hearts, thinking: ‘This is the monument for that just and principled king!’*";
P_HTM[2346]="*Te tattha cittaṃ pasādetvā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjanti.**And having done so, when their body breaks up, after death, they are reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2347]="*Idaṃ kho, ānanda, atthavasaṃ paṭicca rājā cakkavattī thūpāraho.**It is for this reason that a wheel-turning monarch is worthy of a monument.*";
P_HTM[2348]="*Ime kho, ānanda, cattāro thūpārahā”ti.**These four are worthy of a monument.”*";
P_HTM[2349]="*31. Ānandaacchariyadhamma**31. Ānanda’s Incredible Qualities*";
P_HTM[2350]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando vihāraṃ pavisitvā kapisīsaṃ ālambitvā rodamāno aṭṭhāsi:**Then Venerable Ānanda entered a dwelling, and stood there leaning against the door-jamb and crying,*";
P_HTM[2351]="*“ahañca vatamhi sekho sakaraṇīyo, satthu ca me parinibbānaṃ bhavissati, yo mama anukampako”ti.**“Oh! I’m still only a trainee with work left to do; and my Teacher’s about to become fully extinguished, he who is so kind to me!”*";
P_HTM[2352]="*Atha kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then the Buddha said to the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[2353]="*“kahaṃ nu kho, bhikkhave, ānando”ti?**“Mendicants, where is Ānanda?”*";
P_HTM[2354]="*“Eso, bhante, āyasmā ānando vihāraṃ pavisitvā kapisīsaṃ ālambitvā rodamāno ṭhito:**“Sir, Ānanda has entered a dwelling, and stands there leaning against the door-jamb and crying:*";
P_HTM[2355]="*‘ahañca vatamhi sekho sakaraṇīyo, satthu ca me parinibbānaṃ bhavissati, yo mama anukampako’”ti.**‘Oh! I’m still only a trainee with work left to do; and my Teacher’s about to become fully extinguished, he who is so kind to me!’”*";
P_HTM[2356]="*Atha kho bhagavā aññataraṃ bhikkhuṃ āmantesi:**So the Buddha said to a certain monk,*";
P_HTM[2357]="*“ehi tvaṃ, bhikkhu, mama vacanena ānandaṃ āmantehi:**“Please, monk, in my name tell Ānanda that*";
P_HTM[2358]="*‘satthā taṃ, āvuso ānanda, āmantetī’”ti.**the teacher summons him.”*";
P_HTM[2359]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho so bhikkhu bhagavato paṭissutvā yenāyasmā ānando tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavoca:**“Yes, sir,” that monk replied. He went to Ānanda and said to him,*";
P_HTM[2360]="*“satthā taṃ, āvuso ānanda, āmantetī”ti.**“Reverend Ānanda, the teacher summons you.”*";
P_HTM[2361]="*“Evamāvuso”ti kho āyasmā ānando tassa bhikkhuno paṭissutvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**“Yes, reverend,” Ānanda replied. He went to the Buddha, bowed, and sat down to one side. The Buddha said to him:*";
P_HTM[2362]="*“alaṃ, ānanda, mā soci mā paridevi, nanu etaṃ, ānanda, mayā paṭikacceva akkhātaṃ:**“Enough, Ānanda! Do not grieve, do not lament. Did I not prepare for this when I explained that*";
P_HTM[2363]="*‘sabbeheva piyehi manāpehi nānābhāvo vinābhāvo aññathābhāvo’;**we must be parted and separated from all we hold dear and beloved?*";
P_HTM[2364]="*taṃ kutettha, ānanda, labbhā. Yaṃ taṃ jātaṃ bhūtaṃ saṅkhataṃ palokadhammaṃ, ‘taṃ vata tathāgatassāpi sarīraṃ mā palujjī’ti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**How could it possibly be so that what is born, created, conditioned, and liable to fall apart should not fall apart, even the Realized One’s body?*";
P_HTM[2365]="*Dīgharattaṃ kho te, ānanda, tathāgato paccupaṭṭhito mettena kāyakammena hitena sukhena advayena appamāṇena, mettena vacīkammena hitena sukhena advayena appamāṇena, mettena manokammena hitena sukhena advayena appamāṇena.**For a long time, Ānanda, you’ve treated the Realized One with deeds of body, speech, and mind that are loving, beneficial, pleasant, whole-hearted, and limitless.*";
P_HTM[2366]="*Katapuññosi tvaṃ, ānanda, padhānamanuyuñja, khippaṃ hohisi anāsavo”ti.**You have done good deeds, Ānanda. Devote yourself to meditation, and you will soon be free of defilements.”*";
P_HTM[2367]="*Atha kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then the Buddha said to the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[2368]="*“yepi te, bhikkhave, ahesuṃ atītamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā, tesampi bhagavantānaṃ etapparamāyeva upaṭṭhākā ahesuṃ, seyyathāpi mayhaṃ ānando.**“The Buddhas of the past or the future have attendants who are no better than Ānanda is for me.*";
P_HTM[2369]="*Yepi te, bhikkhave, bhavissanti anāgatamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā, tesampi bhagavantānaṃ etapparamāyeva upaṭṭhākā bhavissanti, seyyathāpi mayhaṃ ānando.* **";
P_HTM[2370]="*Paṇḍito, bhikkhave, ānando;**Ānanda is astute,*";
P_HTM[2371]="*medhāvī, bhikkhave, ānando.**he is intelligent.*";
P_HTM[2372]="*Jānāti ‘ayaṃ kālo tathāgataṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ bhikkhūnaṃ, ayaṃ kālo bhikkhunīnaṃ, ayaṃ kālo upāsakānaṃ, ayaṃ kālo upāsikānaṃ, ayaṃ kālo rañño rājamahāmattānaṃ titthiyānaṃ titthiyasāvakānan’ti.**He knows the time for monks, nuns, laymen, laywomen, king’s ministers, religious founders, and the disciples of religious founders to visit the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[2373]="*Cattārome, bhikkhave, acchariyā abbhutā dhammā ānande.**There are these four incredible and amazing things about Ānanda.*";
P_HTM[2374]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[2375]="*Sace, bhikkhave, bhikkhuparisā ānandaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamati, dassanena sā attamanā hoti.**If an assembly of monks goes to see Ānanda, they’re uplifted by seeing him*";
P_HTM[2376]="*Tatra ce ānando dhammaṃ bhāsati, bhāsitenapi sā attamanā hoti.**and uplifted by hearing him speak.*";
P_HTM[2377]="*Atittāva, bhikkhave, bhikkhuparisā hoti, atha kho ānando tuṇhī hoti.**And when he falls silent, they’ve never had enough.*";
P_HTM[2378]="*Sace, bhikkhave, bhikkhunīparisā ānandaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamati, dassanena sā attamanā hoti.**If an assembly of nuns …*";
P_HTM[2379]="*Tatra ce ānando dhammaṃ bhāsati, bhāsitenapi sā attamanā hoti.* **";
P_HTM[2380]="*Atittāva, bhikkhave, bhikkhunīparisā hoti, atha kho ānando tuṇhī hoti.* **";
P_HTM[2381]="*Sace, bhikkhave, upāsakaparisā ānandaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamati, dassanena sā attamanā hoti.**laymen …*";
P_HTM[2382]="*Tatra ce ānando dhammaṃ bhāsati, bhāsitenapi sā attamanā hoti.* **";
P_HTM[2383]="*Atittāva, bhikkhave, upāsakaparisā hoti, atha kho ānando tuṇhī hoti.* **";
P_HTM[2384]="*Sace, bhikkhave, upāsikāparisā ānandaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamati, dassanena sā attamanā hoti.**or laywomen goes to see Ānanda, they’re uplifted by seeing him*";
P_HTM[2385]="*Tatra ce ānando dhammaṃ bhāsati, bhāsitenapi sā attamanā hoti.**and uplifted by hearing him speak.*";
P_HTM[2386]="*Atittāva, bhikkhave, upāsikāparisā hoti, atha kho ānando tuṇhī hoti.**And when he falls silent, they’ve never had enough.*";
P_HTM[2387]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro acchariyā abbhutā dhammā ānande.**These are the four incredible and amazing things about Ānanda.*";
P_HTM[2388]="*Cattārome, bhikkhave, acchariyā abbhutā dhammā raññe cakkavattimhi.**There are these four incredible and amazing things about a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[2389]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[2390]="*Sace, bhikkhave, khattiyaparisā rājānaṃ cakkavattiṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamati, dassanena sā attamanā hoti.**If an assembly of aristocrats goes to see a wheel-turning monarch, they’re uplifted by seeing him*";
P_HTM[2391]="*Tatra ce rājā cakkavattī bhāsati, bhāsitenapi sā attamanā hoti.**and uplifted by hearing him speak.*";
P_HTM[2392]="*Atittāva, bhikkhave, khattiyaparisā hoti. Atha kho rājā cakkavattī tuṇhī hoti.**And when he falls silent, they’ve never had enough.*";
P_HTM[2393]="*Sace bhikkhave, brāhmaṇaparisā … pe …**If an assembly of brahmins …*";
P_HTM[2394]="*gahapatiparisā … pe …**householders …*";
P_HTM[2395]="*samaṇaparisā rājānaṃ cakkavattiṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamati, dassanena sā attamanā hoti.**or ascetics goes to see a wheel-turning monarch, they’re uplifted by seeing him*";
P_HTM[2396]="*Tatra ce rājā cakkavattī bhāsati, bhāsitenapi sā attamanā hoti.**and uplifted by hearing him speak.*";
P_HTM[2397]="*Atittāva, bhikkhave, samaṇaparisā hoti. Atha kho rājā cakkavattī tuṇhī hoti.**And when he falls silent, they’ve never had enough.*";
P_HTM[2398]="*Evameva kho, bhikkhave, cattārome acchariyā abbhutā dhammā ānande.**In the same way, there are those four incredible and amazing things about Ānanda.”*";
P_HTM[2399]="*Sace, bhikkhave, bhikkhuparisā ānandaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamati, dassanena sā attamanā hoti.* **";
P_HTM[2400]="*Tatra ce ānando dhammaṃ bhāsati, bhāsitenapi sā attamanā hoti.* **";
P_HTM[2401]="*Atittāva, bhikkhave, bhikkhuparisā hoti.* **";
P_HTM[2402]="*Atha kho ānando tuṇhī hoti.* **";
P_HTM[2403]="*Sace, bhikkhave bhikkhunīparisā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2404]="*upāsakaparisā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2405]="*upāsikāparisā ānandaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamati, dassanena sā attamanā hoti.* **";
P_HTM[2406]="*Tatra ce ānando dhammaṃ bhāsati, bhāsitenapi sā attamanā hoti.* **";
P_HTM[2407]="*Atittāva, bhikkhave, upāsikāparisā hoti.* **";
P_HTM[2408]="*Atha kho ānando tuṇhī hoti.* **";
P_HTM[2409]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, cattāro acchariyā abbhutā dhammā ānande”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2410]="*32. Mahāsudassanasuttadesanā**32. Teaching the Discourse on Mahāsudassana*";
P_HTM[2411]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Venerable Ānanda said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[2412]="*“mā, bhante, bhagavā imasmiṃ khuddakanagarake ujjaṅgalanagarake sākhānagarake parinibbāyi.**“Sir, please don’t become fully extinguished in this little hamlet, this jungle hamlet, this branch hamlet.*";
P_HTM[2413]="*Santi, bhante, aññāni mahānagarāni, seyyathidaṃ—**There are other great cities such as*";
P_HTM[2414]="*campā rājagahaṃ sāvatthī sāketaṃ kosambī bārāṇasī;**Campā, Rājagaha, Sāvatthī, Sāketa, Kosambī, and Benares.*";
P_HTM[2415]="*ettha bhagavā parinibbāyatu.**Let the Buddha become fully extinguished there.*";
P_HTM[2416]="*Ettha bahū khattiyamahāsālā, brāhmaṇamahāsālā gahapatimahāsālā tathāgate abhippasannā.**There are many well-to-do aristocrats, brahmins, and householders there who are devoted to the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2417]="*Te tathāgatassa sarīrapūjaṃ karissantī”ti**They will perform the rites of venerating the Realized One’s corpse.”*";
P_HTM[2418]="*“mā hevaṃ, ānanda, avaca, mā hevaṃ, ānanda, avaca:**“Don’t say that Ānanda! Don’t say that*";
P_HTM[2419]="*‘khuddakanagarakaṃ ujjaṅgalanagarakaṃ sākhānagarakan’ti.**this is a little hamlet, a jungle hamlet, a branch hamlet.*";
P_HTM[2420]="*Bhūtapubbaṃ, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano nāma ahosi cakkavattī dhammiko dhammarājā cāturanto vijitāvī janapadatthāvariyappatto sattaratanasamannāgato.**Once upon a time there was a king named Mahāsudassana who was a wheel-turning monarch, a just and principled king. His dominion extended to all four sides, he achieved stability in the country, and he possessed the seven treasures.*";
P_HTM[2421]="*Rañño, ānanda, mahāsudassanassa ayaṃ kusinārā kusāvatī nāma rājadhānī ahosi.**His capital was this Kusinārā, which at the time was named Kusāvatī.*";
P_HTM[2422]="*puratthimena ca pacchimena ca dvādasayojanāni āyāmena; uttarena ca dakkhiṇena ca sattayojanāni vitthārena.**It stretched for twelve leagues from east to west, and seven leagues from north to south.*";
P_HTM[2423]="*Kusāvatī, ānanda, rājadhānī iddhā ceva ahosi phītā ca bahujanā ca ākiṇṇamanussā ca subhikkhā ca.**The royal capital of Kusāvatī was successful, prosperous, populous, full of people, with plenty of food.*";
P_HTM[2424]="*Seyyathāpi, ānanda, devānaṃ āḷakamandā nāma rājadhānī iddhā ceva hoti phītā ca bahujanā ca ākiṇṇayakkhā ca subhikkhā ca;**It was just like Āḷakamandā, the royal capital of the gods, which is successful, prosperous, populous, full of spirits, with plenty of food.*";
P_HTM[2425]="*evameva kho, ānanda, kusāvatī rājadhānī iddhā ceva ahosi phītā ca bahujanā ca ākiṇṇamanussā ca subhikkhā ca.* **";
P_HTM[2426]="*Kusāvatī, ānanda, rājadhānī dasahi saddehi avivittā ahosi divā ceva rattiñca, seyyathidaṃ—**Kusāvatī was never free of ten sounds by day or night, namely:*";
P_HTM[2427]="*hatthisaddena assasaddena rathasaddena bherisaddena mudiṅgasaddena vīṇāsaddena gītasaddena saṅkhasaddena sammasaddena pāṇitāḷasaddena ‘asnātha pivatha khādathā’ti dasamena saddena.**the sound of elephants, horses, chariots, drums, clay drums, arched harps, singing, horns, gongs, and handbells; and the cry: ‘Eat, drink, be merry!’ as the tenth.*";
P_HTM[2428]="*Gaccha tvaṃ, ānanda, kusināraṃ pavisitvā kosinārakānaṃ mallānaṃ ārocehi:**Go, Ānanda, into Kusinārā and inform the Mallas:*";
P_HTM[2429]="*‘ajja kho, vāseṭṭhā, rattiyā pacchime yāme tathāgatassa parinibbānaṃ bhavissati.**‘This very day, Vāseṭṭhas, in the last watch of the night, the Realized One will become fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[2430]="*Abhikkamatha, vāseṭṭhā, abhikkamatha, vāseṭṭhā.**Come forth, Vāseṭṭhas! Come forth, Vāseṭṭhas!*";
P_HTM[2431]="*Mā pacchā vippaṭisārino ahuvattha—**Don’t regret it later, thinking:*";
P_HTM[2432]="*amhākañca no gāmakkhette tathāgatassa parinibbānaṃ ahosi, na mayaṃ labhimhā pacchime kāle tathāgataṃ dassanāyā’”ti.**‘The Realized One became fully extinguished in our own village district, but we didn’t get a chance to see him in his final hour.’”*";
P_HTM[2433]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paṭissutvā nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya attadutiyo kusināraṃ pāvisi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Ānanda. Then he robed up and, taking his bowl and robe, entered Kusinārā with a companion.*";
P_HTM[2434]="*33. Mallānaṃvandanā**33. The Mallas Pay Homage*";
P_HTM[2435]="*Tena kho pana samayena kosinārakā mallā sandhāgāre sannipatitā honti kenacideva karaṇīyena.**Now at that time the Mallas of Kusinārā were sitting together at the meeting hall on some business.*";
P_HTM[2436]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando yena kosinārakānaṃ mallānaṃ sandhāgāraṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā kosinārakānaṃ mallānaṃ ārocesi:**Ānanda went up to them, and announced:*";
P_HTM[2437]="*“ajja kho, vāseṭṭhā, rattiyā pacchime yāme tathāgatassa parinibbānaṃ bhavissati.**“This very day, Vāseṭṭhas, in the last watch of the night, the Realized One will become fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[2438]="*Abhikkamatha, vāseṭṭhā, abhikkamatha, vāseṭṭhā.**Come forth, Vāseṭṭhas! Come forth, Vāseṭṭhas!*";
P_HTM[2439]="*Mā pacchā vippaṭisārino ahuvattha:**Don’t regret it later, thinking:*";
P_HTM[2440]="*‘amhākañca no gāmakkhette tathāgatassa parinibbānaṃ ahosi, na mayaṃ labhimhā pacchime kāle tathāgataṃ dassanāyā’”ti.**‘The Realized One became fully extinguished in our own village district, but we didn’t get a chance to see him in his final hour.’”*";
P_HTM[2441]="*Idamāyasmato ānandassa vacanaṃ sutvā mallā ca mallaputtā ca mallasuṇisā ca mallapajāpatiyo ca aghāvino dummanā cetodukkhasamappitā appekacce kese pakiriya kandanti, bāhā paggayha kandanti, chinnapātaṃ papatanti, āvaṭṭanti vivaṭṭanti:**When they heard what Ānanda had to say, the Mallas, their sons, daughters-in-law, and wives became distraught, saddened, and grief-stricken. And some, with hair disheveled and arms raised, falling down like their feet were chopped off, rolling back and forth, lamented,*";
P_HTM[2442]="*“atikhippaṃ bhagavā parinibbāyissati, atikhippaṃ sugato parinibbāyissati, atikhippaṃ cakkhuṃ loke antaradhāyissatī”ti.**“Too soon the Blessed One will become fully extinguished! Too soon the Holy One will become fully extinguished! Too soon the seer will vanish from the world!”*";
P_HTM[2443]="*Atha kho mallā ca mallaputtā ca mallasuṇisā ca mallapajāpatiyo ca aghāvino dummanā cetodukkhasamappitā yena upavattanaṃ mallānaṃ sālavanaṃ yenāyasmā ānando tenupasaṅkamiṃsu.**Then the Mallas, their sons, daughters-in-law, and wives, distraught, saddened, and grief-stricken went to the Mallian sal grove at Upavattana and approached Ānanda.*";
P_HTM[2444]="*Atha kho āyasmato ānandassa etadahosi:**Then Ānanda thought,*";
P_HTM[2445]="*“sace kho ahaṃ kosinārake malle ekamekaṃ bhagavantaṃ vandāpessāmi, avandito bhagavā kosinārakehi mallehi bhavissati, athāyaṃ ratti vibhāyissati.**“If I have the Mallas pay homage to the Buddha one by one, they won’t be finished before first light.*";
P_HTM[2446]="*Yannūnāhaṃ kosinārake malle kulaparivattaso kulaparivattaso ṭhapetvā bhagavantaṃ vandāpeyyaṃ:**I’d better separate them family by family and then have them pay homage, saying:*";
P_HTM[2447]="*‘itthannāmo, bhante, mallo saputto sabhariyo sapariso sāmacco bhagavato pāde sirasā vandatī’”ti.**‘Sir, the Malla named so-and-so with children, wives, retinue, and ministers bows with his head at your feet.’”*";
P_HTM[2448]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando kosinārake malle kulaparivattaso kulaparivattaso ṭhapetvā bhagavantaṃ vandāpesi:**And so that’s what he did.*";
P_HTM[2449]="*“itthannāmo, bhante, mallo saputto sabhariyo sapariso sāmacco bhagavato pāde sirasā vandatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2450]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando etena upāyena paṭhameneva yāmena kosinārake malle bhagavantaṃ vandāpesi.**So by this means Ānanda got the Mallas to finish paying homage to the Buddha in the first watch of the night.*";
P_HTM[2451]="*34. Subhaddaparibbājakavatthu**34. On Subhadda the Wanderer*";
P_HTM[2452]="*Tena kho pana samayena subhaddo nāma paribbājako kusinārāyaṃ paṭivasati.**Now at that time a wanderer named Subhadda was residing near Kusinārā.*";
P_HTM[2453]="*Assosi kho subhaddo paribbājako:**He heard that*";
P_HTM[2454]="*“ajja kira rattiyā pacchime yāme samaṇassa gotamassa parinibbānaṃ bhavissatī”ti.**on that very day, in the last watch of the night, the ascetic Gotama would become fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[2455]="*Atha kho subhaddassa paribbājakassa etadahosi:**He thought:*";
P_HTM[2456]="*“sutaṃ kho pana metaṃ paribbājakānaṃ vuḍḍhānaṃ mahallakānaṃ ācariyapācariyānaṃ bhāsamānānaṃ:**“I have heard that brahmins of the past who were elderly and senior, the teachers of teachers, said:*";
P_HTM[2457]="*‘kadāci karahaci tathāgatā loke uppajjanti arahanto sammāsambuddhā’ti.**‘Only rarely do Realized Ones arise in the world, perfected ones, fully awakened Buddhas.’*";
P_HTM[2458]="*Ajjeva rattiyā pacchime yāme samaṇassa gotamassa parinibbānaṃ bhavissati.**And this very day, in the last watch of the night, the ascetic Gotama will become fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[2459]="*Atthi ca me ayaṃ kaṅkhādhammo uppanno,**This state of uncertainty has come up in me.*";
P_HTM[2460]="*evaṃ pasanno ahaṃ samaṇe gotame, ‘pahoti me samaṇo gotamo tathā dhammaṃ desetuṃ, yathāhaṃ imaṃ kaṅkhādhammaṃ pajaheyyan’”ti.**I am quite confident that the Buddha is capable of teaching me so that I can give up this state of uncertainty.”*";
P_HTM[2461]="*Atha kho subhaddo paribbājako yena upavattanaṃ mallānaṃ sālavanaṃ, yenāyasmā ānando tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavoca:**Then Subhadda went to the Mallian sal grove at Upavattana, approached Ānanda, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[2462]="*“sutaṃ metaṃ, bho ānanda, paribbājakānaṃ vuḍḍhānaṃ mahallakānaṃ ācariyapācariyānaṃ bhāsamānānaṃ:**“Master Ānanda, I have heard that brahmins of the past who were elderly and senior, the teachers of teachers, said:*";
P_HTM[2463]="*‘kadāci karahaci tathāgatā loke uppajjanti arahanto sammāsambuddhā’ti.**‘Only rarely do Realized Ones arise in the world, perfected ones, fully awakened Buddhas.’*";
P_HTM[2464]="*Ajjeva rattiyā pacchime yāme samaṇassa gotamassa parinibbānaṃ bhavissati.**And this very day, in the last watch of the night, the ascetic Gotama will become fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[2465]="*Atthi ca me ayaṃ kaṅkhādhammo uppanno—**This state of uncertainty has come up in me.*";
P_HTM[2466]="*evaṃ pasanno ahaṃ samaṇe gotame ‘pahoti me samaṇo gotamo tathā dhammaṃ desetuṃ, yathāhaṃ imaṃ kaṅkhādhammaṃ pajaheyyan’ti.**I am quite confident that the Buddha is capable of teaching me so that I can give up this state of uncertainty.*";
P_HTM[2467]="*Sādhāhaṃ, bho ānanda, labheyyaṃ samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāyā”ti.**Master Ānanda, please let me see the ascetic Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[2468]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā ānando subhaddaṃ paribbājakaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, Ānanda said,*";
P_HTM[2469]="*“alaṃ, āvuso subhadda, mā tathāgataṃ viheṭhesi, kilanto bhagavā”ti.**“Enough, Reverend Subhadda, do not trouble the Realized One. He is tired.”*";
P_HTM[2470]="*Dutiyampi kho subhaddo paribbājako … pe …**For a second time,*";
P_HTM[2471]="*tatiyampi kho subhaddo paribbājako āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavoca:**and a third time, Subhadda asked Ānanda, and a third time Ānanda refused.*";
P_HTM[2472]="*“sutaṃ metaṃ, bho ānanda, paribbājakānaṃ vuḍḍhānaṃ mahallakānaṃ ācariyapācariyānaṃ bhāsamānānaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[2473]="*‘kadāci karahaci tathāgatā loke uppajjanti arahanto sammāsambuddhā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2474]="*Ajjeva rattiyā pacchime yāme samaṇassa gotamassa parinibbānaṃ bhavissati.* **";
P_HTM[2475]="*Atthi ca me ayaṃ kaṅkhādhammo uppanno—* **";
P_HTM[2476]="*evaṃ pasanno ahaṃ samaṇe gotame, ‘pahoti me samaṇo gotamo tathā dhammaṃ desetuṃ, yathāhaṃ imaṃ kaṅkhādhammaṃ pajaheyyan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2477]="*Sādhāhaṃ, bho ānanda, labheyyaṃ samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2478]="*Tatiyampi kho āyasmā ānando subhaddaṃ paribbājakaṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[2479]="*“alaṃ, āvuso subhadda, mā tathāgataṃ viheṭhesi, kilanto bhagavā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2480]="*Assosi kho bhagavā āyasmato ānandassa subhaddena paribbājakena saddhiṃ imaṃ kathāsallāpaṃ.**The Buddha heard that discussion between Ānanda and Subhadda.*";
P_HTM[2481]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**He said to Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[2482]="*“alaṃ, ānanda, mā subhaddaṃ vāresi, labhataṃ, ānanda, subhaddo tathāgataṃ dassanāya.**“Enough, Ānanda, don’t obstruct Subhadda; let him see the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[2483]="*Yaṃ kiñci maṃ subhaddo pucchissati, sabbaṃ taṃ aññāpekkhova pucchissati, no vihesāpekkho.**For whatever he asks me, he will only be looking for understanding, not trouble.*";
P_HTM[2484]="*Yañcassāhaṃ puṭṭho byākarissāmi, taṃ khippameva ājānissatī”ti.**And he will quickly understand any answer I give to his question.”*";
P_HTM[2485]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando subhaddaṃ paribbājakaṃ etadavoca:**So Ānanda said to the wanderer Subhadda,*";
P_HTM[2486]="*“gacchāvuso subhadda, karoti te bhagavā okāsan”ti.**“Go, Reverend Subhadda, the Buddha is taking the time for you.”*";
P_HTM[2487]="*Atha kho subhaddo paribbājako yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodi, sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho subhaddo paribbājako bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then the wanderer Subhadda went up to the Buddha, and exchanged greetings with him. When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[2488]="*“yeme, bho gotama, samaṇabrāhmaṇā saṅghino gaṇino gaṇācariyā ñātā yasassino titthakarā sādhusammatā bahujanassa,**“Master Gotama, there are those ascetics and brahmins who lead an order and a community, and teach a community. They’re well-known and famous religious founders, regarded as holy by many people.*";
P_HTM[2489]="*seyyathidaṃ—pūraṇo kassapo, makkhali gosālo, ajito kesakambalo, pakudho kaccāyano, sañcayo belaṭṭhaputto, nigaṇṭho nāṭaputto,**Namely: Pūraṇa Kassapa, Makkhali Gosāla, Nigaṇṭha Nāṭaputta, Sañjaya Belaṭṭhiputta, Pakudha Kaccāyana, and Ajita Kesakambala.*";
P_HTM[2490]="*sabbete sakāya paṭiññāya abbhaññiṃsu, sabbeva na abbhaññiṃsu, udāhu ekacce abbhaññiṃsu, ekacce na abbhaññiṃsū”ti?**According to their own claims, did all of them have direct knowledge, or none of them, or only some?”*";
P_HTM[2491]="*“Alaṃ, subhadda, tiṭṭhatetaṃ:**“Enough, Subhadda, let that be.*";
P_HTM[2492]="*‘sabbete sakāya paṭiññāya abbhaññiṃsu, sabbeva na abbhaññiṃsu, udāhu ekacce abbhaññiṃsu, ekacce na abbhaññiṃsū’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2493]="*Dhammaṃ te, subhadda, desessāmi;**I shall teach you the Dhamma.*";
P_HTM[2494]="*taṃ suṇāhi sādhukaṃ manasikarohi, bhāsissāmī”ti.**Listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[2495]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho subhaddo paribbājako bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Subhadda replied.*";
P_HTM[2496]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[2497]="*“Yasmiṃ kho, subhadda, dhammavinaye ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo na upalabbhati, samaṇopi tattha na upalabbhati. Dutiyopi tattha samaṇo na upalabbhati. Tatiyopi tattha samaṇo na upalabbhati. Catutthopi tattha samaṇo na upalabbhati.**“Subhadda, in whatever teaching and training the noble eightfold path is not found, there is no true ascetic found, no second ascetic, no third ascetic, and no fourth ascetic.*";
P_HTM[2498]="*Yasmiñca kho, subhadda, dhammavinaye ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo upalabbhati, samaṇopi tattha upalabbhati, dutiyopi tattha samaṇo upalabbhati, tatiyopi tattha samaṇo upalabbhati, catutthopi tattha samaṇo upalabbhati.**In whatever teaching and training the noble eightfold path is found, there is a true ascetic found, a second ascetic, a third ascetic, and a fourth ascetic.*";
P_HTM[2499]="*Imasmiṃ kho, subhadda, dhammavinaye ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo upalabbhati, idheva, subhadda, samaṇo, idha dutiyo samaṇo, idha tatiyo samaṇo, idha catuttho samaṇo, suññā parappavādā samaṇebhi aññehi.**In this teaching and training the noble eightfold path is found. Only here is there a true ascetic, here a second ascetic, here a third ascetic, and here a fourth ascetic. Other sects are empty of ascetics.*";
P_HTM[2500]="*Ime ca, subhadda, bhikkhū sammā vihareyyuṃ, asuñño loko arahantehi assāti.**Were these mendicants to practice well, the world would not be empty of perfected ones.*";
P_HTM[2501]="*Ekūnatiṃso vayasā subhadda,**I was twenty-nine years of age, Subaddha,*";
P_HTM[2502]="*Yaṃ pabbajiṃ kiṅkusalānuesī;**when I went forth to discover what is skilful.*";
P_HTM[2503]="*Vassāni paññāsa samādhikāni,**It’s been over fifty years*";
P_HTM[2504]="*Yato ahaṃ pabbajito subhadda;**since I went forth.*";
P_HTM[2505]="*Ñāyassa dhammassa padesavattī,**I am the one who points out the proper teaching:*";
P_HTM[2506]="*Ito bahiddhā samaṇopi natthi.**Outside of here there is no true ascetic.*";
P_HTM[2507]="*Dutiyopi samaṇo natthi.* **";
P_HTM[2508]="*Tatiyopi samaṇo natthi.* **";
P_HTM[2509]="*Catutthopi samaṇo natthi.* **";
P_HTM[2510]="*Suññā parappavādā samaṇebhi aññehi.* **";
P_HTM[2511]="*Ime ca, subhadda, bhikkhū sammā vihareyyuṃ, asuñño loko arahantehi assā”ti.**Were these mendicants to practice well, the world would not be empty of perfected ones.”*";
P_HTM[2512]="*Evaṃ vutte, subhaddo paribbājako bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, Subhadda said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[2513]="*“abhikkantaṃ, bhante, abhikkantaṃ, bhante.**“Excellent, sir! Excellent!*";
P_HTM[2514]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante, nikkujjitaṃ vā ukkujjeyya, paṭicchannaṃ vā vivareyya, mūḷhassa vā maggaṃ ācikkheyya, andhakāre vā telapajjotaṃ dhāreyya: ‘cakkhumanto rūpāni dakkhantī’ti; evamevaṃ bhagavatā anekapariyāyena dhammo pakāsito.**As if he were righting the overturned, or revealing the hidden, or pointing out the path to the lost, or lighting a lamp in the dark so people with good eyes can see what’s there, the Buddha has made the teaching clear in many ways.*";
P_HTM[2515]="*Esāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāmi dhammañca bhikkhusaṅghañca.**I go for refuge to the Buddha, to the teaching, and to the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[2516]="*Labheyyāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato santike pabbajjaṃ, labheyyaṃ upasampadan”ti.**Sir, may I receive the going forth, the ordination in the Buddha’s presence?”*";
P_HTM[2517]="*“Yo kho, subhadda, aññatitthiyapubbo imasmiṃ dhammavinaye ākaṅkhati pabbajjaṃ, ākaṅkhati upasampadaṃ, so cattāro māse parivasati. Catunnaṃ māsānaṃ accayena āraddhacittā bhikkhū pabbājenti upasampādenti bhikkhubhāvāya.**“Subhadda, if someone formerly ordained in another sect wishes to take the going forth, the ordination in this teaching and training, they must spend four months on probation. When four months have passed, if the mendicants are satisfied, they’ll give the going forth, the ordination into monkhood.*";
P_HTM[2518]="*Api ca mettha puggalavemattatā viditā”ti.**However, I have recognized individual differences in this matter.”*";
P_HTM[2519]="*“Sace, bhante, aññatitthiyapubbā imasmiṃ dhammavinaye ākaṅkhantā pabbajjaṃ ākaṅkhantā upasampadaṃ cattāro māse parivasanti, catunnaṃ māsānaṃ accayena āraddhacittā bhikkhū pabbājenti upasampādenti bhikkhubhāvāya. Ahaṃ cattāri vassāni parivasissāmi, catunnaṃ vassānaṃ accayena āraddhacittā bhikkhū pabbājentu upasampādentu bhikkhubhāvāyā”ti.**“Sir, if four months probation are required in such a case, I’ll spend four years on probation. When four years have passed, if the mendicants are satisfied, let them give me the going forth, the ordination into monkhood.”*";
P_HTM[2520]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**Then the Buddha said to Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[2521]="*“tenahānanda, subhaddaṃ pabbājehī”ti.**“Well then, Ānanda, give Subhadda the going forth.”*";
P_HTM[2522]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Ānanda replied.*";
P_HTM[2523]="*Atha kho subhaddo paribbājako āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavoca:**Then Subhadda said to Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[2524]="*“lābhā vo, āvuso ānanda; suladdhaṃ vo, āvuso ānanda,**“You’re so fortunate, Reverand Ānanda, so very fortunate,*";
P_HTM[2525]="*ye ettha satthu sammukhā antevāsikābhisekena abhisittā”ti.**to be anointed here in the Teacher’s presence as his pupil!”*";
P_HTM[2526]="*Alattha kho subhaddo paribbājako bhagavato santike pabbajjaṃ, alattha upasampadaṃ.**And the wanderer Subhadda received the going forth, the ordination in the Buddha’s presence.*";
P_HTM[2527]="*Acirūpasampanno kho panāyasmā subhaddo eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto nacirasseva—yassatthāya kulaputtā sammadeva agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajanti—tadanuttaraṃ brahmacariyapariyosānaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja vihāsi.**Not long after his ordination, Venerable Subhadda, living alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute, soon realized the supreme end of the spiritual path in this very life. He lived having achieved with his own insight the goal for which gentlemen rightly go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[2528]="*“Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā”ti abbhaññāsi.**He understood: “Rebirth is ended; the spiritual journey has been completed; what had to be done has been done; there is no return to any state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[2529]="*Aññataro kho panāyasmā subhaddo arahataṃ ahosi.**And Venerable Subhadda became one of the perfected.*";
P_HTM[2530]="*So bhagavato pacchimo sakkhisāvako ahosīti.**He was the last personal disciple of the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2531]="*Pañcamo bhāṇavāro.* **";
P_HTM[2532]="*35. Tathāgatapacchimavācā**35. The Buddha’s Last Words*";
P_HTM[2533]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**Then the Buddha addressed Venerable Ānanda:*";
P_HTM[2534]="*“siyā kho panānanda, tumhākaṃ evamassa:**“Now, Ānanda, some of you might think:*";
P_HTM[2535]="*‘atītasatthukaṃ pāvacanaṃ, natthi no satthā’ti.**‘The teacher’s dispensation has passed. Now we have no Teacher.’*";
P_HTM[2536]="*Na kho panetaṃ, ānanda, evaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ.**But you should not see it like this.*";
P_HTM[2537]="*Yo vo, ānanda, mayā dhammo ca vinayo ca desito paññatto, so vo mamaccayena satthā.**The teaching and training that I have taught and pointed out for you shall be your Teacher after my passing.*";
P_HTM[2538]="*Yathā kho panānanda, etarahi bhikkhū aññamaññaṃ āvusovādena samudācaranti, na kho mamaccayena evaṃ samudācaritabbaṃ.**After my passing, mendicants ought not address each other as ‘reverend’, as they do today.*";
P_HTM[2539]="*Theratarena, ānanda, bhikkhunā navakataro bhikkhu nāmena vā gottena vā āvusovādena vā samudācaritabbo.**A more senior mendicant ought to address a more junior mendicant by name or clan, or by saying ‘reverend’.*";
P_HTM[2540]="*Navakatarena bhikkhunā therataro bhikkhu ‘bhante’ti vā ‘āyasmā’ti vā samudācaritabbo.**A more junior mendicant ought to address a more senior mendicant using ‘sir’ or ‘venerable’.*";
P_HTM[2541]="*Ākaṅkhamāno, ānanda, saṃgho mamaccayena khuddānukhuddakāni sikkhāpadāni samūhanatu.**If it wishes, after my passing the Saṅgha may abolish the lesser and minor training rules.*";
P_HTM[2542]="*Channassa, ānanda, bhikkhuno mamaccayena brahmadaṇḍo dātabbo”ti.**After my passing, give the prime punishment to the mendicant Channa.”*";
P_HTM[2543]="*“Katamo pana, bhante, brahmadaṇḍo”ti?**“But sir, what is the prime punishment?”*";
P_HTM[2544]="*“Channo, ānanda, bhikkhu yaṃ iccheyya, taṃ vadeyya.**“Channa may say what he likes,*";
P_HTM[2545]="*So bhikkhūhi neva vattabbo, na ovaditabbo, na anusāsitabbo”ti.**but the mendicants should not advise or instruct him.”*";
P_HTM[2546]="*Atha kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then the Buddha said to the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[2547]="*“siyā kho pana, bhikkhave, ekabhikkhussāpi kaṅkhā vā vimati vā buddhe vā dhamme vā saṅghe vā magge vā paṭipadāya vā, pucchatha, bhikkhave, mā pacchā vippaṭisārino ahuvattha:**“Perhaps even a single mendicant has doubt or uncertainty regarding the Buddha, the teaching, the Saṅgha, the path, or the practice. So ask, mendicants! Don’t regret it later, thinking:*";
P_HTM[2548]="*‘sammukhībhūto no satthā ahosi, na mayaṃ sakkhimhā bhagavantaṃ sammukhā paṭipucchitun’”ti.**‘We were in the Teacher’s presence and we weren’t able to ask the Buddha a question.’”*";
P_HTM[2549]="*Evaṃ vutte, te bhikkhū tuṇhī ahesuṃ.**When this was said, the mendicants kept silent.*";
P_HTM[2550]="*Dutiyampi kho bhagavā … pe …**For a second time,*";
P_HTM[2551]="*tatiyampi kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**and a third time the Buddha addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[2552]="*“siyā kho pana, bhikkhave, ekabhikkhussāpi kaṅkhā vā vimati vā buddhe vā dhamme vā saṅghe vā magge vā paṭipadāya vā, pucchatha, bhikkhave, mā pacchā vippaṭisārino ahuvattha:**“Perhaps even a single mendicant has doubt or uncertainty regarding the Buddha, the teaching, the Saṅgha, the path, or the practice. So ask, mendicants! Don’t regret it later, thinking:*";
P_HTM[2553]="*‘sammukhībhūto no satthā ahosi, na mayaṃ sakkhimhā bhagavantaṃ sammukhā paṭipucchitun’”ti.**‘We were in the Teacher’s presence and we weren’t able to ask the Buddha a question.’”*";
P_HTM[2554]="*Tatiyampi kho te bhikkhū tuṇhī ahesuṃ.**For a third time, the mendicants kept silent.*";
P_HTM[2555]="*Atha kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then the Buddha said to the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[2556]="*“siyā kho pana, bhikkhave, satthugāravenapi na puccheyyātha. Sahāyakopi, bhikkhave, sahāyakassa ārocetū”ti.**“Mendicants, perhaps you don’t ask out of respect for the Teacher. So let a friend tell a friend.”*";
P_HTM[2557]="*Evaṃ vutte, te bhikkhū tuṇhī ahesuṃ.**When this was said, the mendicants kept silent.*";
P_HTM[2558]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Ānanda said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[2559]="*“acchariyaṃ, bhante, abbhutaṃ, bhante, evaṃ pasanno ahaṃ, bhante, imasmiṃ bhikkhusaṅghe, ‘natthi ekabhikkhussāpi kaṅkhā vā vimati vā buddhe vā dhamme vā saṅghe vā magge vā paṭipadāya vā’”ti.**“It’s incredible, sir, it’s amazing! I am quite confident that there’s not even a single mendicant in this Saṅgha who has doubt or uncertainty regarding the Buddha, the teaching, the Saṅgha, the path, or the practice.”*";
P_HTM[2560]="*“Pasādā kho tvaṃ, ānanda, vadesi, ñāṇameva hettha, ānanda, tathāgatassa. Natthi imasmiṃ bhikkhusaṅghe ekabhikkhussāpi kaṅkhā vā vimati vā buddhe vā dhamme vā saṅghe vā magge vā paṭipadāya vā.**“Ānanda, you speak from faith. But the Realized One knows that there’s not even a single mendicant in this Saṅgha who has doubt or uncertainty regarding the Buddha, the teaching, the Saṅgha, the path, or the practice.*";
P_HTM[2561]="*Imesañhi, ānanda, pañcannaṃ bhikkhusatānaṃ yo pacchimako bhikkhu, so sotāpanno avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo”ti.**Even the last of these five hundred mendicants is a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.”*";
P_HTM[2562]="*Atha kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then the Buddha said to the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[2563]="*“handa dāni, bhikkhave, āmantayāmi vo,**“Come now, mendicants, I say to you all:*";
P_HTM[2564]="*vayadhammā saṅkhārā appamādena sampādethā”ti.**‘Conditions fall apart. Persist with diligence.’”*";
P_HTM[2565]="*Ayaṃ tathāgatassa pacchimā vācā.**These were the Realized One’s last words.*";
P_HTM[2566]="*36. Parinibbutakathā**36. The Full Extinguishment*";
P_HTM[2567]="*Atha kho bhagavā paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ samāpajji, paṭhamajjhānā vuṭṭhahitvā dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ samāpajji, dutiyajjhānā vuṭṭhahitvā tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ samāpajji, tatiyajjhānā vuṭṭhahitvā catutthaṃ jhānaṃ samāpajji, catutthajjhānā vuṭṭhahitvā ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samāpajji, ākāsānañcāyatanasamāpattiyā vuṭṭhahitvā viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samāpajji, viññāṇañcāyatanasamāpattiyā vuṭṭhahitvā ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samāpajji, ākiñcaññāyatanasamāpattiyā vuṭṭhahitvā nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samāpajji, nevasaññānāsaññāyatanasamāpattiyā vuṭṭhahitvā saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ samāpajji.**Then the Buddha entered the first absorption. Emerging from that, he entered the second absorption. Emerging from that, he successively entered into and emerged from the third absorption, the fourth absorption, the dimension of infinite space, the dimension of infinite consciousness, the dimension of nothingness, and the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception. Then he entered the cessation of perception and feeling.*";
P_HTM[2568]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando āyasmantaṃ anuruddhaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Ānanda said to Venerable Anuruddha,*";
P_HTM[2569]="*“parinibbuto, bhante anuruddha, bhagavā”ti.**“Venerable Anuruddha, has the Buddha become fully extinguished?”*";
P_HTM[2570]="*“Nāvuso ānanda, bhagavā parinibbuto, saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ samāpanno”ti.**“No, Reverend Ānanda. He has entered the cessation of perception and feeling.”*";
P_HTM[2571]="*Atha kho bhagavā saññāvedayitanirodhasamāpattiyā vuṭṭhahitvā nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samāpajji, nevasaññānāsaññāyatanasamāpattiyā vuṭṭhahitvā ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samāpajji, ākiñcaññāyatanasamāpattiyā vuṭṭhahitvā viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samāpajji, viññāṇañcāyatanasamāpattiyā vuṭṭhahitvā ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samāpajji, ākāsānañcāyatanasamāpattiyā vuṭṭhahitvā catutthaṃ jhānaṃ samāpajji, catutthajjhānā vuṭṭhahitvā tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ samāpajji, tatiyajjhānā vuṭṭhahitvā dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ samāpajji, dutiyajjhānā vuṭṭhahitvā paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ samāpajji, paṭhamajjhānā vuṭṭhahitvā dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ samāpajji, dutiyajjhānā vuṭṭhahitvā tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ samāpajji, tatiyajjhānā vuṭṭhahitvā catutthaṃ jhānaṃ samāpajji, catutthajjhānā vuṭṭhahitvā samanantarā bhagavā parinibbāyi.**Then the Buddha emerged from the cessation of perception and feeling and entered the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception. Emerging from that, he successively entered into and emerged from the dimension of nothingness, the dimension of infinite consciousness, the dimension of infinite space, the fourth absorption, the third absorption, the second absorption, and the first absorption. Emerging from that, he successively entered into and emerged from the second absorption and the third absorption. Then he entered the fourth absorption. Emerging from that the Buddha immediately became fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[2572]="*Parinibbute bhagavati saha parinibbānā mahābhūmicālo ahosi bhiṃsanako salomahaṃso. Devadundubhiyo ca phaliṃsu.**When the Buddha became fully extinguished, along with the full extinguishment there was a great earthquake, awe-inspiring and hair-raising, and thunder cracked the sky.*";
P_HTM[2573]="*Parinibbute bhagavati saha parinibbānā brahmāsahampati imaṃ gāthaṃ abhāsi:**When the Buddha became fully extinguished, Brahmā Sahampati recited this verse:*";
P_HTM[2574]="*“Sabbeva nikkhipissanti,**“All creatures in this world*";
P_HTM[2575]="*bhūtā loke samussayaṃ;**must lay down this bag of bones.*";
P_HTM[2576]="*Yattha etādiso satthā,**For even a Teacher such as this,*";
P_HTM[2577]="*loke appaṭipuggalo;**unrivaled in the world,*";
P_HTM[2578]="*Tathāgato balappatto,**the Realized One, attained to power,*";
P_HTM[2579]="*sambuddho parinibbuto”ti.**the Buddha became fully extinguished.”*";
P_HTM[2580]="*Parinibbute bhagavati saha parinibbānā sakko devānamindo imaṃ gāthaṃ abhāsi:**When the Buddha became fully extinguished, Sakka, lord of gods, recited this verse:*";
P_HTM[2581]="*“Aniccā vata saṅkhārā,**“Oh! Conditions are impermanent,*";
P_HTM[2582]="*uppādavayadhammino;**their nature is to rise and fall;*";
P_HTM[2583]="*Uppajjitvā nirujjhanti,**having arisen, they cease;*";
P_HTM[2584]="*tesaṃ vūpasamo sukho”ti.**their stilling is true bliss.”*";
P_HTM[2585]="*Parinibbute bhagavati saha parinibbānā āyasmā anuruddho imā gāthāyo abhāsi:**When the Buddha became fully extinguished, Venerable Anuruddha recited this verse:*";
P_HTM[2586]="*“Nāhu assāsapassāso,**“There was no more breathing*";
P_HTM[2587]="*ṭhitacittassa tādino;**for the poised one of steady heart.*";
P_HTM[2588]="*Anejo santimārabbha,**Imperturbable, committed to peace,*";
P_HTM[2589]="*yaṃ kālamakarī muni.**the sage has done his time.*";
P_HTM[2590]="*Asallīnena cittena,**He put up with painful feelings*";
P_HTM[2591]="*vedanaṃ ajjhavāsayi;**without flinching.*";
P_HTM[2592]="*Pajjotasseva nibbānaṃ,**The liberation of his heart*";
P_HTM[2593]="*vimokkho cetaso ahū”ti.**was like the extinguishing of a lamp.”*";
P_HTM[2594]="*Parinibbute bhagavati saha parinibbānā āyasmā ānando imaṃ gāthaṃ abhāsi:**When the Buddha became fully extinguished, Venerable Ānanda recited this verse:*";
P_HTM[2595]="*“Tadāsi yaṃ bhiṃsanakaṃ,**“Then there was terror!*";
P_HTM[2596]="*tadāsi lomahaṃsanaṃ;**Then they had goosebumps!*";
P_HTM[2597]="*Sabbākāravarūpete,**When the Buddha, endowed with all fine qualities,*";
P_HTM[2598]="*sambuddhe parinibbute”ti.**became fully extinguished.”*";
P_HTM[2599]="*Parinibbute bhagavati ye te tattha bhikkhū avītarāgā appekacce bāhā paggayha kandanti, chinnapātaṃ papatanti, āvaṭṭanti vivaṭṭanti, “atikhippaṃ bhagavā parinibbuto, atikhippaṃ sugato parinibbuto, atikhippaṃ cakkhuṃ loke antarahito”ti.**When the Buddha became fully extinguished, some of the mendicants there, with arms raised, falling down like their feet were chopped off, rolling back and forth, lamented: “Too soon the Blessed One has become fully extinguished! Too soon the Holy One has become fully extinguished! Too soon the seer has vanished from the world!”*";
P_HTM[2600]="*Ye pana te bhikkhū vītarāgā, te satā sampajānā adhivāsenti:**But the mendicants who were free of desire endured, mindful and aware, thinking,*";
P_HTM[2601]="*“aniccā saṅkhārā, taṃ kutettha labbhā”ti.**“Conditions are impermanent. How could it possibly be otherwise?”*";
P_HTM[2602]="*Atha kho āyasmā anuruddho bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then Anuruddha addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[2603]="*“alaṃ, āvuso, mā socittha mā paridevittha.**“Enough, reverends, do not grieve or lament.*";
P_HTM[2604]="*Nanu etaṃ, āvuso, bhagavatā paṭikacceva akkhātaṃ:**Did the Buddha not prepare us for this when he explained that*";
P_HTM[2605]="*‘sabbeheva piyehi manāpehi nānābhāvo vinābhāvo aññathābhāvo’.**we must be parted and separated from all we hold dear and beloved?*";
P_HTM[2606]="*Taṃ kutettha, āvuso, labbhā. ‘Yaṃ taṃ jātaṃ bhūtaṃ saṅkhataṃ palokadhammaṃ, taṃ vata mā palujjī’ti, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**How could it possibly be so that what is born, created, conditioned, and liable to fall apart should not fall apart?*";
P_HTM[2607]="*Devatā, āvuso, ujjhāyantī”ti.**The deities are complaining.”*";
P_HTM[2608]="*“Kathaṃbhūtā pana, bhante, āyasmā anuruddho devatā manasi karotī”ti?**“But sir, what kind of deities are you thinking of?”*";
P_HTM[2609]="*“Santāvuso ānanda, devatā ākāse pathavīsaññiniyo kese pakiriya kandanti, bāhā paggayha kandanti, chinnapātaṃ papatanti, āvaṭṭanti, vivaṭṭanti:**“There are, Ānanda, deities—both in the sky and on the earth—who are percipient of the earth. With hair disheveled and arms raised, they fall down like their feet were chopped off, rolling back and forth, lamenting:*";
P_HTM[2610]="*‘atikhippaṃ bhagavā parinibbuto, atikhippaṃ sugato parinibbuto, atikhippaṃ cakkhuṃ loke antarahito’ti.**‘Too soon the Blessed One has become fully extinguished! Too soon the Holy One has become fully extinguished! Too soon the seer has vanished from the world!’*";
P_HTM[2611]="*Santāvuso ānanda, devatā pathaviyā pathavīsaññiniyo kese pakiriya kandanti, bāhā paggayha kandanti, chinnapātaṃ papatanti, āvaṭṭanti, vivaṭṭanti:* **";
P_HTM[2612]="*‘atikhippaṃ bhagavā parinibbuto, atikhippaṃ sugato parinibbuto, atikhippaṃ cakkhuṃ loke antarahito’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2613]="*Yā pana tā devatā vītarāgā, tā satā sampajānā adhivāsenti:**But the deities who are free of desire endure, mindful and aware, thinking:*";
P_HTM[2614]="*‘aniccā saṅkhārā, taṃ kutettha labbhā’”ti.**‘Conditions are impermanent. How could it possibly be otherwise?’”*";
P_HTM[2615]="*Atha kho āyasmā ca anuruddho āyasmā ca ānando taṃ rattāvasesaṃ dhammiyā kathāya vītināmesuṃ.**Ānanda and Anuruddha spent the rest of the night talking about Dhamma.*";
P_HTM[2616]="*Atha kho āyasmā anuruddho āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ āmantesi:**Then Anuruddha said to Ānanda,*";
P_HTM[2617]="*“gacchāvuso ānanda, kusināraṃ pavisitvā kosinārakānaṃ mallānaṃ ārocehi:**“Go, Ānanda, into Kusinārā and inform the Mallas:*";
P_HTM[2618]="*‘parinibbuto, vāseṭṭhā, bhagavā,**‘Vāseṭṭhas, the Buddha has become fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[2619]="*yassadāni kālaṃ maññathā’”ti.**Please come at your convenience.’”*";
P_HTM[2620]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā ānando āyasmato anuruddhassa paṭissutvā pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya attadutiyo kusināraṃ pāvisi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Ānanda. Then, in the morning, he robed up and, taking his bowl and robe, entered Kusinārā with a companion.*";
P_HTM[2621]="*Tena kho pana samayena kosinārakā mallā sandhāgāre sannipatitā honti teneva karaṇīyena.**Now at that time the Mallas of Kusinārā were sitting together at the meeting hall on some business.*";
P_HTM[2622]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando yena kosinārakānaṃ mallānaṃ sandhāgāraṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā kosinārakānaṃ mallānaṃ ārocesi:**Ānanda went up to them, and announced,*";
P_HTM[2623]="*“parinibbuto, vāseṭṭhā, bhagavā,**“Vāseṭṭhas, the Buddha has become fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[2624]="*yassadāni kālaṃ maññathā”ti.**Please come at your convenience.”*";
P_HTM[2625]="*Idamāyasmato ānandassa vacanaṃ sutvā mallā ca mallaputtā ca mallasuṇisā ca mallapajāpatiyo ca aghāvino dummanā cetodukkhasamappitā appekacce kese pakiriya kandanti, bāhā paggayha kandanti, chinnapātaṃ papatanti, āvaṭṭanti, vivaṭṭanti:**When they heard what Ānanda had to say, the Mallas, their sons, daughters-in-law, and wives became distraught, saddened, and grief-stricken. And some, with hair disheveled and arms raised, falling down like their feet were chopped off, rolling back and forth, lamented,*";
P_HTM[2626]="*“atikhippaṃ bhagavā parinibbuto, atikhippaṃ sugato parinibbuto, atikhippaṃ cakkhuṃ loke antarahito”ti.**“Too soon the Blessed One has become fully extinguished! Too soon the Holy One has become fully extinguished! Too soon the seer has vanished from the world!”*";
P_HTM[2627]="*37. Buddhasarīrapūjā**37. The Rites of Venerating the Buddha’s Corpse*";
P_HTM[2628]="*Atha kho kosinārakā mallā purise āṇāpesuṃ:**Then the Mallas ordered their men,*";
P_HTM[2629]="*“tena hi, bhaṇe, kusinārāyaṃ gandhamālañca sabbañca tāḷāvacaraṃ sannipātethā”ti.**“So then, my men, collect fragrances and garlands, and all the musical instruments in Kusinārā.”*";
P_HTM[2630]="*Atha kho kosinārakā mallā gandhamālañca sabbañca tāḷāvacaraṃ pañca ca dussayugasatāni ādāya yena upavattanaṃ mallānaṃ sālavanaṃ, yena bhagavato sarīraṃ tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavato sarīraṃ naccehi gītehi vāditehi mālehi gandhehi sakkarontā garuṃ karontā mānentā pūjentā celavitānāni karontā maṇḍalamāḷe paṭiyādentā ekadivasaṃ vītināmesuṃ.**Then—taking those fragrances and garlands, all the musical instruments, and five hundred pairs of garments—they went to the Mallian sal grove at Upavattana and approached the Buddha’s corpse. They spent the day honoring, respecting, revering, and venerating the Buddha’s corpse with dance and song and music and garlands and fragrances, and making awnings and setting up pavilions.*";
P_HTM[2631]="*Atha kho kosinārakānaṃ mallānaṃ etadahosi:**Then they thought,*";
P_HTM[2632]="*“ativikālo kho ajja bhagavato sarīraṃ jhāpetuṃ, sve dāni mayaṃ bhagavato sarīraṃ jhāpessāmā”ti.**“It’s too late to cremate the Buddha’s corpse today. Let’s do it tomorrow.”*";
P_HTM[2633]="*Atha kho kosinārakā mallā bhagavato sarīraṃ naccehi gītehi vāditehi mālehi gandhehi sakkarontā garuṃ karontā mānentā pūjentā celavitānāni karontā maṇḍalamāḷe paṭiyādentā dutiyampi divasaṃ vītināmesuṃ, tatiyampi divasaṃ vītināmesuṃ, catutthampi divasaṃ vītināmesuṃ, pañcamampi divasaṃ vītināmesuṃ, chaṭṭhampi divasaṃ vītināmesuṃ.**But they spent the next day the same way, and so too the third, fourth, fifth, and sixth days.*";
P_HTM[2634]="*Atha kho sattamaṃ divasaṃ kosinārakānaṃ mallānaṃ etadahosi:**Then on the seventh day they thought,*";
P_HTM[2635]="*“mayaṃ bhagavato sarīraṃ naccehi gītehi vāditehi mālehi gandhehi sakkarontā garuṃ karontā mānentā pūjentā dakkhiṇena dakkhiṇaṃ nagarassa haritvā bāhirena bāhiraṃ dakkhiṇato nagarassa bhagavato sarīraṃ jhāpessāmā”ti.**“Honoring, respecting, revering, and venerating the Buddha’s corpse with dance and song and music and garlands and fragrances, let us carry it to the south of the town, and cremate it there outside the town.”*";
P_HTM[2636]="*Tena kho pana samayena aṭṭha mallapāmokkhā sīsaṃnhātā ahatāni vatthāni nivatthā:**Now at that time eight of the leading Mallas, having bathed their heads and dressed in unworn clothes, said,*";
P_HTM[2637]="*“mayaṃ bhagavato sarīraṃ uccāressāmā”ti na sakkonti uccāretuṃ.**“We shall lift the Buddha’s corpse.” But they were unable to do so.*";
P_HTM[2638]="*Atha kho kosinārakā mallā āyasmantaṃ anuruddhaṃ etadavocuṃ:**The Mallas said to Anuruddha,*";
P_HTM[2639]="*“ko nu kho, bhante anuruddha, hetu ko paccayo, yenime aṭṭha mallapāmokkhā sīsaṃnhātā ahatāni vatthāni nivatthā:**“What is the cause, Venerable Anuruddha, what is the reason why these eight Mallian leaders are unable to lift the Buddha’s corpse?”*";
P_HTM[2640]="*‘mayaṃ bhagavato sarīraṃ uccāressāmā’ti na sakkonti uccāretun”ti?* **";
P_HTM[2641]="*“Aññathā kho, vāseṭṭhā, tumhākaṃ adhippāyo, aññathā devatānaṃ adhippāyo”ti.**“Vāseṭṭhas, you have one plan, but the deities have a different one.”*";
P_HTM[2642]="*“Kathaṃ pana, bhante, devatānaṃ adhippāyo”ti?**“But sir, what is the deities’ plan?”*";
P_HTM[2643]="*“Tumhākaṃ kho, vāseṭṭhā, adhippāyo:**“You plan to*";
P_HTM[2644]="*‘mayaṃ bhagavato sarīraṃ naccehi gītehi vāditehi mālehi gandhehi sakkarontā garuṃ karontā mānentā pūjentā dakkhiṇena dakkhiṇaṃ nagarassa haritvā bāhirena bāhiraṃ dakkhiṇato nagarassa bhagavato sarīraṃ jhāpessāmā’ti;**carry the Buddha’s corpse to the south of the town while venerating it with dance and song and music and garlands and fragrances, and cremate it there outside the town.*";
P_HTM[2645]="*devatānaṃ kho, vāseṭṭhā, adhippāyo:**The deities plan to*";
P_HTM[2646]="*‘mayaṃ bhagavato sarīraṃ dibbehi naccehi gītehi vāditehi mālehi gandhehi sakkarontā garuṃ karontā mānentā pūjentā uttarena uttaraṃ nagarassa haritvā uttarena dvārena nagaraṃ pavesetvā majjhena majjhaṃ nagarassa haritvā puratthimena dvārena nikkhamitvā puratthimato nagarassa makuṭabandhanaṃ nāma mallānaṃ cetiyaṃ ettha bhagavato sarīraṃ jhāpessāmā’”ti.**carry the Buddha’s corpse to the north of the town while venerating it with heavenly dance and song and music and garlands and fragrances. Then they plan to enter the town by the northern gate, carry it through the center of the town, leave by the eastern gate, and cremate it there at the Mallian shrine named Makuṭabandhana.”*";
P_HTM[2647]="*“Yathā, bhante, devatānaṃ adhippāyo, tathā hotū”ti.**“Sir, let it be as the deities plan.”*";
P_HTM[2648]="*Tena kho pana samayena kusinārā yāva sandhisamalasaṅkaṭīrā jaṇṇumattena odhinā mandāravapupphehi santhatā hoti.**Now at that time the whole of Kusinārā was covered knee-deep with the flowers of the Flame Tree, without gaps even on the filth and rubbish heaps.*";
P_HTM[2649]="*Atha kho devatā ca kosinārakā ca mallā bhagavato sarīraṃ dibbehi ca mānusakehi ca naccehi gītehi vāditehi mālehi gandhehi sakkarontā garuṃ karontā mānentā pūjentā uttarena uttaraṃ nagarassa haritvā uttarena dvārena nagaraṃ pavesetvā majjhena majjhaṃ nagarassa haritvā puratthimena dvārena nikkhamitvā puratthimato nagarassa makuṭabandhanaṃ nāma mallānaṃ cetiyaṃ ettha ca bhagavato sarīraṃ nikkhipiṃsu.**Then the deities and the Mallas of Kusinārā carried the Buddha’s corpse to the north of the town while venerating it with heavenly and human dance and song and music and garlands and fragrances. Then they entered the town by the northern gate, carried it through the center of the town, left by the eastern gate, and deposited the corpse there at the Mallian shrine named Makuṭabandhana.*";
P_HTM[2650]="*Atha kho kosinārakā mallā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavocuṃ:**Then the Mallas said to Anuruddha,*";
P_HTM[2651]="*“kathaṃ mayaṃ, bhante ānanda, tathāgatassa sarīre paṭipajjāmā”ti?**“Sir, how do we proceed when it comes to the Realized One’s corpse?”*";
P_HTM[2652]="*“Yathā kho, vāseṭṭhā, rañño cakkavattissa sarīre paṭipajjanti, evaṃ tathāgatassa sarīre paṭipajjitabban”ti.**“Proceed in the same way as they do for the corpse of a wheel-turning monarch.”*";
P_HTM[2653]="*“Kathaṃ pana, bhante ānanda, rañño cakkavattissa sarīre paṭipajjantī”ti?**“But how do they proceed with a wheel-turning monarch’s corpse?”*";
P_HTM[2654]="*“Rañño, vāseṭṭhā, cakkavattissa sarīraṃ ahatena vatthena veṭhenti, ahatena vatthena veṭhetvā vihatena kappāsena veṭhenti, vihatena kappāsena veṭhetvā ahatena vatthena veṭhenti.**“They wrap a wheel-turning monarch’s corpse with unworn cloth, then with uncarded cotton, then again with unworn cloth.*";
P_HTM[2655]="*Etena upāyena pañcahi yugasatehi rañño cakkavattissa sarīraṃ veṭhetvā āyasāya teladoṇiyā pakkhipitvā aññissā āyasāya doṇiyā paṭikujjitvā sabbagandhānaṃ citakaṃ karitvā rañño cakkavattissa sarīraṃ jhāpenti.**In this way they wrap the corpse with five hundred double-layers. Then they place it in an iron case filled with oil and close it up with another case. Then, having built a funeral pyre out of all kinds of fragrant substances, they cremate the corpse.*";
P_HTM[2656]="*Cātumahāpathe rañño cakkavattissa thūpaṃ karonti.**They build a monument for the wheel-turning monarch at the crossroads.*";
P_HTM[2657]="*Evaṃ kho, vāseṭṭhā, rañño cakkavattissa sarīre paṭipajjanti.**That’s how they proceed with a wheel-turning monarch’s corpse.*";
P_HTM[2658]="*Yathā kho, vāseṭṭhā, rañño cakkavattissa sarīre paṭipajjanti, evaṃ tathāgatassa sarīre paṭipajjitabbaṃ.**Proceed in the same way with the Realized One’s corpse.*";
P_HTM[2659]="*Cātumahāpathe tathāgatassa thūpo kātabbo.**A monument for the Realized One is to be built at the crossroads.*";
P_HTM[2660]="*Tattha ye mālaṃ vā gandhaṃ vā cuṇṇakaṃ vā āropessanti vā abhivādessanti vā cittaṃ vā pasādessanti, tesaṃ taṃ bhavissati dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāyā”ti.**When someone there lifts up garlands or fragrance or powder, or bows, or inspires confidence in their heart, that will be for their lasting welfare and happiness.”*";
P_HTM[2661]="*Atha kho kosinārakā mallā purise āṇāpesuṃ:**Then the Mallas ordered their men,*";
P_HTM[2662]="*“tena hi, bhaṇe, mallānaṃ vihataṃ kappāsaṃ sannipātethā”ti.**“So then, my men, collect uncarded cotton.”*";
P_HTM[2663]="*Atha kho kosinārakā mallā bhagavato sarīraṃ ahatena vatthena veṭhetvā vihatena kappāsena veṭhesuṃ, vihatena kappāsena veṭhetvā ahatena vatthena veṭhesuṃ.**So the Mallas wrapped the Buddha’s corpse,*";
P_HTM[2664]="*Etena upāyena pañcahi yugasatehi bhagavato sarīraṃ veṭhetvā āyasāya teladoṇiyā pakkhipitvā aññissā āyasāya doṇiyā paṭikujjitvā sabbagandhānaṃ citakaṃ karitvā bhagavato sarīraṃ citakaṃ āropesuṃ.**and placed it in an iron case filled with oil. Then, having built a funeral pyre out of all kinds of fragrant substances, they lifted the corpse on to the pyre.*";
P_HTM[2665]="*38. Mahākassapattheravatthu**38. Mahākassapa’s Arrival*";
P_HTM[2666]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā mahākassapo pāvāya kusināraṃ addhānamaggappaṭipanno hoti mahatā bhikkhusaṃghena saddhiṃ pañcamattehi bhikkhusatehi.**Now at that time Venerable Mahākassapa was traveling along the road from Pāvā to Kusinārā together with a large Saṅgha of around five hundred mendicants.*";
P_HTM[2667]="*Atha kho āyasmā mahākassapo maggā okkamma aññatarasmiṃ rukkhamūle nisīdi.**Then he left the road and sat at the root of a tree.*";
P_HTM[2668]="*Tena kho pana samayena aññataro ājīvako kusinārāya mandāravapupphaṃ gahetvā pāvaṃ addhānamaggappaṭipanno hoti.**Now at that time a certain ājīvaka ascetic had picked up a Flame Tree flower in Kusinārā and was traveling along the road to Pāvā.*";
P_HTM[2669]="*Addasā kho āyasmā mahākassapo taṃ ājīvakaṃ dūratova āgacchantaṃ, disvā taṃ ājīvakaṃ etadavoca:**Mahākassapa saw him coming off in the distance and said to him,*";
P_HTM[2670]="*“apāvuso, amhākaṃ satthāraṃ jānāsī”ti?**“Reverend, might you know about our Teacher?”*";
P_HTM[2671]="*“Āmāvuso, jānāmi, ajja sattāhaparinibbuto samaṇo gotamo.**“Yes, reverend. Seven days ago the ascetic Gotama became fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[2672]="*Tato me idaṃ mandāravapupphaṃ gahitan”ti.**From there I picked up this Flame Tree flower.”*";
P_HTM[2673]="*Tattha ye te bhikkhū avītarāgā appekacce bāhā paggayha kandanti, chinnapātaṃ papatanti, āvaṭṭanti, vivaṭṭanti:**Some of the mendicants there, with arms raised, falling down like their feet were chopped off, rolling back and forth, lamented,*";
P_HTM[2674]="*“atikhippaṃ bhagavā parinibbuto, atikhippaṃ sugato parinibbuto, atikhippaṃ cakkhuṃ loke antarahito”ti.**“Too soon the Blessed One has become fully extinguished! Too soon the Holy One has become fully extinguished! Too soon the seer has vanished from the world!”*";
P_HTM[2675]="*Ye pana te bhikkhū vītarāgā, te satā sampajānā adhivāsenti:**But the mendicants who were free of desire endured, mindful and aware, thinking,*";
P_HTM[2676]="*“aniccā saṅkhārā, taṃ kutettha labbhā”ti.**“Conditions are impermanent. How could it possibly be otherwise?”*";
P_HTM[2677]="*Tena kho pana samayena subhaddo nāma vuddhapabbajito tassaṃ parisāyaṃ nisinno hoti.**Now at that time a monk named Subhadda, who had gone forth when old, was sitting in that assembly.*";
P_HTM[2678]="*Atha kho subhaddo vuddhapabbajito te bhikkhū etadavoca:**He said to those mendicants,*";
P_HTM[2679]="*“alaṃ, āvuso, mā socittha, mā paridevittha, sumuttā mayaṃ tena mahāsamaṇena. Upaddutā ca homa:**“Enough, reverends, do not grieve or lament. We’re well rid of that Great Ascetic harassing us:*";
P_HTM[2680]="*‘idaṃ vo kappati, idaṃ vo na kappatī’ti.**‘This is allowable for you; this is not allowable for you.’*";
P_HTM[2681]="*Idāni pana mayaṃ yaṃ icchissāma, taṃ karissāma, yaṃ na icchissāma, na taṃ karissāmā”ti.**Well, now we shall do what we want and not do what we don’t want.”*";
P_HTM[2682]="*Atha kho āyasmā mahākassapo bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then Venerable Mahākassapa addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[2683]="*“alaṃ, āvuso, mā socittha, mā paridevittha.**“Enough, reverends, do not grieve or lament.*";
P_HTM[2684]="*Nanu etaṃ, āvuso, bhagavatā paṭikacceva akkhātaṃ:**Did the Buddha not prepare us for this when he explained that*";
P_HTM[2685]="*‘sabbeheva piyehi manāpehi nānābhāvo vinābhāvo aññathābhāvo’.**we must be parted and separated from all we hold dear and beloved?*";
P_HTM[2686]="*Taṃ kutettha, āvuso, labbhā. ‘Yaṃ taṃ jātaṃ bhūtaṃ saṅkhataṃ palokadhammaṃ, taṃ tathāgatassāpi sarīraṃ mā palujjī’ti, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjatī”ti.**How could it possibly be so that what is born, created, conditioned, and liable to fall apart should not fall apart, even the Realized One’s body?”*";
P_HTM[2687]="*Tena kho pana samayena cattāro mallapāmokkhā sīsaṃnhātā ahatāni vatthāni nivatthā:**Now at that time four of the leading Mallas, having bathed their heads and dressed in unworn clothes, said,*";
P_HTM[2688]="*“mayaṃ bhagavato citakaṃ āḷimpessāmā”ti na sakkonti āḷimpetuṃ.**“We shall light the Buddha’s funeral pyre.” But they were unable to do so.*";
P_HTM[2689]="*Atha kho kosinārakā mallā āyasmantaṃ anuruddhaṃ etadavocuṃ:**The Mallas said to Anuruddha,*";
P_HTM[2690]="*“ko nu kho, bhante anuruddha, hetu ko paccayo, yenime cattāro mallapāmokkhā sīsaṃnhātā ahatāni vatthāni nivatthā:**“What is the cause, Venerable Anuruddha, what is the reason why these four Mallian leaders are unable to light the Buddha’s funeral pyre?”*";
P_HTM[2691]="*‘mayaṃ bhagavato citakaṃ āḷimpessāmā’ti na sakkonti āḷimpetun”ti?* **";
P_HTM[2692]="*“Aññathā kho, vāseṭṭhā, devatānaṃ adhippāyo”ti.**“Vāseṭṭhas, the deities have a different plan.”*";
P_HTM[2693]="*“Kathaṃ pana, bhante, devatānaṃ adhippāyo”ti?**“But sir, what is the deities’ plan?”*";
P_HTM[2694]="*“Devatānaṃ kho, vāseṭṭhā, adhippāyo:**“The deities’ plan is this:*";
P_HTM[2695]="*‘ayaṃ āyasmā mahākassapo pāvāya kusināraṃ addhānamaggappaṭipanno mahatā bhikkhusaṅghena saddhiṃ pañcamattehi bhikkhusatehi.**Venerable Mahākassapa is traveling along the road from Pāvā to Kusinārā together with a large Saṅgha of around five hundred mendicants.*";
P_HTM[2696]="*Na tāva bhagavato citako pajjalissati, yāvāyasmā mahākassapo bhagavato pāde sirasā na vandissatī’”ti.**The Buddha’s funeral pyre shall not burn until he bows with his head at the Buddha’s feet.”*";
P_HTM[2697]="*“Yathā, bhante, devatānaṃ adhippāyo, tathā hotū”ti.**“Sir, let it be as the deities plan.”*";
P_HTM[2698]="*Atha kho āyasmā mahākassapo yena kusinārā makuṭabandhanaṃ nāma mallānaṃ cetiyaṃ, yena bhagavato citako tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā ekaṃsaṃ cīvaraṃ katvā añjaliṃ paṇāmetvā tikkhattuṃ citakaṃ padakkhiṇaṃ katvā bhagavato pāde sirasā vandi.**Then Venerable Mahākassapa came to the Mallian shrine named Makuṭabandhana at Kusinārā and approached the Buddha’s funeral pyre. Arranging his robe over one shoulder and raising his joined palms, he respectfully circled the Buddha three times, keeping him on his right, and bowed with his head to the Buddha’s feet.*";
P_HTM[2699]="*Tānipi kho pañcabhikkhusatāni ekaṃsaṃ cīvaraṃ katvā añjaliṃ paṇāmetvā tikkhattuṃ citakaṃ padakkhiṇaṃ katvā bhagavato pāde sirasā vandiṃsu.**And the five hundred mendicants did likewise.*";
P_HTM[2700]="*Vandite ca panāyasmatā mahākassapena tehi ca pañcahi bhikkhusatehi sayameva bhagavato citako pajjali.**And when Mahākassapa and the five hundred mendicants bowed the Buddha’s funeral pyre burst into flames all by itself.*";
P_HTM[2701]="*Jhāyamānassa kho pana bhagavato sarīrassa yaṃ ahosi chavīti vā cammanti vā maṃsanti vā nhārūti vā lasikāti vā, tassa neva chārikā paññāyittha, na masi;**And when the Buddha’s corpse was cremated no ash or soot was found from outer or inner skin, flesh, sinews, or synovial fluid.*";
P_HTM[2702]="*sarīrāneva avasissiṃsu.**Only the relics remained.*";
P_HTM[2703]="*Seyyathāpi nāma sappissa vā telassa vā jhāyamānassa neva chārikā paññāyati, na masi;**It’s like when ghee or oil blaze and burn, and neither ashes nor soot are found.*";
P_HTM[2704]="*evameva bhagavato sarīrassa jhāyamānassa yaṃ ahosi chavīti vā cammanti vā maṃsanti vā nhārūti vā lasikāti vā, tassa neva chārikā paññāyittha, na masi;**In the same way, when the Buddha’s corpse was cremated no ash or soot was found from outer or inner skin, flesh, sinews, or synovial fluid.*";
P_HTM[2705]="*sarīrāneva avasissiṃsu.**Only the relics remained.*";
P_HTM[2706]="*Tesañca pañcannaṃ dussayugasatānaṃ dveva dussāni na ḍayhiṃsu yañca sabbaabbhantarimaṃ yañca bāhiraṃ.**And of those five hundred pairs of garments only two were not burnt: the innermost and the outermost.*";
P_HTM[2707]="*Daḍḍhe ca kho pana bhagavato sarīre antalikkhā udakadhārā pātubhavitvā bhagavato citakaṃ nibbāpesi.**But when the Buddha’s corpse was consumed the funeral pyre was extinguished by a stream of water that appeared in the sky,*";
P_HTM[2708]="*Udakasālatopi abbhunnamitvā bhagavato citakaṃ nibbāpesi.**by water dripping from the sal trees,*";
P_HTM[2709]="*Kosinārakāpi mallā sabbagandhodakena bhagavato citakaṃ nibbāpesuṃ.**and by the Mallas’ fragrant water.*";
P_HTM[2710]="*Atha kho kosinārakā mallā bhagavato sarīrāni sattāhaṃ sandhāgāre sattipañjaraṃ karitvā dhanupākāraṃ parikkhipāpetvā naccehi gītehi vāditehi mālehi gandhehi sakkariṃsu garuṃ kariṃsu mānesuṃ pūjesuṃ.**Then the Mallas made a cage of spears for the Buddha’s relics in the meeting hall and surrounded it with a buttress of bows. For seven days they honored, respected, revered, and venerated them with dance and song and music and garlands and fragrances.*";
P_HTM[2711]="*39. Sarīradhātuvibhajana**39. Distributing the Relics*";
P_HTM[2712]="*Assosi kho rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto:**King Ajātasattu of Magadha heard*";
P_HTM[2713]="*“bhagavā kira kusinārāyaṃ parinibbuto”ti.**that the Buddha had become fully extinguished at Kusinārā.*";
P_HTM[2714]="*Atha kho rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto kosinārakānaṃ mallānaṃ dūtaṃ pāhesi:**He sent an envoy to the Mallas of Kusinārā:*";
P_HTM[2715]="*“bhagavāpi khattiyo ahampi khattiyo, ahampi arahāmi bhagavato sarīrānaṃ bhāgaṃ, ahampi bhagavato sarīrānaṃ thūpañca mahañca karissāmī”ti.**“The Buddha was an aristocrat, and so am I. I too deserve a share of the Buddha’s relics. I will build a large monument for them.”*";
P_HTM[2716]="*Assosuṃ kho vesālikā licchavī:**The Licchavis of Vesālī also heard*";
P_HTM[2717]="*“bhagavā kira kusinārāyaṃ parinibbuto”ti.**that the Buddha had become fully extinguished at Kusinārā.*";
P_HTM[2718]="*Atha kho vesālikā licchavī kosinārakānaṃ mallānaṃ dūtaṃ pāhesuṃ:**They sent an envoy to the Mallas of Kusinārā:*";
P_HTM[2719]="*“bhagavāpi khattiyo mayampi khattiyā, mayampi arahāma bhagavato sarīrānaṃ bhāgaṃ, mayampi bhagavato sarīrānaṃ thūpañca mahañca karissāmā”ti.**“The Buddha was an aristocrat, and so are we. We too deserve a share of the Buddha’s relics. We will build a large monument for them.”*";
P_HTM[2720]="*Assosuṃ kho kapilavatthuvāsī sakyā:**The Sakyans of Kapilavatthu also heard*";
P_HTM[2721]="*“bhagavā kira kusinārāyaṃ parinibbuto”ti.**that the Buddha had become fully extinguished at Kusinārā.*";
P_HTM[2722]="*Atha kho kapilavatthuvāsī sakyā kosinārakānaṃ mallānaṃ dūtaṃ pāhesuṃ:**They sent an envoy to the Mallas of Kusinārā:*";
P_HTM[2723]="*“bhagavā amhākaṃ ñātiseṭṭho, mayampi arahāma bhagavato sarīrānaṃ bhāgaṃ, mayampi bhagavato sarīrānaṃ thūpañca mahañca karissāmā”ti.**“The Buddha was our foremost relative. We too deserve a share of the Buddha’s relics. We will build a large monument for them.”*";
P_HTM[2724]="*Assosuṃ kho allakappakā bulayo:**The Bulas of Allakappa also heard*";
P_HTM[2725]="*“bhagavā kira kusinārāyaṃ parinibbuto”ti.**that the Buddha had become fully extinguished at Kusinārā.*";
P_HTM[2726]="*Atha kho allakappakā bulayo kosinārakānaṃ mallānaṃ dūtaṃ pāhesuṃ:**They sent an envoy to the Mallas of Kusinārā:*";
P_HTM[2727]="*“bhagavāpi khattiyo mayampi khattiyā, mayampi arahāma bhagavato sarīrānaṃ bhāgaṃ, mayampi bhagavato sarīrānaṃ thūpañca mahañca karissāmā”ti.**“The Buddha was an aristocrat, and so are we. We too deserve a share of the Buddha’s relics. We will build a large monument for them.”*";
P_HTM[2728]="*Assosuṃ kho rāmagāmakā koḷiyā:**The Koḷiyans of Rāmagāma also heard*";
P_HTM[2729]="*“bhagavā kira kusinārāyaṃ parinibbuto”ti.**that the Buddha had become fully extinguished at Kusinārā.*";
P_HTM[2730]="*Atha kho rāmagāmakā koḷiyā kosinārakānaṃ mallānaṃ dūtaṃ pāhesuṃ:**They sent an envoy to the Mallas of Kusinārā:*";
P_HTM[2731]="*“bhagavāpi khattiyo mayampi khattiyā, mayampi arahāma bhagavato sarīrānaṃ bhāgaṃ, mayampi bhagavato sarīrānaṃ thūpañca mahañca karissāmā”ti.**“The Buddha was an aristocrat, and so are we. We too deserve a share of the Buddha’s relics. We will build a large monument for them.”*";
P_HTM[2732]="*Assosi kho veṭṭhadīpako brāhmaṇo:**The brahmin of Veṭhadīpa also heard*";
P_HTM[2733]="*“bhagavā kira kusinārāyaṃ parinibbuto”ti.**that the Buddha had become fully extinguished at Kusinārā.*";
P_HTM[2734]="*Atha kho veṭṭhadīpako brāhmaṇo kosinārakānaṃ mallānaṃ dūtaṃ pāhesi:**He sent an envoy to the Mallas of Kusinārā:*";
P_HTM[2735]="*“bhagavāpi khattiyo ahampismi brāhmaṇo, ahampi arahāmi bhagavato sarīrānaṃ bhāgaṃ, ahampi bhagavato sarīrānaṃ thūpañca mahañca karissāmī”ti.**“The Buddha was an aristocrat, and I am a brahmin. I too deserve a share of the Buddha’s relics. I will build a large monument for them.”*";
P_HTM[2736]="*Assosuṃ kho pāveyyakā mallā:**The Mallas of Pāvā also heard*";
P_HTM[2737]="*“bhagavā kira kusinārāyaṃ parinibbuto”ti.**that the Buddha had become fully extinguished at Kusinārā.*";
P_HTM[2738]="*Atha kho pāveyyakā mallā kosinārakānaṃ mallānaṃ dūtaṃ pāhesuṃ:**They sent an envoy to the Mallas of Kusinārā:*";
P_HTM[2739]="*“bhagavāpi khattiyo mayampi khattiyā, mayampi arahāma bhagavato sarīrānaṃ bhāgaṃ, mayampi bhagavato sarīrānaṃ thūpañca mahañca karissāmā”ti.**“The Buddha was an aristocrat, and so are we. We too deserve a share of the Buddha’s relics. We will build a large monument for them.”*";
P_HTM[2740]="*Evaṃ vutte, kosinārakā mallā te saṅghe gaṇe etadavocuṃ:**When they had spoken, the Mallas of Kusinārā said to those various groups:*";
P_HTM[2741]="*“bhagavā amhākaṃ gāmakkhette parinibbuto, na mayaṃ dassāma bhagavato sarīrānaṃ bhāgan”ti.**“The Buddha became fully extinguished in our village district. We will not give away a share of his relics.”*";
P_HTM[2742]="*Evaṃ vutte, doṇo brāhmaṇo te saṅghe gaṇe etadavoca:**Then Doṇa the brahmin said to those various groups:*";
P_HTM[2743]="*“Suṇantu bhonto mama ekavācaṃ,**“Hear, sirs, a single word from me.*";
P_HTM[2744]="*Amhāka buddho ahu khantivādo;**Our Buddha’s teaching was acceptance.*";
P_HTM[2745]="*Na hi sādhu yaṃ uttamapuggalassa,**It would not be good to fight over*";
P_HTM[2746]="*Sarīrabhāge siyā sampahāro.**a share of the supreme person’s relics.*";
P_HTM[2747]="*Sabbeva bhonto sahitā samaggā,**Let us make eight portions, good sirs,*";
P_HTM[2748]="*Sammodamānā karomaṭṭhabhāge;**rejoicing in unity and harmony.*";
P_HTM[2749]="*Vitthārikā hontu disāsu thūpā,**Let there be monuments far and wide,*";
P_HTM[2750]="*Bahū janā cakkhumato pasannā”ti.**so many folk may gain faith in the Seer!”*";
P_HTM[2751]="*“Tena hi, brāhmaṇa, tvaññeva bhagavato sarīrāni aṭṭhadhā samaṃ savibhattaṃ vibhajāhī”ti.**“Well then, brahmin, you yourself should fairly divide the Buddha’s relics in eight portions.”*";
P_HTM[2752]="*“Evaṃ, bho”ti kho doṇo brāhmaṇo tesaṃ saṅghānaṃ gaṇānaṃ paṭissutvā bhagavato sarīrāni aṭṭhadhā samaṃ suvibhattaṃ vibhajitvā te saṅghe gaṇe etadavoca:**“Yes, sirs,” replied Doṇa to those various groups. He divided the relics as asked and said to them,*";
P_HTM[2753]="*“imaṃ me bhonto tumbaṃ dadantu ahampi tumbassa thūpañca mahañca karissāmī”ti.**“Sirs, please give me the urn, and I shall build a large monument for it.”*";
P_HTM[2754]="*Adaṃsu kho te doṇassa brāhmaṇassa tumbaṃ.**So they gave Doṇa the urn.*";
P_HTM[2755]="*Assosuṃ kho pippalivaniyā moriyā:**The Moras of Pippalivana heard*";
P_HTM[2756]="*“bhagavā kira kusinārāyaṃ parinibbuto”ti.**that the Buddha had become fully extinguished at Kusinārā.*";
P_HTM[2757]="*Atha kho pippalivaniyā moriyā kosinārakānaṃ mallānaṃ dūtaṃ pāhesuṃ:**They sent an envoy to the Mallas of Kusinārā:*";
P_HTM[2758]="*“bhagavāpi khattiyo mayampi khattiyā, mayampi arahāma bhagavato sarīrānaṃ bhāgaṃ, mayampi bhagavato sarīrānaṃ thūpañca mahañca karissāmā”ti.**“The Buddha was an aristocrat, and so are we. We too deserve a share of the Buddha’s relics. We will build a large monument for them.”*";
P_HTM[2759]="*“Natthi bhagavato sarīrānaṃ bhāgo, vibhattāni bhagavato sarīrāni.**“There is no portion of the Buddha’s relics left, they have already been portioned out.*";
P_HTM[2760]="*Ito aṅgāraṃ harathā”ti.**Here, take the embers.”*";
P_HTM[2761]="*Te tato aṅgāraṃ hariṃsu.**So they took the embers.*";
P_HTM[2762]="*40. Dhātuthūpapūjā**40. Venerating the Relics*";
P_HTM[2763]="*Atha kho rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto rājagahe bhagavato sarīrānaṃ thūpañca mahañca akāsi.**Then King Ajātasattu of Magadha,*";
P_HTM[2764]="*Vesālikāpi licchavī vesāliyaṃ bhagavato sarīrānaṃ thūpañca mahañca akaṃsu.**the Licchavis of Vesālī,*";
P_HTM[2765]="*Kapilavatthuvāsīpi sakyā kapilavatthusmiṃ bhagavato sarīrānaṃ thūpañca mahañca akaṃsu.**the Sakyans of Kapilavatthu,*";
P_HTM[2766]="*Allakappakāpi bulayo allakappe bhagavato sarīrānaṃ thūpañca mahañca akaṃsu.**the Bulas of Allakappa,*";
P_HTM[2767]="*Rāmagāmakāpi koḷiyā rāmagāme bhagavato sarīrānaṃ thūpañca mahañca akaṃsu.**the Koḷiyans of Rāmagāma,*";
P_HTM[2768]="*Veṭṭhadīpakopi brāhmaṇo veṭṭhadīpe bhagavato sarīrānaṃ thūpañca mahañca akāsi.**the brahmin of Veṭhadīpa,*";
P_HTM[2769]="*Pāveyyakāpi mallā pāvāyaṃ bhagavato sarīrānaṃ thūpañca mahañca akaṃsu.**the Mallas of Pāvā,*";
P_HTM[2770]="*Kosinārakāpi mallā kusinārāyaṃ bhagavato sarīrānaṃ thūpañca mahañca akaṃsu.**the Mallas of Kusinārā,*";
P_HTM[2771]="*Doṇopi brāhmaṇo tumbassa thūpañca mahañca akāsi.**the brahmin Doṇa,*";
P_HTM[2772]="*Pippalivaniyāpi moriyā pippalivane aṅgārānaṃ thūpañca mahañca akaṃsu.**and the Moriyas of Pippalivana built large monuments for their portions and held festivals in their honor.*";
P_HTM[2773]="*Iti aṭṭha sarīrathūpā navamo tumbathūpo dasamo aṅgārathūpo.**Thus there were eight monuments for the relics, a ninth for the urn, and a tenth for the embers.*";
P_HTM[2774]="*Evametaṃ bhūtapubbanti.**That is how it was in those days.*";
P_HTM[2775]="*Aṭṭhadoṇaṃ cakkhumato sarīraṃ,**There were eight shares of the Seer’s relics.*";
P_HTM[2776]="*Sattadoṇaṃ jambudīpe mahenti;**Seven were worshipped throughout India.*";
P_HTM[2777]="*Ekañca doṇaṃ purisavaruttamassa,**But one share of the most excellent of men*";
P_HTM[2778]="*Rāmagāme nāgarājā maheti.**was worshipped in Rāmagāma by a dragon king.*";
P_HTM[2779]="*Ekāhi dāṭhā tidivehi pūjitā,**One tooth is venerated by the gods of the Three and Thirty,*";
P_HTM[2780]="*Ekā pana gandhārapure mahīyati;**and one is worshipped in the city of Gandhāra;*";
P_HTM[2781]="*Kāliṅgarañño vijite punekaṃ,**another one in the realm of the Kaliṅga King,*";
P_HTM[2782]="*Ekaṃ pana nāgarājā maheti.**and one is worshipped by a dragon king.*";
P_HTM[2783]="*Tasseva tejena ayaṃ vasundharā,**Through their glory this rich earth*";
P_HTM[2784]="*Āyāgaseṭṭhehi mahī alaṅkatā;**is adorned with the best of offerings.*";
P_HTM[2785]="*Evaṃ imaṃ cakkhumato sarīraṃ,**Thus the Seer’s corpse*";
P_HTM[2786]="*Susakkataṃ sakkatasakkatehi.**is well honored by the honorable.*";
P_HTM[2787]="*Devindanāgindanarindapūjito,**It’s venerated by lords of gods, dragons, and spirits;*";
P_HTM[2788]="*Manussindaseṭṭhehi tatheva pūjito;**and likewise venerated by the finest lords of men.*";
P_HTM[2789]="*Taṃ vandatha pañjalikā labhitvā,**Honor it with joined palms when you get the chance,*";
P_HTM[2790]="*Buddho have kappasatehi dullabhoti.**for a Buddha is rare even in a hundred eons.*";
P_HTM[2791]="*Cattālīsa samā dantā,**Altogether forty even teeth,*";
P_HTM[2792]="*kesā lomā ca sabbaso;**and the body hair and head hair,*";
P_HTM[2793]="*Devā hariṃsu ekekaṃ,**were carried off individually by gods*";
P_HTM[2794]="*cakkavāḷaparamparāti.**across the universe.*";
P_HTM[2795]="*Mahāparinibbānasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2796]="*17. Mahāsudassanasutta  ** King Mahāsudassana *";
P_HTM[2797]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[2798]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā kusinārāyaṃ viharati upavattane mallānaṃ sālavane antarena yamakasālānaṃ parinibbānasamaye.**At one time the Buddha was staying between a pair of sal trees in the sal forest of the Mallas at Upavattana near Kusinārā at the time of his final extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[2799]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Venerable Ānanda went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[2800]="*“mā, bhante, bhagavā imasmiṃ khuddakanagarake ujjaṅgalanagarake sākhānagarake parinibbāyi.**“Sir, please don’t become fully extinguished in this little hamlet, this jungle hamlet, this branch hamlet.*";
P_HTM[2801]="*Santi, bhante, aññāni mahānagarāni.**There are other great cities such as*";
P_HTM[2802]="*Seyyathidaṃ—campā, rājagahaṃ, sāvatthi, sāketaṃ, kosambī, bārāṇasī;**Campā, Rājagaha, Sāvatthī, Sāketa, Kosambī, and Benares.*";
P_HTM[2803]="*ettha bhagavā parinibbāyatu.**Let the Buddha become fully extinguished there.*";
P_HTM[2804]="*Ettha bahū khattiyamahāsālā brāhmaṇamahāsālā gahapatimahāsālā tathāgate abhippasannā, te tathāgatassa sarīrapūjaṃ karissantī”ti.**There are many well-to-do aristocrats, brahmins, and householders there who are devoted to the Buddha. They will perform the rites of venerating the Realized One’s corpse.”*";
P_HTM[2805]="*“Mā hevaṃ, ānanda, avaca; mā hevaṃ, ānanda, avaca:**“Don’t say that, Ānanda! Don’t say that*";
P_HTM[2806]="*‘khuddakanagarakaṃ ujjaṅgalanagarakaṃ sākhānagarakan’ti.**this is a little hamlet, a jungle hamlet, a branch hamlet.*";
P_HTM[2807]="*1. Kusāvatīrājadhānī**1. The Capital City of Kusāvatī*";
P_HTM[2808]="*Bhūtapubbaṃ, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano nāma ahosi khattiyo muddhāvasitto cāturanto vijitāvī janapadatthāvariyappatto.**Once upon a time there was a king named Mahāsudassana whose dominion extended to all four sides, and who achieved stability in the country.*";
P_HTM[2809]="*Rañño, ānanda, mahāsudassanassa ayaṃ kusinārā kusāvatī nāma rājadhānī ahosi.**His capital was this Kusinārā, which at the time was named Kusāvatī.*";
P_HTM[2810]="*Puratthimena ca pacchimena ca dvādasayojanāni āyāmena, uttarena ca dakkhiṇena ca sattayojanāni vitthārena.**It stretched for twelve leagues from east to west, and seven leagues from north to south.*";
P_HTM[2811]="*Kusāvatī, ānanda, rājadhānī iddhā ceva ahosi phītā ca bahujanā ca ākiṇṇamanussā ca subhikkhā ca.**The royal capital of Kusāvatī was successful, prosperous, populous, full of people, with plenty of food.*";
P_HTM[2812]="*Seyyathāpi, ānanda, devānaṃ āḷakamandā nāma rājadhānī iddhā ceva hoti phītā ca bahujanā ca ākiṇṇayakkhā ca subhikkhā ca;**It was just like Āḷakamandā, the royal capital of the gods, which is successful, prosperous, populous, full of spirits, with plenty of food.*";
P_HTM[2813]="*evameva kho, ānanda, kusāvatī rājadhānī iddhā ceva ahosi phītā ca bahujanā ca ākiṇṇamanussā ca subhikkhā ca.* **";
P_HTM[2814]="*Kusāvatī, ānanda, rājadhānī dasahi saddehi avivittā ahosi divā ceva rattiñca, seyyathidaṃ—**Kusāvatī was never free of ten sounds by day or night, namely:*";
P_HTM[2815]="*hatthisaddena assasaddena rathasaddena bherisaddena mudiṅgasaddena vīṇāsaddena gītasaddena saṅkhasaddena sammasaddena pāṇitāḷasaddena ‘asnātha pivatha khādathā’ti dasamena saddena.**the sound of elephants, horses, chariots, drums, clay drums, arched harps, singing, horns, gongs, and handbells; and the cry, ‘Eat, drink, be merry!’ as the tenth.*";
P_HTM[2816]="*Kusāvatī, ānanda, rājadhānī sattahi pākārehi parikkhittā ahosi.**Kusāvatī was encircled by seven ramparts:*";
P_HTM[2817]="*Eko pākāro sovaṇṇamayo, eko rūpiyamayo, eko veḷuriyamayo, eko phalikamayo, eko lohitaṅkamayo, eko masāragallamayo, eko sabbaratanamayo.**one made of gold, one made of silver, one made of beryl, one made of crystal, one made of ruby, one made of emerald, and one made of all precious things.*";
P_HTM[2818]="*Kusāvatiyā, ānanda, rājadhāniyā catunnaṃ vaṇṇānaṃ dvārāni ahesuṃ.**It had four gates,*";
P_HTM[2819]="*Ekaṃ dvāraṃ sovaṇṇamayaṃ, ekaṃ rūpiyamayaṃ, ekaṃ veḷuriyamayaṃ, ekaṃ phalikamayaṃ.**made of gold, silver, beryl, and crystal.*";
P_HTM[2820]="*Ekekasmiṃ dvāre satta satta esikā nikhātā ahesuṃ tiporisaṅgā tiporisanikhātā dvādasaporisā ubbedhena.**At each gate there were seven pillars, three fathoms deep and four fathoms high,*";
P_HTM[2821]="*Ekā esikā sovaṇṇamayā, ekā rūpiyamayā, ekā veḷuriyamayā, ekā phalikamayā, ekā lohitaṅkamayā, ekā masāragallamayā, ekā sabbaratanamayā.**made of gold, silver, beryl, crystal, ruby, emerald, and all precious things.*";
P_HTM[2822]="*Kusāvatī, ānanda, rājadhānī sattahi tālapantīhi parikkhittā ahosi.**It was surrounded by seven rows of palm trees,*";
P_HTM[2823]="*Ekā tālapanti sovaṇṇamayā, ekā rūpiyamayā, ekā veḷuriyamayā, ekā phalikamayā, ekā lohitaṅkamayā, ekā masāragallamayā, ekā sabbaratanamayā.**made of gold, silver, beryl, crystal, ruby, emerald, and all precious things.*";
P_HTM[2824]="*Sovaṇṇamayassa tālassa sovaṇṇamayo khandho ahosi, rūpiyamayāni pattāni ca phalāni ca.**The golden palms had trunks of gold, and leaves and fruits of silver.*";
P_HTM[2825]="*Rūpiyamayassa tālassa rūpiyamayo khandho ahosi, sovaṇṇamayāni pattāni ca phalāni ca.**The silver palms had trunks of silver, and leaves and fruits of gold.*";
P_HTM[2826]="*Veḷuriyamayassa tālassa veḷuriyamayo khandho ahosi, phalikamayāni pattāni ca phalāni ca.**The beryl palms had trunks of beryl, and leaves and fruits of crystal.*";
P_HTM[2827]="*Phalikamayassa tālassa phalikamayo khandho ahosi, veḷuriyamayāni pattāni ca phalāni ca.**The crystal palms had trunks of crystal, and leaves and fruits of beryl.*";
P_HTM[2828]="*Lohitaṅkamayassa tālassa lohitaṅkamayo khandho ahosi, masāragallamayāni pattāni ca phalāni ca.**The ruby palms had trunks of ruby, and leaves and fruits of emerald.*";
P_HTM[2829]="*Masāragallamayassa tālassa masāragallamayo khandho ahosi, lohitaṅkamayāni pattāni ca phalāni ca.**The emerald palms had trunks of emerald, and leaves and fruits of ruby.*";
P_HTM[2830]="*Sabbaratanamayassa tālassa sabbaratanamayo khandho ahosi, sabbaratanamayāni pattāni ca phalāni ca.**The palms of all precious things had trunks of all precious things, and leaves and fruits of all precious things.*";
P_HTM[2831]="*Tāsaṃ kho panānanda, tālapantīnaṃ vāteritānaṃ saddo ahosi vaggu ca rajanīyo ca khamanīyo ca madanīyo ca.**When those rows of palm trees were blown by the wind they sounded graceful, tantalizing, sensuous, lovely, and intoxicating,*";
P_HTM[2832]="*Seyyathāpi, ānanda, pañcaṅgikassa tūriyassa suvinītassa suppaṭitāḷitassa sukusalehi samannāhatassa saddo hoti vaggu ca rajanīyo ca khamanīyo ca madanīyo ca;**like a quintet made up of skilled musicians who had practiced well and kept excellent rhythm.*";
P_HTM[2833]="*evameva kho, ānanda, tāsaṃ tālapantīnaṃ vāteritānaṃ saddo ahosi vaggu ca rajanīyo ca khamanīyo ca madanīyo ca.* **";
P_HTM[2834]="*Ye kho panānanda, tena samayena kusāvatiyā rājadhāniyā dhuttā ahesuṃ soṇḍā pipāsā, te tāsaṃ tālapantīnaṃ vāteritānaṃ saddena paricāresuṃ.**And any addicts, libertines, or drunkards in Kusāvatī at that time were entertained by that sound.*";
P_HTM[2835]="*2. Sattaratanasamannāgata**2. The Seven Treasures*";
P_HTM[2836]="*2.1. Cakkaratana**2.1. The Wheel Treasure*";
P_HTM[2837]="*Rājā, ānanda, mahāsudassano sattahi ratanehi samannāgato ahosi catūhi ca iddhīhi.**King Mahāsudassana possessed seven treasures and four blessings.*";
P_HTM[2838]="*Katamehi sattahi?**What seven?*";
P_HTM[2839]="*Idhānanda, rañño mahāsudassanassa tadahuposathe pannarase sīsaṃnhātassa uposathikassa uparipāsādavaragatassa**On a fifteenth day sabbath, King Mahāsudassana had bathed his head and gone upstairs in the stilt longhouse to observe the sabbath.*";
P_HTM[2840]="*dibbaṃ cakkaratanaṃ pāturahosi sahassāraṃ sanemikaṃ sanābhikaṃ sabbākāraparipūraṃ.**And the heavenly wheel-treasure appeared to him, with a thousand spokes, with rim and hub, complete in every detail.*";
P_HTM[2841]="*Disvā rañño mahāsudassanassa etadahosi:**Seeing this, the king thought,*";
P_HTM[2842]="*‘sutaṃ kho pana metaṃ: “yassa rañño khattiyassa muddhāvasittassa tadahuposathe pannarase sīsaṃnhātassa uposathikassa uparipāsādavaragatassa dibbaṃ cakkaratanaṃ pātubhavati sahassāraṃ sanemikaṃ sanābhikaṃ sabbākāraparipūraṃ, so hoti rājā cakkavattī”ti.**‘I have heard that when the heavenly wheel-treasure appears to a king in this way, he becomes a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[2843]="*Assaṃ nu kho ahaṃ rājā cakkavattī’ti.**Am I then a wheel-turning monarch?’*";
P_HTM[2844]="*Atha kho, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano uṭṭhāyāsanā ekaṃsaṃ uttarāsaṅgaṃ karitvā vāmena hatthena suvaṇṇabhiṅkāraṃ gahetvā dakkhiṇena hatthena cakkaratanaṃ abbhukkiri:**Then King Mahāsudassana, rising from his seat and arranging his robe over one shoulder, took a ceremonial vase in his left hand and besprinkled the wheel-treasure with his right hand, saying:*";
P_HTM[2845]="*‘pavattatu bhavaṃ cakkaratanaṃ, abhivijinātu bhavaṃ cakkaratanan’ti.**‘Roll forth, O wheel-treasure! Triumph, O wheel-treasure!’*";
P_HTM[2846]="*Atha kho taṃ, ānanda, cakkaratanaṃ puratthimaṃ disaṃ pavatti, anvadeva rājā mahāsudassano saddhiṃ caturaṅginiyā senāya, yasmiṃ kho panānanda, padese cakkaratanaṃ patiṭṭhāsi, tattha rājā mahāsudassano vāsaṃ upagacchi saddhiṃ caturaṅginiyā senāya.**Then the wheel-treasure rolled towards the east. And the king followed it together with his army of four divisions. In whatever place the wheel-treasure stood still, there the king came to stay together with his army.*";
P_HTM[2847]="*Ye kho panānanda, puratthimāya disāya paṭirājāno, te rājānaṃ mahāsudassanaṃ upasaṅkamitvā evamāhaṃsu:**And any opposing rulers of the eastern quarter came to him and said,*";
P_HTM[2848]="*‘ehi kho, mahārāja, svāgataṃ te, mahārāja, sakaṃ te, mahārāja, anusāsa, mahārājā’ti.**‘Come, great king! Welcome, great king! We are yours, great king, instruct us.’*";
P_HTM[2849]="*Rājā mahāsudassano evamāha:**The king said,*";
P_HTM[2850]="*‘pāṇo na hantabbo, adinnaṃ na ādātabbaṃ, kāmesu micchā na caritabbā, musā na bhaṇitabbā, majjaṃ na pātabbaṃ, yathābhuttañca bhuñjathā’ti.**‘Do not kill living creatures. Do not steal. Do not commit sexual misconduct. Do not lie. Do not drink alcohol. Maintain the current level of taxation.’*";
P_HTM[2851]="*Ye kho panānanda, puratthimāya disāya paṭirājāno, te rañño mahāsudassanassa anuyantā ahesuṃ.**And so the opposing rulers of the eastern quarter became his vassals.*";
P_HTM[2852]="*Atha kho taṃ, ānanda, cakkaratanaṃ puratthimaṃ samuddaṃ ajjhogāhetvā paccuttaritvā dakkhiṇaṃ disaṃ pavatti … pe …**Then the wheel-treasure, having plunged into the eastern ocean and emerged again, rolled towards the south. …*";
P_HTM[2853]="*dakkhiṇaṃ samuddaṃ ajjhogāhetvā paccuttaritvā pacchimaṃ disaṃ pavatti … pe …**Having plunged into the southern ocean and emerged again, it rolled towards the west. …*";
P_HTM[2854]="*pacchimaṃ samuddaṃ ajjhogāhetvā paccuttaritvā uttaraṃ disaṃ pavatti, anvadeva rājā mahāsudassano saddhiṃ caturaṅginiyā senāya.**Having plunged into the western ocean and emerged again, it rolled towards the north, followed by the king together with his army of four divisions.*";
P_HTM[2855]="*Yasmiṃ kho panānanda, padese cakkaratanaṃ patiṭṭhāsi, tattha rājā mahāsudassano vāsaṃ upagacchi saddhiṃ caturaṅginiyā senāya.**In whatever place the wheel-treasure stood still, there the king came to stay together with his army.*";
P_HTM[2856]="*Ye kho panānanda, uttarāya disāya paṭirājāno, te rājānaṃ mahāsudassanaṃ upasaṅkamitvā evamāhaṃsu:**And any opposing rulers of the northern quarter came to him and said,*";
P_HTM[2857]="*‘ehi kho, mahārāja, svāgataṃ te, mahārāja, sakaṃ te, mahārāja, anusāsa, mahārājā’ti.**‘Come, great king! Welcome, great king! We are yours, great king, instruct us.’*";
P_HTM[2858]="*Rājā mahāsudassano evamāha:**The king said,*";
P_HTM[2859]="*‘pāṇo na hantabbo, adinnaṃ na ādātabbaṃ, kāmesu micchā na caritabbā, musā na bhaṇitabbā, majjaṃ na pātabbaṃ, yathābhuttañca bhuñjathā’ti.**‘Do not kill living creatures. Do not steal. Do not commit sexual misconduct. Do not lie. Do not drink alcohol. Maintain the current level of taxation.’*";
P_HTM[2860]="*Ye kho panānanda, uttarāya disāya paṭirājāno, te rañño mahāsudassanassa anuyantā ahesuṃ.**And so the opposing rulers of the northern quarter became his vassals.*";
P_HTM[2861]="*Atha kho taṃ, ānanda, cakkaratanaṃ samuddapariyantaṃ pathaviṃ abhivijinitvā kusāvatiṃ rājadhāniṃ paccāgantvā rañño mahāsudassanassa antepuradvāre atthakaraṇapamukhe akkhāhataṃ maññe aṭṭhāsi rañño mahāsudassanassa antepuraṃ upasobhayamānaṃ.**And then the wheel-treasure, having triumphed over this land surrounded by ocean, returned to the royal capital of Kusāvatī. There it stood still by the gate to Mahāsudassana’s royal compound at the High Court as if fixed to an axle, illuminating the royal compound.*";
P_HTM[2862]="*Rañño, ānanda, mahāsudassanassa evarūpaṃ cakkaratanaṃ pāturahosi.**Such is the wheel-treasure that appeared to King Mahāsudassana.*";
P_HTM[2863]="*2.2. Hatthiratana**2.2. The Elephant Treasure*";
P_HTM[2864]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, rañño mahāsudassanassa hatthiratanaṃ pāturahosi**Next, the elephant-treasure appeared to King Mahāsudassana.*";
P_HTM[2865]="*sabbaseto sattappatiṭṭho iddhimā vehāsaṅgamo uposatho nāma nāgarājā.**It was an all-white sky-walker with psychic power, touching the ground in seven places, a king of elephants named Sabbath.*";
P_HTM[2866]="*Taṃ disvā rañño mahāsudassanassa cittaṃ pasīdi:**Seeing him, the king was impressed,*";
P_HTM[2867]="*‘bhaddakaṃ vata bho hatthiyānaṃ, sace damathaṃ upeyyā’ti.**‘This would truly be a fine elephant vehicle, if he would submit to taming.’*";
P_HTM[2868]="*Atha kho taṃ, ānanda, hatthiratanaṃ—seyyathāpi nāma gandhahatthājāniyo dīgharattaṃ suparidanto; evameva damathaṃ upagacchi.**Then the elephant-treasure submitted to taming, as if he was a fine thoroughbred elephant that had been tamed for a long time.*";
P_HTM[2869]="*Bhūtapubbaṃ, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano tameva hatthiratanaṃ vīmaṃsamāno pubbaṇhasamayaṃ abhiruhitvā samuddapariyantaṃ pathaviṃ anuyāyitvā kusāvatiṃ rājadhāniṃ paccāgantvā pātarāsamakāsi.**Once it so happened that King Mahāsudassana, testing that same elephant-treasure, mounted him in the morning and traversed the land surrounded by ocean before returning to the royal capital in time for breakfast.*";
P_HTM[2870]="*Rañño, ānanda, mahāsudassanassa evarūpaṃ hatthiratanaṃ pāturahosi.**Such is the elephant-treasure that appeared to King Mahāsudassana.*";
P_HTM[2871]="*2.3. Assaratana**2.3. The Horse-Treasure*";
P_HTM[2872]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, rañño mahāsudassanassa assaratanaṃ pāturahosi**Next, the horse-treasure appeared to King Mahāsudassana.*";
P_HTM[2873]="*sabbaseto kāḷasīso muñjakeso iddhimā vehāsaṅgamo valāhako nāma assarājā.**It was an all-white sky-walker with psychic power, with head of black and mane like woven reeds, a royal steed named Thundercloud.*";
P_HTM[2874]="*Taṃ disvā rañño mahāsudassanassa cittaṃ pasīdi:**Seeing him, the king was impressed,*";
P_HTM[2875]="*‘bhaddakaṃ vata bho assayānaṃ sace damathaṃ upeyyā’ti.**‘This would truly be a fine horse vehicle, if he would submit to taming.’*";
P_HTM[2876]="*Atha kho taṃ, ānanda, assaratanaṃ seyyathāpi nāma bhaddo assājāniyo dīgharattaṃ suparidanto; evameva damathaṃ upagacchi.**Then the horse-treasure submitted to taming, as if he was a fine thoroughbred horse that had been tamed for a long time.*";
P_HTM[2877]="*Bhūtapubbaṃ, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano tameva assaratanaṃ vīmaṃsamāno pubbaṇhasamayaṃ abhiruhitvā samuddapariyantaṃ pathaviṃ anuyāyitvā kusāvatiṃ rājadhāniṃ paccāgantvā pātarāsamakāsi.**Once it so happened that King Mahāsudassana, testing that same horse-treasure, mounted him in the morning and traversed the land surrounded by ocean before returning to the royal capital in time for breakfast.*";
P_HTM[2878]="*Rañño, ānanda, mahāsudassanassa evarūpaṃ assaratanaṃ pāturahosi.**Such is the horse-treasure that appeared to King Mahāsudassana.*";
P_HTM[2879]="*2.4. Maṇiratana**2.4. The Jewel Treasure*";
P_HTM[2880]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, rañño mahāsudassanassa maṇiratanaṃ pāturahosi.**Next, the jewel-treasure appeared to King Mahāsudassana.*";
P_HTM[2881]="*So ahosi maṇi veḷuriyo subho jātimā aṭṭhaṃso suparikammakato accho vippasanno anāvilo sabbākārasampanno.**It was a beryl gem that was naturally beautiful, eight-faceted, well-worked, transparent, clear, and unclouded, endowed with all good qualities.*";
P_HTM[2882]="*Tassa kho panānanda, maṇiratanassa ābhā samantā yojanaṃ phuṭā ahosi.**And the radiance of that jewel spread all-round for a league.*";
P_HTM[2883]="*Bhūtapubbaṃ, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano tameva maṇiratanaṃ vīmaṃsamāno caturaṅginiṃ senaṃ sannayhitvā maṇiṃ dhajaggaṃ āropetvā rattandhakāratimisāya pāyāsi.**Once it so happened that King Mahāsudassana, testing that same jewel-treasure, mobilized his army of four divisions and, with the jewel hoisted on his banner, set out in the dark of the night.*";
P_HTM[2884]="*Ye kho panānanda, samantā gāmā ahesuṃ, te tenobhāsena kammante payojesuṃ divāti maññamānā.**Then the villagers around them set off to work, thinking that it was day.*";
P_HTM[2885]="*Rañño, ānanda, mahāsudassanassa evarūpaṃ maṇiratanaṃ pāturahosi.**Such is the jewel-treasure that appeared to King Mahāsudassana.*";
P_HTM[2886]="*2.5. Itthiratana**2.5. The Woman Treasure*";
P_HTM[2887]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, rañño mahāsudassanassa itthiratanaṃ pāturahosi**Next, the woman-treasure appeared to King Mahāsudassana.*";
P_HTM[2888]="*abhirūpā dassanīyā pāsādikā paramāya vaṇṇapokkharatāya samannāgatā nātidīghā nātirassā nātikisā nātithūlā nātikāḷikā nāccodātā atikkantā mānusivaṇṇaṃ appattā dibbavaṇṇaṃ.**She was attractive, good-looking, lovely, of surpassing beauty. She was neither too tall nor too short; neither too thin nor too fat; neither too dark nor too light. She outdid human beauty without reaching divine beauty.*";
P_HTM[2889]="*Tassa kho panānanda, itthiratanassa evarūpo kāyasamphasso hoti, seyyathāpi nāma tūlapicuno vā kappāsapicuno vā.**And her touch was like a tuft of cotton-wool or kapok.*";
P_HTM[2890]="*Tassa kho panānanda, itthiratanassa sīte uṇhāni gattāni honti, uṇhe sītāni.**When it was cool her limbs were warm, and when it was warm her limbs were cool.*";
P_HTM[2891]="*Tassa kho panānanda, itthiratanassa kāyato candanagandho vāyati, mukhato uppalagandho.**The fragrance of sandal floated from her body, and lotus from her mouth.*";
P_HTM[2892]="*Taṃ kho panānanda, itthiratanaṃ rañño mahāsudassanassa pubbuṭṭhāyinī ahosi pacchānipātinī kiṃkārapaṭissāvinī manāpacārinī piyavādinī.**She got up before the king and went to bed after him, and was obliging, behaving nicely and speaking politely.*";
P_HTM[2893]="*Taṃ kho panānanda, itthiratanaṃ rājānaṃ mahāsudassanaṃ manasāpi no aticari, kuto pana kāyena.**The woman-treasure did not betray the wheel-turning monarch even in thought, still less in deed.*";
P_HTM[2894]="*Rañño, ānanda, mahāsudassanassa evarūpaṃ itthiratanaṃ pāturahosi.**Such is the woman-treasure that appeared to King Mahāsudassana.*";
P_HTM[2895]="*2.6. Gahapatiratana**2.6. The Householder Treasure*";
P_HTM[2896]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, rañño mahāsudassanassa gahapatiratanaṃ pāturahosi.**Next, the householder-treasure appeared to King Mahāsudassana.*";
P_HTM[2897]="*Tassa kammavipākajaṃ dibbacakkhu pāturahosi yena nidhiṃ passati sassāmikampi assāmikampi.**The power of clairvoyance manifested in him as a result of past deeds, by which he sees hidden treasure, both owned and ownerless.*";
P_HTM[2898]="*So rājānaṃ mahāsudassanaṃ upasaṅkamitvā evamāha:**He approached the king and said,*";
P_HTM[2899]="*‘appossukko tvaṃ, deva, hohi, ahaṃ te dhanena dhanakaraṇīyaṃ karissāmī’ti.**‘Relax, sire. I will take care of the treasury.’*";
P_HTM[2900]="*Bhūtapubbaṃ, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano tameva gahapatiratanaṃ vīmaṃsamāno nāvaṃ abhiruhitvā majjhe gaṅgāya nadiyā sotaṃ ogāhitvā gahapatiratanaṃ etadavoca:**Once it so happened that the wheel-turning monarch, testing that same householder-treasure, boarded a boat and sailed to the middle of the Ganges river. Then he said to the householder-treasure,*";
P_HTM[2901]="*‘attho me, gahapati, hiraññasuvaṇṇenā’ti.**‘Householder, I need gold coins and bullion.’*";
P_HTM[2902]="*‘Tena hi, mahārāja, ekaṃ tīraṃ nāvā upetū’ti.**‘Well then, great king, draw the boat up to one shore.’*";
P_HTM[2903]="*‘Idheva me, gahapati, attho hiraññasuvaṇṇenā’ti.**‘It’s right here, householder, that I need gold coins and bullion.’*";
P_HTM[2904]="*Atha kho taṃ, ānanda, gahapatiratanaṃ ubhohi hatthehi udakaṃ omasitvā pūraṃ hiraññasuvaṇṇassa kumbhiṃ uddharitvā rājānaṃ mahāsudassanaṃ etadavoca:**Then that householder-treasure, immersing both hands in the water, pulled up a pot full of gold coin and bullion, and said to the king,*";
P_HTM[2905]="*‘alamettāvatā, mahārāja, katamettāvatā, mahārāja, pūjitamettāvatā, mahārājā’ti?**‘Is this sufficient, great king? Has enough been done, great king, enough offered?’*";
P_HTM[2906]="*Rājā mahāsudassano evamāha:**The king said,*";
P_HTM[2907]="*‘alamettāvatā, gahapati, katamettāvatā, gahapati, pūjitamettāvatā, gahapatī’ti.**‘That is sufficient, householder. Enough has been done, enough offered.’*";
P_HTM[2908]="*Rañño, ānanda, mahāsudassanassa evarūpaṃ gahapatiratanaṃ pāturahosi.**Such is the householder-treasure that appeared to King Mahāsudassana.*";
P_HTM[2909]="*2.7. Pariṇāyakaratana**2.7. The Counselor Treasure*";
P_HTM[2910]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, rañño mahāsudassanassa pariṇāyakaratanaṃ pāturahosi**Next, the counselor-treasure appeared to King Mahāsudassana.*";
P_HTM[2911]="*paṇḍito viyatto medhāvī paṭibalo rājānaṃ mahāsudassanaṃ upayāpetabbaṃ upayāpetuṃ, apayāpetabbaṃ apayāpetuṃ, ṭhapetabbaṃ ṭhapetuṃ.**He was astute, competent, intelligent, and capable of getting the king to appoint who should be appointed, dismiss who should be dismissed, and retain who should be retained.*";
P_HTM[2912]="*So rājānaṃ mahāsudassanaṃ upasaṅkamitvā evamāha:**He approached the king and said,*";
P_HTM[2913]="*‘appossukko tvaṃ, deva, hohi, ahamanusāsissāmī’ti.**‘Relax, sire. I shall issue instructions.’*";
P_HTM[2914]="*Rañño, ānanda, mahāsudassanassa evarūpaṃ pariṇāyakaratanaṃ pāturahosi.**Such is the counselor-treasure that appeared to King Mahāsudassana.*";
P_HTM[2915]="*Rājā, ānanda, mahāsudassano imehi sattahi ratanehi samannāgato ahosi.**These are the seven treasures possessed by King Mahāsudassana.*";
P_HTM[2916]="*3. Catuiddhisamannāgata**3. The Four Blessings*";
P_HTM[2917]="*Rājā, ānanda, mahāsudassano catūhi iddhīhi samannāgato ahosi.**King Mahāsudassana possessed four blessings.*";
P_HTM[2918]="*Katamāhi catūhi iddhīhi?**And what are the four blessings?*";
P_HTM[2919]="*Idhānanda, rājā mahāsudassano abhirūpo ahosi dassanīyo pāsādiko paramāya vaṇṇapokkharatāya samannāgato ativiya aññehi manussehi.**He was attractive, good-looking, lovely, of surpassing beauty, more so than other people.*";
P_HTM[2920]="*Rājā, ānanda, mahāsudassano imāya paṭhamāya iddhiyā samannāgato ahosi.**This is the first blessing.*";
P_HTM[2921]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano dīghāyuko ahosi ciraṭṭhitiko ativiya aññehi manussehi.**Furthermore, he was long-lived, more so than other people.*";
P_HTM[2922]="*Rājā, ānanda, mahāsudassano imāya dutiyāya iddhiyā samannāgato ahosi.**This is the second blessing.*";
P_HTM[2923]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano appābādho ahosi appātaṅko samavepākiniyā gahaṇiyā samannāgato nātisītāya nāccuṇhāya ativiya aññehi manussehi.**Furthermore, he was rarely ill or unwell, and his stomach digested well, being neither too hot nor too cold, more so than other people.*";
P_HTM[2924]="*Rājā, ānanda, mahāsudassano imāya tatiyāya iddhiyā samannāgato ahosi.**This is the third blessing.*";
P_HTM[2925]="*Puna caparaṃ, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano brāhmaṇagahapatikānaṃ piyo ahosi manāpo.**Furthermore, he was as dear and beloved to the brahmins and householders*";
P_HTM[2926]="*Seyyathāpi, ānanda, pitā puttānaṃ piyo hoti manāpo;**as a father is to his children.*";
P_HTM[2927]="*evameva kho, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano brāhmaṇagahapatikānaṃ piyo ahosi manāpo.* **";
P_HTM[2928]="*Raññopi, ānanda, mahāsudassanassa brāhmaṇagahapatikā piyā ahesuṃ manāpā.**And the brahmins and householders were as dear to the king*";
P_HTM[2929]="*Seyyathāpi, ānanda, pitu puttā piyā honti manāpā;**as children are to their father.*";
P_HTM[2930]="*evameva kho, ānanda, raññopi mahāsudassanassa brāhmaṇagahapatikā piyā ahesuṃ manāpā.* **";
P_HTM[2931]="*Bhūtapubbaṃ, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano caturaṅginiyā senāya uyyānabhūmiṃ niyyāsi.**Once it so happened that King Mahāsudassana went with his army of four divisions to visit a park.*";
P_HTM[2932]="*Atha kho, ānanda, brāhmaṇagahapatikā rājānaṃ mahāsudassanaṃ upasaṅkamitvā evamāhaṃsu:**Then the brahmins and householders went up to him and said,*";
P_HTM[2933]="*‘ataramāno, deva, yāhi, yathā taṃ mayaṃ cirataraṃ passeyyāmā’ti.**‘Slow down, Your Majesty, so we may see you longer!’*";
P_HTM[2934]="*Rājāpi, ānanda, mahāsudassano sārathiṃ āmantesi:**And the king addressed his charioteer,*";
P_HTM[2935]="*‘ataramāno, sārathi, rathaṃ pesehi, yathā ahaṃ brāhmaṇagahapatike cirataraṃ passeyyan’ti.**‘Drive slowly, charioteer, so I can see the brahmins and householders longer!’*";
P_HTM[2936]="*Rājā, ānanda, mahāsudassano imāya catutthiyā iddhiyā samannāgato ahosi.**This is the fourth blessing.*";
P_HTM[2937]="*Rājā, ānanda, mahāsudassano imāhi catūhi iddhīhi samannāgato ahosi.**These are the four blessings possessed by King Mahāsudassana.*";
P_HTM[2938]="*4. Dhammapāsādapokkharaṇī**4. Lotus Ponds in the Palace of Principle*";
P_HTM[2939]="*Atha kho, ānanda, rañño mahāsudassanassa etadahosi:**Then King Mahāsudassana thought,*";
P_HTM[2940]="*‘yannūnāhaṃ imāsu tālantarikāsu dhanusate dhanusate pokkharaṇiyo māpeyyan’ti.**‘Why don’t I have lotus ponds built between the palms, at intervals of a hundred bow lengths?’*";
P_HTM[2941]="*Māpesi kho, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano tāsu tālantarikāsu dhanusate dhanusate pokkharaṇiyo.**So that’s what he did.*";
P_HTM[2942]="*Tā kho panānanda, pokkharaṇiyo catunnaṃ vaṇṇānaṃ iṭṭhakāhi citā ahesuṃ—**The lotus ponds were lined with tiles of four colors,*";
P_HTM[2943]="*ekā iṭṭhakā sovaṇṇamayā, ekā rūpiyamayā, ekā veḷuriyamayā, ekā phalikamayā.**made of gold, silver, beryl, and crystal.*";
P_HTM[2944]="*Tāsu kho panānanda, pokkharaṇīsu cattāri cattāri sopānāni ahesuṃ catunnaṃ vaṇṇānaṃ,**And four flights of stairs of four colors descended into each lotus pond,*";
P_HTM[2945]="*ekaṃ sopānaṃ sovaṇṇamayaṃ ekaṃ rūpiyamayaṃ ekaṃ veḷuriyamayaṃ ekaṃ phalikamayaṃ.**made of gold, silver, beryl, and crystal.*";
P_HTM[2946]="*Sovaṇṇamayassa sopānassa sovaṇṇamayā thambhā ahesuṃ, rūpiyamayā sūciyo ca uṇhīsañca.**The golden stairs had posts of gold, and banisters and finials of silver.*";
P_HTM[2947]="*Rūpiyamayassa sopānassa rūpiyamayā thambhā ahesuṃ, sovaṇṇamayā sūciyo ca uṇhīsañca.**The silver stairs had posts of silver, and banisters and finials of gold.*";
P_HTM[2948]="*Veḷuriyamayassa sopānassa veḷuriyamayā thambhā ahesuṃ, phalikamayā sūciyo ca uṇhīsañca.**The beryl stairs had posts of beryl, and banisters and finials of crystal.*";
P_HTM[2949]="*Phalikamayassa sopānassa phalikamayā thambhā ahesuṃ, veḷuriyamayā sūciyo ca uṇhīsañca.**The crystal stairs had posts of crystal, and banisters and finials of beryl.*";
P_HTM[2950]="*Tā kho panānanda, pokkharaṇiyo dvīhi vedikāhi parikkhittā ahesuṃ ekā vedikā sovaṇṇamayā, ekā rūpiyamayā.**Those lotus ponds were surrounded by two balustrades, made of gold and silver.*";
P_HTM[2951]="*Sovaṇṇamayāya vedikāya sovaṇṇamayā thambhā ahesuṃ, rūpiyamayā sūciyo ca uṇhīsañca.**The golden balustrades had posts of gold, and banisters and finials of silver.*";
P_HTM[2952]="*Rūpiyamayāya vedikāya rūpiyamayā thambhā ahesuṃ, sovaṇṇamayā sūciyo ca uṇhīsañca.**The silver balustrades had posts of silver, and banisters and finials of gold.*";
P_HTM[2953]="*Atha kho, ānanda, rañño mahāsudassanassa etadahosi:**Then King Mahāsudassana thought,*";
P_HTM[2954]="*‘yannūnāhaṃ imāsu pokkharaṇīsu evarūpaṃ mālaṃ ropāpeyyaṃ uppalaṃ padumaṃ kumudaṃ puṇḍarīkaṃ sabbotukaṃ sabbajanassa anāvaṭan’ti.**‘Why don’t I plant flowers in the lotus ponds such as blue water lilies, and lotuses of pink, yellow, and white, blooming all year round, and accessible to the public?’*";
P_HTM[2955]="*Ropāpesi kho, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano tāsu pokkharaṇīsu evarūpaṃ mālaṃ uppalaṃ padumaṃ kumudaṃ puṇḍarīkaṃ sabbotukaṃ sabbajanassa anāvaṭaṃ.**So that’s what he did.*";
P_HTM[2956]="*Atha kho, ānanda, rañño mahāsudassanassa etadahosi:**Then King Mahāsudassana thought,*";
P_HTM[2957]="*‘yannūnāhaṃ imāsaṃ pokkharaṇīnaṃ tīre nhāpake purise ṭhapeyyaṃ, ye āgatāgataṃ janaṃ nhāpessantī’ti.**‘Why don’t I appoint bath attendants to help bathe the people who come to bathe in the lotus ponds?’*";
P_HTM[2958]="*Ṭhapesi kho, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano tāsaṃ pokkharaṇīnaṃ tīre nhāpake purise, ye āgatāgataṃ janaṃ nhāpesuṃ.**So that’s what he did.*";
P_HTM[2959]="*Atha kho, ānanda, rañño mahāsudassanassa etadahosi:**Then King Mahāsudassana thought,*";
P_HTM[2960]="*‘yannūnāhaṃ imāsaṃ pokkharaṇīnaṃ tīre evarūpaṃ dānaṃ paṭṭhapeyyaṃ—**‘Why don’t I set up charities on the banks of the lotus ponds,*";
P_HTM[2961]="*annaṃ annaṭṭhikassa, pānaṃ pānaṭṭhikassa, vatthaṃ vatthaṭṭhikassa, yānaṃ yānaṭṭhikassa, sayanaṃ sayanaṭṭhikassa, itthiṃ itthiṭṭhikassa, hiraññaṃ hiraññaṭṭhikassa, suvaṇṇaṃ suvaṇṇaṭṭhikassā’ti.**so that those in need of food, drink, clothes, vehicles, beds, women, gold, or silver can get what they need?’*";
P_HTM[2962]="*Paṭṭhapesi kho, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano tāsaṃ pokkharaṇīnaṃ tīre evarūpaṃ dānaṃ—**So that’s what he did.*";
P_HTM[2963]="*annaṃ annaṭṭhikassa, pānaṃ pānaṭṭhikassa, vatthaṃ vatthaṭṭhikassa, yānaṃ yānaṭṭhikassa, sayanaṃ sayanaṭṭhikassa, itthiṃ itthiṭṭhikassa, hiraññaṃ hiraññaṭṭhikassa, suvaṇṇaṃ suvaṇṇaṭṭhikassa.* **";
P_HTM[2964]="*Atha kho, ānanda, brāhmaṇagahapatikā pahūtaṃ sāpateyyaṃ ādāya rājānaṃ mahāsudassanaṃ upasaṅkamitvā evamāhaṃsu:**Then the brahmins and householders came to the king bringing abundant wealth and said,*";
P_HTM[2965]="*‘idaṃ, deva, pahūtaṃ sāpateyyaṃ devaññeva uddissa ābhataṃ, taṃ devo paṭiggaṇhatū’ti.**‘Sire, this abundant wealth is specially for you alone; may Your Highness accept it!’*";
P_HTM[2966]="*‘Alaṃ, bho, mamapidaṃ pahūtaṃ sāpateyyaṃ dhammikena balinā abhisaṅkhataṃ, tañca vo hotu, ito ca bhiyyo harathā’ti.**‘There’s enough raised for me through regular taxes. Let this be for you; and here, take even more!’*";
P_HTM[2967]="*Te raññā paṭikkhittā ekamantaṃ apakkamma evaṃ samacintesuṃ:**When the king turned them down, they withdrew to one side to think up a plan,*";
P_HTM[2968]="*‘na kho etaṃ amhākaṃ patirūpaṃ, yaṃ mayaṃ imāni sāpateyyāni punadeva sakāni gharāni paṭihareyyāma.**‘It wouldn’t be proper for us to take this abundant wealth back to our own homes.*";
P_HTM[2969]="*Yannūna mayaṃ rañño mahāsudassanassa nivesanaṃ māpeyyāmā’ti.**Why don’t we build a home for King Mahāsudassana?’*";
P_HTM[2970]="*Te rājānaṃ mahāsudassanaṃ upasaṅkamitvā evamāhaṃsu:**They went up to the king and said,*";
P_HTM[2971]="*‘nivesanaṃ te, deva, māpessāmā’ti.**‘We shall have a home built for you, sire!’*";
P_HTM[2972]="*Adhivāsesi kho, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano tuṇhībhāvena.**King Mahāsudassana consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[2973]="*Atha kho, ānanda, sakko devānamindo rañño mahāsudassanassa cetasā cetoparivitakkamaññāya vissakammaṃ devaputtaṃ āmantesi:**And then Sakka, lord of gods, knowing what the king was thinking, addressed the god Vissakamma,*";
P_HTM[2974]="*‘ehi tvaṃ, samma vissakamma, rañño mahāsudassanassa nivesanaṃ māpehi dhammaṃ nāma pāsādan’ti.**‘Come, dear Vissakamma, build a palace named Principle as a home for King Mahāsudassana.’*";
P_HTM[2975]="*‘Evaṃ, bhaddantavā’ti kho, ānanda, vissakammo devaputto sakkassa devānamindassa paṭissutvā seyyathāpi nāma balavā puriso samiñjitaṃ vā bāhaṃ pasāreyya pasāritaṃ vā bāhaṃ samiñjeyya; evameva—devesu tāvatiṃsesu antarahito rañño mahāsudassanassa purato pāturahosi.**‘Yes, lord,’ replied Vissakamma. Then, as easily as a strong person would extend or contract their arm, he vanished from the gods of the Thirty-Three and appeared in front of King Mahāsudassana.*";
P_HTM[2976]="*Atha kho, ānanda, vissakammo devaputto rājānaṃ mahāsudassanaṃ etadavoca:**Vissakamma said to the king,*";
P_HTM[2977]="*‘nivesanaṃ te, deva, māpessāmi dhammaṃ nāma pāsādan’ti.**‘I shall build a palace named Principle as a home for you, sire.’*";
P_HTM[2978]="*Adhivāsesi kho, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano tuṇhībhāvena.**King Mahāsudassana consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[2979]="*Māpesi kho, ānanda, vissakammo devaputto rañño mahāsudassanassa nivesanaṃ dhammaṃ nāma pāsādaṃ.**And so that’s what Vissakamma did.*";
P_HTM[2980]="*Dhammo, ānanda, pāsādo puratthimena pacchimena ca yojanaṃ āyāmena ahosi. Uttarena dakkhiṇena ca aḍḍhayojanaṃ vitthārena.**The Palace of Principle stretched for a league from east to west, and half a league from north to south.*";
P_HTM[2981]="*Dhammassa, ānanda, pāsādassa tiporisaṃ uccatarena vatthu citaṃ ahosi catunnaṃ vaṇṇānaṃ iṭṭhakāhi—**It was lined with tiles of four colors, three fathoms high,*";
P_HTM[2982]="*ekā iṭṭhakā sovaṇṇamayā, ekā rūpiyamayā, ekā veḷuriyamayā, ekā phalikamayā.**made of gold, silver, beryl, and crystal.*";
P_HTM[2983]="*Dhammassa, ānanda, pāsādassa caturāsītithambhasahassāni ahesuṃ catunnaṃ vaṇṇānaṃ—**It had 84,000 pillars of four colors,*";
P_HTM[2984]="*eko thambho sovaṇṇamayo, eko rūpiyamayo, eko veḷuriyamayo, eko phalikamayo.**made of gold, silver, beryl, and crystal.*";
P_HTM[2985]="*Dhammo, ānanda, pāsādo catunnaṃ vaṇṇānaṃ phalakehi santhato ahosi—**It was covered with panels of four colors,*";
P_HTM[2986]="*ekaṃ phalakaṃ sovaṇṇamayaṃ, ekaṃ rūpiyamayaṃ, ekaṃ veḷuriyamayaṃ, ekaṃ phalikamayaṃ.**made of gold, silver, beryl, and crystal.*";
P_HTM[2987]="*Dhammassa, ānanda, pāsādassa catuvīsati sopānāni ahesuṃ catunnaṃ vaṇṇānaṃ—**It had twenty-four staircases of four colors,*";
P_HTM[2988]="*ekaṃ sopānaṃ sovaṇṇamayaṃ, ekaṃ rūpiyamayaṃ, ekaṃ veḷuriyamayaṃ, ekaṃ phalikamayaṃ.**made of gold, silver, beryl, and crystal.*";
P_HTM[2989]="*Sovaṇṇamayassa sopānassa sovaṇṇamayā thambhā ahesuṃ rūpiyamayā sūciyo ca uṇhīsañca.**The golden stairs had posts of gold, and banisters and finials of silver.*";
P_HTM[2990]="*Rūpiyamayassa sopānassa rūpiyamayā thambhā ahesuṃ sovaṇṇamayā sūciyo ca uṇhīsañca.**The silver stairs had posts of silver, and banisters and finials of gold.*";
P_HTM[2991]="*Veḷuriyamayassa sopānassa veḷuriyamayā thambhā ahesuṃ phalikamayā sūciyo ca uṇhīsañca.**The beryl stairs had posts of beryl, and banisters and finials of crystal.*";
P_HTM[2992]="*Phalikamayassa sopānassa phalikamayā thambhā ahesuṃ veḷuriyamayā sūciyo ca uṇhīsañca.**The crystal stairs had posts of crystal, and banisters and finials of beryl.*";
P_HTM[2993]="*Dhamme, ānanda, pāsāde caturāsītikūṭāgārasahassāni ahesuṃ catunnaṃ vaṇṇānaṃ—**It had 84,000 chambers of four colors,*";
P_HTM[2994]="*ekaṃ kūṭāgāraṃ sovaṇṇamayaṃ, ekaṃ rūpiyamayaṃ, ekaṃ veḷuriyamayaṃ, ekaṃ phalikamayaṃ.**made of gold, silver, beryl, and crystal.*";
P_HTM[2995]="*Sovaṇṇamaye kūṭāgāre rūpiyamayo pallaṅko paññatto ahosi, rūpiyamaye kūṭāgāre sovaṇṇamayo pallaṅko paññatto ahosi, veḷuriyamaye kūṭāgāre dantamayo pallaṅko paññatto ahosi, phalikamaye kūṭāgāre sāramayo pallaṅko paññatto ahosi.**In each chamber a couch was spread: in the golden chamber a couch of silver; in the silver chamber a couch of beryl; in the beryl chamber a couch of ivory; in the crystal chamber a couch of hardwood.*";
P_HTM[2996]="*Sovaṇṇamayassa kūṭāgārassa dvāre rūpiyamayo tālo ṭhito ahosi, tassa rūpiyamayo khandho sovaṇṇamayāni pattāni ca phalāni ca.**At the door of the golden chamber stood a palm tree of silver, with trunk of silver, and leaves and fruits of gold.*";
P_HTM[2997]="*Rūpiyamayassa kūṭāgārassa dvāre sovaṇṇamayo tālo ṭhito ahosi, tassa sovaṇṇamayo khandho, rūpiyamayāni pattāni ca phalāni ca.**At the door of the silver chamber stood a palm tree of gold, with trunk of gold, and leaves and fruits of silver.*";
P_HTM[2998]="*Veḷuriyamayassa kūṭāgārassa dvāre phalikamayo tālo ṭhito ahosi, tassa phalikamayo khandho, veḷuriyamayāni pattāni ca phalāni ca.**At the door of the beryl chamber stood a palm tree of crystal, with trunk of crystal, and leaves and fruits of beryl.*";
P_HTM[2999]="*Phalikamayassa kūṭāgārassa dvāre veḷuriyamayo tālo ṭhito ahosi, tassa veḷuriyamayo khandho, phalikamayāni pattāni ca phalāni ca.**At the door of the crystal chamber stood a palm tree of beryl, with trunk of beryl, and leaves and fruits of crystal.*";
P_HTM[3000]="*Atha kho, ānanda, rañño mahāsudassanassa etadahosi:**Then King Mahāsudassana thought,*";
P_HTM[3001]="*‘yannūnāhaṃ mahāviyūhassa kūṭāgārassa dvāre sabbasovaṇṇamayaṃ tālavanaṃ māpeyyaṃ, yattha divāvihāraṃ nisīdissāmī’ti.**‘Why don’t I build a grove of golden palm trees at the door to the great foyer, where I can sit for the day?’*";
P_HTM[3002]="*Māpesi kho, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano mahāviyūhassa kūṭāgārassa dvāre sabbasovaṇṇamayaṃ tālavanaṃ, yattha divāvihāraṃ nisīdi.**So that’s what he did.*";
P_HTM[3003]="*Dhammo, ānanda, pāsādo dvīhi vedikāhi parikkhitto ahosi, ekā vedikā sovaṇṇamayā, ekā rūpiyamayā.**The Palace of Principle was surrounded by two balustrades, made of gold and silver.*";
P_HTM[3004]="*Sovaṇṇamayāya vedikāya sovaṇṇamayā thambhā ahesuṃ, rūpiyamayā sūciyo ca uṇhīsañca.**The golden balustrades had posts of gold, and banisters and finials of silver.*";
P_HTM[3005]="*Rūpiyamayāya vedikāya rūpiyamayā thambhā ahesuṃ, sovaṇṇamayā sūciyo ca uṇhīsañca.**The silver balustrades had posts of silver, and banisters and finials of gold.*";
P_HTM[3006]="*Dhammo, ānanda, pāsādo dvīhi kiṅkiṇikajālehi parikkhitto ahosi—**The Palace of Principle was surrounded by two nets of bells,*";
P_HTM[3007]="*ekaṃ jālaṃ sovaṇṇamayaṃ ekaṃ rūpiyamayaṃ.**made of gold and silver.*";
P_HTM[3008]="*Sovaṇṇamayassa jālassa rūpiyamayā kiṅkiṇikā ahesuṃ, rūpiyamayassa jālassa sovaṇṇamayā kiṅkiṇikā ahesuṃ.**The golden net had bells of silver, and the silver net had bells of gold.*";
P_HTM[3009]="*Tesaṃ kho panānanda, kiṅkiṇikajālānaṃ vāteritānaṃ saddo ahosi vaggu ca rajanīyo ca khamanīyo ca madanīyo ca.**When those nets of bells were blown by the wind they sounded graceful, tantalizing, sensuous, lovely, and intoxicating,*";
P_HTM[3010]="*Seyyathāpi, ānanda, pañcaṅgikassa tūriyassa suvinītassa suppaṭitāḷitassa sukusalehi samannāhatassa saddo hoti, vaggu ca rajanīyo ca khamanīyo ca madanīyo ca;**like a quintet made up of skilled musicians who had practiced well and kept excellent rhythm.*";
P_HTM[3011]="*evameva kho, ānanda, tesaṃ kiṅkiṇikajālānaṃ vāteritānaṃ saddo ahosi vaggu ca rajanīyo ca khamanīyo ca madanīyo ca.* **";
P_HTM[3012]="*Ye kho panānanda, tena samayena kusāvatiyā rājadhāniyā dhuttā ahesuṃ soṇḍā pipāsā, te tesaṃ kiṅkiṇikajālānaṃ vāteritānaṃ saddena paricāresuṃ.**And any addicts, libertines, or drunkards in Kusāvatī at that time were entertained by that sound.*";
P_HTM[3013]="*Niṭṭhito kho panānanda, dhammo pāsādo duddikkho ahosi musati cakkhūni.**When it was finished, the palace was hard to look at, dazzling to the eyes,*";
P_HTM[3014]="*Seyyathāpi, ānanda, vassānaṃ pacchime māse saradasamaye viddhe vigatavalāhake deve ādicco nabhaṃ abbhussakkamāno duddikkho hoti musati cakkhūni;**like the sun rising in a clear and cloudless sky in the last month of the rainy season.*";
P_HTM[3015]="*evameva kho, ānanda, dhammo pāsādo duddikkho ahosi musati cakkhūni.* **";
P_HTM[3016]="*Atha kho, ānanda, rañño mahāsudassanassa etadahosi:**Then King Mahāsudassana thought,*";
P_HTM[3017]="*‘yannūnāhaṃ dhammassa pāsādassa purato dhammaṃ nāma pokkharaṇiṃ māpeyyan’ti.**‘Why don’t I build a lotus pond named Principle in front of the palace?’*";
P_HTM[3018]="*Māpesi kho, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano dhammassa pāsādassa purato dhammaṃ nāma pokkharaṇiṃ.**So that’s what he did.*";
P_HTM[3019]="*Dhammā, ānanda, pokkharaṇī puratthimena pacchimena ca yojanaṃ āyāmena ahosi, uttarena dakkhiṇena ca aḍḍhayojanaṃ vitthārena.**The Lotus Pond of Principle stretched for a league from east to west, and half a league from north to south.*";
P_HTM[3020]="*Dhammā, ānanda, pokkharaṇī catunnaṃ vaṇṇānaṃ iṭṭhakāhi citā ahosi—**It was lined with tiles of four colors,*";
P_HTM[3021]="*ekā iṭṭhakā sovaṇṇamayā, ekā rūpiyamayā, ekā veḷuriyamayā, ekā phalikamayā.**made of gold, silver, beryl, and crystal.*";
P_HTM[3022]="*Dhammāya, ānanda, pokkharaṇiyā catuvīsati sopānāni ahesuṃ catunnaṃ vaṇṇānaṃ—**It had twenty-four staircases of four colors,*";
P_HTM[3023]="*ekaṃ sopānaṃ sovaṇṇamayaṃ, ekaṃ rūpiyamayaṃ, ekaṃ veḷuriyamayaṃ, ekaṃ phalikamayaṃ.**made of gold, silver, beryl, and crystal.*";
P_HTM[3024]="*Sovaṇṇamayassa sopānassa sovaṇṇamayā thambhā ahesuṃ rūpiyamayā sūciyo ca uṇhīsañca.**The golden stairs had posts of gold, and banisters and finials of silver.*";
P_HTM[3025]="*Rūpiyamayassa sopānassa rūpiyamayā thambhā ahesuṃ sovaṇṇamayā sūciyo ca uṇhīsañca.**The silver stairs had posts of silver, and banisters and finials of gold.*";
P_HTM[3026]="*Veḷuriyamayassa sopānassa veḷuriyamayā thambhā ahesuṃ phalikamayā sūciyo ca uṇhīsañca.**The beryl stairs had posts of beryl, and banisters and finials of crystal.*";
P_HTM[3027]="*Phalikamayassa sopānassa phalikamayā thambhā ahesuṃ veḷuriyamayā sūciyo ca uṇhīsañca.**The crystal stairs had posts of crystal, and banisters and finials of beryl.*";
P_HTM[3028]="*Dhammā, ānanda, pokkharaṇī dvīhi vedikāhi parikkhittā ahosi—ekā vedikā sovaṇṇamayā, ekā rūpiyamayā.**It was surrounded by two balustrades, made of gold and silver.*";
P_HTM[3029]="*Sovaṇṇamayāya vedikāya sovaṇṇamayā thambhā ahesuṃ rūpiyamayā sūciyo ca uṇhīsañca.**The golden balustrades had posts of gold, and banisters and finials of silver.*";
P_HTM[3030]="*Rūpiyamayāya vedikāya rūpiyamayā thambhā ahesuṃ sovaṇṇamayā sūciyo ca uṇhīsañca.**The silver balustrades had posts of silver, and banisters and finials of gold.*";
P_HTM[3031]="*Dhammā, ānanda, pokkharaṇī sattahi tālapantīhi parikkhittā ahosi—**It was surrounded by seven rows of palm trees,*";
P_HTM[3032]="*ekā tālapanti sovaṇṇamayā, ekā rūpiyamayā, ekā veḷuriyamayā, ekā phalikamayā, ekā lohitaṅkamayā, ekā masāragallamayā, ekā sabbaratanamayā.**made of gold, silver, beryl, crystal, ruby, emerald, and all precious things.*";
P_HTM[3033]="*Sovaṇṇamayassa tālassa sovaṇṇamayo khandho ahosi rūpiyamayāni pattāni ca phalāni ca.**The golden palms had trunks of gold, and leaves and fruits of silver.*";
P_HTM[3034]="*Rūpiyamayassa tālassa rūpiyamayo khandho ahosi sovaṇṇamayāni pattāni ca phalāni ca.**The silver palms had trunks of silver, and leaves and fruits of gold.*";
P_HTM[3035]="*Veḷuriyamayassa tālassa veḷuriyamayo khandho ahosi phalikamayāni pattāni ca phalāni ca.**The beryl palms had trunks of beryl, and leaves and fruits of crystal.*";
P_HTM[3036]="*Phalikamayassa tālassa phalikamayo khandho ahosi veḷuriyamayāni pattāni ca phalāni ca.**The crystal palms had trunks of crystal, and leaves and fruits of beryl.*";
P_HTM[3037]="*Lohitaṅkamayassa tālassa lohitaṅkamayo khandho ahosi masāragallamayāni pattāni ca phalāni ca.**The ruby palms had trunks of ruby, and leaves and fruits of emerald.*";
P_HTM[3038]="*Masāragallamayassa tālassa masāragallamayo khandho ahosi lohitaṅkamayāni pattāni ca phalāni ca.**The emerald palms had trunks of emerald, and leaves and fruits of ruby.*";
P_HTM[3039]="*Sabbaratanamayassa tālassa sabbaratanamayo khandho ahosi, sabbaratanamayāni pattāni ca phalāni ca.**The palms of all precious things had trunks of all precious things, and leaves and fruits of all precious things.*";
P_HTM[3040]="*Tāsaṃ kho panānanda, tālapantīnaṃ vāteritānaṃ saddo ahosi, vaggu ca rajanīyo ca khamanīyo ca madanīyo ca.**When those rows of palm trees were blown by the wind they sounded graceful, tantalizing, sensuous, lovely, and intoxicating,*";
P_HTM[3041]="*Seyyathāpi, ānanda, pañcaṅgikassa tūriyassa suvinītassa suppaṭitāḷitassa sukusalehi samannāhatassa saddo hoti vaggu ca rajanīyo ca khamanīyo ca madanīyo ca;**like a quintet made up of skilled musicians who had practiced well and kept excellent rhythm.*";
P_HTM[3042]="*evameva kho, ānanda, tāsaṃ tālapantīnaṃ vāteritānaṃ saddo ahosi vaggu ca rajanīyo ca khamanīyo ca madanīyo ca.* **";
P_HTM[3043]="*Ye kho panānanda, tena samayena kusāvatiyā rājadhāniyā dhuttā ahesuṃ soṇḍā pipāsā, te tāsaṃ tālapantīnaṃ vāteritānaṃ saddena paricāresuṃ.**And any addicts, libertines, or drunkards in Kusāvatī at that time were entertained by that sound.*";
P_HTM[3044]="*Niṭṭhite kho panānanda, dhamme pāsāde niṭṭhitāya dhammāya ca pokkharaṇiyā rājā mahāsudassano ‘ye tena samayena samaṇesu vā samaṇasammatā brāhmaṇesu vā brāhmaṇasammatā’, te sabbakāmehi santappetvā dhammaṃ pāsādaṃ abhiruhi.**When the palace and its lotus pond were finished, King Mahāsudassana served those who were reckoned as true ascetics and brahmins with all they desired. Then he ascended the Palace of Principle.*";
P_HTM[3045]="*Paṭhamabhāṇavāro.* **";
P_HTM[3046]="*5. Jhānasampatti**5. Attaining Absorption*";
P_HTM[3047]="*Atha kho, ānanda, rañño mahāsudassanassa etadahosi:**Then King Mahāsudassana thought,*";
P_HTM[3048]="*‘kissa nu kho me idaṃ kammassa phalaṃ kissa kammassa vipāko, yenāhaṃ etarahi evaṃmahiddhiko evaṃmahānubhāvo’ti?**‘Of what deed of mine is this the fruit and result, that I am now so mighty and powerful?’*";
P_HTM[3049]="*Atha kho, ānanda, rañño mahāsudassanassa etadahosi:**Then King Mahāsudassana thought,*";
P_HTM[3050]="*‘tiṇṇaṃ kho me idaṃ kammānaṃ phalaṃ tiṇṇaṃ kammānaṃ vipāko, yenāhaṃ etarahi evaṃmahiddhiko evaṃmahānubhāvo, seyyathidaṃ—**‘It is the fruit and result of three kinds of deeds:*";
P_HTM[3051]="*dānassa damassa saṃyamassā’ti.**giving, self-control, and restraint.’*";
P_HTM[3052]="*Atha kho, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano yena mahāviyūhaṃ kūṭāgāraṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā mahāviyūhassa kūṭāgārassa dvāre ṭhito udānaṃ udānesi:**Then he went to the great foyer, stood at the door, and was inspired to exclaim:*";
P_HTM[3053]="*‘tiṭṭha, kāmavitakka, tiṭṭha, byāpādavitakka, tiṭṭha, vihiṃsāvitakka.**‘Stop here, sensual, malicious, and cruel thoughts—*";
P_HTM[3054]="*Ettāvatā, kāmavitakka, ettāvatā, byāpādavitakka, ettāvatā, vihiṃsāvitakkā’ti.**no further!’*";
P_HTM[3055]="*Atha kho, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano mahāviyūhaṃ kūṭāgāraṃ pavisitvā sovaṇṇamaye pallaṅke nisinno vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja vihāsi.**Then he entered the great foyer and sat on the golden couch. Quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, he entered and remained in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[3056]="*Vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja vihāsi.**As the placing of the mind and keeping it connected were stilled, he entered and remained in the second absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of immersion, with internal clarity and confidence, and unified mind, without placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[3057]="*Pītiyā ca virāgā upekkhako ca vihāsi, sato ca sampajāno sukhañca kāyena paṭisaṃvedesi, yaṃ taṃ ariyā ācikkhanti: ‘upekkhako satimā sukhavihārī’ti tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja vihāsi.**And with the fading away of rapture, he entered and remained in the third absorption, where he meditated with equanimity, mindful and aware, personally experiencing the bliss of which the noble ones declare, ‘Equanimous and mindful, one meditates in bliss.’*";
P_HTM[3058]="*Sukhassa ca pahānā dukkhassa ca pahānā pubbeva somanassadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamā adukkhamasukhaṃ upekkhāsatipārisuddhiṃ catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja vihāsi.**With the giving up of pleasure and pain, and the ending of former happiness and sadness, he entered and remained in the fourth absorption, without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[3059]="*Atha kho, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano mahāviyūhā kūṭāgārā nikkhamitvā sovaṇṇamayaṃ kūṭāgāraṃ pavisitvā rūpiyamaye pallaṅke nisinno**Then King Mahāsudassana left the great foyer and entered the golden chamber, where he sat on the golden couch.*";
P_HTM[3060]="*mettāsahagatena cetasā ekaṃ disaṃ pharitvā vihāsi. Tathā dutiyaṃ tathā tatiyaṃ tathā catutthaṃ. Iti uddhamadho tiriyaṃ sabbadhi sabbattatāya sabbāvantaṃ lokaṃ mettāsahagatena cetasā vipulena mahaggatena appamāṇena averena abyāpajjena pharitvā vihāsi.**He meditated spreading a heart full of love to one direction, and to the second, and to the third, and to the fourth. In the same way he spread a heart full of love above, below, across, everywhere, all around, to everyone in the world—abundant, expansive, limitless, free of enmity and ill will.*";
P_HTM[3061]="*Karuṇāsahagatena cetasā … pe …**He meditated spreading a heart full of compassion …*";
P_HTM[3062]="*muditāsahagatena cetasā … pe …**He meditated spreading a heart full of rejoicing …*";
P_HTM[3063]="*upekkhāsahagatena cetasā ekaṃ disaṃ pharitvā vihāsi. Tathā dutiyaṃ tathā tatiyaṃ tathā catutthaṃ. Iti uddhamadho tiriyaṃ sabbadhi sabbattatāya sabbāvantaṃ lokaṃ upekkhāsahagatena cetasā vipulena mahaggatena appamāṇena averena abyāpajjena pharitvā vihāsi.**He meditated spreading a heart full of equanimity to one direction, and to the second, and to the third, and to the fourth. In the same way above, below, across, everywhere, all around, he spread a heart full of equanimity to the whole world—abundant, expansive, limitless, free of enmity and ill will.*";
P_HTM[3064]="*6. Caturāsītinagarasahassādi**6. Of All Cities*";
P_HTM[3065]="*Rañño, ānanda, mahāsudassanassa caturāsīti nagarasahassāni ahesuṃ kusāvatīrājadhānippamukhāni;**King Mahāsudassana had 84,000 cities, with the royal capital of Kusāvatī foremost.*";
P_HTM[3066]="*caturāsīti pāsādasahassāni ahesuṃ dhammapāsādappamukhāni;**He had 84,000 palaces, with the Palace of Principle foremost.*";
P_HTM[3067]="*caturāsīti kūṭāgārasahassāni ahesuṃ mahāviyūhakūṭāgārappamukhāni;**He had 84,000 chambers, with the great foyer foremost.*";
P_HTM[3068]="*caturāsīti pallaṅkasahassāni ahesuṃ sovaṇṇamayāni rūpiyamayāni dantamayāni sāramayāni gonakatthatāni paṭikatthatāni paṭalikatthatāni kadalimigapavarapaccattharaṇāni sauttaracchadāni ubhatolohitakūpadhānāni;**He had 84,000 couches made of gold, silver, ivory, and hardwood. They were spread with woollen covers—shag-piled, pure white, or embroidered with flowers—and spread with a fine deer hide, with a canopy above and red pillows at both ends.*";
P_HTM[3069]="*caturāsīti nāgasahassāni ahesuṃ sovaṇṇālaṅkārāni sovaṇṇadhajāni hemajālapaṭicchannāni uposathanāgarājappamukhāni;**He had 84,000 bull elephants with gold adornments and banners, covered with gold netting, with the royal bull elephant named Sabbath foremost.*";
P_HTM[3070]="*caturāsīti assasahassāni ahesuṃ sovaṇṇālaṅkārāni sovaṇṇadhajāni hemajālapaṭicchannāni valāhakaassarājappamukhāni;**He had 84,000 horses with gold adornments and banners, covered with gold netting, with the royal steed named Thundercloud foremost.*";
P_HTM[3071]="*caturāsīti rathasahassāni ahesuṃ sīhacammaparivārāni byagghacammaparivārāni dīpicammaparivārāni paṇḍukambalaparivārāni sovaṇṇālaṅkārāni sovaṇṇadhajāni hemajālapaṭicchannāni vejayantarathappamukhāni;**He had 84,000 chariots upholstered with the hide of lions, tigers, and leopards, and cream rugs, with gold adornments and banners, covered with gold netting, with the chariot named Triumph foremost.*";
P_HTM[3072]="*caturāsīti maṇisahassāni ahesuṃ maṇiratanappamukhāni;**He had 84,000 jewels, with the jewel-treasure foremost.*";
P_HTM[3073]="*caturāsīti itthisahassāni ahesuṃ subhaddādevippamukhāni;**He had 84,000 women, with Queen Subhaddā foremost.*";
P_HTM[3074]="*caturāsīti gahapatisahassāni ahesuṃ gahapatiratanappamukhāni;**He had 84,000 householders, with the householder-treasure foremost.*";
P_HTM[3075]="*caturāsīti khattiyasahassāni ahesuṃ anuyantāni pariṇāyakaratanappamukhāni;**He had 84,000 aristocrat vassals, with the counselor-treasure foremost.*";
P_HTM[3076]="*caturāsīti dhenusahassāni ahesuṃ duhasandanāni kaṃsūpadhāraṇāni;**He had 84,000 milk-cows with silken reins and bronze pails.*";
P_HTM[3077]="*caturāsīti vatthakoṭisahassāni ahesuṃ khomasukhumānaṃ kappāsikasukhumānaṃ koseyyasukhumānaṃ kambalasukhumānaṃ;**He had 8,400,000,000 fine cloths of linen, silk, wool, and cotton.*";
P_HTM[3078]="*rañño, ānanda, mahāsudassanassa caturāsīti thālipākasahassāni ahesuṃ sāyaṃ pātaṃ bhattābhihāro abhihariyittha.**He had 84,000 servings of food, which were presented to him as offerings in the morning and evening.*";
P_HTM[3079]="*Tena kho panānanda, samayena rañño mahāsudassanassa caturāsīti nāgasahassāni sāyaṃ pātaṃ upaṭṭhānaṃ āgacchanti.**Now at that time his 84,000 royal elephants came to attend on him in the morning and evening.*";
P_HTM[3080]="*Atha kho, ānanda, rañño mahāsudassanassa etadahosi:**Then King Mahāsudassana thought,*";
P_HTM[3081]="*‘imāni kho me caturāsīti nāgasahassāni sāyaṃ pātaṃ upaṭṭhānaṃ āgacchanti, yannūna vassasatassa vassasatassa accayena dvecattālīsaṃ dvecattālīsaṃ nāgasahassāni sakiṃ sakiṃ upaṭṭhānaṃ āgaccheyyun’ti.**‘What if instead half of the elephants took turns to attend on me at the end of each century?’*";
P_HTM[3082]="*Atha kho, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano pariṇāyakaratanaṃ āmantesi:**He instructed the counselor-treasure to do this, and so it was done.*";
P_HTM[3083]="*‘imāni kho me, samma pariṇāyakaratana, caturāsīti nāgasahassāni sāyaṃ pātaṃ upaṭṭhānaṃ āgacchanti, tena hi, samma pariṇāyakaratana, vassasatassa vassasatassa accayena dvecattālīsaṃ dvecattālīsaṃ nāgasahassāni sakiṃ sakiṃ upaṭṭhānaṃ āgacchantū’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3084]="*‘Evaṃ, devā’ti kho, ānanda, pariṇāyakaratanaṃ rañño mahāsudassanassa paccassosi.* **";
P_HTM[3085]="*Atha kho, ānanda, rañño mahāsudassanassa aparena samayena vassasatassa vassasatassa accayena dvecattālīsaṃ dvecattālīsaṃ nāgasahassāni sakiṃ sakiṃ upaṭṭhānaṃ āgamaṃsu.* **";
P_HTM[3086]="*7. Subhaddādeviupasaṅkamana**7. The Visit of Queen Subhaddā*";
P_HTM[3087]="*Atha kho, ānanda, subhaddāya deviyā bahunnaṃ vassānaṃ bahunnaṃ vassasatānaṃ bahunnaṃ vassasahassānaṃ accayena etadahosi:**Then, after many years, many hundred years, many thousand years had passed, Queen Subhaddā thought,*";
P_HTM[3088]="*‘ciraṃ diṭṭho kho me rājā mahāsudassano. Yannūnāhaṃ rājānaṃ mahāsudassanaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkameyyan’ti.**‘It is long since I have seen the king. Why don’t I go to see him?’*";
P_HTM[3089]="*Atha kho, ānanda, subhaddā devī itthāgāraṃ āmantesi:**So the queen addressed the ladies of the harem,*";
P_HTM[3090]="*‘etha tumhe sīsāni nhāyatha pītāni vatthāni pārupatha.**‘Come, bathe your heads and dress in yellow.*";
P_HTM[3091]="*Ciraṃ diṭṭho no rājā mahāsudassano, rājānaṃ mahāsudassanaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamissāmā’ti.**It is long since we saw the king, and we shall go to see him.’*";
P_HTM[3092]="*‘Evaṃ, ayye’ti kho, ānanda, itthāgāraṃ subhaddāya deviyā paṭissutvā sīsāni nhāyitvā pītāni vatthāni pārupitvā yena subhaddā devī tenupasaṅkami.**‘Yes, ma’am,’ replied the ladies of the harem. They did as she asked and returned to the queen.*";
P_HTM[3093]="*Atha kho, ānanda, subhaddā devī pariṇāyakaratanaṃ āmantesi:**Then the queen addressed the counselor-treasure,*";
P_HTM[3094]="*‘kappehi, samma pariṇāyakaratana, caturaṅginiṃ senaṃ, ciraṃ diṭṭho no rājā mahāsudassano, rājānaṃ mahāsudassanaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamissāmā’ti.**‘Dear counselor-treasure, please ready the army with four divisions. It is long since we saw the king, and we shall go to see him.’*";
P_HTM[3095]="*‘Evaṃ, devī’ti kho, ānanda, pariṇāyakaratanaṃ subhaddāya deviyā paṭissutvā caturaṅginiṃ senaṃ kappāpetvā subhaddāya deviyā paṭivedesi:**‘Yes, my queen,’ he replied, and did as he was asked. He informed the queen,*";
P_HTM[3096]="*‘kappitā kho, devi, caturaṅginī senā,**‘My queen, the army with four divisions is ready,*";
P_HTM[3097]="*yassadāni kālaṃ maññasī’ti.**please go at your convenience.’*";
P_HTM[3098]="*Atha kho, ānanda, subhaddā devī caturaṅginiyā senāya saddhiṃ itthāgārena yena dhammo pāsādo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā dhammaṃ pāsādaṃ abhiruhitvā yena mahāviyūhaṃ kūṭāgāraṃ tenupasaṅkami.**Then Queen Subhaddā together with the ladies of the harem went with the army to the Palace of Principle. She ascended the palace and went to the great foyer,*";
P_HTM[3099]="*Upasaṅkamitvā mahāviyūhassa kūṭāgārassa dvārabāhaṃ ālambitvā aṭṭhāsi.**where she stood leaning against a door-post.*";
P_HTM[3100]="*Atha kho, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano saddaṃ sutvā:**Hearing them, the king thought,*";
P_HTM[3101]="*‘kiṃ nu kho mahato viya janakāyassa saddo’ti mahāviyūhā kūṭāgārā nikkhamanto addasa subhaddaṃ deviṃ dvārabāhaṃ ālambitvā ṭhitaṃ, disvāna subhaddaṃ deviṃ etadavoca:**‘What’s that, it sounds like a big crowd!’ Coming out of the foyer he saw Queen Subhaddā leaning against a door-post and said to her,*";
P_HTM[3102]="*‘ettheva, devi, tiṭṭha mā pāvisī’ti.**‘Please stay there, my queen, don’t enter in here.’*";
P_HTM[3103]="*Atha kho, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano aññataraṃ purisaṃ āmantesi:**Then he addressed a certain man,*";
P_HTM[3104]="*‘ehi tvaṃ, ambho purisa, mahāviyūhā kūṭāgārā sovaṇṇamayaṃ pallaṅkaṃ nīharitvā sabbasovaṇṇamaye tālavane paññapehī’ti.**‘Come, mister, bring the golden couch from the great foyer and set it up in the golden palm grove.’*";
P_HTM[3105]="*‘Evaṃ, devā’ti kho, ānanda, so puriso rañño mahāsudassanassa paṭissutvā mahāviyūhā kūṭāgārā sovaṇṇamayaṃ pallaṅkaṃ nīharitvā sabbasovaṇṇamaye tālavane paññapesi.**‘Yes, Your Majesty,’ that man replied, and did as he was asked.*";
P_HTM[3106]="*Atha kho, ānanda, rājā mahāsudassano dakkhiṇena passena sīhaseyyaṃ kappesi pāde pādaṃ accādhāya sato sampajāno.**The king laid down in the lion’s posture—on the right side, placing one foot on top of the other—mindful and aware.*";
P_HTM[3107]="*Atha kho, ānanda, subhaddāya deviyā etadahosi:**Then Queen Subhaddā thought,*";
P_HTM[3108]="*‘vippasannāni kho rañño mahāsudassanassa indriyāni, parisuddho chavivaṇṇo pariyodāto, mā heva kho rājā mahāsudassano kālamakāsī’ti rājānaṃ mahāsudassanaṃ etadavoca:**‘The king’s faculties are so very clear, and the complexion of his skin is pure and bright. Let him not pass away!’ She said to him,*";
P_HTM[3109]="*‘Imāni te, deva, caturāsīti nagarasahassāni kusāvatīrājadhānippamukhāni.**‘Sire, you have 84,000 cities, with the royal capital of Kusāvatī foremost.*";
P_HTM[3110]="*Ettha, deva, chandaṃ janehi jīvite apekkhaṃ karohi.**Arouse desire for these! Take an interest in life!’*";
P_HTM[3111]="*Imāni te, deva, caturāsīti pāsādasahassāni dhammapāsādappamukhāni.**And she likewise urged the king to live on by taking an interest in all his possessions as described above.*";
P_HTM[3112]="*Ettha, deva, chandaṃ janehi jīvite apekkhaṃ karohi.* **";
P_HTM[3113]="*Imāni te, deva, caturāsīti kūṭāgārasahassāni mahāviyūhakūṭāgārappamukhāni.* **";
P_HTM[3114]="*Ettha, deva, chandaṃ janehi jīvite apekkhaṃ karohi.* **";
P_HTM[3115]="*Imāni te, deva, caturāsīti pallaṅkasahassāni sovaṇṇamayāni rūpiyamayāni dantamayāni sāramayāni gonakatthatāni paṭikatthatāni paṭalikatthatāni kadalimigapavarapaccattharaṇāni sauttaracchadāni ubhatolohitakūpadhānāni.* **";
P_HTM[3116]="*Ettha, deva, chandaṃ janehi, jīvite apekkhaṃ karohi.* **";
P_HTM[3117]="*Imāni te, deva, caturāsīti nāgasahassāni sovaṇṇālaṅkārāni sovaṇṇadhajāni hemajālapaṭicchannāni uposathanāgarājappamukhāni.* **";
P_HTM[3118]="*Ettha, deva, chandaṃ janehi jīvite apekkhaṃ karohi.* **";
P_HTM[3119]="*Imāni te, deva, caturāsīti assasahassāni sovaṇṇālaṅkārāni sovaṇṇadhajāni hemajālapaṭicchannāni valāhakaassarājappamukhāni.* **";
P_HTM[3120]="*Ettha, deva, chandaṃ janehi jīvite apekkhaṃ karohi.* **";
